var textForPages =["THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a\u2014 1 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aTHE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO\u000d\u000aBuilding in\u000d\u000aRegulated Markets\u000d\u000aHow African Startups Navigate Blockchain,\u000d\u000aDigital Assets & the New Rules of Money\u000d\u000aCHIMEZIE CHUTA\u000d\u000aChairman, National Blockchain Policy Implementation Steering Committee, NITDA\u000d\u000aMember, Blockchain & Virtual Asset Working Group, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000a\u00a9 2026 Blockspace Technologies Limited. All rights reserved.\u000d\u000a\u2014 2 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCONTENTS\u000d\u000aTable of Contents\u000d\u000aForeword - Musa Itopa Jimoh - Director Payment System Policy Department, CBN v\u000d\u000aForeword - Mrs. Mary Uduk, MNI. Acting Director-General, SEC, Nigeria vi\u000d\u000aA Note from the Fintech Ecosystem, Dr. Babatunde Obrimah, FintechNGR vii\u000d\u000aPreface - Dr Timi Agama, PhD. Director General, SEC Nigeria ix\u000d\u000aIntroduction: The Letter, the Founder, and the Country We Are Building xi\u000d\u000aA Note on How to Use This Handbook xxi\u000d\u000aPART ONE\u000d\u000aThe Mindset Shift \u2014 Regulation Is Not Your Enemy, It Is Your Moat\u000d\u000a1. The Letter You Were Not Prepared For 3\u000d\u000a2. Compliance as Competitive Advantage 14\u000d\u000a3. The Three Myths That Get African Founders in Trouble 24\u000d\u000a4. How to Read a Regulatory Document Like a Strategist 35\u000d\u000aPART TWO\u000d\u000aThe Terrain \u2014 Who Regulates What, Where, and Why\u000d\u000a5. How Regulation Actually Gets Made in Nigeria 49\u000d\u000a6. The Regulator Map: CBN, SEC Nigeria, NITDA, NFIU, EFCC, NAICOM & Beyond\u000d\u000a62\u000d\u000a7. Nigeria's Digital Asset Regulatory Journey \u2014 A Timeline With Lessons 76\u000d\u000a8. Beyond Nigeria: Ghana, Kenya, and the Pan-African Patchwork 90\u000d\u000a9. Global Standards and What They Mean for You: FATF, BIS, IMF, MiCA 104\u000d\u000aPART THREE\u000d\u000aThe Products \u2014 What You Are Building and What It Triggers\u000d\u000a10. Stablecoins and Digital Payments: The CBN Minefield and How to Cross It 119\u000d\u000a11. Virtual Asset Services: VASP Licensing, Custody & Exchange Infrastructure 132\u000d\u000a\u2014 3 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a12. Tokenisation: Real-World Assets, Securities, and the New Capital Markets 147\u000d\u000a13. DeFi, DAOs & Smart Contracts: Building Decentralised Products in a Centralised\u000d\u000aRegulatory World 160\u000d\u000a14. AI-Enabled Financial Products: The Emerging Regulatory Frontier 173\u000d\u000aPART FOUR\u000d\u000aThe Practice \u2014 Being Compliant on Paper vs. Regulator-Ready in Practice\u000d\u000a15. Building Your AML/CFT Framework From Scratch 189\u000d\u000a16. How to Engage a Regulator Before They Engage You 204\u000d\u000a17. Using the Innovation Sandbox as a Launch Strategy 218\u000d\u000a18. Compliance-First Product Architecture: Building It Right From Day One 231\u000d\u000a19. When Things Go Wrong: Responding to Regulatory Action 244\u000d\u000aPART FIVE\u000d\u000aThe Future \u2014 Where This Is All Going and How to Stay Ahead of It\u000d\u000a20. CBDCs, the eNaira, and What Programmable Money Means for Your Business\u000d\u000a259\u000d\u000a21. AfCFTA, Cross-Border Digital Trade & the Coming Pan-African Regulatory\u000d\u000aConvergence 271\u000d\u000a22. Building the Mental Model: How to Navigate Regulations That Don't Exist Yet \u000d\u000a283\u000d\u000aBACK MATTER\u000d\u000aAppendices, Glossary & About the Author\u000d\u000aA. The 90-Day Regulatory Readiness Checklist 297\u000d\u000aB. Africa Regulatory Contact & Resource Directory 305\u000d\u000aC. Product-to-Regulator Mapping Matrix 311\u000d\u000aD. Glossary of Regulatory Terms, Acronyms & Institutions 317\u000d\u000aAbout the Author: Working with Chimezie Chuta 323\u000d\u000aAcknowledgements 327\u000d\u000aReferences\u000d\u000a\u2014 4 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aFOREWORD, by Musa Itopa. Jimoh\u000d\u000aThere is a particular kind of clarity that comes from being present when history is still\u000d\u000auncertain about what it will become.\u000d\u000aIn 2017, I accepted an invitation to deliver the keynote address at Nigeria\u2019s first National\u000d\u000aBlockchain and Cryptocurrency Conference, convened by Chimezie Chuta and the\u000d\u000aBlockchain Nigeria User Group. I did so not because the Central Bank of Nigeria had\u000d\u000areached a settled position on blockchain technology or virtual assets; it had not. I accepted\u000d\u000abecause the Bank\u2019s mandate\u2014to keep Nigeria\u2019s payments system safe, efficient, and\u000d\u000arobust enough to support innovation in financial services\u2014requires us to be present\u000d\u000awhere financial innovation is taking shape, before it is fully formed.\u000d\u000aWhat I encountered at that conference was not what I had expected. I had anticipated\u000d\u000aenthusiasm; what I found was seriousness\u2014a community of builders, thinkers, and\u000d\u000apractitioners who understood that the technology they were developing carried real\u000d\u000aimplications for monetary sovereignty, financial inclusion, and the integrity of systems on\u000d\u000awhich millions of Nigerians depend. Chimezie was at the centre of that seriousness.\u000d\u000aIn the years that followed, the relationship between the Central Bank of Nigeria and\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s blockchain ecosystem was not always smooth. Regulation and innovation rarely\u000d\u000amove at the same pace, and the tensions that arise when they diverge are real\u2014and\u000d\u000asometimes public. The measures the Central Bank took in 2021 in relation to crypto\u000d\u000aexchange service providers were controversial within the industry, but they were not\u000d\u000ataken lightly within the institution either.\u000d\u000aFrom the vantage point of someone who participated directly in those policy\u000d\u000aconversations, I can say that the concern was not hostility to digital assets or to the\u000d\u000afounders building with them. It was an operational challenge: the supervisory\u000d\u000ainfrastructure of the payments system could not adequately see, assess, or account for\u000d\u000atransaction flows of a scale and velocity that had implications for monetary stability and\u000d\u000afor the integrity of the financial system.\u000d\u000aChimezie understood this. More importantly, he helped the industry understand it, while\u000d\u000aalso helping the institution recognise that much of the industry it was struggling to see\u000d\u000awas, in fact, trying to be seen. That ability to hold both sides of a difficult conversation\u000d\u000ahonestly and at the same time is rare. It is also, I would argue, essential to building any\u000d\u000asustainable regulatory relationship in a rapidly evolving sector.\u000d\u000a\u2014 5 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe book you are holding is the most complete account I have encountered of what that\u000d\u000arelationship-building looks like from the inside. It is not a theoretical text; it is a\u000d\u000apractitioner\u2019s account, written by someone who stood both inside the policy rooms where\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s digital asset framework was being shaped and inside the businesses that\u000d\u000aframework was intended to govern. That dual vantage point is unusual, and it makes this\u000d\u000abook especially valuable.\u000d\u000a\u2022 For regulators, it provides an honest account of how regulatory processes are\u000d\u000aexperienced by those they govern, and what that experience means for behaviour,\u000d\u000astrategy, and institutional trust.\u000d\u000a\u2022 For founders and builders, it offers a practical framework for navigating a\u000d\u000aregulatory environment that is increasingly complex, consequential, and\u000d\u000afast-evolving.\u000d\u000aThe Central Bank of Nigeria\u2019s work in the digital assets and payments space continues.\u000d\u000aThe framework for virtual asset service providers, the evolving position on stablecoins,\u000d\u000athe ongoing development of the eNaira, and the broader question of how programmable\u000d\u000amoney intersects with monetary sovereignty remain live issues. They are being worked\u000d\u000athrough by serious people across multiple institutions, in ongoing dialogue with an\u000d\u000aindustry that is itself still evolving.\u000d\u000aThat dialogue is more informed, more honest, and more productive because of the work\u000d\u000aChimezie Chuta and the Blockchain Nigeria User Group have done over the past decade\u000d\u000ato build the institutional and community infrastructure that makes it possible. This book is\u000d\u000apart of that infrastructure, and I believe it will help make the next decade of that dialogue\u000d\u000astronger still.\u000d\u000aTo the founders, regulators, and practitioners who will read this book: the work of\u000d\u000abuilding a safe, efficient, and innovation-enabling financial system for Nigeria belongs to\u000d\u000aall of us. This book is a meaningful contribution to that work, and I recommend it to you\u000d\u000aunreservedly.\u000d\u000aMusa Itopa Jimoh\u000d\u000aDirector, Payments System Policy Department, Central Bank of Nigeria, Abuja, 2026\u000d\u000a\u2014 6 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aFOREWORD, by Ms. Mary Uduk, mni\u000d\u000aWhen Chimezie Chuta approached me to write the foreword to this book, my initial\u000d\u000areaction was hesitation. I have never been inclined toward public attention, and much of\u000d\u000athe work I consider most meaningful during my time at the Securities and Exchange\u000d\u000aCommission was never undertaken for recognition. It was undertaken because the market\u000d\u000arequired direction, and the institution had a responsibility to respond.\u000d\u000aHowever, as our discussions progressed, I was reminded that the story behind Nigeria\u2019s\u000d\u000adigital asset regulatory evolution is one that deserves to be properly documented. The\u000d\u000aframeworks and structures that now shape conversations around blockchain, virtual\u000d\u000aassets, innovation programmes, and digital finance did not emerge suddenly. They were\u000d\u000athe result of deliberate institutional thinking, difficult policy conversations, and the\u000d\u000acollective efforts of professionals who understood early enough that technology was\u000d\u000aalready reshaping the future of finance.\u000d\u000aWhen I assumed office as Acting Director-General of the Securities and Exchange\u000d\u000aCommission in April 2018, blockchain technology and digital assets were already\u000d\u000aattracting significant attention within Nigeria\u2019s financial ecosystem. Trading activities\u000d\u000ainvolving cryptocurrencies had increased considerably, technology entrepreneurs were\u000d\u000aintroducing innovative financial solutions, and new forms of digital fundraising were\u000d\u000abeginning to emerge. Yet, from a regulatory standpoint, there was very limited\u000d\u000ainstitutional guidance on how these developments should be approached.\u000d\u000aAt the time, caution among regulators was understandable. Emerging technologies often\u000d\u000araise complex legal, operational, and investor protection concerns. Nevertheless, I believed\u000d\u000astrongly that regulatory caution should not translate into institutional silence. A regulator\u000d\u000amust engage with innovation early, thoughtfully, and responsibly, especially when\u000d\u000amarket activities have implications for investor confidence and market integrity.\u000d\u000aIt was against this background that the Fintech Roadmap Committee of the Nigerian\u000d\u000aCapital Market was setup. One of the important decisions taken within that process was\u000d\u000athe recognition of blockchain and virtual financial assets as a distinct area requiring\u000d\u000afocused attention. That decision represented, in many respects, one of the earliest formal\u000d\u000aacknowledgments within Nigeria\u2019s regulatory environment that digital assets were not\u000d\u000amerely a passing technological trend, but an emerging capital market reality that required\u000d\u000astructured policy consideration.\u000d\u000aThis work later led to the inauguration of the Blockchain and Virtual Financial Assets\u000d\u000aFramework Committee on August 20, 2019, under the chairmanship of Francis Chuka\u000d\u000aAgbu, SAN. The Committee was tasked with examining global regulatory developments,\u000d\u000astudying the classification and treatment of digital assets, assessing associated risks and\u000d\u000aopportunities, and recommending an appropriate framework for innovation, investor\u000d\u000aprotection, and market oversight within the Nigerian context.\u000d\u000aThe Committee brought together individuals from diverse professional backgrounds,\u000d\u000aincluding legal practitioners, forensic experts, consultants, market operators, and staff of\u000d\u000athe Commission. Mr. Chimezie Chuta was a member of that Committee and contributed\u000d\u000a\u2014 7 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000ameaningfully to its work. What united the members was not ideology or enthusiasm for\u000d\u000atechnology alone, but a shared recognition that Nigeria needed a balanced regulatory\u000d\u000aapproach, one that would encourage innovation while preserving market discipline and\u000d\u000ainvestor protection.\u000d\u000aThe framework developed at the time became an important foundation for subsequent\u000d\u000aregulatory developments in digital asset ecosystem in Nigeria. It informed the\u000d\u000aCommission\u2019s 2020 Statement on Digital Assets, contributed to the development of later\u000d\u000aDigital Asset Rules, and influenced broader conversations that eventually shaped\u000d\u000aprogrammes such as the Accelerated Regulatory Incubation Programme (ARIP), the\u000d\u000aVirtual Asset Service Provider (VASP) regulatory structure, and the provisions reflected in\u000d\u000athe Investments and Securities Act (ISA), 2025.\u000d\u000aImportantly, the work did not end with those initial efforts. I must acknowledge and\u000d\u000acommend the individuals, industry stakeholders, regulatory professionals, and successive\u000d\u000aleadership within the SEC who continued to build upon those foundations.\u000d\u000aRegulatory development is rarely the work of one administration or one committee. It is\u000d\u000aan ongoing institutional process that requires continuity, collaboration, and the\u000d\u000awillingness of successive actors to refine, strengthen, and implement ideas over time. I am\u000d\u000apleased that the work initiated during that period has continued to mature with greater\u000d\u000adepth, sophistication, and strategic relevance for Nigeria\u2019s financial system.\u000d\u000aThis book is particularly valuable because it is written by someone who participated\u000d\u000adirectly in many of those formative conversations and policy engagements. It therefore\u000d\u000aoffers not only technical insight, but also institutional context that is often missing in\u000d\u000adiscussions about digital asset regulation in Nigeria.\u000d\u000aFor innovators, entrepreneurs, policymakers, and market participants who will read this\u000d\u000awork, I hope it serves as both a guide and a reminder that sustainable innovation thrives\u000d\u000abest within systems that promote trust, accountability, and regulatory clarity.\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s digital financial future will continue to be shaped by bold ideas, responsible\u000d\u000aleadership, and institutions willing to adapt thoughtfully to change. The responsibility\u000d\u000anow lies with the next generation of builders, regulators, and industry leaders to continue\u000d\u000astrengthening that foundation for the benefit of the market and the broader economy.\u000d\u000aMs. Mary Uduk, mni\u000d\u000aFormer Acting Director-General, Securities and Exchange Commission Nigeria\u000d\u000aApril 2018 \u2013 June 2020\u000d\u000a\u2014 8 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aA Note from the Fintech Ecosystem, by Dr. Babatunde Obrimah\u000d\u000aThe future of money will be the interaction between Fiat, Central Bank Digital Currency\u000d\u000a(CBDC), StableCoins, and Cryptocurrencies. While the first two are transactional\u000d\u000ainstruments, the last two are transformational instruments for investments. Stablecoins\u000d\u000aplay a major bridging role to enable the transition from Fiat to cryptocurrencies. The\u000d\u000ainteresting thing is that the last three run on blockchain technology, hence the importance\u000d\u000aof blockchain in the financial services sector. A staggering amount of $205 billion of digital\u000d\u000aassets was traded in Africa between July 2024 and June 2025, with $92 billion in Nigeria\u000d\u000a(Chainanalysis). This is no mean amount and majority were P2P transactions which\u000d\u000adefinitely would attract attention of regulators.\u000d\u000aThe financial system is however, as stable as the regulations that govern it, hence the\u000d\u000aimportance of regulation in this sector. However, regulation needs to be proactive, agile\u000d\u000aand innovative to ensure that innovation is not stifled, risks are managed and there is\u000d\u000aeconomic growth.\u000d\u000aRegulation helps to put the ecosystem in the right perspective for innovators, investors\u000d\u000aand consumers. You hear a lot of why should there be regulation? Founders coming into\u000d\u000athe Blockchain financial ecosystem without prior experience in the financial sector need to\u000d\u000aunderstand that this is a highly regulated sector and regulation is not a limitation.\u000d\u000aProactive players look for opportunities to explore within and around the regulation.\u000d\u000aThe book \u201cThe Founder\u2019s Guide to Building in Regulated Markets\u201d by Chuta Chimezie\u000d\u000acould not have come at a better time for founders already in the blockchain financial\u000d\u000aecosystem or planning to do so. The book addresses the fears of founders, the\u000d\u000apreparedness of legacy financial institutions as well as other institutions who might use\u000d\u000aderivatives of Blockchain technology such as tokenization. Within limits provided by\u000d\u000aregulators, what roles can various parties play presently and how should they position for\u000d\u000athe future?\u000d\u000aThe success of regulation in the Blockchain financial ecosystem will however, be the\u000d\u000ainteroperability of regulators working together as a team and not in silos. Collaboration\u000d\u000abetween Central Banks, Securities & Exchange Commissions, Financial Intelligence Units\u000d\u000aand Security Agencies is critical to effective regulation that will not stifle innovation.\u000d\u000a\u2014 9 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe author\u2019s wealth of experiences in the Blockchain ecosystem is expressed in this book\u000d\u000aas an operator with visible interactions with regulators and his vision of the future.\u000d\u000aThis book is a must read for Blockchain founders, financial services operators (banks,\u000d\u000aMFBs, Asset Managers, etc.), Board members of financial institutions and institutions that\u000d\u000amight employ derivatives like tokenization, Lawyers, Regulators and Security agencies.\u000d\u000aIt is my pleasure to write the forward of this book at this important phase of Blockchain\u000d\u000atechnology adoption in the financial services ecosystem in Africa.\u000d\u000aDr Babatunde Oghenobruche Obrimah\u000d\u000aFintech Enthusiast & Former COO, FintechNGR\u000d\u000a\u2014 10 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aPREFACE, by Dr. Emomotimi Agama, PhD.\u000d\u000aWhen Chimezie Chuta first shared his manuscript with me, I recognised immediately\u000d\u000awhat I was reading: not a policy document, not a legal treatise, but something far more\u000d\u000avaluable; a translation manual for a conversation that Africa's entrepreneurial\u000d\u000aecosystem has needed to have for years.\u000d\u000aI have led the Securities and Exchange Commission through one of the most\u000d\u000aconsequential transformations in our institution's history. The Investments and\u000d\u000aSecurities Act 2025 formally recognised digital assets as a category of financial\u000d\u000ainstruments. In that moment, we faced not merely a regulatory task, but a\u000d\u000afundamental institutional question: what does it mean for the SEC to govern a\u000d\u000acategory that did not exist in any previous framework? What are the precedents? How\u000d\u000ado we adapt instruments designed for a different era to the realities of blockchain,\u000d\u000avirtual assets, and programmable money?\u000d\u000aBut that is not the conversation I want to have in this preface. What I want to speak to\u000d\u000ais something I have observed repeatedly in my years in this role, and what this\u000d\u000ahandbook finally addresses.\u000d\u000aI have received founders in my office, brilliant builders, visionary in their conception\u000d\u000aof what technology might accomplish for African finance, who sat across from me\u000d\u000awith an expression I have come to know too well. They had built products that\u000d\u000amarkets wanted. They had assembled teams of uncommon talent. They had attracted\u000d\u000acapital from sophisticated investors. And yet they arrived at the moment of regulatory\u000d\u000aengagement feeling entirely unequipped to interpret what was happening, to respond\u000d\u000ato what was being asked of them, or to understand the institutional logic that had\u000d\u000aproduced the letter on their desk or the guidance they had just received.\u000d\u000aIn almost every case, they said the same thing: 'I feel like I'm navigating a foreign country\u000d\u000awithout a map.'\u000d\u000aWhat troubled me about those conversations was not the letters themselves. The SEC's\u000d\u000aregulatory actions are always grounded in genuine institutional concerns: systemic\u000d\u000astability, consumer protection, and the integrity of the financial system. These are\u000d\u000alegitimate preoccupations. What troubled me was the distanc, the vast, seemingly\u000d\u000aunbridgeable distance between the world in which those regulatory concerns are\u000d\u000aformed and the world in which entrepreneurs are trying to build.\u000d\u000aThat distance is not inevitable. It is not the natural state of things. And it is\u000d\u000aenormously costly.\u000d\u000a\u2014 11 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe founders who understand regulations, not as an obstacle to be circumvented, but\u000d\u000aas a foundation upon which serious businesses are built, are the founders who\u000d\u000asucceed at scale. They are the ones who build at scale. They are the ones who attract\u000d\u000ainstitutional capital. They are the ones who last. The founders who do not understand\u000d\u000athis continue to find themselves on the wrong end of letters they struggle to interpret,\u000d\u000awritten by institutions whose logic remains opaque to them.\u000d\u000aThis handbook bridges that gap. It does something I have not seen done before in the\u000d\u000aAfrican digital asset context: it explains, from inside the policy rooms, how regulation\u000d\u000aactually gets made. It teaches the reader not what the rules are, but why the rules are\u000d\u000awhat they are. It provides a framework for understanding the institutional thinking\u000d\u000athat produces regulatory guidance. And it gives entrepreneurs a language for\u000d\u000aengaging with regulators from a position of strategic clarity rather than from a\u000d\u000aposition of alarm.\u000d\u000aAt the SEC, we have a conviction that is sometimes difficult to articulate in a world\u000d\u000awhere regulation is so often cast as the adversary of innovation. That conviction is this:\u000d\u000agood regulation is the precondition for serious innovation. It is the substrate on which\u000d\u000adurable businesses are built. It is the framework that distinguishes the credible from\u000d\u000athe speculative, the legitimate from the predatory. It is the assurance that allows\u000d\u000ainstitutional capital to allocate to a category at scale. Without regulation, you do not\u000d\u000ahave innovation; you have speculation. You do not have a market; you have a casino.\u000d\u000aThe founders who understand this are the ones who will build the next generation of\u000d\u000aAfrican financial institutions. They are the ones who will attract the capital, the talent,\u000d\u000aand the institutional support that serious entrepreneurship requires. This handbook\u000d\u000agives them the understanding they need to do that.\u000d\u000aI commend this work to every founder engaged in building Africa's digital financial\u000d\u000afuture. Read it. Study it. Make it a reference document for your organisation. The\u000d\u000ainvestment of your time will be repaid many times over in the clarity it brings, the\u000d\u000amistakes it helps you avoid, and the foundation it provides for building something\u000d\u000adurable in a regulated environment.\u000d\u000aWe are at a defining moment for African finance. Between July 2024 and June 2025,\u000d\u000aSub-Saharan Africa received over USD 205 billion in on-chain value, a 52%\u000d\u000ayear-on-year increase that placed the region among the world's fastest-growing digital\u000d\u000aasset markets. That growth is real. That growth is significant. But for that growth to\u000d\u000atranslate into the kind of institutional financial infrastructure that Africa needs,\u000d\u000ainfrastructure that can compete on a global stage, that can channel capital at scale, that\u000d\u000a\u2014 12 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000acan serve consumers with sophistication and integrity, it must be built on a foundation\u000d\u000aof mutual understanding between regulators and entrepreneurs.\u000d\u000aThis handbook makes that foundation possible. It is the book I have been waiting\u000d\u000ayears to see written. And it is the book that, I believe, will change the trajectory of this\u000d\u000aconversation on our continent.\u000d\u000aDr. Emomotimi Agama\u000d\u000aDirector-General & Chief Executive Officer\u000d\u000aSecurities and Exchange Commission of Nigeria\u000d\u000aVice Chair, IOSCO Africa/Middle East Regional Committee (2026\u20132028)\u000d\u000aChairman, West Africa Securities Regulators Association (WASRA)\u000d\u000aAbuja, Federal Capital Territory\u000d\u000aMay 2026\u000d\u000a\u2014 13 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aINTRODUCTION\u000d\u000aThe Letter, the Founder, and the Country We Are Building\u000d\u000aSometime in the middle of 2022, I sat across from a Nigerian fintech founder in his\u000d\u000aoffices in Yaba. He had raised a seed round from a well-known international fund. His\u000d\u000aproduct was working. His team was lean and talented. His user numbers were\u000d\u000agrowing.\u000d\u000aOn the desk between us was a letter from a regulator. He had received it three weeks\u000d\u000aearlier. He had read it perhaps a hundred times. He had paid two firms of lawyers to\u000d\u000aread it as well. And as he slid the letter across to me, he asked the question that has\u000d\u000abecome the most common opening line of every advisory conversation I have had\u000d\u000asince:\u000d\u000a\"Chimezie, what does this actually mean, and what am I supposed to do?\"\u000d\u000aThe letter, as it happened, was not catastrophic. It was a notice of inquiry, a routine\u000d\u000ainstrument that any digital asset business operating in Nigeria today should expect to\u000d\u000areceive at some point in its life. With the right response, it could have been resolved in\u000d\u000aa fortnight. With the wrong response, it could have ended his business.\u000d\u000aWhat troubled me was not the letter. It was the founder's face. Here was a man who\u000d\u000ahad built a product good enough to attract international capital, scaled it to tens of\u000d\u000athousands of users, and assembled a team that could compete with anything Silicon\u000d\u000aValley was producing,... and yet the moment a regulator's letter arrived on his desk, he\u000d\u000awas entirely unequipped to interpret it, respond to it, or understand the institutional\u000d\u000alogic that produced it. He was, in his own words, \"flying blind\".\u000d\u000aIn the years since that conversation, I have sat across from variations of that same\u000d\u000afounder more times than I can count. Sometimes the founder is in Lagos, sometimes in\u000d\u000aAccra, sometimes in Nairobi. Sometimes the letter is from the Central Bank of Nigeria,\u000d\u000asometimes from the Securities and Exchange Commission, sometimes from the\u000d\u000a\u2014 14 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aFinancial Intelligence Unit. Sometimes there is no letter at all,... only the founder's\u000d\u000agnawing sense that one is coming and that he is not ready.\u000d\u000aThis book is for that founder.\u000d\u000aIt is also for the corporate innovation lead at a Tier-1 Nigerian bank, sitting in a\u000d\u000ameeting with her Managing Director, who has just instructed her to \"do something with\u000d\u000ablockchain\", and who has no Web3 background, no compliance framework, and no\u000d\u000aidea where to begin. It is for the pan-African team building a cross-border stablecoin\u000d\u000aproduct who must operate under three different national regulatory regimes\u000d\u000asimultaneously, and who cannot afford to hire three different compliance counsels in\u000d\u000athree different countries. It is, in short, for everyone who is building, advising, or\u000d\u000agoverning the next chapter of African finance, and who must do so inside a regulatory\u000d\u000aenvironment that is more complex, more consequential, and more rapidly evolving\u000d\u000athan at any point in our continent's history.\u000d\u000aWhy This Book Now\u000d\u000aAfrica is at a defining inflection point in its financial development. Between July 2024\u000d\u000aand June 2025, Sub-Saharan Africa received over USD 205 billion in onchain value; a\u000d\u000a52% year-on-year increase that placed the region among the world's fastest-growing\u000d\u000adigital asset markets. Nigeria's Investments and Securities Act 2025 formally\u000d\u000arecognised digital assets as securities, and later added that they might also be\u000d\u000acommodities. Just recently, the Central Bank of Nigeria launched an AML/CFT\u000d\u000asupervision pilot for Virtual Asset Service Providers. South Africa has issued its first\u000d\u000acrypto-asset service provider licences. Kenya, Ghana, Mauritius, and a dozen other\u000d\u000ajurisdictions are moving, at different speeds, in different directions, but unmistakably\u000d\u000amoving toward formal regulatory frameworks for digital assets, stablecoins,\u000d\u000atokenisation, and programmable money.\u000d\u000aThis is the world African founders are now building in. And it is a world for which\u000d\u000amost of them are unprepared; not for lack of intelligence or ambition, but because\u000d\u000anobody has yet written, in plain language and from inside the policy rooms, what it\u000d\u000aactually takes to build, scale, and survive in this environment.\u000d\u000a\u2014 15 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe existing literature, where it exists at all, is one of three things. It is academic;\u000d\u000athorough, exhaustive, and written for other academics. It is legal; accurate,\u000d\u000aconservative, and written for other lawyers. Or it is foreign; drawn from European or\u000d\u000aAmerican frameworks that map only imperfectly onto the institutional realities of\u000d\u000aAfrican regulation.\u000d\u000aNone of it is written by someone who has sat in the working groups where Nigerian\u000d\u000ablockchain policy actually gets made, built the infrastructure that those policies seek to\u000d\u000agovern, and advised the founders who must operate within them, all at the same time.\u000d\u000aThat is the gap this book seeks to fill.\u000d\u000aWhat This Book Is, and What It Is Not\u000d\u000aThis is a handbook, not a treatise. It is written to be read by busy people who have\u000d\u000aneither the time nor the inclination to consume hundreds of pages of regulatory\u000d\u000atheory. Every chapter is designed to leave the reader with something they can act on; a\u000d\u000aframework, a checklist, a decision tree, a relationship map, or a way of thinking that\u000d\u000athey did not have before they opened the book.\u000d\u000aIt is not legal advice. It is not investment advice. It is not a substitute for engaging\u000d\u000aqualified counsel, licensed compliance professionals, or appropriate regulators at the\u000d\u000aright stages of a business's life. What it is, and what it aspires to be, is a practitioner's\u000d\u000aguide written by a practitioner, for practitioners. It is the book I wish someone had\u000d\u000ahanded me ten years ago when I first began trying to navigate the intersection of\u000d\u000atechnology, policy, virtual assets, and finance in Nigeria.\u000d\u000aIt is, above all, a book about a particular kind of skill: the skill of building a business in\u000d\u000aa regulated environment without being broken by that environment, and without\u000d\u000aabandoning the conviction that what one is building is genuinely worth building.\u000d\u000aA Word About the Region\u000d\u000aAlthough this book is written from the vantage point of Nigeria, and though Nigerian\u000d\u000aregulatory frameworks, institutions, and case studies appear throughout, its\u000d\u000aapplicability is regional. The patterns of regulatory development across West and East\u000d\u000aAfrica share more in common than they differ. The institutional logics that govern\u000d\u000a\u2014 16 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000ahow the Central Bank of Nigeria approaches stablecoin oversight are recognisable in\u000d\u000athe approaches of the Bank of Ghana, the Central Bank of Kenya, and the Bank of\u000d\u000aTanzania. The questions that the Nigerian Securities and Exchange Commission is\u000d\u000aasking about virtual asset service providers are the same questions being asked, in\u000d\u000aslightly different forms, by the Capital Markets Authority in Nairobi and the Securities\u000d\u000aCommission of Mauritius.\u000d\u000aThis book, therefore, is written for a Pan-African audience. Where Nigerian specifics\u000d\u000aappear, they are intended as a detailed case study from which broader regional\u000d\u000aprinciples can be drawn. Dedicated chapters address Ghana, Kenya, and the emerging\u000d\u000aframeworks of the AfCFTA digital trade protocols. And throughout, the underlying\u000d\u000alogic is one of regional applicability, because the future of African finance will be a\u000d\u000aregional future, and the founders who succeed in it will be those who can navigate not\u000d\u000aone regulatory environment, but several.\u000d\u000aMy Position, and Why It Matters\u000d\u000aI write this book from a particular vantage point, and the reader is owed an account of\u000d\u000awhat that vantage point is, and what its limitations are.\u000d\u000aI currently serve as Chairman of the Federal Government of Nigeria's National\u000d\u000aBlockchain Policy Implementation Steering Committee under the National\u000d\u000aInformation Technology Development Agency (NITDA). I sit on the Blockchain and\u000d\u000aVirtual Asset Working Group of the Securities and Exchange Commission of Nigeria,\u000d\u000ahaving served in the Fintech Roadmap Committee of the Nigeria Capital Market in\u000d\u000a2019-2020. I have contributed to knowledge-sharing sessions and consultations across\u000d\u000athe Central Bank of Nigeria, the National Insurance Commission, the Nigeria Deposit\u000d\u000aInsurance Corporation, and the Nigerian Fintech Association, where I currently serve\u000d\u000aas a domain leader. I founded and continue to coordinate the Blockchain Nigeria User\u000d\u000aGroup, which today brings together over twenty-five thousand members of this\u000d\u000acountry's blockchain community.\u000d\u000aI have also built things. I have served as Regional Director for Africa at Paxful, the\u000d\u000apeer-to-peer Bitcoin marketplace that, at its peak, processed billions of dollars in\u000d\u000atransaction volume across our continent. I have advised companies, including\u000d\u000a\u2014 17 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aKinesis.money, the BANTU Blockchain Foundation, and Adaverse VC. I have worked\u000d\u000ain various capacities with multiple Web3 companies, including Binance, Celo, Solana,\u000d\u000aTezos, and the Ethereum Foundation. At some point, I operated a Bitcoin Lightning\u000d\u000aNetwork node, a lonely Bitcoin node in Nigeria at that time. I have spent over a\u000d\u000adecade writing software, designing systems, and shipping products in the same\u000d\u000aenvironment whose regulation I now help to shape.\u000d\u000aThese are not credentials offered for their own sake. They matter because this book is\u000d\u000awritten from a position that almost no one else occupies: simultaneously inside the\u000d\u000arooms where Nigerian digital asset policy is made, and inside the businesses that must\u000d\u000aoperate under those policies. Most regulatory analysts have never built a product.\u000d\u000aMost founders have never sat in a working group. The gap between these two\u000d\u000aexperiences is, in my observation, where most of the misunderstanding, mistrust, and\u000d\u000amissed opportunities in our ecosystem currently live.\u000d\u000aThis book is my attempt to bridge that gap.\u000d\u000aIts limitations are real and ought to be stated. I am not a lawyer, and where this book\u000d\u000atouches on legal questions, the reader is encouraged to consult one. I am Nigerian, and\u000d\u000amy deepest knowledge is of the Nigerian institutional environment; my treatment of\u000d\u000aGhana, Kenya, and other African jurisdictions is informed but not authoritative. And I\u000d\u000aam writing in a moment of rapid regulatory evolution. What is current at the time of\u000d\u000athis book's publication will, in some cases, have shifted by the time the reader holds it.\u000d\u000aWhere possible, I have written about underlying principles and durable patterns\u000d\u000arather than transient particulars. But the reader is asked to remember that this is a\u000d\u000aguide to navigating a moving target, and that the moving never stops.\u000d\u000aWhat I Hope This Book Will Do\u000d\u000aMy hope for this book is modest and immodest at once. The modest hope is that some\u000d\u000anumber of founders, somewhere in Africa, will read it and avoid a regulatory mistake\u000d\u000athat would have cost them their business. The immodest hope is that it will contribute,\u000d\u000ain a small way, to building the kind of institutional understanding between regulators\u000d\u000aand innovators that our continent's financial future will require.\u000d\u000a\u2014 18 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aRegulation is often spoken of as though it were the natural adversary of innovation. In\u000d\u000amy experience, there is no such thing. Good regulation is the precondition for serious\u000d\u000ainnovation; the substrate on which durable businesses are built, the framework that\u000d\u000adistinguishes the credible from the speculative, the assurance that allows institutional\u000d\u000acapital to allocate to a category at scale. The founders who understand these are the\u000d\u000afounders who will build the next generation of African financial institutions. The\u000d\u000afounders who do not will continue to find themselves on the wrong end of letters they\u000d\u000ado not understand, written by institutions whose logic remains opaque to them, in a\u000d\u000acountry whose digital financial future they could have helped to shape.\u000d\u000aI have written this book because I believe African founders, Nigerian, Ghanaian,\u000d\u000aKenyan, South African, all of them, are entirely capable of being the latter rather than\u000d\u000athe former. What has been missing is not the talent, the vision, or the ambition. What\u000d\u000ahas been missing is the guidebook.\u000d\u000aThis is that guidebook.\u000d\u000aChimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aLagos, Nigeria\u000d\u000aMay 2026\u000d\u000a\u2014 19 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aA NOTE ON HOW TO USE THIS HANDBOOK\u000d\u000aHow to Use This Book\u000d\u000aThis book is structured as both a sequential argument and a reference document. It\u000d\u000acan be read cover to cover, and the reader who does so will, I believe, come away with\u000d\u000athe most coherent overall mental model of the regulated landscape we are operating\u000d\u000ain. But it has also been designed to be read in pieces, out of order, and according to the\u000d\u000areader's immediate need.\u000d\u000aDifferent readers will use it in different ways. The following guidance is offered to\u000d\u000ahelp each reader find their fastest path to value.\u000d\u000aIf You Are a Founder Who Has Just Received a Regulatory Notice\u000d\u000aSkip directly to Chapter 19 (\"When things go wrong: responding to regulatory\u000d\u000aaction\"). Then read Chapter 16 (\"How to engage a regulator before they engage you\")\u000d\u000afor context on the response posture that gives you the best chance of a constructive\u000d\u000aoutcome. Once the immediate situation is stabilised, return to Part One and read the\u000d\u000abook sequentially.\u000d\u000aIf You Are a Founder Building a New Product\u000d\u000aStart with Parts One and Two to establish the mental model. Then move to the chapter\u000d\u000ain Part Three (Chapters 10 through 14) that most closely describes the product you are\u000d\u000abuilding, be it stablecoins, virtual asset services, tokenisation, DeFi, or AI-enabled\u000d\u000afinance. From there, Part Four provides the operational frameworks for building\u000d\u000acompliance into your product from the first sprint.\u000d\u000aIf You Are a Corporate Innovation Lead at a Bank, Telco, or Insurance Firm\u000d\u000aBegin with Chapter 2 (\"Compliance as competitive advantage\"), then read Part Two in\u000d\u000afull to develop a clear map of the regulatory landscape and the institutions that govern\u000d\u000ayour initiative. Chapter 17 (\"Using the innovation sandbox as a launch strategy\") and\u000d\u000aChapter 18 (\"Compliance-first product architecture\") will be particularly relevant. Use\u000d\u000a\u2014 20 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000athe book as a shared reference document with your legal, compliance, and product\u000d\u000ateams.\u000d\u000aIf You Are an Advisor, Consultant, or Board Member\u000d\u000aRead Part Five first. The framework for navigating regulations that don't yet exist\u000d\u000a(Chapter 22) is the most strategically valuable chapter in the book for advisors. Then\u000d\u000aread Parts One and Two for the institutional context, and use Parts Three and Four as\u000d\u000atopic-specific reference material when client situations require.\u000d\u000aIf You Are a Regulator, Policymaker, or Public-Sector Reader\u000d\u000aThis book has been written with regulators in mind as much as founders. The reader\u000d\u000afrom the public sector is encouraged to read Part One for an articulation of how the\u000d\u000aregulated community perceives and responds to regulation, and Chapter 5 (\"How\u000d\u000aregulation actually gets made in Nigeria\") for a candid account of the policy formation\u000d\u000aprocess as experienced from the outside. The book is offered, in part, as a contribution\u000d\u000ato the institutional dialogue between regulators and innovators that all of our work\u000d\u000aultimately depends on.\u000d\u000aOn the Chapter Tags\u000d\u000aEach chapter in the Table of Contents carries one or more thematic tags, designed to\u000d\u000ahelp the reader navigate by need:\u000d\u000aINSIDER: chapters drawing on direct experience inside policy formation processes\u000d\u000aTOOLKIT: chapters containing checklists, templates, or frameworks for immediate\u000d\u000aapplication\u000d\u000aMYTH-BUSTING: chapters that confront and correct commonly held misconceptions\u000d\u000aSTRATEGY: chapters concerned with positioning, competitive advantage, and\u000d\u000along-term thinking\u000d\u000aREFERENCE: chapters offering structured reference material on institutions,\u000d\u000aframeworks, or product categories\u000d\u000aCORE SKILL: chapters that develop a transferable analytical capability\u000d\u000aEMERGING: chapters addressing regulatory questions that are still being formed\u000d\u000a\u2014 21 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aOn the Appendices\u000d\u000aThe four appendices at the end of the book are intended as standalone working tools.\u000d\u000aThe ninety-day regulatory readiness checklist (Appendix A) is designed to be torn out,\u000d\u000aphotocopied, or printed for the reader's wall. The product-to-regulator mapping\u000d\u000amatrix (Appendix C) is intended to be consulted at the start of every new product\u000d\u000ainitiative. The resource directory (Appendix B) and the glossary (Appendix D) are\u000d\u000areference instruments to be returned to as needed. The reader is encouraged to make\u000d\u000aliberal use of them all.\u000d\u000aOn Confidentiality\u000d\u000aMany of the case studies and examples in this book are drawn from real situations\u000d\u000ainvolving real institutions, founders, and regulators. Where naming a party would\u000d\u000aserve no instructive purpose, or where doing so would breach the confidence in\u000d\u000awhich the information was originally shared, the case has been anonymised. Where\u000d\u000ainstitutions or individuals are named, they are named with their consent or because\u000d\u000athe matter is already public record. Every effort has been made to honour the trust that\u000d\u000ahas been extended to me over the years by the founders, regulators, and institutional\u000d\u000aleaders who have shared their challenges with me. Without that trust, this book could\u000d\u000anot have been written.\u000d\u000a\u2014 22 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aPart One\u000d\u000aThe Mindset Shift\u000d\u000aRegulation Is Not Your Enemy. It Is Your Moat\u000d\u000a\u2014 23 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aIn September 2023, a colleague forwarded me a message from a founder in his network. It\u000d\u000awas a screenshot of a letter. The letterhead was unmistakable: the Securities and Exchange\u000d\u000aCommission of Nigeria. The founder, a talented product builder who had been working\u000d\u000aon a tokenised real estate platform for nearly two years, had received a formal regulatory\u000d\u000anotice requesting authorisation. His platform had been directed to cease its investment\u000d\u000apromotion activities until it could demonstrate compliance with SEC Nigeria's framework.\u000d\u000aThe message my colleague forwarded was short. It said: 'I don\u2019t know what to do. I didn\u2019t\u000d\u000aeven know I was doing something wrong.'\u000d\u000aThat sentence has stayed with me.\u000d\u000aNot because it reflects ignorance, this founder was demonstrably intelligent, driven, and\u000d\u000abuilding something genuinely valuable. It has stayed with me because it reflects a gap:\u000d\u000abetween the pace at which Nigeria\u2019s digital asset regulatory landscape has evolved, and\u000d\u000athe pace at which the information about that landscape has reached the founders who\u000d\u000aneed it most.\u000d\u000aPart One of this book exists to close that gap, starting with the most important reframe in\u000d\u000athe entire book.\u000d\u000aRegulation is not your enemy. It never was. The founders who treat it as a threat will\u000d\u000acontinue to be surprised by letters, paralysed by uncertainty, and outcompeted by the\u000d\u000afounders who treat it as a strategic asset. Part One is about becoming the second kind of\u000d\u000afounder.\u000d\u000aFour chapters. Four shifts in how you think. Everything that follows in this book, the\u000d\u000aframeworks, the checklists, the institutional maps, the product-specific guidance, rests on\u000d\u000athe foundation laid here. Read this part before you read anything else. If you are already\u000d\u000ain regulatory trouble, read Chapter One first, then come back to the beginning.\u000d\u000aLet\u2019s start with Emeka.\u000d\u000a\u2014 24 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER One\u000d\u000aThe Letter You Were Not Prepared For\u000d\u000a\u201cThe most dangerous assumption a founder can make is that silence means approval.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aEmeka had been building for twenty-two months.\u000d\u000aHe had the product. A tokenised real estate platform, Proptech LLC, built around a\u000d\u000acompelling thesis: that ordinary Nigerians should be able to own fractions of premium\u000d\u000areal estate in Abuja without needing millions of naira in savings or access to a mortgage\u000d\u000asystem that excluded most of them. The anchor asset was a twelve-storey mixed-use\u000d\u000adevelopment in Maitama. Users could buy tokens representing fractions of off-plan\u000d\u000aapartments from as little as fifty thousand naira. The token carried a proportional right to\u000d\u000arental income once the building was complete and a share of the capital appreciation at\u000d\u000asale.\u000d\u000aIt was, by any honest assessment, a good idea. The technology worked. The legal\u000d\u000aagreements had been drafted by a firm that specialised in real estate transactions. The\u000d\u000adeveloper was credible, the building was real, and the pipeline of interested buyers,\u000d\u000agathered through months of social media promotion, webinars, and referrals, was\u000d\u000agrowing steadily. Emeka had co-founders who believed in him. He had raised a small\u000d\u000around from angel investors. He was, to use the phrase he used himself when we\u000d\u000aeventually spoke, 'three months from launch.'\u000d\u000aThe letter arrived on a Tuesday morning in September.\u000d\u000aIt was from the Securities and Exchange Commission of Nigeria. It was addressed to\u000d\u000aProptech LLC. It used formal language that Emeka later described as 'reading like it was\u000d\u000awritten by someone who wanted to make sure I didn\u2019t understand it.' It informed him that\u000d\u000ahis platform appeared to be engaged in the solicitation of investments from members of\u000d\u000athe public in connection with a capital market instrument, specifically, a tokenised\u000d\u000asecurity, without the requisite registration and authorisation from the Commission. It\u000d\u000a\u2014 25 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000adirected Proptech LLC to immediately cease the promotion of the investment offering\u000d\u000apending the provision of satisfactory documentation demonstrating compliance with the\u000d\u000arelevant provisions of the Investments and Securities Act and applicable SEC rules. It gave\u000d\u000ahim twenty-one days to respond.\u000d\u000aEmeka read the letter four times.\u000d\u000aThen he called his lawyer. His lawyer read it twice and said,\u000d\u000a\u2018I think you should pause everything.\u2019\u000d\u000aThat was the full extent of the advice.\u000d\u000aWhat Emeka did not know, what almost nobody had told him, was that the moment his\u000d\u000aplatform began offering tokens that carried rights to income and capital appreciation from\u000d\u000aa real estate project to members of the public, he had crossed a line that the Nigerian\u000d\u000aregulatory framework had drawn with considerable clarity. The tokens he was selling\u000d\u000awere not utility tokens. They were not access rights to a service. They were, in every\u000d\u000ameaningful functional sense, investment securities, fractional interests in a real estate\u000d\u000aasset, offered to retail investors in exchange for money, with a reasonable expectation of\u000d\u000aprofit derived from the efforts of others.\u000d\u000aThis is the definition of a security under any framework you care to consult, Nigerian,\u000d\u000aAmerican, British, or South African. The ISA 2025, which consolidated and reinforced this\u000d\u000aposition, classifies digital assets of exactly this description as securities subject to SEC\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s full regulatory oversight. The SEC\u2019s letter was not capricious. It was not an\u000d\u000aoverreach. It was a regulator doing precisely what regulators exist to do: protecting the\u000d\u000amembers of the public who might invest their fifty thousand naira in a platform that,\u000d\u000ahowever well-intentioned, had not met the minimum standards of transparency,\u000d\u000agovernance, and financial accountability that securities regulation requires.\u000d\u000aNone of this made it easier for Emeka on that Tuesday morning.\u000d\u000a\u2014 26 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe Wrong Room\u000d\u000aThe first call Emeka made after speaking to his real estate lawyer was to a general\u000d\u000acorporate attorney he had used for his CAC registration. This lawyer, competent in his\u000d\u000afield but entirely unfamiliar with the digital asset regulatory landscape, gave Emeka\u000d\u000aadvice that very nearly ended the project permanently.\u000d\u000aThe advice had three components. First: engage a PR firm to manage any reputational\u000d\u000afallout from the SEC contact. Second: do not communicate with SEC directly without\u000d\u000aextensive legal preparation. Third: consider restructuring the tokens as \u2018utility tokens\u2019 to\u000d\u000aremove them from the securities framework.\u000d\u000aThe third piece of advice was the most damaging. The idea that you can restructure a\u000d\u000atoken to avoid securities classification by relabelling it as \u2018utility\u2019 reflects a fundamental\u000d\u000amisunderstanding of how regulators, and specifically SEC Nigeria, approach token\u000d\u000aclassification. What determines whether a token is a security is not its label. It is its\u000d\u000afunction. If a token carries rights to economic benefit from a common enterprise, it is a\u000d\u000asecurity. Full stop. Relabelling it does not change its substance. It only makes the\u000d\u000aregulatory problem worse, because it signals to the regulator that the issuer is attempting\u000d\u000ato evade rather than comply.\u000d\u000aEmeka spent four weeks and a significant sum implementing this advice. He hired a PR\u000d\u000afirm. He retained a barrister who prepared an elaborate response asserting that the tokens\u000d\u000awere utilities. He redesigned the white paper. He paused all promotion, but the pause was\u000d\u000aunstructured and communicated poorly to his pipeline of prospective investors, several of\u000d\u000awhom interpreted it as a sign of financial trouble and quietly withdrew.\u000d\u000aThe SEC response to his restructured submission was polite but unmoved. The\u000d\u000aCommission noted that the functional characteristics of the offering had not materially\u000d\u000achanged, and reiterated its original request for authorisation under the applicable\u000d\u000aframework.\u000d\u000aIt was at this point, six weeks after the original letter, with the project stalled, the angel\u000d\u000ainvestors growing anxious, and the developer beginning to ask questions, that Emeka was\u000d\u000a\u2014 27 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aconnected, through a mutual contact, to someone who had actually read the SEC\u2019s Digital\u000d\u000aAsset Rules.\u000d\u000aThe Conversation That Changed Everything\u000d\u000aI was not that person. But I know the person who was, and I have spoken at length with\u000d\u000aEmeka about what followed. The conversation that changed the trajectory of his project\u000d\u000alasted approximately ninety minutes and covered three things.\u000d\u000aFirst: a plain-language explanation of what SEC Nigeria had actually asked for, and why.\u000d\u000aThe Commission\u2019s letter was not a death sentence. It was an administrative request, one\u000d\u000athat dozens of businesses in Nigeria were navigating simultaneously through the ARIP\u000d\u000a(Accelerated Regulatory Incubation Programme) framework. The SEC was not asking\u000d\u000aEmeka to shut down. It was asking him to come in from the cold: to register, meet\u000d\u000aminimum capital requirements, implement investor protection measures, and operate\u000d\u000awithin a framework that would actually give his investors the protections they deserved.\u000d\u000aSecond: an honest assessment of what Proptech LLC\u2019s token actually was. Not a utility.\u000d\u000aNot a payment instrument. A security, specifically, a tokenised fractional interest in real\u000d\u000aestate with income and capital appreciation rights. Once Emeka accepted this\u000d\u000aclassification rather than fighting it, the path forward became clear. He needed to apply\u000d\u000afor registration as a Digital Asset Offering Platform (DAOP) with SEC Nigeria, structure\u000d\u000athe offering in compliance with investor protection requirements, and file the\u000d\u000adocumentation that the Commission had originally requested.\u000d\u000aThird: a map of the process. The ARIP application. The initial assessment filing. The legal\u000d\u000aopinion on token classification. The requirements for minimum capital, Nigerian\u000d\u000aincorporation, and local management. The timeline, realistically, three to six months for\u000d\u000agetting from where he was to a position where he could relaunch.\u000d\u000aEmeka described the ninety-minute conversation this way: \u2018It was the first\u000d\u000atime I felt like I actually understood what was happening. Not afraid of it.\u000d\u000aNot angry about it. Just clear.\u2019\u000d\u000a\u2014 28 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThat clarity, the shift from fear and confusion to understanding and agency, is the first\u000d\u000athing this book is designed to give you. Everything that follows is built on it.\u000d\u000aWhat the Letter Actually Was\u000d\u000aLet us be precise about what SEC Nigeria\u2019s letter to Proptech LLC represented, because\u000d\u000aprecision here matters for every founder reading this.\u000d\u000aIt was not a criminal charge. It was not a finding of guilt. It was not a demand that the\u000d\u000abusiness cease to exist. It was a formal administrative notice informing a market\u000d\u000aparticipant that it appeared to be conducting regulated activities without the requisite\u000d\u000aauthorisation, and requesting either authorisation or a satisfactory explanation of why\u000d\u000aauthorisation was not required.\u000d\u000aThis is standard regulatory procedure in every jurisdiction in the world. The Financial\u000d\u000aConduct Authority in the United Kingdom sends equivalent letters. The Securities and\u000d\u000aExchange Commission in the United States does the same. The difference, and it is a\u000d\u000asignificant one, is that in those jurisdictions, the founders who receive such letters have\u000d\u000atypically been advised, by lawyers and mentors who understand the regulatory\u000d\u000alandscape, to expect them. They have compliance frameworks in place. They know what\u000d\u000athe letter means and what they need to do.\u000d\u000aIn Nigeria, in 2023, when Emeka received his letter, that support infrastructure barely\u000d\u000aexisted. The ecosystem of lawyers, advisors, and consultants who truly understood the\u000d\u000aintersection of blockchain technology and Nigerian capital markets regulation was\u000d\u000avanishingly small. The body of plain-language guidance written for founders, as opposed\u000d\u000ato legal practitioners, was essentially nonexistent.\u000d\u000aThat is the gap this book exists to fill.\u000d\u000aFive Things the Letter Was Telling You\u000d\u000aIf you are a founder who has received, or is likely to receive, a regulatory notice from SEC\u000d\u000aNigeria, the CBN, the NFIU, or any other Nigerian regulatory body, here is what that\u000d\u000aletter is almost always communicating beneath its formal language:\u000d\u000a\u2014 29 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a1. We know you exist. Regulators do not send letters to businesses they are unaware of. The fact of\u000d\u000athe letter means that your platform has come to the Commission\u2019s attention, through monitoring of\u000d\u000asocial media, referrals from financial institutions, or market intelligence. This is not inherently bad\u000d\u000anews. It means you are building something visible enough to matter.\u000d\u000a2. We believe you may be conducting regulated activities. The letter will typically state that your\u000d\u000aplatform \u2018appears to be\u2019 engaged in specified activities. This is deliberately qualified language. The\u000d\u000aCommission is giving you the opportunity to demonstrate that its assessment is incorrect, or to begin\u000d\u000athe process of regularisation. It is an opening, not a verdict.\u000d\u000a3. We want you to engage, not disappear. Regulatory agencies are not primarily in the business of\u000d\u000ashutting companies down. They are in the business of bringing market participants into a framework\u000d\u000athat protects investors and maintains market integrity. A founder who responds promptly, engages\u000d\u000aconstructively, and demonstrates a genuine intention to comply is treated very differently from one\u000d\u000awho goes silent or attempts to obfuscate.\u000d\u000a4. The clock is now running. Regulatory notices come with response deadlines. Missing those\u000d\u000adeadlines, or responding with material that is clearly designed to delay rather than address the\u000d\u000asubstance of the enquiry, will escalate the matter. Time is the one resource you genuinely do not have\u000d\u000awhen a regulatory notice arrives.\u000d\u000a5. You need the right room. General corporate lawyers, real estate solicitors, and even most fintech\u000d\u000alawyers do not have the specific expertise to navigate a SEC Nigeria digital asset matter. The first and\u000d\u000amost important decision you will make after receiving a regulatory notice is who to call. Chapter\u000d\u000aSixteen of this book is entirely devoted to that question.\u000d\u000aThe Emeka Principle\u000d\u000aThe fundamental mistake Emeka made was not in building a tokenised real estate platform.\u000d\u000aThe idea was sound. The technology was functional. The market need was real. The mistake\u000d\u000awas in not knowing, months before the letter arrived, that his product would trigger\u000d\u000asecurities regulation. Had he known that, he could have structured the project compliantly\u000d\u000afrom the outset, approached SEC Nigeria proactively, used the ARIP framework as a launch\u000d\u000amechanism rather than a crisis response, and been three months ahead of where he ended\u000d\u000aup. This book is designed to ensure you have that knowledge before the letter arrives, not\u000d\u000aafter.\u000d\u000aWhere Emeka Ended Up\u000d\u000aThe arc of Emeka\u2019s story does not end with the letter. It ends, approximately nine months\u000d\u000aafter that Tuesday morning in September, with Proptech LLC having submitted its ARIP\u000d\u000a\u2014 30 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aapplication, received preliminary feedback from SEC Nigeria, restructured its offering\u000d\u000adocumentation to meet investor protection requirements, and re-engaged its development\u000d\u000apartner on a timeline that, while delayed, remained viable.\u000d\u000aThe angel investors, once briefed on the regulatory journey and its resolution, did not\u000d\u000awithdraw. Two of them, in fact, increased their commitments, not despite the regulatory\u000d\u000aprocess, but partly because of it. The platform\u2019s credibility with sophisticated investors\u000d\u000awas higher, not lower, because it could demonstrate that it had engaged with and\u000d\u000anavigated the Commission\u2019s framework.\u000d\u000aThe promotional pipeline that had paused during the crisis was rebuilt. More slowly than\u000d\u000abefore. But on a foundation that Emeka described, when I last spoke with him, as 'one that\u000d\u000aI actually trust.' He knew what he was building, inside what framework, with what\u000d\u000aprotections for his investors. He understood, for the first time, that SEC Nigeria was not\u000d\u000atrying to stop him. It was trying to make sure that when his platform eventually failed, as\u000d\u000asome percentage of all platforms do, his investors would not lose everything without\u000d\u000arecourse.\u000d\u000aThat is what regulation is. Not an obstacle. Not a tax on innovation. A framework for\u000d\u000aaccountability that makes markets function over the long term.\u000d\u000aEmeka\u2019s platform has not yet launched at the time of this writing. But it will. And when it\u000d\u000adoes, it will do so as a licensed operator in a regulated market, with every meaningful\u000d\u000acompetitive advantage that implies.\u000d\u000aWe will return to his story throughout this book.\u000d\u000aThe Question This Chapter Leaves You With\u000d\u000aBefore you read on, I want to leave you with one question. It is not rhetorical. It requires a\u000d\u000agenuine answer, written down if possible, because the answer will shape how you read\u000d\u000aeverything that follows.\u000d\u000a\u2014 31 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aIf you received a regulatory notice from SEC Nigeria tomorrow morning, do you\u000d\u000aknow what it would say, why it would say it, and what you would do in the first\u000d\u000atwenty-four hours?\u000d\u000aIf the honest answer is no, or even \u2018I\u2019m not sure\u2019, then this book is doing exactly what it is\u000d\u000adesigned to do. By the time you finish Part Four, the answer will be yes.\u000d\u000aLet\u2019s keep going.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 32 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Two\u000d\u000aCompliance as Competitive Advantage\u000d\u000a\u201cThe companies that will dominate African finance in ten years are being licensed today. Most of them\u000d\u000adon't realise it yet.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aIn 2024, SEC Nigeria\u2019s Accelerated Regulatory Incubation Programme granted its first\u000d\u000aprovisional approvals to two Nigerian digital asset exchanges: Quidax and Busha. The\u000d\u000aannouncement was greeted with modest industry attention: a paragraph in the fintech\u000d\u000apress, a few congratulatory posts on LinkedIn, and then the news cycle moved on.\u000d\u000aI believe that announcement will eventually be seen as one of the most consequential\u000d\u000amoments in Nigerian financial technology history.\u000d\u000aHere is why.\u000d\u000aThe number of crypto exchanges serving Nigerian users at that time was not two. It was\u000d\u000anot twenty. Estimates placed the number of platforms with active Nigerian user bases,\u000d\u000aincluding foreign exchanges operating without local registration, P2P platforms operating\u000d\u000ainformally, and locally built products still in development, in the hundreds. In a market of\u000d\u000athat size, with that level of competition, being one of the first two platforms to hold\u000d\u000aregulatory authorisation from the apex capital markets regulator was not merely a\u000d\u000acompliance achievement.\u000d\u000aIt was a market positioning event.\u000d\u000aWhat a Licence Actually Buys You\u000d\u000aFounders in regulated industries often experience licensing as a cost centre, an expense of\u000d\u000atime, capital, and management attention that produces nothing except the right to\u000d\u000acontinue operating. This framing is understandable. The process is demanding. The\u000d\u000acapital requirements are significant. The documentation is exhausting. And at the end of\u000d\u000ait, you hold a piece of paper that does not, by itself, generate a single naira of revenue.\u000d\u000a\u2014 33 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aBut this framing confuses the instrument with its effects. A licence from SEC Nigeria,\u000d\u000aCBN, or any credible regulatory authority is not a piece of paper. It is a signal, one that is\u000d\u000asimultaneously transmitted to every stakeholder your business depends on.\u000d\u000aTo your customers, it says: this platform has been examined by an independent authority,\u000d\u000ahas met minimum standards of financial soundness and operational integrity, and is\u000d\u000aaccountable to a regulatory body with the power to enforce its obligations. In a market\u000d\u000ascarred by exchange collapses, exit scams, and platform insolvencies, this signal is worth\u000d\u000amore than any marketing campaign you will ever run.\u000d\u000aTo institutional investors and partners, it says: we can do business with this company\u000d\u000awithout triggering our own compliance concerns. Institutional capital, the kind that takes\u000d\u000aplatforms from promising to dominant, cannot flow to unlicensed entities in regulated\u000d\u000amarkets. The licensed operator is not merely accessible to this capital. It is often the only\u000d\u000aoption.\u000d\u000aTo banks and payment processors, it says: this is a counterparty we can serve without\u000d\u000aregulatory risk. The CBN\u2019s 2023 relaxation of restrictions specifically allowed banks to\u000d\u000awork with SEC-licensed digital asset service providers. Without a licence, you are locked\u000d\u000aout of the naira banking rails. With one, the entire financial infrastructure of the country\u000d\u000abecomes available to your platform.\u000d\u000aTo talented employees, it says: this is a company with a future. The best compliance\u000d\u000aofficers, technology architects, and product managers in the Nigerian market increasingly\u000d\u000achoose employers whose regulatory standing is clear. Regulatory uncertainty is a talent\u000d\u000arepellent.\u000d\u000aAnd to your competitors, it says: the cost of entry into this market has just risen. Every\u000d\u000amonth that passes without them achieving equivalent authorisation is a month of\u000d\u000acompounding advantage for you.\u000d\u000aThe First-Mover Licence Premium\u000d\u000aIn most markets, first-mover advantage dissipates quickly as competitors copy the product. Regulatory\u000d\u000afirst-mover advantage compounds over time. A licensed operator builds institutional relationships,\u000d\u000a\u2014 34 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aregulatory trust, and operational compliance infrastructure that unlicensed competitors cannot\u000d\u000areplicate overnight. When the regulator eventually turns its attention to enforcement, and it always\u000d\u000adoes, the licensed operator is not just protected. It benefits directly, as the market contracts around it.\u000d\u000aThe Cost of Waiting\u000d\u000aThere is a version of the founder\u2019s calculation that appears rational but is actually\u000d\u000acatastrophically short-sighted: the decision to delay compliance until the regulatory\u000d\u000aenvironment \u2018settles.\u2019\u000d\u000aI hear this frequently. \u2018The rules are still changing.\u2019 \u2018We\u2019re waiting to see what the final\u000d\u000aframework looks like.\u2019 \u2018We don\u2019t want to lock ourselves into a compliance structure that\u000d\u000abecomes obsolete.\u2019 These are intelligent people making an understandable argument. And\u000d\u000athey are wrong in at least three important ways.\u000d\u000aFirst, the rules will always be changing. Regulatory evolution is not a phase that ends. It is\u000d\u000athe permanent condition of operating in a regulated industry. The CBN has revised its\u000d\u000adigital asset guidance multiple times. SEC Nigeria\u2019s Digital Asset Rules were issued in\u000d\u000a2022, amended significantly in 2024, and further amended in 2025. The founders who wait\u000d\u000afor the rules to stop moving will wait forever.\u000d\u000aSecond, early engagement with regulators during a framework\u2019s development is itself a\u000d\u000acompetitive advantage. The companies that engaged with SEC Nigeria\u2019s ARIP programme\u000d\u000ain its earliest phases helped shape its operational requirements through the feedback\u000d\u000aprocess. They understood the framework\u2019s logic before their competitors did. They built\u000d\u000arelationships with Commission staff during a period of relative goodwill. These are\u000d\u000aadvantages that late entrants cannot purchase.\u000d\u000aThird, and most practically: the cost of compliance is significantly lower when you build it\u000d\u000ain from the beginning than when you retrofit it onto an existing product. A platform\u000d\u000adesigned from day one with AML infrastructure, KYC processes, audit trails, and investor\u000d\u000aprotection mechanisms costs a fraction of what it costs to rebuild those systems into a\u000d\u000aplatform that was architected without them. Emeka\u2019s story is a painful illustration of this:\u000d\u000athe cost of restructuring his offering documentation, retraining his team, and rebuilding\u000d\u000a\u2014 35 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000ainvestor confidence was multiples of what it would have cost to build compliantly in the\u000d\u000afirst place.\u000d\u000aThe Three Levels of Compliance Advantage\u000d\u000aNot all compliance advantages are equal. The most sophisticated founders think about\u000d\u000aregulatory compliance on three distinct levels, each building on the previous:\u000d\u000aLevel 1. Defensive compliance: Meeting the minimum requirements to avoid regulatory action. This is\u000d\u000athe floor, not the ceiling. A platform that is defensively compliant has done the work required to\u000d\u000aavoid the letter Emeka received. It has registered with the appropriate authority, implemented basic\u000d\u000aAML/KYC, and filed the required reports. This is necessary but not sufficient for competitive\u000d\u000aadvantage.\u000d\u000aLevel 2. Reputational compliance: Exceeding minimum requirements in visible ways that build\u000d\u000acustomer and partner confidence. This includes voluntary disclosures beyond what is required,\u000d\u000athird-party audits published openly, proactive communication with customers about how their funds\u000d\u000aare protected, and a public compliance culture. Platforms that achieve Level 2 compliance convert it\u000d\u000ainto marketing, not by boasting about their regulatory status, but by making it visible and legible to\u000d\u000athe customers who care about it.\u000d\u000aLevel 3. Strategic compliance: Using regulatory engagement as a tool for market shaping. This is the\u000d\u000alevel at which the most sophisticated operators play. They participate in regulatory consultations.\u000d\u000aThey provide technical assistance to regulators developing new frameworks. They sit on industry\u000d\u000abodies that shape policy. They are, in effect, inside the rooms where the rules are written, ensuring\u000d\u000athat the rules that emerge are ones they can operate under, and ones that their less-engaged\u000d\u000acompetitors will struggle to meet. This is not corruption. It is legitimate, legal, and in most advanced\u000d\u000afinancial markets, expected.\u000d\u000aQuidax and Busha achieved Level 1 compliance when they obtained their ARIP approvals.\u000d\u000aThe question for every other Nigerian digital asset platform is not whether to pursue this\u000d\u000alevel; the regulatory reality of ISA 2025 has made it mandatory, but how quickly to move\u000d\u000ato Levels 2 and 3.\u000d\u000aThe Evidence from Other Markets\u000d\u000aNigeria is not the first market to go through this transition. The pattern, initial regulatory\u000d\u000auncertainty, then framework development, then enforcement, then market consolidation\u000d\u000a\u2014 36 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aaround licensed operators, is visible in the recent history of every major digital asset\u000d\u000amarket.\u000d\u000aIn the United Kingdom, the Financial Conduct Authority began requiring crypto asset\u000d\u000afirms to register under its AML/CTF regime in 2020. The registration process was\u000d\u000ademanding: more than eighty percent of applicants who entered it did not complete it\u000d\u000asuccessfully. The firms that survived and obtained authorisation did not merely continue\u000d\u000aoperating, they captured the institutional business that had been waiting on the regulatory\u000d\u000asidelines. Coinbase UK, Revolut, and a handful of others became the dominant platforms\u000d\u000afor institutional and high-net-worth customers specifically because they had\u000d\u000ademonstrated regulatory fitness.\u000d\u000aIn South Africa, the FSCA\u2019s 2023 CASP licensing regime produced a similar dynamic. The\u000d\u000aplatforms that had done the preparatory compliance work, KYC infrastructure, AML\u000d\u000aprogrammes, capital adequacy, moved through the authorisation process with relative\u000d\u000aspeed. Those that had deferred compliance scrambled and, in several cases, exited the\u000d\u000amarket.\u000d\u000aIn each of these cases, the compliant operators did not merely survive the regulatory\u000d\u000atransition. They emerged from it in a structurally stronger competitive position than they\u000d\u000ahad entered it. The regulatory process had done their competitive work for them,\u000d\u000aeliminating the least serious and least capitalised participants from the market while they\u000d\u000acontinued to serve it.\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s digital asset market will follow the same pattern. The question is only whether\u000d\u000ayou will be among the operators who emerge stronger, or among those who are\u000d\u000aeliminated.\u000d\u000aA Note on Sincerity\u000d\u000aI want to be direct about something, because this book is not designed to be a collection of\u000d\u000areassuring platitudes.\u000d\u000aCompliance as competitive advantage is not a comfortable or painless strategy. The capital\u000d\u000arequirements for SEC Nigeria VASP registration are significant, particularly for early-stage\u000d\u000a\u2014 37 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000acompanies. The documentation demands are real. The time required is measured in\u000d\u000amonths, not weeks. The process requires engaging legal counsel with genuine expertise in\u000d\u000athis specific area, which is not cheap and not always easy to find.\u000d\u000aThere will be moments, particularly in the early stages of building your compliance\u000d\u000ainfrastructure, when the cost feels disproportionate to the benefit. There will be\u000d\u000acompetitors who continue to operate without authorisation, apparently successfully,\u000d\u000awhile you invest in the compliance work they are deferring. There will be investors who\u000d\u000aquestion why you are spending capital on regulatory infrastructure rather than product\u000d\u000adevelopment.\u000d\u000aMy answer to all of these concerns is the same: look at what happened to\u000d\u000athe exchanges that ignored regulation. Then look at what happened to the\u000d\u000aones that embraced it. The evidence is not ambiguous.\u000d\u000aThe cost of compliance is real. The cost of non-compliance, measured in frozen accounts,\u000d\u000aregulatory action, reputational damage, loss of institutional partners, and in some cases\u000d\u000acriminal liability, is categorically higher. And the competitive advantage of being among\u000d\u000athe first licensed operators in a market that is going to grow significantly over the next\u000d\u000adecade is worth considerably more than the cost of achieving it.\u000d\u000aEmeka understood this, eventually. The nine months he spent navigating SEC Nigeria\u2019s\u000d\u000aframework were painful. But the platform he is building on the other side of that process\u000d\u000ais categorically more valuable, to investors, to partners, to customers, and to himself, than\u000d\u000athe one he was building before the letter arrived.\u000d\u000aHe told me once, \u2018I used to think the regulator was trying to stop me. Now I think they were\u000d\u000atrying to make me serious.\u2019\u000d\u000aThat is exactly right.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 38 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Three\u000d\u000aThe Three Myths That Get African Founders in\u000d\u000aTrouble\u000d\u000a\u201cEvery preventable regulatory crisis I have witnessed began with one of three sentences.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aIn nearly a decade of working at the intersection of blockchain technology and Nigerian\u000d\u000aregulatory policy, I have observed a remarkable consistency in the thinking that leads\u000d\u000afounders into regulatory trouble. The product categories vary. The founders are different\u000d\u000apeople, with different backgrounds and different levels of sophistication. But the\u000d\u000aunderlying errors in reasoning trace back, almost without exception, to one of three\u000d\u000afoundational myths.\u000d\u000aI call them myths rather than mistakes because they are not individual failures of\u000d\u000aattention. They are shared cultural beliefs, stories that circulate in the founder community,\u000d\u000athat contain enough surface plausibility to be convincing, and that lead, reliably, toward\u000d\u000apreventable disaster.\u000d\u000aThis chapter names them, examines them, and replaces them with the beliefs that actually\u000d\u000aserve you in this environment.\u000d\u000aMYTH 1\u000d\u000a\"We will deal with compliance later, once we have product-market fit.\"\u000d\u000aTHE TRUTH\u000d\u000aCompliance is not a phase you enter after finding product-market fit. It is a design constraint you\u000d\u000aincorporate before you write your first line of code. Products built without compliance architecture\u000d\u000acannot have it added later without fundamental restructuring, and the cost of that restructuring,\u000d\u000ameasured in time, capital, and momentum, is almost always greater than the cost of building it in\u000d\u000afrom the start.\u000d\u000a\u2014 39 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThis is the most common myth in the Nigerian tech ecosystem, and it is the one I hear\u000d\u000afrom the most intelligent founders. The reasoning sounds like engineering pragmatism:\u000d\u000abuild the thing first, prove that people want it, then worry about the regulatory overhead\u000d\u000aonce you have traction. Move fast, iterate, optimise later.\u000d\u000aThe problem is that compliance is not an overhead that can be cleanly separated from the\u000d\u000aproduct and added later. It is woven into the architecture of the product itself.\u000d\u000aConsider what building compliantly actually requires. A KYC system is not a feature you\u000d\u000abolt onto a finished product. It is a foundational requirement that determines how users\u000d\u000aare onboarded, what data you collect, how that data is stored and secured, what\u000d\u000ajurisdictions you can serve, and what transaction limits you can apply to different\u000d\u000acustomer tiers. Building a product without KYC architecture and then adding it later\u000d\u000ameans rebuilding the user onboarding flow, the data model, the storage and access\u000d\u000acontrols, the transaction monitoring system, and in many cases the front-end entirely.\u000d\u000aAn AML transaction monitoring system is not a plugin. It is a set of rules, alert thresholds,\u000d\u000ainvestigation workflows, and reporting pipelines that must be integrated into the\u000d\u000atransaction processing layer of the platform from the beginning. Adding it retroactively\u000d\u000arequires either a complete rebuild of the transaction layer or the creation of an awkward\u000d\u000aparallel system that generates false positives, misses genuine risks, and costs significantly\u000d\u000amore to operate than an integrated system would have.\u000d\u000aInvestor protection disclosures, for platforms offering tokenised securities, as Emeka was,\u000d\u000aare not marketing copy. They are legally prescribed documents that determine what you\u000d\u000acan say to potential investors, how you must say it, what risks you must disclose, and\u000d\u000awhat cooling-off periods and redemption rights you must offer. Building a promotional\u000d\u000aand sales infrastructure without these requirements baked in means rebuilding it entirely\u000d\u000aonce the regulator arrives.\u000d\u000aThe founders who build compliantly from the outset do not spend more time building.\u000d\u000aThey spend the same time building, but they build the right thing the first time.\u000d\u000aThere is a second, less often discussed cost of the \u2018compliance later\u2019 approach: regulatory\u000d\u000atrust.\u000d\u000a\u2014 40 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aRegulators have long institutional memories. When a company comes to them in the\u000d\u000aaftermath of a regulatory notice, as Emeka did, having operated without authorisation for\u000d\u000amonths or years, the initial posture of the regulatory relationship is adversarial. The\u000d\u000aburden of demonstrating good faith falls entirely on the company. The regulator\u2019s natural\u000d\u000adisposition is scepticism: if this company was not compliant when it mattered, why\u000d\u000ashould we believe its compliance commitments now?\u000d\u000aContrast this with the company that approaches the regulator proactively, through the\u000d\u000aARIP programme or its equivalent, before launching its product. That relationship begins\u000d\u000afrom a completely different starting point. The regulator\u2019s posture is facilitative rather\u000d\u000athan adversarial. The company is not defending itself; it is building something together\u000d\u000awith the regulator. The benefits of this relationship, regulatory intelligence, informal\u000d\u000aguidance, goodwill during the inevitable disputes that arise in any regulated business, are\u000d\u000asignificant and compounding.\u000d\u000aDeal with compliance first. Build product-market fit within a regulated framework. The\u000d\u000atwo are not in conflict. They are, for any serious business with a long time horizon,\u000d\u000ainseparable.\u000d\u000aMYTH 2\u000d\u000a\"Our lawyers will handle the regulatory side.\"\u000d\u000aTHE TRUTH\u000d\u000aMost lawyers, including most fintech lawyers, do not have the specialist knowledge to navigate the\u000d\u000aNigerian digital asset regulatory landscape. The intersection of blockchain technology, capital\u000d\u000amarkets law, payment systems regulation, AML/CFT compliance, and emerging global standards\u000d\u000a(FATF, BIS, MiCA) is one of the most technically demanding areas of practice that exists in Nigerian\u000d\u000alaw today. Engaging a general commercial lawyer, or even a competent fintech lawyer without\u000d\u000aspecific digital asset expertise, is not the same as having effective regulatory representation. In many\u000d\u000acases, it is worse, because it creates the illusion of protection without the substance.\u000d\u000aThis myth operates through a kind of institutional transference: the belief that engaging a\u000d\u000aprofessional means transferring responsibility to them, and that transferring responsibility\u000d\u000aconstitutes managing the risk. It does not.\u000d\u000a\u2014 41 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe legal landscape surrounding digital assets in Nigeria is genuinely complex, and it is\u000d\u000amoving faster than most practitioners can track. ISA 2025 was enacted this year. SEC\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s Digital Asset Rules were substantially amended in 2024, with further\u000d\u000aamendments effective June 2025. The CBN\u2019s guidance on digital assets and payment\u000d\u000asystems has evolved through multiple circulars. The MLPPA 2022 created new obligations\u000d\u000afor VASPs that most lawyers had not previously had to engage with. FATF\u2019s\u000d\u000aRecommendation 15 and its Travel Rule implications are not standard components of\u000d\u000aNigerian legal training.\u000d\u000aThe lawyer who handled your CAC registration does not know this landscape. The\u000d\u000aconveyancing solicitor who drafted your real estate agreements does not know it. Even\u000d\u000amany lawyers who describe themselves as \u2018fintech lawyers\u2019 are primarily familiar with\u000d\u000apayment systems licensing and e-money regulation, a different, though related, body of\u000d\u000alaw from digital asset securities regulation.\u000d\u000aThis is not a criticism of the legal profession. It is an observation about the pace of\u000d\u000aregulatory development relative to the pace of professional education. The specialists in\u000d\u000athis area, practitioners with deep fluency in both the technology and the regulatory\u000d\u000aframeworks, are rare, because the field is young and the learning curve is steep.\u000d\u000aThe practical consequence of this myth is what happened to Emeka: he engaged lawyers\u000d\u000awho were competent in their own areas and who gave him advice that was, from their\u000d\u000aperspective, reasonable, but that was based on a fundamental misunderstanding of how\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria approaches token classification. The advice made his situation worse rather\u000d\u000athan better.\u000d\u000aThere are three things a founder needs that a generalist lawyer cannot provide, but that a\u000d\u000aspecialist in this field can:\u000d\u000a1. Regulatory intelligence: Knowledge of how the regulator actually operates in practice, not just what\u000d\u000athe rules say, but how they are interpreted, how enforcement decisions are made, and what\u000d\u000aarguments are persuasive versus what arguments irritate the people reviewing your application. This\u000d\u000aknowledge comes from proximity to the regulator, which generalist lawyers do not have.\u000d\u000a2. Structural advice: The ability to advise on how to structure a product, the token design, the\u000d\u000acorporate structure, the investor rights, the terms of service in a way that meets regulatory\u000d\u000a\u2014 42 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000arequirements without compromising the product\u2019s commercial proposition. This requires\u000d\u000aunderstanding both the law and the technology at a level that generalist lawyers typically do not\u000d\u000aachieve.\u000d\u000a3. Crisis navigation: When a regulatory notice arrives, you need someone who has navigated that\u000d\u000aspecific process before. Not someone who can research it. Someone who has done it. The difference\u000d\u000ain outcome can be the difference between a three-month regulatory engagement and a three-year\u000d\u000aone.\u000d\u000aThe solution to this myth is not to distrust lawyers. It is to be rigorous about which\u000d\u000alawyers you engage for which purposes. Your CAC registration lawyer is excellent at CAC\u000d\u000aregistrations. Your real estate solicitor is excellent at real estate transactions. For digital\u000d\u000aasset regulatory matters in Nigeria, you need a practitioner who has specific,\u000d\u000ademonstrable, recent experience in that specific area. Chapter Sixteen provides detailed\u000d\u000aguidance on how to identify and evaluate such practitioners.\u000d\u000aMYTH 3\u000d\u000a\"What works in the US or EU will work here.\"\u000d\u000aTHE TRUTH\u000d\u000aThe Nigerian and broader African regulatory environment operates according to different\u000d\u000ainstitutional logics, different enforcement patterns, different relationships between formal rules and\u000d\u000ainformal practice, and different timelines than the frameworks most international references\u000d\u000adescribe. A compliance structure designed for the US or European regulatory environment will not,\u000d\u000awithout material adaptation, work in Nigeria. Worse: it may give you dangerous false confidence that\u000d\u000ayou are compliant when you are not.\u000d\u000aThis myth most commonly affects three categories of founders: Nigerians who have spent\u000d\u000asignificant time abroad and absorbed the regulatory frameworks of other markets; foreign\u000d\u000afounders or investors who are building for the Nigerian market from outside it; and local\u000d\u000afounders who, understandably, look to the more developed documentation and guidance\u000d\u000aavailable in American and European markets as a template for their compliance approach.\u000d\u000aThe error is not in learning from international frameworks. There is much to learn. The\u000d\u000aerror is in assuming that those frameworks translate directly, without significant local\u000d\u000aadaptation.\u000d\u000a\u2014 43 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aLet me give you three specific examples of where this assumption breaks down.\u000d\u000aFirst: the role of the Central Bank. In the United States, the Federal Reserve is not the\u000d\u000aprimary regulator of digital asset service providers, that role is divided between the SEC,\u000d\u000athe CFTC, FinCEN, and state-level regulators. In Nigeria, the CBN plays a far more central\u000d\u000aand active role in the overall financial regulatory landscape, and its approach to digital\u000d\u000aassets, which has shifted several times and continues to evolve, has no precise\u000d\u000ainternational equivalent. A compliance framework built on the assumption that monetary\u000d\u000aauthorities are peripheral to digital asset regulation will systematically underestimate the\u000d\u000aCBN\u2019s relevance to your business.\u000d\u000aSecond: the relationship between written rules and practical implementation. In many\u000d\u000adeveloped market contexts, the written regulatory framework is a reliable guide to how\u000d\u000athe regulator will actually behave in practice. In Nigeria, understanding the written rules\u000d\u000ais necessary but not sufficient. The practical implementation of those rules, how\u000d\u000aapplications are processed, what informal guidance is available, what the regulator\u2019s\u000d\u000aactual priorities are in a given period, is substantially shaped by institutional culture,\u000d\u000astaffing, and the ongoing policy dialogue between the regulator and the industry.\u000d\u000aNavigating this landscape effectively requires local knowledge and institutional\u000d\u000arelationships that no international compliance template can provide.\u000d\u000aThird: the timelines. An AML programme designed to meet UK FCA requirements is\u000d\u000alikely to include controls, documentation standards, and reporting frequencies that are\u000d\u000acalibrated for the UK financial system, its transaction volumes, its correspondent banking\u000d\u000ainfrastructure, its court system, and its enforcement mechanisms. The same programme,\u000d\u000aapplied in Nigeria, may be simultaneously over-engineered in some dimensions (building\u000d\u000afor risks that are not the primary concerns of Nigerian regulators) and under-engineered\u000d\u000ain others (not addressing the specific risks, P2P transaction flows, informal naira-to-crypto\u000d\u000arails, high-risk cross-border jurisdictions, that are most salient in the Nigerian context).\u000d\u000aThe right approach is to use international frameworks as a reference architecture, not a\u000d\u000atemplate. They tell you what a mature AML programme looks like. They do not tell you\u000d\u000awhat a mature AML programme looks like for a Nigerian digital asset exchange serving a\u000d\u000apredominantly mobile-first, predominantly unbanked user base, operating in a\u000d\u000a\u2014 44 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000ahigh-P2P-volume environment, under the specific oversight of the NFIU and SEC Nigeria.\u000d\u000aBuilding that requires local expertise, local relationships, and a genuine engagement with\u000d\u000athe specific regulatory environment you are operating in.\u000d\u000aThe most expensive words in the Nigerian digital asset market are: \u2018but this is\u000d\u000ahow we did it in London.\u2019\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 45 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Four\u000d\u000aHow to Read a Regulatory Document Like a\u000d\u000aStrategist\u000d\u000a\u201cThe founder who can read a regulatory circular and find the opportunity inside it is worth more to\u000d\u000atheir company than the founder who sends it to their lawyer and waits.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aSometime in the second quarter of 2022, the Securities and Exchange Commission of\u000d\u000aNigeria published a document titled \u2018New Rules on Issuance, Offering Platforms and\u000d\u000aCustody of Digital Assets.\u2019 It ran to dozens of pages. It was written in formal regulatory\u000d\u000alanguage, dense with defined terms, cross-references, and administrative requirements. It\u000d\u000awas published on the SEC\u2019s website with relatively little fanfare, and most of the founders\u000d\u000aoperating in Nigeria\u2019s digital asset space at the time either did not see it, or saw it and\u000d\u000afiled it away as something for their lawyers to review.\u000d\u000aA small number of founders read it themselves. Within it, they found something that the\u000d\u000amajority of the market had missed: a structured pathway, the ARIP framework, through\u000d\u000awhich digital asset businesses could achieve provisional regulatory approval in Nigeria\u000d\u000afor the first time. Two years later, the first companies to emerge from that pathway held\u000d\u000aprovisional licences that their competitors were still scrambling to obtain.\u000d\u000aThe difference between those two groups of founders was not intelligence. It was a skill:\u000d\u000athe ability to read a regulatory document not as a compliance burden to be delegated, but\u000d\u000aas a strategic map to be interrogated.\u000d\u000aThis chapter teaches that skill.\u000d\u000aWhy Most Founders Cannot Read Regulatory Documents\u000d\u000aRegulatory documents are written primarily for regulators, lawyers, and compliance\u000d\u000aprofessionals, people with training in how to parse formal legal language, cross-reference\u000d\u000adefinitions, and understand the structural logic of regulatory frameworks. For everyone\u000d\u000a\u2014 46 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aelse, they are genuinely difficult to read. The language is precise to the point of opacity,\u000d\u000athe structure is non-linear, and the practical implications of any given provision are often\u000d\u000aburied under layers of qualification.\u000d\u000aThis is not a conspiracy. Precision in regulatory language serves real purposes: it reduces\u000d\u000aambiguity, limits the scope for creative misinterpretation, and ensures that the framework\u000d\u000ais enforceable. The problem is that it creates a significant information asymmetry: the\u000d\u000apeople best equipped to extract strategic intelligence from regulatory documents are the\u000d\u000avery insiders, lawyers, former regulators, and institutional compliance officers, who often\u000d\u000ado not have the operator\u2019s intuition for what is commercially significant.\u000d\u000aThe goal of this chapter is not to turn you into a regulatory lawyer. It is to give you a\u000d\u000asystematic method for extracting the commercially relevant intelligence from regulatory\u000d\u000adocuments yourself, quickly, so that you can identify the opportunities and risks that\u000d\u000arequire deeper expert analysis, and so that when you do engage your lawyer, you can\u000d\u000adirect their attention to the right questions.\u000d\u000aThe Six Questions\u000d\u000aWhen a new regulatory document is published, whether it is a CBN circular, a SEC\u000d\u000aNigeria rule amendment, a NFIU compliance guideline, or an NITDA policy statement,\u000d\u000aread it with six questions in mind. Apply them in order. The answers will give you ninety\u000d\u000apercent of the strategic intelligence the document contains.\u000d\u000aQuestion One: Who Does This Apply To?\u000d\u000aThe scope provision of any regulatory document is the most important paragraph in it. It\u000d\u000atells you whether the document applies to your business at all.\u000d\u000aRegulatory documents are not universally applicable. They are targeted at specific\u000d\u000acategories of entities, specific types of activities, specific transaction sizes, or specific\u000d\u000acustomer types. The first question to answer, before reading anything else, is whether you\u000d\u000aare within the scope of the document.\u000d\u000aIn practice, this means finding and reading the definitions section carefully. Most Nigerian\u000d\u000aregulatory documents contain a \u2018Definitions\u2019 or \u2018Interpretation\u2019 section that specifies what\u000d\u000a\u2014 47 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aparticular terms mean in the context of that document. The term \u2018VASP\u2019 in the SEC\u2019s\u000d\u000aDigital Asset Rules has a specific definition. The term \u2018digital asset\u2019 under ISA 2025 has a\u000d\u000aspecific definition. The term \u2018offer to the public\u2019 under the same Act has a specific\u000d\u000adefinition that determines whether your token sale is subject to prospectus requirements.\u000d\u000aRead those definitions first. Ask: does my business, as I actually operate it, fall within\u000d\u000athese definitions? If the honest answer is yes, or even probably yes, read on with\u000d\u000amaximum attention. If the honest answer is clearly no, you still need to understand the\u000d\u000adocument (because the regulatory landscape around you shapes your market even if a\u000d\u000aspecific rule does not apply to you directly), but the urgency is lower.\u000d\u000aThe Scope Trap\u000d\u000aOne of the most common errors founders make when reading regulatory documents is applying the\u000d\u000adefinitions too narrowly. They read a rule about 'digital asset exchanges' and conclude, because\u000d\u000athey describe their platform as something other than an exchange, that the rule does not apply to\u000d\u000athem. Regulators are not bound by the labels you apply to your product. They assess what your\u000d\u000aproduct functionally does and apply the definition that fits. If your platform facilitates the trading of\u000d\u000adigital assets between buyers and sellers, you are operating an exchange regardless of what you call\u000d\u000ait. When assessing scope, always ask: what does this product actually do, as distinct from what I call\u000d\u000ait?\u000d\u000aQuestion Two: What Is the Regulator Trying to Achieve?\u000d\u000aEvery regulatory document has a stated purpose, usually in a preamble, recitals, or\u000d\u000aobjectives section, and a real purpose that can be inferred from its substantive provisions.\u000d\u000aUnderstanding both is important, but understanding the real purpose is more valuable.\u000d\u000aRegulators issue documents in response to specific problems they have identified in the\u000d\u000amarket, or in response to international standards obligations (such as FATF requirements)\u000d\u000aor political imperatives (such as consumer protection concerns elevated by high-profile\u000d\u000acollapses). The substantive provisions of a regulatory document are essentially tools\u000d\u000achosen to address those underlying concerns.\u000d\u000aWhen you understand what problem the regulator is trying to solve, you understand\u000d\u000awhat kind of compliance evidence will be persuasive. If the document is primarily\u000d\u000a\u2014 48 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000amotivated by investor protection concerns following platform insolvencies, evidence of\u000d\u000arobust custodial arrangements, segregated client funds, and insurance coverage will carry\u000d\u000amore weight with the regulator than extensive documentation of your KYC process. If the\u000d\u000adocument is motivated by AML concerns following enforcement actions against P2P\u000d\u000aplatforms, evidence of your transaction monitoring infrastructure will be more persuasive\u000d\u000athan your investor disclosure documentation.\u000d\u000aThe regulator\u2019s motivating concern is usually visible in the language of the preamble, in\u000d\u000aany accompanying press release or regulatory statement, and in the pattern of\u000d\u000aenforcement actions that preceded the document\u2019s publication. Reading a regulatory\u000d\u000adocument in isolation, without understanding the context that produced it, gives you the\u000d\u000arules without the logic. Understanding the logic makes every compliance decision easier\u000d\u000aand every regulator conversation more productive.\u000d\u000aQuestion Three: What Does This Require Me to Do?\u000d\u000aThis is the question most founders ask first. It is actually more useful as the third question,\u000d\u000aafter you have established scope and purpose, because the requirements only make sense\u000d\u000aonce you understand who they apply to and why.\u000d\u000aThe requirements section of a regulatory document will typically be structured around\u000d\u000acategories of obligation: registration requirements, capital requirements, governance\u000d\u000arequirements, operational requirements, reporting requirements, and conduct\u000d\u000arequirements. Read each category and ask: which of these apply to my business today,\u000d\u000aand which will apply as we scale?\u000d\u000aPay particular attention to:\u000d\u000a\u2022 Thresholds and triggers. Many requirements are activated by crossing a threshold, a certain\u000d\u000atransaction volume, a certain number of users, a certain amount of customer funds under\u000d\u000amanagement. Know where those thresholds are before you cross them.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Timing requirements. How much notice must be given before launching a new product? How many\u000d\u000adays to respond to a regulatory enquiry? How frequently must reports be filed? Timing violations are\u000d\u000aamong the most common, and most avoidable regulatory infractions.\u000d\u000a\u2014 49 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a\u2022 Negative obligations. What does the document prohibit? Sometimes the most commercially\u000d\u000asignificant provision is not a requirement to do something, but a prohibition on doing something you\u000d\u000awere planning. Find these early.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Transitional provisions. Most regulatory documents include transitional arrangements for businesses\u000d\u000aalready operating at the time of publication. These provisions, which specify how long existing\u000d\u000aoperators have to achieve compliance, and what they can do in the interim, are often the most\u000d\u000apractically important provisions for an operating business. They are also, routinely the most\u000d\u000aoverlooked.\u000d\u000aQuestion Four: What Is Not Addressed?\u000d\u000aThis is the question that separates strategic readers from reactive ones. Every regulatory\u000d\u000adocument has a scope, and outside that scope lies whitespace, activities, products, and\u000d\u000abusiness models that the document has not yet regulated.\u000d\u000aWhitespace is not a permanent safe harbour. Regulators regularly return to fill gaps in\u000d\u000atheir frameworks, and what is unregulated today may be regulated tomorrow. But\u000d\u000awhitespace represents a window: a period during which a business can operate, learn,\u000d\u000aestablish market position, and build regulatory relationships before the framework\u000d\u000acatches up with it.\u000d\u000aIdentifying whitespace requires reading the document not just for what it says, but for\u000d\u000awhat it conspicuously does not say. The SEC\u2019s 2022 Digital Asset Rules addressed the\u000d\u000aoffering, trading, and custody of digital assets with considerable specificity. They said\u000d\u000arelatively little about DeFi protocols. They did not address DAO governance structures.\u000d\u000aThey were silent on the specific treatment of yield-generating products. These gaps were\u000d\u000anot permanent; subsequent amendments began to address them, but they represented an\u000d\u000aoperating window that sophisticated founders used deliberately.\u000d\u000aThe caveat is important: operating in regulatory whitespace requires ongoing monitoring\u000d\u000aand a genuine commitment to proactive compliance when the gap closes. The founders\u000d\u000awho use whitespace strategically are the ones who are already engaging with the\u000d\u000aregulator on the forthcoming framework while operating in the gap, not the ones who are\u000d\u000ahoping the gap will never close.\u000d\u000aQuestion Five: What Is the Enforcement Mechanism?\u000d\u000a\u2014 50 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aA regulatory requirement without an enforcement mechanism is a recommendation. A\u000d\u000arequirement with a clear enforcement mechanism is a constraint. Knowing which is which\u000d\u000adetermines how urgently you need to act.\u000d\u000aMost Nigerian regulatory documents specify penalties for non-compliance, fines,\u000d\u000asuspension of licence, revocation, criminal prosecution in the most serious cases. The\u000d\u000aNTAA 2025 introduced substantial penalty provisions for VASPs. The MLPPA 2022 carries\u000d\u000acriminal liability. The ISA 2025 provisions on unlicensed securities offerings carry\u000d\u000asignificant consequences.\u000d\u000aBut the formal penalty is only part of the enforcement picture. The practical enforcement\u000d\u000acapacity of the regulator, their ability to identify violations and impose consequences, is\u000d\u000aalso relevant. A regulator with limited supervisory resources may issue rules that are\u000d\u000aformally binding but practically under-enforced in the near term. A regulator with strong\u000d\u000aenforcement capacity and active market monitoring is a different proposition entirely.\u000d\u000aI am not suggesting that founders should calibrate their compliance to the regulator\u2019s\u000d\u000aenforcement capacity. I am suggesting that understanding enforcement mechanisms and\u000d\u000acapacity helps you prioritise: which compliance obligations require immediate action, and\u000d\u000awhich can be implemented over a reasonable timeline without material risk.\u000d\u000aQuestion Six: Where Is the Opportunity?\u000d\u000aThis is the question that justifies reading a regulatory document yourself rather than\u000d\u000adelegating it entirely to your lawyer.\u000d\u000aYour lawyer will tell you what the document requires. They will identify the risks. They\u000d\u000awill advise you on how to achieve compliance. What they will rarely do, because it is not\u000d\u000atheir role, is tell you how the document creates commercial opportunities that your\u000d\u000acompetitors are missing.\u000d\u000aEvery significant regulatory document creates opportunities for the founders who read it\u000d\u000acarefully. Some of those opportunities are direct: the ARIP framework in the SEC\u2019s 2022\u000d\u000arules created a direct pathway to provisional licensing that the first applicants exploited\u000d\u000adecisively. The ISA 2025\u2019s recognition of tokenised securities as a regulated asset class\u000d\u000a\u2014 51 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000acreates a direct opportunity for RWA tokenisation businesses that are now operating in a\u000d\u000aframework of legal clarity that did not exist two years ago.\u000d\u000aSome opportunities are indirect: a new AML requirement that imposes significant\u000d\u000acompliance costs on existing platforms creates an opening for a well-capitalised,\u000d\u000acompliance-first new entrant to position itself as the trusted alternative. A new consumer\u000d\u000aprotection framework that requires platforms to publish risk disclosures creates an\u000d\u000aopportunity for the platform whose disclosures are most clear and honest to differentiate\u000d\u000aitself on trust.\u000d\u000aAnd some opportunities are temporal: a transitional provision that gives existing\u000d\u000aoperators twelve months to achieve compliance gives a new entrant who launches\u000d\u000aalready-compliant a twelve-month window of regulatory advantage before its incumbent\u000d\u000acompetitors have caught up.\u000d\u000aPutting It Together: A Worked Example\u000d\u000aLet me apply the six questions to a real document: the SEC Nigeria Circular on the\u000d\u000aAccelerated Regulatory Incubation Programme (ARIP), published in 2022.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Who does this apply to? Entities operating digital asset exchange, offering, custodian, or intermediary\u000d\u000aplatforms in Nigeria, or targeting Nigerian investors. Any company facilitating the trading, offering, or\u000d\u000asafekeeping of digital assets for Nigerian users.\u000d\u000a\u2022 What is the regulator trying to achieve? To bring an already-operating, largely unregulated digital\u000d\u000aasset industry within the supervisory perimeter of SEC Nigeria, while managing the transition in a way\u000d\u000athat does not immediately shut down the market. The ARIP reflects an acknowledgement that\u000d\u000aoutright prohibition is not viable; the goal is regulated inclusion.\u000d\u000a\u2022 What does it require me to do? Submit an initial assessment form and draft white paper. Obtain a\u000d\u000alegal opinion on token classification. Meet minimum capital requirements. Incorporate in Nigeria with\u000d\u000alocal CEO. Apply for Approval-in-Principle. Comply with ongoing reporting and governance obligations\u000d\u000aduring the AIP period.\u000d\u000a\u2022 What is not addressed? DeFi protocols without a central operator. Pure non-custodial wallet\u000d\u000aproviders. Cross-border VASPs with no Nigerian user acquisition activities. DAO-governed platforms.\u000d\u000aThese gaps have narrowed with subsequent amendments, but represented operating windows at the\u000d\u000atime.\u000d\u000a\u2014 52 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a\u2022 What is the enforcement mechanism? SEC Nigeria has the power to pursue VASPs operating without\u000d\u000aauthorisation under the ISA. Post-2025, the NTAA penalty provisions apply. The CBN\u2019s banking\u000d\u000arestrictions on unlicensed VASPs create additional practical enforcement pressure.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Where is the opportunity? First-mover advantage in provisional licensing. Institutional investor\u000d\u000aaccess. Banking rail access under the CBN\u2019s relaxation. Talent attraction. Reputational differentiation\u000d\u000afrom the unregulated market.\u000d\u000aThe founders who applied this analysis to the 2022 ARIP circular were in the ARIP\u000d\u000aapplication queue within weeks of its publication. Their competitors spent those same\u000d\u000aweeks arguing about whether the document applied to them.\u000d\u000aReading a regulatory document like a strategist means asking not just \u2018what\u000d\u000adoes this require?\u2019 but \u2018what does this make possible?\u2019 The answer to the\u000d\u000asecond question is almost always more valuable than the answer to the first.\u000d\u000aBuilding Your Regulatory Reading Practice\u000d\u000aThe six questions are most useful when applied consistently, not just to major regulatory\u000d\u000adocuments, but to everything the relevant agencies publish. CBN circulars. SEC notices.\u000d\u000aNFIU guidelines. NITDA policy statements. International regulatory developments at\u000d\u000aFATF, BIS, and the FSB that will eventually shape Nigerian frameworks.\u000d\u000aThis is not a daily commitment. It is a weekly one. Set aside time each week to scan the\u000d\u000awebsites of the CBN, SEC Nigeria, NFIU, and NITDA for new publications. Scan the\u000d\u000apublications of GIABA and FATF for international developments. Scan the fintech and\u000d\u000adigital asset legal newsletters that track Nigerian regulatory developments (several exist\u000d\u000aand are published regularly). Build a simple log: what was published, when, who it\u000d\u000aapplies to, what it requires, and what it makes possible.\u000d\u000aOver time, this practice does something valuable that no individual document reading can\u000d\u000aachieve: it gives you a picture of the direction of regulatory travel. You begin to see not\u000d\u000ajust where the rules are today, but where they are going. And the founder who knows\u000d\u000awhere the rules are going, before they arrive, is the founder who is always three months\u000d\u000aahead of their competitors.\u000d\u000a\u2014 53 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThat is the ultimate value of reading regulatory documents like a strategist. Not\u000d\u000acompliance. Not risk avoidance. Foresight.\u000d\u000aWe will return to this theme in Part Five, where Chapter Twenty-Two is devoted entirely\u000d\u000ato the question of how to navigate regulations that do not yet exist.\u000d\u000aFor now, it is enough to leave Part One with this: the mindset shift is complete. Regulation\u000d\u000ais not your enemy. It is your moat, your map, and, for those who learn to read it well\u000d\u000aenough, your competitive weapon.\u000d\u000aPart Two gives you the terrain.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 54 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aPart Two\u000d\u000aThe Terrain\u000d\u000aWho Regulates What, Where, and Why\u000d\u000a\u2014 55 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aPart One gave you the mindset. Part Two gives you the map.\u000d\u000aBefore you can navigate the Nigerian regulatory landscape, before you can engage a\u000d\u000aregulator productively, structure a product compliantly, or identify the opportunity inside\u000d\u000aa regulatory document, you need to understand the terrain itself. Who are the institutions\u000d\u000athat govern your business? How did they come to occupy the positions they hold? How\u000d\u000adoes a regulation actually move from a concern in an official\u2019s mind to a circular on your\u000d\u000adesk? And how does the Nigerian experience fit within the broader continental and global\u000d\u000aframeworks that are increasingly shaping local rules?\u000d\u000aThese are not academic questions. Every practical decision you make as a founder, which\u000d\u000aregulator to approach first, which compliance infrastructure to build, which markets to\u000d\u000aenter, which global standards to design for, depends on having accurate answers to them.\u000d\u000aThe founders who get them wrong do not just waste time and money. They build on\u000d\u000afaulty assumptions, and the cracks eventually show.\u000d\u000aFive chapters. Five dimensions of terrain. Read them in order, because each builds on the\u000d\u000aprevious. By the end of Part Two, you will have a working map of the regulatory\u000d\u000alandscape that most Nigerian founders never acquire, and that most foreign founders\u000d\u000anever bother to build.\u000d\u000a\u2014 56 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Five\u000d\u000aHow Regulation Actually Gets Made in Nigeria\u000d\u000a\u201cUnderstanding how the rules are written is more valuable than understanding what they say. The\u000d\u000arules change. The process never does.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aThere is a version of Nigerian regulatory history that reads cleanly. A regulator identifies\u000d\u000aa problem. It drafts a framework. It consults the industry. It publishes the final rules.\u000d\u000aBusinesses comply. The market is better for it.\u000d\u000aThis version is not entirely false. It is the formal architecture. What it omits is everything\u000d\u000athat actually determines the outcome: the informal conversations that happen before any\u000d\u000adocument is drafted, the institutional rivalries that shape what gets included and what\u000d\u000agets quietly removed, the political pressures that arrive late in the process and redirect\u000d\u000aframeworks that had been years in development, and the gap between what a policy says\u000d\u000ain its final published form and what it means in practice when the people who wrote it\u000d\u000abegin to implement it.\u000d\u000aI have been inside enough of these processes, as a member of working groups at SEC\u000d\u000aNigeria and NITDA, as a contributor to industry submissions, and as someone who picks\u000d\u000aup the phone to regulators on both sides of a policy announcement, to tell you what they\u000d\u000aactually look like. This chapter does that.\u000d\u000aIt is also, I should say upfront, the chapter that will give you the most durable competitive\u000d\u000aadvantage of anything in this book. Products change. Markets shift. Regulatory\u000d\u000arequirements evolve. But the process by which those requirements are produced, and the\u000d\u000aways in which that process can be influenced by founders who understand it, is\u000d\u000aremarkably stable.\u000d\u000a\u2014 57 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe Five Stages of Regulatory Development in Nigeria\u000d\u000aBefore examining the informal dynamics that shape outcomes, it helps to understand the\u000d\u000aformal architecture. Regulatory frameworks in Nigeria move through five broadly\u000d\u000aconsistent stages, each of which creates different opportunities for founder engagement.\u000d\u000aStage 1. Internal problem identification: A regulatory concern is identified within the institution,\u000d\u000atypically by technical staff in the relevant department, sometimes triggered by a specific market event\u000d\u000a(a platform collapse, an investor complaint, a FATF assessment finding), sometimes by a broader\u000d\u000apolicy imperative from the supervising ministry. At this stage, the process is entirely internal and\u000d\u000ainvisible to the market.\u000d\u000aStage 2. Internal framework development: The regulatory institution develops a draft framework\u000d\u000athrough its own internal processes, committees, working group discussions, legal review, economic\u000d\u000aanalysis. This stage can take months or years. The outputs range from detailed rule proposals to\u000d\u000abroad policy positions. Internal politics, between departments, between agencies, between the\u000d\u000ainstitution and its supervising ministry, begin to shape the document here.\u000d\u000aStage 3. Industry consultation: Before a framework is formally published for public comment, most\u000d\u000aNigerian regulators seek informal input from selected industry practitioners, either through formal\u000d\u000aindustry bodies, working groups, or direct bilateral conversations. This stage is the highest-leverage\u000d\u000apoint for founders who want to influence the shape of a framework. The people invited into these\u000d\u000aconversations are typically those whom the regulator already trusts and has an established\u000d\u000arelationship with. Industry bodies, the Fintech Association of Nigeria (FintechNGR), BNUG, BICCON\u000d\u000aplay a critical role as aggregators of industry voice.\u000d\u000aStage 4. Public exposure: The draft framework is published for public comment for a specified period,\u000d\u000atypically thirty to ninety days. This is the stage most founders are aware of, because it is the one that\u000d\u000aproduces public announcements. It is also, in most cases, the stage at which the framework\u2019s\u000d\u000afundamental architecture has already been determined. Substantive changes following public\u000d\u000aexposure are possible but require sustained, well-argued submissions from credible industry voices.\u000d\u000aSubmissions that arrive at this stage without the relationship capital built in Stage 3 are significantly\u000d\u000aless likely to influence the outcome.\u000d\u000aStage 5. Internal vetting, political review, and finalisation: After public consultation closes, the\u000d\u000aframework returns to the regulator for internal processing. This is where the framework is most\u000d\u000avulnerable to forces that have nothing to do with its technical merits. It passes through legal review,\u000d\u000athrough senior management, through the institution\u2019s governing board, and, depending on the\u000d\u000apolicy\u2019s significance and its intersection with other institutions\u2019 mandates, through inter-agency\u000d\u000aconsultation and ministerial or presidential review. The final published document is the product of all\u000d\u000aof these filters.\u000d\u000a\u2014 58 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe Stage That Matters Most\u000d\u000aStage 3: informal industry consultation, is where regulatory outcomes are most malleable and\u000d\u000awhere founder engagement is most valuable. By Stage 4, the fundamental choices have been\u000d\u000amade. By Stage 5, the political pressures have arrived. The founders and industry bodies who\u000d\u000ashape Stage 3 conversations are the ones who shape the regulation that eventually governs their\u000d\u000amarket. This is not a matter of lobbying or improper influence. It is the legitimate, expected role of\u000d\u000athe private sector in regulatory development, and it is how the world's most sophisticated\u000d\u000aregulatory ecosystems function.\u000d\u000aThe CBN Exception: Why the Naira Changes Everything\u000d\u000aEvery regulatory framework in Nigeria operates within a broader institutional context,\u000d\u000aand the most important institution in that context is one that most digital asset founders\u000d\u000aunderestimate until they run into it.\u000d\u000aThe Central Bank of Nigeria is not simply one regulator among several. It occupies a\u000d\u000astructurally distinct position in the Nigerian regulatory architecture, and that position has\u000d\u000aprofound implications for any digital asset framework that touches the naira, which, in\u000d\u000apractice, means almost all of them.\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria, NITDA, the NFIU, NAICOM, and the NDIC are all parastatals, government\u000d\u000aagencies operating under the supervision of their respective ministries. When a policy\u000d\u000aframework emerges from any of these institutions, it operates within the normal\u000d\u000abureaucratic hierarchy: the agency reports to its minister, the minister operates within\u000d\u000acabinet, and cabinet is accountable to the Presidency.\u000d\u000aThe CBN operates differently. It reports directly to the Presidency. Its Governor holds a\u000d\u000astatus in Nigerian public life comparable to a cabinet minister. Its mandate, maintaining\u000d\u000amonetary and price stability, managing the naira, supervising the banking system, is\u000d\u000aconstitutionally grounded in a way that makes it substantially independent of the normal\u000d\u000aministerial hierarchy. When the CBN takes a position on a policy question, it does not\u000d\u000aneed ministerial cover. It can act.\u000d\u000a\u2014 59 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe day that any digital asset framework begins to intersect with how\u000d\u000athe naira moves, how it is priced, or how it is held by Nigerians, the\u000d\u000aCBN becomes a co-author of that framework, whether or not it has been\u000d\u000aformally consulted.\u000d\u000aI experienced this directly during the development of Nigeria\u2019s digital asset regulatory\u000d\u000aframework. SEC Nigeria had done considerable technical work on the VASP licensing\u000d\u000aframework. The Digital Asset Rules of 2022 were the product of months of internal\u000d\u000adevelopment and industry consultation. But the moment those rules touched anything\u000d\u000ainvolving naira on-ramps, naira off-ramps, naira-denominated stablecoin products, or the\u000d\u000ainterface between virtual assets and the banking system, the CBN\u2019s position became\u000d\u000adecisive.\u000d\u000aIt was not that the CBN blocked everything. It is that the CBN\u2019s concerns, primarily about\u000d\u000amonetary sovereignty, illicit financial flows, and the integrity of the naira, had to be\u000d\u000aaddressed before any framework could be finalised. And the CBN\u2019s concerns were not\u000d\u000aalways communicated through formal channels. They arrived through the relationships\u000d\u000abetween senior officials, through the informal consultations that happen between\u000d\u000aregulatory chiefs, and sometimes through the Presidency itself.\u000d\u000aThe practical lesson for founders is straightforward but frequently missed: if your product\u000d\u000atouches the naira, as an on-ramp, as a settlement currency, as the denomination for a\u000d\u000astablecoin, or as the mechanism through which users access your platform, you are\u000d\u000aoperating in CBN territory as well as SEC territory. A SEC licence alone does not give you\u000d\u000aa clear path to naira banking access. Understanding the CBN\u2019s concerns and addressing\u000d\u000athem in your product architecture is not optional. It is foundational.\u000d\u000aPolitical Pressure at Stage 5\u000d\u000aI want to address directly a dynamic that is rarely discussed openly but that every serious\u000d\u000aparticipant in Nigerian regulatory development understands: the role of political influence\u000d\u000ain the finalisation of regulatory frameworks.\u000d\u000a\u2014 60 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aBy Stage 5 of the process I described above, a regulatory framework has typically been\u000d\u000atechnically sound for some time. The lawyers have reviewed it. The economists have\u000d\u000astress-tested it. The industry has commented on it. And then it sits.\u000d\u000aSometimes it sits because of institutional caution, a regulator waiting for the right\u000d\u000amoment, or a senior official who wants more time to study the implications. Sometimes it\u000d\u000asits because of resource constraints, the institution does not have the capacity to process it\u000d\u000aquickly alongside its other obligations. And sometimes it sits because of something harder\u000d\u000ato name: the intersection of the framework with interests that are not fully in public view.\u000d\u000aDigital asset regulation in Nigeria has experienced all three of these. The ISA 2025, which\u000d\u000aformally resolved the question of digital assets as securities and gave SEC Nigeria its\u000d\u000aunambiguous jurisdictional mandate, took years to pass, despite the technical framework\u000d\u000ahaving been largely in place for much of that time. The delays were not primarily\u000d\u000atechnical. They were the product of the institutional and political complexity of legislation\u000d\u000athat touched the CBN\u2019s domain, that had implications for foreign exchange flows, and\u000d\u000athat required careful navigation of a legislative process with its own calendar and its own\u000d\u000apressures.\u000d\u000aThe MLPPA 2022; critical for establishing the AML framework that VASPs needed, also\u000d\u000arequired sustained political commitment to enact, partly because it imposed obligations\u000d\u000aon sectors (real estate, legal professionals, accountants) that had historically operated with\u000d\u000asignificant regulatory light.\u000d\u000aWhat This Means for Founders\u000d\u000aPolitical processes are not predictable, but they are not random either. Founders who want to\u000d\u000aunderstand why a specific framework has been delayed, or what conditions would allow it to\u000d\u000aprogress, benefit from understanding the political economy of the regulatory space they operate\u000d\u000ain: which institutions have competing interests, which ministries have intersecting jurisdiction,\u000d\u000awhich political considerations are active at a given moment. This knowledge is not easily acquired\u000d\u000afrom public sources. It comes from being present in the industry conversation, attending the\u000d\u000aconferences, participating in the industry bodies, building the relationships with regulators and\u000d\u000apolicy officials that give you access to the informal intelligence that shapes your planning.\u000d\u000a\u2014 61 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe Working Group Reality\u000d\u000aMost Nigerian regulatory frameworks are developed in part through working groups:\u000d\u000astructured multi-stakeholder consultations convened by the regulator and populated by a\u000d\u000amix of government officials, industry practitioners, legal experts, and civil society\u000d\u000arepresentatives. I have served on several of these, including at SEC Nigeria and under\u000d\u000aNITDA\u2019s blockchain policy development process.\u000d\u000aThe gap between how working groups are described in official communications and how\u000d\u000athey actually function is considerable.\u000d\u000aIn their best form, working groups are genuine collaborative development processes.\u000d\u000aTechnical staff from the regulator bring institutional knowledge and policy objectives.\u000d\u000aIndustry practitioners bring market intelligence and operational experience. The\u000d\u000acombination produces frameworks that are both technically rigorous and practically\u000d\u000aimplementable; the kind of regulation that neither side would have produced alone.\u000d\u000aIn their less effective forms, working groups become parallel processes: the regulator\u2019s\u000d\u000atechnical team develops the framework it intended to develop, the industry members\u000d\u000agenerate reports that are noted and filed, and the published framework reflects the\u000d\u000aregulator\u2019s original thinking with modest modifications around the edges. The working\u000d\u000agroup has provided procedural cover for a predetermined outcome rather than genuinely\u000d\u000ashaped it.\u000d\u000aThe founders who extract maximum value from working group participation are the ones\u000d\u000awho understand which kind of process they are in, and who calibrate their investment\u000d\u000aaccordingly. A working group where the regulator\u2019s senior leadership is actively engaged,\u000d\u000awhere technical staff are genuinely open to reconsidering their assumptions, and where\u000d\u000aindustry input is being incorporated in real time into evolving drafts is worth significant\u000d\u000ainvestment of your time and attention. A working group where the agenda is set entirely\u000d\u000aby the regulator, where industry input is collected in writing and rarely discussed, and\u000d\u000awhere the convening official is a junior secondee rather than a decision-maker, is a\u000d\u000arelationship-building opportunity, valuable, but not a policy-shaping one.\u000d\u000a\u2014 62 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe Phone Call You Should Have Made\u000d\u000aThere is one more dimension of how regulation gets made in Nigeria that I want to\u000d\u000adescribe, because it is the dimension that is most completely absent from any formal\u000d\u000adescription of the process and most completely present in the experience of practitioners\u000d\u000awho navigate it effectively.\u000d\u000aRegulatory outcomes in Nigeria are shaped significantly by personal relationships\u000d\u000abetween senior industry practitioners and senior regulatory officials. Not corrupt\u000d\u000arelationships. Not transactional ones. Professional relationships, built over years of\u000d\u000aengagement at conferences, working groups, industry consultations, and the countless\u000d\u000ainformal conversations that constitute the lifeblood of any ecosystem.\u000d\u000aWhen the CBN issued its circular in February 2021, the one that directed all banks and\u000d\u000afinancial institutions to identify persons and entities transacting in virtual assets and close\u000d\u000atheir accounts. The announcement arrived without warning to the market. The reaction\u000d\u000awas shock and confusion. Exchanges scrambled. Users panicked. Social media filled with\u000d\u000aspeculation about what the circular actually meant.\u000d\u000aI made a phone call that evening to Musa Itopa, who at the time was the CBN official who\u000d\u000ahad signed the circular and who today serves as the Director of Payment Systems. Musa\u000d\u000ahad been the keynote speaker at the first National Blockchain and Cryptocurrency\u000d\u000aConference I ever convened, in 2017. We had maintained a professional relationship and a\u000d\u000agenuine mutual respect ever since.\u000d\u000aHis response to my question about what the circular was actually trying to achieve was\u000d\u000adirect and unvarnished. He said, in essence: \u201cYou crypto people are making nonsense of\u000d\u000aour policies with your huge untraceable transactions.\u201d\u000d\u000aThat single sentence told me more about the CBN\u2019s actual position than the\u000d\u000acircular itself, any press release, or any analysis published in the weeks that\u000d\u000afollowed. It told me that this was not a philosophical opposition to digital assets.\u000d\u000a\u2014 63 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aIt was a specific, operational frustration about the inability to supervise\u000d\u000atransaction flows. It was solvable.\u000d\u000aThe path from that frustration to a workable regulatory relationship, the one that\u000d\u000aeventually produced the ARIP framework and the CBN\u2019s subsequent relaxation of\u000d\u000abanking restrictions for licensed VASPs, ran directly through addressing the concern that\u000d\u000aMusa had named. Not through lobbying. Not through legal argument. Through building\u000d\u000athe compliance infrastructure and the institutional relationships that made the digital\u000d\u000aasset industry legible to regulators who had found it opaque.\u000d\u000aThe phone call is not a luxury. It is the mechanism through which the informal\u000d\u000aintelligence that shapes regulatory outcomes is transmitted between the public and private\u000d\u000asectors. The founders who have those relationships are the ones who see regulatory\u000d\u000achanges coming before they arrive. The ones who do not are the ones who read about\u000d\u000athem in the press and scramble to respond.\u000d\u000aBuilding those relationships takes time. It cannot be done in a crisis. Part Four of this book\u000d\u000ais devoted to how to build them constructively, and how to engage regulators proactively\u000d\u000abefore you receive the letter that makes the relationship feel adversarial.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 64 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Six\u000d\u000aThe Regulator Map: CBN, SEC Nigeria, NITDA,\u000d\u000aNFIU, EFCC, NAICOM & Beyond\u000d\u000a\u201cKnowing which regulator to call is half the battle. Calling the wrong one is how regulatory crises\u000d\u000abecome regulatory disasters.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aOne of the most reliable indicators of a founder\u2019s regulatory sophistication is how they\u000d\u000adescribe who regulates their business. Unsophisticated founders name one regulator,\u000d\u000ausually SEC Nigeria or the CBN, depending on which they have most recently\u000d\u000aencountered. Moderately sophisticated founders name two. The most sophisticated\u000d\u000afounders understand that most digital asset businesses in Nigeria are operating at the\u000d\u000aintersection of at least three regulatory mandates, and that the spaces where those\u000d\u000amandates overlap, or conflict, are precisely where the most consequential compliance\u000d\u000adecisions must be made.\u000d\u000aThis chapter maps the regulatory landscape your business operates within. Not as an\u000d\u000aorganisational chart, but as a practical guide to who cares about what, why they care\u000d\u000aabout it, and what that means for you.\u000d\u000aA Note on Institutional Architecture\u000d\u000aWith one significant exception, Nigeria\u2019s regulatory agencies operate as parastatals,\u000d\u000agovernment-owned entities with their own governing boards, budgets, and technical staff,\u000d\u000abut ultimately accountable to supervising ministries and through those ministries to the\u000d\u000aexecutive branch of government. This architecture has implications for how quickly\u000d\u000aagencies can act, how much independence their decisions reflect, and how they respond to\u000d\u000apolitical direction.\u000d\u000aThe exception is the Central Bank of Nigeria, which operates under a framework of\u000d\u000astatutory independence. Its mandate and governance are set out in the CBN Act, it has its\u000d\u000aown revenue from open market operations, and its Governor has direct access to the\u000d\u000a\u2014 65 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aPresidency in a way that no other regulator does. This independence is significant in\u000d\u000apractice: the CBN can move faster, speak more directly, and apply more force than any\u000d\u000aother regulatory institution in the Nigerian financial system.\u000d\u000aUnderstanding this architecture, who is a parastatal, who reports to which ministry, who\u000d\u000ahas statutory independence, is not bureaucratic trivia. It determines the speed at which\u000d\u000aregulatory frameworks develop, the political conditions under which they change, and the\u000d\u000achannels through which founder engagement can be most effective.\u000d\u000aCBN\u000d\u000aCentral Bank of Nigeria\u000d\u000aMinistry / Oversight: Directly under the Presidency of the Federal Republic of Nigeria\u000d\u000aCore mandate: Monetary policy, financial system stability, regulation and supervision of\u000d\u000abanks and payment systems, management of the naira and foreign exchange.\u000d\u000aDigital assets role: Regulates the naira dimension of any digital asset product, on-ramps,\u000d\u000aoff-ramps, naira-denominated stablecoins, payment rails connecting digital assets to the\u000d\u000abanking system. Oversees the eNaira (Nigeria\u2019s CBDC). Issues guidance on whether banks\u000d\u000acan service digital asset businesses.\u000d\u000aFounder watch-out: Any product that moves naira to or from a digital asset ecosystem\u000d\u000arequires CBN engagement, regardless of SEC Nigeria\u2019s position. The CBN\u2019s concern is\u000d\u000amonetary sovereignty, financial stability, and AML. A SEC licence does not give you\u000d\u000abanking access, that requires demonstrating to the CBN\u2019s satisfaction that your product\u000d\u000amanages its concerns.\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aSecurities and Exchange\u000d\u000aCommission Nigeria\u000d\u000aMinistry / Oversight: Federal Ministry of Finance / Budget and National Planning\u000d\u000aCore mandate: Regulation and development of the Nigerian capital market, investor\u000d\u000aprotection, market integrity.\u000d\u000aDigital assets role: Primary regulator for digital assets as securities under ISA 2025.\u000d\u000aIssues VASP licences (DAX, DAOP, DAC, DAI) through the ARIP programme. Oversees\u000d\u000atoken offerings, digital asset exchanges, custodians, and intermediaries. Publishes the\u000d\u000aDigital Asset Rules that define the licensing framework.\u000d\u000aFounder watch-out: If your product involves the issuance, offering, trading, or custody of\u000d\u000adigital assets for Nigerian investors, you almost certainly need SEC Nigeria registration.\u000d\u000aDo not rely on the \u2018utility token\u2019 label to avoid this. SEC Nigeria assesses function, not\u000d\u000anomenclature. The ARIP process is the starting point for any VASP seeking to operate\u000d\u000alegally.\u000d\u000aNITDA\u000d\u000aNational Information\u000d\u000aTechnology Development\u000d\u000aAgency\u000d\u000aMinistry / Oversight: Federal Ministry of Communications, Innovation and Digital\u000d\u000aEconomy\u000d\u000aCore mandate: IT policy, standards, infrastructure development, and regulation of IT\u000d\u000apractices across the Nigerian economy.\u000d\u000aDigital assets role: Developed and oversees Nigeria\u2019s National Blockchain Policy (2023).\u000d\u000aIssues data protection guidance under the Nigeria Data Protection Regulation (NDPR).\u000d\u000aRelevant to blockchain-based products involving personal data.\u000d\u000aFounder watch-out: Your blockchain product\u2019s interaction with Nigerian users\u2019 personal\u000d\u000adata is subject to NITDA\u2019s NDPR framework. If you are building identity solutions,\u000d\u000ablockchain-based KYC, or data-intensive applications, NITDA is your regulator as well as\u000d\u000a\u2014 66 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aSEC and the CBN. NITDA is also your best entry point into the policy dialogue around\u000d\u000ablockchain adoption. Its working groups are more technically open than the CBN\u2019s.\u000d\u000aNFIU\u000d\u000aNigerian Financial\u000d\u000aIntelligence Unit\u000d\u000aMinistry / Oversight: Office of the National Security Adviser / operationally independent\u000d\u000aCore mandate: Receiving, analysing, and disseminating financial intelligence;\u000d\u000acoordinating Nigeria\u2019s AML/CFT framework; overseeing suspicious transaction reporting.\u000d\u000aDigital assets role: Every VASP operating in Nigeria must register with the NFIU and file\u000d\u000aSuspicious Transaction Reports (STRs) and Currency Transaction Reports (CTRs). The NFIU\u000d\u000aissues AML/CFT compliance guidelines specifically for VASPs and oversees the\u000d\u000aimplementation of Nigeria\u2019s FATF obligations.\u000d\u000aFounder watch-out: The NFIU is not optional. It is a separate registration and compliance\u000d\u000aobligation from your SEC licence. Many founders discover this late, and the NFIU\u2019s\u000d\u000aenforcement posture has hardened significantly since Nigeria\u2019s 2023 grey listing. Build\u000d\u000ayour STR and CTR filing infrastructure before you need it.\u000d\u000aEFCC\u000d\u000aEconomic and Financial\u000d\u000aCrimes Commission\u000d\u000aMinistry / Oversight: Office of the Attorney General of the Federation / Ministry of\u000d\u000aJustice\u000d\u000aCore mandate: Investigation and prosecution of economic and financial crimes, including\u000d\u000amoney laundering, advance fee fraud, and cybercrime.\u000d\u000aDigital assets role: The EFCC investigates and prosecutes criminal offences involving\u000d\u000adigital assets \u2014 including platforms used to facilitate fraud, money laundering, or\u000d\u000aunlicensed securities offerings. It has broad investigative powers including account\u000d\u000afreezing, asset seizure, and device confiscation.\u000d\u000aFounder watch-out: The EFCC is not a licensing authority and is not part of your\u000d\u000aday-to-day compliance landscape, until something goes wrong. Operating an unlicensed\u000d\u000aVASP, facilitating transactions that are later found to involve illicit funds, or failing to\u000d\u000arespond adequately to an NFIU referral can bring the EFCC to your door. AML compliance\u000d\u000ais your best protection. You will need SCUML (Special Control Unit Against Money\u000d\u000aLaundering) from EFCC. The registration is mandatory for Designated Non-Financial\u000d\u000aBusinesses and Professions (DNFBPs) in Nigeria to comply with anti-money laundering\u000d\u000alaws. It is essential for businesses handling high-value cash transactions, including real\u000d\u000aestate, law firms, VASPs, car dealers, luxury goods dealers, and hotels, to operate legally\u000d\u000aand maintain bank accounts.\u000d\u000aNAICOM\u000d\u000aNational Insurance\u000d\u000aCommission\u000d\u000aMinistry / Oversight: Federal Ministry of Finance\u000d\u000aCore mandate: Regulation and supervision of the Nigerian insurance industry.\u000d\u000aDigital assets role: Relevant to digital asset businesses that operate insurance-adjacent\u000d\u000aproducts, require fidelity bonds (as VASP licensing does), or are building parametric\u000d\u000ainsurance products on blockchain. NAICOM has participated in fintech roadmap\u000d\u000aconsultations relevant to digital products in the insurance space.\u000d\u000aFounder watch-out: Most digital asset founders will not have a primary regulatory\u000d\u000arelationship with NAICOM. However, if your product involves any form of risk transfer,\u000d\u000ainvestment guarantee, or insurance mechanism, including the fidelity bond required by\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria for VASP registration, understanding NAICOM\u2019s regulatory position is\u000d\u000anecessary.\u000d\u000aNDIC\u000d\u000aNigeria Deposit Insurance\u000d\u000aCorporation\u000d\u000aMinistry / Oversight: Federal Ministry of Finance\u000d\u000aCore mandate: Deposit insurance for bank depositors; orderly resolution of failed\u000d\u000afinancial institutions.\u000d\u000a\u2014 67 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aDigital assets role: The NDIC\u2019s relevance to digital asset businesses is indirect but\u000d\u000agrowing: as the CBN begins to allow licensed banks to offer digital asset custody and\u000d\u000asettlement services, the question of whether digital asset deposits are covered by the\u000d\u000aNDIC\u2019s deposit insurance scheme becomes consequential for consumer protection\u000d\u000aframeworks.\u000d\u000aFounder watch-out: Monitor NDIC guidance if your product involves any form of\u000d\u000adeposit-taking or fiat custody in conjunction with digital asset services. The boundaries\u000d\u000ahere are still being drawn.\u000d\u000aNCC\u000d\u000aNigerian Communications\u000d\u000aCommission\u000d\u000aMinistry / Oversight: Federal Ministry of Communications, Innovation and Digital\u000d\u000aEconomy\u000d\u000aCore mandate: Regulation of telecommunications infrastructure and services.\u000d\u000aDigital assets role: Relevant to digital asset businesses that rely on USSD, SMS, or mobile\u000d\u000anetwork infrastructure, common in financial inclusion products serving unbanked users.\u000d\u000aThe NCC\u2019s licensing framework applies to any platform that constitutes a 'value added\u000d\u000aservice' on mobile networks.\u000d\u000aFounder watch-out: If your digital asset product is delivered through mobile network\u000d\u000ainfrastructure, USSD codes, SMS-based wallets, SIM-linked accounts, you may require\u000d\u000aNCC engagement in addition to your SEC and CBN obligations. Fintech products serving\u000d\u000athe mass market frequently operate in the intersection of NCC and CBN jurisdiction.\u000d\u000aCAC\u000d\u000aCorporate Affairs\u000d\u000aCommission\u000d\u000aMinistry / Oversight: Federal Ministry of Industry, Trade and Investment\u000d\u000aCore mandate: Registration of companies, business names, and incorporated trustees.\u000d\u000aDigital assets role: Every VASP seeking SEC Nigeria registration must first be incorporated\u000d\u000aat the CAC. The CAC also maintains the Beneficial Ownership Register, a key component\u000d\u000aof Nigeria\u2019s FATF compliance reforms.\u000d\u000aFounder watch-out: CAC registration is the administrative prerequisite for everything\u000d\u000aelse. Ensure your corporate structure, share capital, shareholders, directors, is correctly\u000d\u000aconstituted for the regulatory landscape you are entering. SEC Nigeria\u2019s requirements for\u000d\u000alocal incorporation, Nigerian CEO residency, and board composition must be reflected in\u000d\u000ayour CAC registration.\u000d\u000aThe Overlap Problem \u2014 and How to Navigate It\u000d\u000aThe most challenging regulatory situations founders face are not the ones where a single\u000d\u000aregulator has clear jurisdiction. They are the ones where multiple regulators have\u000d\u000aoverlapping or conflicting jurisdiction over the same product.\u000d\u000aA stablecoin payment product in Nigeria is the clearest example. The stablecoin itself is a\u000d\u000adigital asset under ISA 2025, SEC Nigeria\u2019s territory. The naira conversion mechanism is a\u000d\u000apayment system, CBN\u2019s territory. If the stablecoin is denominated in naira, it may\u000d\u000aimplicate monetary policy, CBN\u2019s territory again. If the platform processes transactions\u000d\u000aabove the NFIU\u2019s reporting thresholds, it must file CTRs, NFIU\u2019s territory. If it uses\u000d\u000a\u2014 68 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000amobile network infrastructure for delivery, it may require NCC engagement. A single\u000d\u000aproduct, potentially five regulatory conversations.\u000d\u000aThe Multi-Regulator Strategy\u000d\u000aWhen your product sits at the intersection of multiple regulatory mandates, the instinct is often to\u000d\u000aidentify the 'primary' regulator and focus there. This is usually wrong. Each regulator has its own\u000d\u000aconcerns, its own information, and its own timeline. The SEC may grant you a licence while the CBN\u000d\u000ais still unresolved on the naira question, leaving you with authorisation to operate a platform you\u000d\u000acannot connect to the banking system. The correct approach is to map all regulatory touchpoints at\u000d\u000athe product design stage, engage all relevant regulators early, and sequence your formal\u000d\u000aapplications in the order that builds on each preceding approval rather than leaving gaps.\u000d\u000aThere is no formal inter-agency coordination mechanism that reliably resolves\u000d\u000ajurisdictional overlaps for digital asset businesses in Nigeria. The CBN and SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aconsult each other on major frameworks, but at the level of an individual business\u2019s\u000d\u000alicence application, the founder must do the coordination work. This means\u000d\u000aunderstanding each regulator\u2019s specific concerns well enough to address them proactively,\u000d\u000arather than waiting for them to surface as objections.\u000d\u000aChapter Sixteen provides a detailed framework for managing multi-regulator\u000d\u000aengagement. For now, the principle is simple: know your regulators before they know\u000d\u000ayou.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 69 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Seven\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s Digital Asset Regulatory Journey: A\u000d\u000aTimeline With Lessons\u000d\u000a\u201cHistory does not repeat itself in regulatory markets. But it rhymes so consistently that the founder who\u000d\u000aknows it rarely gets surprised.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s relationship with digital assets spans nearly a decade of policy ambiguity,\u000d\u000ainstitutional conflict, regulatory innovation, and eventual, if cautious,\u000d\u000aframework-building. It is a story that has been told in fragments: a headline about a ban\u000d\u000ahere, a press release about a new framework there, occasional academic analyses that\u000d\u000acapture the formal chronology but miss the institutional dynamics underneath it.\u000d\u000aThis chapter tells the full story, with the lessons that the public record does not contain.\u000d\u000aI should note my own position in this narrative. I have been a participant in Nigeria\u2019s\u000d\u000ablockchain ecosystem since its earliest organised days. I convened Nigeria\u2019s first national\u000d\u000ablockchain conference in 2017. I have served on the SEC Nigeria blockchain working\u000d\u000agroup and on NITDA\u2019s policy steering committee. I was in many of the rooms where the\u000d\u000adecisions described in this chapter were made, or I was on the phone with the people who\u000d\u000awere. The account that follows is as accurate as I can make it, and more complete than any\u000d\u000apublic source can provide.\u000d\u000aThe Timeline\u000d\u000a2014\u2013201\u000d\u000a6\u000d\u000aThe pre-regulatory era: Bitcoin arrives in Nigeria without a framework to receive it.\u000d\u000aLesson: The absence of regulation is not the same as prohibition. Nigeria\u2019s first crypto users,\u000d\u000alargely tech-savvy Lagos professionals, MMM Ponzi scheme \u201cinvestors\u201d, and diaspora returnees,\u000d\u000aoperated in a genuine regulatory vacuum that was simultaneously risky and productive. The\u000d\u000acommunity that formed during this period became the foundation for the ecosystem that\u000d\u000afollowed.\u000d\u000a\u2014 70 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a2017 Nigeria\u2019s first National Blockchain Conference; CBN issues its first cautionary statement on\u000d\u000avirtual currencies.\u000d\u000aLesson: The CBN\u2019s 2017 statement was not a prohibition, it was an advisory, warning members\u000d\u000aof the public about the risks of virtual currencies. The industry read it, noted it, and continued\u000d\u000abuilding. The more important development was the ecosystem formation: conferences, user\u000d\u000agroups, developer communities, and the beginning of organised industry dialogue.\u000d\u000a2018\u2013201\u000d\u000a9\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria begins internal exploration; the ecosystem grows despite CBN caution; P2P\u000d\u000avolumes increase.\u000d\u000aLesson: SEC Nigeria\u2019s internal technical work on digital asset classification began during this\u000d\u000aperiod, largely invisible to the market. Meanwhile, the industry grew substantially, with P2P\u000d\u000atrading volumes expanding as Nigerians found practical utility in crypto for cross-border\u000d\u000atransactions, inflation hedging, and remittances. The gap between the regulator\u2019s internal\u000d\u000atimeline and the market\u2019s operational reality began to widen.\u000d\u000a2020 SEC Nigeria issues a statement on digital assets, classifying them as securities and\u000d\u000aasserting regulatory oversight.\u000d\u000aLesson: This was the first formal assertion of Nigerian regulatory jurisdiction over digital assets.\u000d\u000aIt was technically significant. It established the framework that would eventually become the\u000d\u000aARIP, but practically limited, as the banking system was still accessible to crypto businesses and\u000d\u000athe formal licensing pathway did not yet exist.\u000d\u000aFebruary\u000d\u000a2021\u000d\u000aCBN Circular directing banks to close accounts of crypto businesses and individuals. The\u000d\u000amarket calls it a \u2018ban\u2019. It was not.\u000d\u000aLesson: The 2021 CBN circular is the most misunderstood regulatory action in Nigerian crypto\u000d\u000ahistory. It did not prohibit Nigerians from owning, buying, or selling cryptocurrency. It prohibited\u000d\u000abanks and financial institutions from servicing the accounts of cryptocurrency businesses and\u000d\u000aindividuals identified as transacting in virtual assets. The distinction matters enormously. The\u000d\u000asame week the circular was issued, I called the CBN official who had signed it. His words were\u000d\u000adirect: 'You crypto people are making nonsense of our policies with your huge untraceable\u000d\u000atransactions.' That sentence reveals the actual concern: operational invisibility. The CBN was not\u000d\u000aphilosophically opposed to digital assets. It was operationally frustrated by its inability to\u000d\u000asupervise transaction flows that were, from its perspective, creating channels for unmonitored\u000d\u000afinancial activity. The solution was not prohibition \u2014 it was making the industry legible. That\u000d\u000alesson took two more years to become policy.\u000d\u000a\u2014 71 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a2021\u2013202\u000d\u000a2\u000d\u000aThe grey zone: the industry becomes invisible to regulators; P2P volumes explode;\u000d\u000aFintechNGR becomes the bridge.\u000d\u000aLesson: The eighteen months following the CBN circular produced one of the most instructive\u000d\u000aepisodes in Nigerian fintech history. With banking access cut off, Nigerian crypto users did not\u000d\u000astop transacting. They moved to P2P platforms. Binance P2P, Paxful, Remitano, and local\u000d\u000aalternatives saw Nigerian volumes surge. Estimates placed Nigeria among the top five P2P\u000d\u000amarkets globally during this period. The irony was not lost on anyone paying attention: the CBN\u2019s\u000d\u000aattempt to reduce untraceable transactions had produced an explosion of them. For the industry,\u000d\u000athe immediate task was survival. The Fintech Association of Nigeria (FintechNGR), which had\u000d\u000aexisting credibility and regulatory relationships with both the CBN and SEC, became the primary\u000d\u000avehicle for industry engagement with the regulatory establishment. The BNUG and the broader\u000d\u000ablockchain ecosystem, having no formal regulatory recognition, were in a difficult position: we\u000d\u000awere, in the CBN\u2019s institutional view, essentially invisible. We were not under any framework they\u000d\u000arecognised. We were not in any conversation they were having. FintechNGR built presentations\u000d\u000athat directly addressed the CBN\u2019s stated concerns, money laundering, illicit financial flows,\u000d\u000aterrorism financing, and used those presentations to begin restoring the dialogue that the\u000d\u000acircular had effectively severed.\u000d\u000aMay 2022 SEC Nigeria issues its Digital Asset Rules, including the ARIP framework. The first formal\u000d\u000alicensing pathway is created.\u000d\u000aLesson: The 2022 Digital Asset Rules were a watershed. For the first time, Nigeria had a\u000d\u000adocumented pathway through which digital asset businesses could achieve formal regulatory\u000d\u000arecognition. The ARIP framework acknowledged the reality that an industry was already\u000d\u000aoperating and created a mechanism for bringing it within the supervisory perimeter rather than\u000d\u000asimply prohibiting it. The industry response was cautious: many businesses were reluctant to\u000d\u000aengage with a licensing process whose outcome was uncertain and whose cost was substantial.\u000d\u000aThe founders who did engage early gained an advantage they are still holding.\u000d\u000aFebruary\u000d\u000a2023\u000d\u000aNigeria placed on the FATF grey list. The industry pays a price it largely did not create.\u000d\u000aLesson: Nigeria\u2019s placement on the FATF grey list in February 2023 was the product of a\u000d\u000asystem-wide AML/CFT failure, deficiencies in oversight across the banking system, real estate\u000d\u000asector, legal profession, and a range of other industries that had nothing to do with digital\u000d\u000aassets. But crypto became a visible part of the narrative, partly because of the P2P trading\u000d\u000aexplosion that the 2021 CBN circular had unintentionally produced. The grey listing imposed real\u000d\u000acosts: enhanced due diligence requirements from international banks, increased scrutiny of\u000d\u000aNigerian transactions, a measurable decrease in foreign direct investment. For the digital asset\u000d\u000aindustry, it accelerated the urgency of the regulatory normalisation process, the CBN\u2019s relaxation\u000d\u000aand the ARIP licences were partly driven by the recognition that a structured, supervised industry\u000d\u000awas the answer to the untraceable transaction problem that had triggered the 2021 circular.\u000d\u000a\u2014 72 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a2023\u2013202\u000d\u000a4\u000d\u000aCBN relaxes banking restrictions for SEC-licensed VASPs; ARIP framework operationalises;\u000d\u000afirst provisional licences issued.\u000d\u000aLesson: The policy turn was gradual but consequential. The CBN\u2019s decision to allow banks to\u000d\u000aservice SEC-licensed VASPs was the regulatory unlock that the industry had been waiting for\u000d\u000asince 2021. The first ARIP-stage approvals, to Quidax, Busha, and cNGN Stablecoin project,\u000d\u000ademonstrated that the licensing process was real and achievable. Amended Digital Asset Rules in\u000d\u000a2024 tightened requirements and extended the framework\u2019s scope, particularly to foreign VASPs\u000d\u000atargeting Nigerian users.\u000d\u000a2025 ISA 2025 enacted \u2014 digital assets formally classified as securities. Nigeria exits FATF grey\u000d\u000alist in October.\u000d\u000aLesson: The enactment of ISA 2025 resolved the last major ambiguity in the Nigerian digital asset\u000d\u000aregulatory framework. Digital assets are securities. SEC Nigeria is the apex regulator. The\u000d\u000aframework that had been built incrementally since 2020 now had its constitutional foundation.\u000d\u000aThe FATF grey list exit in October 2025, after Nigeria implemented all 19 action items in its\u000d\u000areform plan, marked the beginning of a new chapter: a country with a functioning digital asset\u000d\u000aregulatory framework, a credible AML/CFT system, and the institutional infrastructure to attract\u000d\u000aserious international capital.\u000d\u000aThe Four Lessons That Run Through the Timeline\u000d\u000aThe decade of regulatory development summarised above contains four lessons that every\u000d\u000afounder building in this market needs to internalise.\u000d\u000aLesson One: Regulatory silence is not regulatory approval. The founders who built most\u000d\u000aconfidently in the 2018-2020 period did so in the belief that the absence of formal\u000d\u000aregulation meant the freedom to operate without it. That belief was occasionally punished,\u000d\u000aby the 2021 circular, which arrived without warning and had immediate practical\u000d\u000aconsequences. The regulators were always watching. The absence of a framework was\u000d\u000anever a signal that one was not coming.\u000d\u000aLesson Two: The stated reason for a regulatory action is rarely the complete reason.\u000d\u000aThe CBN\u2019s 2021 circular was not, at its core, about blockchain or cryptocurrency. It was\u000d\u000aabout operational visibility, the inability of the banking system\u2019s AML machinery to see\u000d\u000aand assess the transaction flows associated with digital asset trading. Understanding the\u000d\u000areal concern, rather than the formal rationale, is what allows founders to address it\u000d\u000a\u2014 73 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aeffectively. The industry\u2019s response to the circular would have been more productive,\u000d\u000afaster, if more founders had made the same kind of direct conversation I had with the\u000d\u000aCBN official that evening, and responded to the real concern rather than the stated one.\u000d\u000aLesson Three: P2P trading is not the wild west your regulator fears. But you need to prove\u000d\u000ait.\u000d\u000aThe P2P explosion of 2021-2023 was, paradoxically, one of the most important\u000d\u000ademonstrations of the inadequacy of prohibition as a regulatory strategy. Millions of\u000d\u000aNigerians continued to access digital assets through channels that were more opaque, less\u000d\u000asupervised, and more susceptible to abuse than the regulated exchange environment that\u000d\u000athe 2021 circular had effectively closed. The lesson for regulators; that bringing the\u000d\u000aindustry into a framework produces better outcomes than pushing it underground, was\u000d\u000aeventually learned. The lesson for founders is that compliance infrastructure is not a cost.\u000d\u000aIt is the argument you make to regulators who are on the fence about whether your\u000d\u000aindustry should be tolerated or embraced.\u000d\u000aLesson Four: Grey listing is a system-wide verdict, not a sector-specific one.\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s 2023 grey listing is frequently discussed in the digital asset press as though it\u000d\u000awere primarily a response to crypto-related AML failures. It was not. The digital asset sector\u000d\u000awas one dimension of a broader finding about the adequacy of Nigeria\u2019s AML/CFT framework\u000d\u000aacross all high-risk sectors. The real estate industry\u2019s exposure to illicit funds, the banking\u000d\u000asystem\u2019s gaps in beneficial ownership verification, and the legal profession\u2019s historical\u000d\u000aexemption from AML obligations all contributed to the FATF\u2019s assessment. Founders who\u000d\u000aunderstand this are better positioned to argue, correctly, that a well-supervised, licensed\u000d\u000adigital asset industry is part of the solution to Nigeria\u2019s AML challenges, not a contributor\u000d\u000ato them. That argument has been made, and it has been heard.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 74 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Eight\u000d\u000aBeyond Nigeria: Ghana, Kenya, and the\u000d\u000aPan-African Patchwork\u000d\u000a\u201cBuilding across Africa is not one regulatory conversation. It is five or six, happening simultaneously,\u000d\u000ain different languages, at different speeds, with different outcomes.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aNigerian founders who build successfully at home and then turn their attention to the\u000d\u000acontinent often make a version of the same mistake. They bring the confidence earned in\u000d\u000athe Nigerian market, the hardest, most complex, most competitive digital finance market\u000d\u000ain Africa, and they apply it to new jurisdictions with the assumption that what got them\u000d\u000ahere will get them there.\u000d\u000aSometimes it does. More often, it does not, and the gap between their assumption and the\u000d\u000areality of each new regulatory environment costs them months of misdirected effort,\u000d\u000apoorly structured products, and regulatory relationships that start from the wrong place.\u000d\u000aThis chapter is about preventing that.\u000d\u000aIts scope is selective, not comprehensive: Ghana, Kenya, and Mauritius receive the most\u000d\u000adetailed treatment because they are the markets where Nigerian founders most frequently\u000d\u000aencounter unexpected regulatory complexity. South Africa is addressed because its\u000d\u000alicensing framework is the most operationally advanced on the continent and provides\u000d\u000aboth a benchmark and a cautionary tale. The Pan-African dimension, AfCFTA, PAPSS,\u000d\u000aand the question of regulatory convergence closes the chapter, because these frameworks\u000d\u000awill reshape every individual jurisdiction\u2019s approach over the next decade.\u000d\u000aThe Competence Trap\u000d\u000a\u2014 75 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe first thing to understand about pan-African digital asset expansion is what I call the\u000d\u000acompetence trap.\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s regulatory environment is genuinely among the most demanding in Africa. Its\u000d\u000acapital requirements are high. Its licensing process is rigorous. Its multi-regulator\u000d\u000alandscape is complex. Its political dynamics are intricate. A founder who has successfully\u000d\u000anavigated all of this has developed real competence in understanding institutional logic,\u000d\u000ain building regulatory relationships, in designing products for complex compliance\u000d\u000aenvironments.\u000d\u000aThat competence is genuinely transferable at the level of principle. The skill of reading a\u000d\u000aregulatory document strategically, the practice of engaging regulators proactively, the\u000d\u000adiscipline of building compliance-first products, these work everywhere.\u000d\u000aWhat is not transferable is the specific knowledge. The CBN\u2019s relationship to the\u000d\u000aPresidency has no direct equivalent in Kenya or Ghana. The ARIP framework is specific to\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria. The informal channels through which regulatory intelligence flows in Lagos\u000d\u000aare different from those in Nairobi or Accra. The institutional culture at the Bank of Ghana\u000d\u000ais different from the institutional culture at the CBN, in ways that are invisible until you\u000d\u000aare in a meeting and suddenly wish someone had told you.\u000d\u000aThe most expensive assumption a Nigerian founder can make in a new African\u000d\u000amarket is: \u2018I know how this works.\u2019 What you know is how Nigeria works. That is\u000d\u000aa foundation, not a map.\u000d\u000aGhana\u000d\u000a\udb80\udfc9 GHANA\u000d\u000aGhana\u2019s digital asset regulatory journey has been characterised by a cautious but\u000d\u000aultimately decisive progression. For years, the Bank of Ghana issued warnings about\u000d\u000acryptocurrency risks while the Securities and Exchange Commission Ghana asserted\u000d\u000a\u2014 76 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aoversight over token offerings, creating a dual-regulator dynamic that predates Nigeria\u2019s\u000d\u000aown multi-agency complexity.\u000d\u000aThe watershed moment came in December 2025, when Ghana\u2019s Parliament passed the\u000d\u000aVirtual Asset Service Providers Act (Act 1154), which President Mahama assented to on 30\u000d\u000aDecember 2025. The Act establishes the Bank of Ghana as the primary licensing authority\u000d\u000afor VASPs, creates a newly established Virtual Assets Regulatory Office within the Bank of\u000d\u000aGhana, and mandates comprehensive licensing for exchanges, custodians, wallet\u000d\u000aproviders, and payment platforms. Virtual assets such as Bitcoin and Ethereum are now\u000d\u000alegal for trading in Ghana, they are not legal tender, but they have legitimate commercial\u000d\u000astanding.\u000d\u000aGhana\u2019s VASP Act reflects lessons drawn explicitly from the regulatory experiences of\u000d\u000aNigeria and Kenya, its AML/CFT requirements are robust, its consumer protection\u000d\u000aprovisions are detailed, and its transition provisions are structured to avoid the abrupt\u000d\u000amarket disruption that Nigeria\u2019s 2021 CBN circular produced.\u000d\u000aThree things a Nigerian founder must know about Ghana:\u000d\u000a\u2022 The Bank of Ghana is the primary VASP regulator, not a securities commission. Its institutional\u000d\u000aculture, priorities, and regulatory logic are more closely related to central banking than to capital\u000d\u000amarkets oversight. Your SEC Nigeria experience is partially relevant, but the framing of your\u000d\u000aengagement should be adjusted accordingly, you are talking to a monetary authority, not a\u000d\u000asecurities regulator. The regulator is different.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Ghana\u2019s P2P crypto market has historically been active and informal, with significant cross-border\u000d\u000aflows connecting Accra to Lagos. The regulatory formalisation will reshape this market in ways that\u000d\u000acreate both opportunities (first-mover advantage for licensed operators) and risks (compliance\u000d\u000acosts that the informal market has never borne). The market structure is different.\u000d\u000a\u2022 The personal relationships you have built with Nigerian regulators and industry figures have no\u000d\u000adirect value in Accra. You will need to build equivalent relationships from scratch, which means\u000d\u000aengagement with the Bank of Ghana, the SEC Ghana, the Financial Intelligence Centre Ghana, and\u000d\u000athe industry associations that have credibility in the Ghanaian market. The relationship capital does\u000d\u000anot transfer.\u000d\u000a\u2014 77 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aKenya\u000d\u000a\udb80\udfe7 KENYA\u000d\u000aKenya is the African jurisdiction that most frequently surprises Nigerian founders, and\u000d\u000aalmost always in the same direction: they arrive expecting a simpler, less developed\u000d\u000aregulatory environment, and they find something more mature in some dimensions than\u000d\u000awhat they left behind.\u000d\u000aKenya\u2019s VASP Act came into force in October 2025, following presidential assent and\u000d\u000aestablishing a dual-regulator model: the Central Bank of Kenya assumes oversight of\u000d\u000awallet providers, payment processors, and stablecoin issuers, while the Capital Markets\u000d\u000aAuthority oversees exchanges, investment advisers, and tokenisation platforms. The Act\u000d\u000awas partly driven by an IMF technical assistance report that had identified Kenya\u2019s\u000d\u000aregulatory gap as an AML risk, and by Kenya\u2019s own FATF grey list concerns.\u000d\u000aWhat the Act formalised was an ecosystem that had already been developing with\u000d\u000aconsiderable sophistication. Kenya\u2019s M-Pesa infrastructure, the world\u2019s most successful\u000d\u000amobile money platform, had created a digital finance culture and a regulatory muscle\u000d\u000amemory that most African markets lack. The Capital Markets Authority had been\u000d\u000aoperating a regulatory sandbox since before most Nigerian equivalents existed. The local\u000d\u000adeveloper community is large, technically capable, and internationally connected.\u000d\u000aThree things a Nigerian founder must know about Kenya:\u000d\u000a\u2022 This surprises Nigerian founders consistently. The CMA\u2019s sandbox experience, the sophistication of\u000d\u000aKenya\u2019s mobile money infrastructure, and the maturity of the local developer ecosystem mean that\u000d\u000ain specific areas, particularly mobile-first financial products and regulatory sandbox design, Kenya\u2019s\u000d\u000aexperience is a model for Nigeria, not the other way around. Approach the Kenyan market with\u000d\u000acuriosity, not superiority. Kenya may be ahead of Nigeria in some dimensions.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Stablecoin products, payment-adjacent wallets, and exchange-linked products may require\u000d\u000aengagement with both the Central Bank of Kenya and the Capital Markets Authority. This is\u000d\u000aconceptually familiar to a founder who has navigated the CBN-SEC Nigeria relationship, but the\u000d\u000aspecific institutional cultures and the informal dynamics between the two Kenyan regulators are\u000d\u000adifferent. Map this before you build. The dual-regulator structure creates the same complexity as\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s.\u000d\u000a\u2014 78 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a\u2022 M-Pesa dominance means that the baseline financial infrastructure your Nigerian product\u000d\u000acompetes against in Kenya is more sophisticated than what your Nigerian users were accustomed\u000d\u000ato. Products that win in Nigeria by being better than nothing will not automatically win in Kenya,\u000d\u000awhere the incumbent is genuinely good. Kenya\u2019s market is genuinely different from Nigeria\u2019s.\u000d\u000aMauritius\u000d\u000a\udb81\udc0c MAURITIUS\u000d\u000aMauritius is the outlier in this chapter, it is not a large consumer market in the way that\u000d\u000aNigeria, Ghana, or Kenya are. Its significance is structural: it is the most internationally\u000d\u000acredible digital asset regulatory jurisdiction on the African continent, and it is increasingly\u000d\u000aused as a regulatory base by African founders seeking international capital and\u000d\u000apartnerships.\u000d\u000aThe Financial Services Commission (FSC) Mauritius administers the Virtual Asset and\u000d\u000aInitial Token Offering Services (VAITOS) Act 2021, one of the earliest comprehensive\u000d\u000adigital asset frameworks in the world, enacted at a time when most African countries were\u000d\u000astill issuing warning statements. The FSC issues VASP licences across multiple categories\u000d\u000aincluding broker-dealer, custodian, wallet provider, and marketplace. Its AML/CFT\u000d\u000arequirements are robust and internationally oriented. In 2025, the FSC issued additional\u000d\u000aguidance on stablecoins and is developing a comprehensive stablecoin regulatory\u000d\u000aframework.\u000d\u000aThe Mauritius Strategy\u000d\u000aAn increasing number of African founders incorporate their holding companies or regional\u000d\u000aoperating entities in Mauritius to access its regulatory credibility and its double-taxation treaty\u000d\u000anetwork, while building their actual market operations in Nigeria, Ghana, or Kenya. This is a\u000d\u000alegitimate and increasingly common approach. It requires understanding both the Mauritius\u000d\u000aregulatory requirements for FSC-licensed entities and the local regulatory requirements in each\u000d\u000amarket where you operate. The FSC licence does not substitute for local VASP authorisation in\u000d\u000aNigeria or Kenya \u2014 it complements it.\u000d\u000a\u2014 79 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aSouth Africa: The Benchmark\u000d\u000a\udb81\udc60 SOUTH AFRICA\u000d\u000aSouth Africa is not a market most Nigerian founders target first. Its distance, currency,\u000d\u000aand market structure make it a later priority than West African neighbours. But its\u000d\u000aregulatory framework is the most operationally advanced on the continent and provides\u000d\u000athe clearest indication of where all African frameworks are heading.\u000d\u000aThe FSCA\u2019s CASP licensing regime, which began accepting applications in June 2023 and\u000d\u000arequired all operating entities to apply by November 2023, produced a striking\u000d\u000amarket-structuring effect: of the many platforms that had been operating in the South\u000d\u000aAfrican market, a significant proportion did not complete the authorisation process. The\u000d\u000asurvivors emerged in a structurally stronger competitive position, with institutional client\u000d\u000aaccess, banking relationships, and regulatory credibility that the unlicensed operators\u000d\u000asimply could not match.\u000d\u000aThe lesson South Africa teaches is one that Nigeria\u2019s framework is now beginning to\u000d\u000areplicate: when a credible licensing regime arrives with a hard deadline, markets contract\u000d\u000aand then reconsolidate around the licensed operators. The question for Nigerian founders\u000d\u000ais not whether this will happen here. It is whether you will be among the operators who\u000d\u000asurvive the contraction.\u000d\u000aThe Pan-African Dimension\u000d\u000aBeneath the jurisdiction-by-jurisdiction differences described above, a more structural\u000d\u000aforce is at work that will reshape all of them over the next decade.\u000d\u000aAfCFTA \u2014 the African Continental Free Trade Area, is the largest free trade agreement in\u000d\u000athe world by number of participating countries. Its digital trade protocols, still under\u000d\u000anegotiation, will establish common frameworks for cross-border digital payments, data\u000d\u000aflows, and potentially digital asset services that cut across the individual regulatory\u000d\u000aarchitectures of all 54 member states.\u000d\u000a\u2014 80 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aPAPSS \u2014 the Pan-African Payment and Settlement System, developed by Afreximbank\u000d\u000aand the African Union, is already operational in a growing number of African markets\u000d\u000aand is designed to eliminate the need for African cross-border payments to be routed\u000d\u000athrough correspondent banks outside the continent. As PAPSS matures, it will create new\u000d\u000ainfrastructure on which digital asset businesses can build cross-border products, and new\u000d\u000aregulatory questions about how those products interact with national monetary\u000d\u000aframeworks.\u000d\u000aThe direction is convergence. Not immediately, and not uniformly, individual\u000d\u000ajurisdictions will continue to develop their own frameworks at their own pace, with their\u000d\u000aown emphases and their own political pressures. But the trajectory is toward a more\u000d\u000ainterconnected, more mutually recognising pan-African regulatory architecture in which a\u000d\u000alicence in one jurisdiction carries at least some weight in others.\u000d\u000aBuilding for Convergence\u000d\u000aThe founders who will benefit most from AfCFTA digital trade convergence are the ones who are\u000d\u000abuilding products and compliance infrastructure that are designed for multiple jurisdictions from the\u000d\u000aoutset. This does not mean building for every jurisdiction simultaneously. It means making\u000d\u000aarchitecture choices, on identity, on transaction data, on AML controls, that do not need to be rebuilt\u000d\u000afor every new market. A KYC system designed to accommodate multiple African identity document\u000d\u000aformats. A transaction monitoring system that can be configured for different jurisdictional risk\u000d\u000athresholds. A reporting infrastructure that can generate filings in multiple formats. These design\u000d\u000achoices are not expensive to make early. They are very expensive to retrofit late.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 81 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Nine\u000d\u000aGlobal Standards and What They Mean for You:\u000d\u000aFATF, BIS, IMF, MiCA\u000d\u000a\u201cThe rules that govern your business in Lagos were written, in part, in Paris, Basel, Washington, and\u000d\u000aBrussels. Understanding them is not optional, it is competitive intelligence.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aOne of the most disorienting realities of operating a digital asset business in Nigeria is that\u000d\u000asome of your most consequential regulators are organisations you have never heard of,\u000d\u000aheadquartered in cities you may never visit, making decisions in processes you are never\u000d\u000ainvited to observe.\u000d\u000aThe Financial Action Task Force meets in Paris. The Bank for International Settlements is\u000d\u000ain Basel. The International Monetary Fund is in Washington. The European Parliament is\u000d\u000ain Brussels. None of these institutions has jurisdiction over your business in the traditional\u000d\u000asense. None of them can issue you a licence, freeze your account, or prosecute you for\u000d\u000anon-compliance.\u000d\u000aWhat they can do, and do, with remarkable consistency, is set the standards that your\u000d\u000aNigerian regulators will adopt, under international pressure, within a timeframe you\u000d\u000ashould be able to predict. Understanding these bodies is not a cosmopolitan affectation. It\u000d\u000ais a form of regulatory forecasting that gives you advance notice of what your domestic\u000d\u000aregulators will require, often two to three years before the local circular arrives.\u000d\u000aThis chapter introduces the four most consequential global standard-setters for Nigerian\u000d\u000adigital asset founders, explains what each actually requires, and, critically, explains how\u000d\u000ato translate their outputs into practical intelligence for your business.\u000d\u000a\u2014 82 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aFATF: The Body That Greylistings Are Made Of\u000d\u000aThe Financial Action Task Force is the most consequential international body for Nigerian\u000d\u000adigital asset founders, because it is the one with the most direct and demonstrated\u000d\u000ainfluence on Nigerian regulatory behaviour.\u000d\u000aFATF was established in 1989 to develop standards for combating money laundering. In\u000d\u000a2019, it updated its foundational Recommendation 15 to extend AML/CFT obligations to\u000d\u000avirtual assets and virtual asset service providers, a decision that reverberated through\u000d\u000aregulatory frameworks worldwide. Every VASP licensing framework in Africa, including\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s, Kenya\u2019s, Ghana\u2019s, South Africa\u2019s, and Mauritius\u2019s, is directly derived from\u000d\u000aFATF\u2019s standards.\u000d\u000aFATF operates through a system of forty Recommendations, the global standards for\u000d\u000aAML/CFT compliance, and a mutual evaluation process in which member countries and\u000d\u000aassociated regional bodies (like GIABA for West Africa) assess each other\u2019s compliance\u000d\u000awith those standards. A poor mutual evaluation result can lead to enhanced monitoring\u000d\u000a(the grey list) or, in the most serious cases, a call for counter-measures (the black list). Both\u000d\u000acarry real economic consequences: international banks apply enhanced due diligence to\u000d\u000ainstitutions in grey-listed countries, increasing transaction costs and reducing\u000d\u000acorrespondent banking access.\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s experience with the FATF grey list is described in Chapter Seven. The critical\u000d\u000apoint here is forward-looking: Nigeria was removed from the grey list in October 2025\u000d\u000aafter implementing all nineteen action items in its reform plan, achieving compliance or\u000d\u000anear-compliance with thirty-seven of FATF\u2019s forty Recommendations. That achievement\u000d\u000awas earned through painful, expensive, multi-year institutional reform across the entire\u000d\u000afinancial system.\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s grey list exit is not an end point. FATF conducts ongoing monitoring\u000d\u000aof all jurisdictions. The compliance infrastructure built during the reform\u000d\u000aprocess must now be maintained and extended. The standards themselves\u000d\u000acontinue to evolve. The 2025 FATF Targeted Update on Virtual Assets\u000d\u000a\u2014 83 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aidentified the rising criminal use of stablecoins as a major emerging risk, a\u000d\u000adevelopment that will shape regulatory guidance on stablecoins globally,\u000d\u000aincluding in Nigeria.\u000d\u000aFATF\u2019s Travel Rule is the specific FATF requirement that most directly affects VASP\u000d\u000aoperations. It requires that when a VASP transfers digital assets on behalf of a customer, it\u000d\u000amust collect, verify, and transmit specified information about the originator and\u000d\u000abeneficiary of that transfer to the counterparty VASP, effectively applying wire transfer\u000d\u000atransparency standards to virtual asset transactions.\u000d\u000aAs of 2026, Nigeria has not yet fully operationalised Travel Rule compliance for VASPs.\u000d\u000aBut the direction is clear: it is coming, and the VASPs that build Travel Rule-compatible\u000d\u000ainfrastructure before it is mandated will have a compliance advantage over those that\u000d\u000amust scramble to retrofit it.\u000d\u000aWhat FATF Means for You \u2014 Practically\u000d\u000aMonitor FATF\u2019s annual Targeted Update on Virtual Assets. It is published each June and identifies the\u000d\u000aemerging risks that regulators worldwide will be focusing on in the following twelve to eighteen\u000d\u000amonths. The 2024 update flagged DeFi and unhosted wallet risks. The 2025 update flagged\u000d\u000astablecoin misuse. These flags become Nigerian regulatory priorities within one to three years. The\u000d\u000afounder who builds stablecoin AML infrastructure in 2026 because they read the 2025 FATF update\u000d\u000ais two years ahead of the founder who waits for the CBN circular.\u000d\u000aBIS: The Central Bankers\u2019 Bank\u000d\u000aThe Bank for International Settlements is the international organisation that serves as a\u000d\u000ahub for cooperation among the world\u2019s central banks. It does not regulate businesses\u000d\u000adirectly. What it does is produce research, guidance, and policy frameworks that central\u000d\u000abanks worldwide, including the CBN, use to inform their own positions.\u000d\u000aBIS\u2019s relevance to Nigerian digital asset founders operates through two specific channels.\u000d\u000aFirst: its work on stablecoins and CBDCs directly shapes how the CBN thinks about these\u000d\u000aproducts. BIS has published extensive research on the risks of global stablecoins to\u000d\u000amonetary sovereignty, the concern that the widespread adoption of dollar-denominated\u000d\u000a\u2014 84 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aprivate stablecoins could effectively dollarise developing economies and compromise\u000d\u000acentral banks\u2019 ability to conduct monetary policy. This is the intellectual foundation of the\u000d\u000aCBN\u2019s stablecoin caution. Understanding the BIS argument does not just explain the\u000d\u000aCBN\u2019s position, it tells you what evidence would be most persuasive in a conversation\u000d\u000awith CBN officials about your stablecoin product.\u000d\u000aSecond: BIS\u2019s Innovation Hub, which operates through centres in several cities including\u000d\u000aone in Nairobi, conducts experimental work on CBDC interoperability, cross-border\u000d\u000apayment systems, and tokenised finance. The practical implications of this work will\u000d\u000aarrive in Nigerian regulation within years. The mBridge project, which explored a\u000d\u000amulti-CBDC platform across central banks, is a precursor to the kind of cross-border\u000d\u000adigital payment infrastructure that AfCFTA\u2019s digital trade protocols will eventually need\u000d\u000ato build on.\u000d\u000aThe BIS Research Habit\u000d\u000aReading BIS working papers is a genuine competitive advantage for founders in the digital finance\u000d\u000aspace. They are freely available at bis.org. The papers published two to three years ago on specific\u000d\u000atopics, stablecoin oversight, CBDC design, DeFi risks, are now the foundations of regulatory\u000d\u000aframeworks being enacted today. The papers being published today are the frameworks that will be\u000d\u000aenacted in two to three years. This is not academic reading. It is market intelligence.\u000d\u000aIMF: The Institution That Shapes the Conversation\u000d\u000aThe International Monetary Fund\u2019s influence on Nigerian digital asset regulation is less\u000d\u000adirect than FATF\u2019s but more pervasive in certain ways. The IMF does not set binding\u000d\u000astandards. What it does is conduct regular Article IV consultations with member\u000d\u000acountries, issue technical assistance reports on specific regulatory questions, and maintain\u000d\u000aa research and policy publication programme that shapes the intellectual environment in\u000d\u000awhich central bankers and finance ministers operate.\u000d\u000aThe IMF\u2019s positions on digital assets have evolved significantly over the past five years. Its\u000d\u000aearlier scepticism, expressed in recommendations to several African countries to ban or\u000d\u000aheavily restrict cryptocurrency, has given way to a more nuanced framework that\u000d\u000aacknowledges the role of digital assets in financial inclusion and cross-border payment\u000d\u000a\u2014 85 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aefficiency, while maintaining concern about AML risks, monetary stability, and consumer\u000d\u000aprotection.\u000d\u000aThe IMF\u2019s 2025 paper on digital payments in Sub-Saharan Africa explicitly notes that\u000d\u000aadequately backed stablecoins can support financial innovations and that CBDCs can\u000d\u000acomplement mobile money systems, a significant departure from earlier positions that\u000d\u000atreated all private digital currencies as primarily risks to be managed.\u000d\u000aFor Nigerian founders, the IMF\u2019s evolving position matters for two reasons. First, it\u000d\u000ashapes the intellectual environment of the CBN, whose senior staff participate in IMF\u000d\u000aconsultations, read IMF research, and are influenced by the normative frameworks the\u000d\u000aIMF promotes. Second, it influences the terms on which international capital, from\u000d\u000adevelopment finance institutions, multilateral funds, and IMF-adjacent investors, is\u000d\u000aavailable for digital finance businesses in Africa. An IMF that frames stablecoins as a\u000d\u000afinancial inclusion tool creates a more favourable fundraising environment than one that\u000d\u000aframes them as monetary sovereignty risks.\u000d\u000aMiCA: The Framework Your International Partners Already Live Under\u000d\u000aThe European Union\u2019s Markets in Crypto-Assets Regulation (MiCA) is not Nigerian law.\u000d\u000aIt will not be applied to you by the SEC or the CBN. And yet, for a growing number of\u000d\u000aNigerian digital asset founders, it is a regulatory framework you must understand,\u000d\u000abecause your international investors, partners, and counterparties already operate under\u000d\u000ait.\u000d\u000aMiCA came into full effect in December 2024, establishing the most comprehensive\u000d\u000aregulatory framework for crypto assets in any major jurisdiction. It covers the issuance of\u000d\u000aasset-referenced tokens (stablecoins pegged to assets other than a single fiat currency),\u000d\u000ae-money tokens (stablecoins pegged to a single fiat currency), and crypto asset service\u000d\u000aproviders (CASPs), requiring licensing, capital requirements, AML compliance, consumer\u000d\u000aprotection measures, and market integrity rules across all twenty-seven EU member\u000d\u000astates.\u000d\u000aMiCA matters to Nigerian founders in three specific ways.\u000d\u000a\u2014 86 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a1. European partners and investors will ask about MiCA alignment. \u2014 European venture funds\u000d\u000ainvesting in African digital finance businesses increasingly use MiCA as a reference framework for\u000d\u000aassessing the regulatory quality of potential portfolio companies. A Nigerian VASP whose AML\u000d\u000aprogramme, consumer protection policies, and operational governance are broadly aligned with\u000d\u000aMiCA standards is an easier investment for a European fund than one whose framework is entirely\u000d\u000alocal. You do not need to be MiCA-compliant. You do need to be able to explain why your standards\u000d\u000aare comparable.\u000d\u000a2. Nigerian VASPs serving EU customers may be subject to MiCA. \u2014 MiCA applies to CASPs actively\u000d\u000atargeting EU customers, regardless of where the CASP is incorporated. A Nigerian exchange that runs\u000d\u000aadvertising campaigns in European markets, maintains a European-language website, or actively\u000d\u000asolicits European customers may be within MiCA\u2019s scope. The \u2018reverse solicitation\u2019 exception, which\u000d\u000aallows EU residents to access offshore services at their own initiative, is narrow and has been actively\u000d\u000aenforced. If you have European customers, obtain legal advice on your MiCA exposure.\u000d\u000a3. MiCA\u2019s stablecoin framework will influence Nigerian stablecoin regulation. \u2014 MiCA\u2019s\u000d\u000arequirements for stablecoin issuers, full reserve backing, redemption at par, segregated custody, strict\u000d\u000aAML compliance, represent the global benchmark toward which all stablecoin regulatory frameworks\u000d\u000aare converging. The CBN\u2019s eventual stablecoin framework will not replicate MiCA in detail, but it will\u000d\u000abe influenced by it. Founders building stablecoin products now who design them to meet MiCA\u2019s\u000d\u000areserve and custody requirements are building to a standard that will serve them in any jurisdiction.\u000d\u000aReading the International Signals: A Practical Framework\u000d\u000aThe four bodies described in this chapter produce a continuous stream of publications,\u000d\u000aguidance papers, and policy statements. No founder has the time to read all of them, and\u000d\u000amost of them are not directly relevant to any specific business at any specific moment.\u000d\u000aThe following approach extracts the maximum intelligence from the minimum reading:\u000d\u000a\u2022 Read in full, every year. This is the single most important publication for Nigerian digital asset\u000d\u000afounders. It tells you what risks are on the global AML radar, and therefore what your local\u000d\u000aregulators will be focused on within twelve to thirty-six months. FATF Targeted Update on Virtual\u000d\u000aAssets (annual, June)\u000d\u000a\u2022 Skim for the sections on digital finance, CBDC, and stablecoins. One hour per quarter. Note any new\u000d\u000aframeworks or experiments that involve African central banks. BIS Quarterly Review and Innovation\u000d\u000aHub publications (quarterly)\u000d\u000a\u2022 Search for IMF publications specifically about Nigeria, West Africa, or digital finance in Sub-Saharan\u000d\u000aAfrica. These papers directly influence your domestic regulators\u2019 thinking. IMF Working Papers and\u000d\u000aTechnical Assistance Reports on Africa (irregular)\u000d\u000a\u2014 87 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a\u2022 Monitor through the European Banking Authority\u2019s publications. Focus specifically on stablecoin\u000d\u000aoversight and CASP licensing guidance, as these are most directly relevant to Nigerian product\u000d\u000aarchitecture decisions. MiCA implementation updates (ongoing through 2025-2026)\u000d\u000aOne more practice worth building: when a significant new international standard is\u000d\u000apublished, translate it into Nigerian terms immediately. Ask: which Nigerian institution\u000d\u000awill implement this? What aspect of my product does it affect? What compliance change\u000d\u000awould I need to make if Nigeria adopted this standard tomorrow? Doing this translation\u000d\u000aexercise regularly keeps you ahead of the regulatory curve rather than behind it.\u000d\u000aThe founders who build the most durable digital financial businesses in Africa will be\u000d\u000athe ones who understand that their regulators are not sovereign. They are participants\u000d\u000ain a global regulatory conversation. Following that conversation is how you see\u000d\u000aaround corners.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 88 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aPart Three\u000d\u000aThe Products\u000d\u000aWhat You Are Building and What It Triggers\u000d\u000a\u2014 89 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aParts One and Two gave you mindset and map. Part Three is where the map meets the\u000d\u000aproduct.\u000d\u000aEvery chapter in this section follows the same architecture: what the product is, what it\u000d\u000adoes, which regulatory framework it triggers, what the specific compliance obligations\u000d\u000alook like in practice, and where the structural traps are hidden. These are the traps that are\u000d\u000anot in the rules. They are in the gap between what the rules say and what they mean when\u000d\u000ayour specific product meets the specific concerns of specific Nigerian regulators.\u000d\u000aFive product categories. Five chapters. Each one written for the founder who is already\u000d\u000abuilding or seriously considering it, not for the theorist who wants to understand it at a\u000d\u000adistance.\u000d\u000aA note on structure: each chapter opens with the product\u2019s regulatory trigger map; a\u000d\u000aquick-reference table showing which product features activate which regulators. Read this\u000d\u000afirst. It tells you immediately whether the chapter is fully relevant to your current product,\u000d\u000aor partially so, or whether it describes something you need to understand for a product\u000d\u000ayou are considering building next.\u000d\u000aThe chapters can be read in order or by the product you are building today. If you are\u000d\u000abuilding a stablecoin product, start with Chapter Ten. If you are building an exchange or\u000d\u000acustody platform, Chapter Eleven is your entry point. If you are tokenising real-world\u000d\u000aassets, Chapter Twelve is the most urgent. If you are building in DeFi or designing DAO\u000d\u000agovernance, Chapter Thirteen. And if you are layering AI into any of the above, Chapter\u000d\u000aFourteen is the chapter that ties them all together.\u000d\u000aLet\u2019s go.\u000d\u000a\u2014 90 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Ten\u000d\u000aStablecoins and Digital Payments: The CBN\u000d\u000aMinefield and How to Cross It\u000d\u000a\u201cThe naira is not just a currency. It is a political object. Any product that touches how it moves, what it\u000d\u000acompetes with, or how Nigerians store their wealth outside it will face the full weight of the Central\u000d\u000aBank\u2019s institutional instincts.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aIf there is a single product category in the Nigerian digital asset market that demands\u000d\u000amore regulatory intelligence than any other, it is stablecoins. Not because the technology\u000d\u000ais uniquely complex. Not because the business model is inherently suspicious. But\u000d\u000abecause stablecoins sit at the precise intersection of two things the Central Bank of Nigeria\u000d\u000acares about more than almost anything else: the integrity of the naira and the legibility of\u000d\u000afinancial flows.\u000d\u000aMore than twenty-six million Nigerians were already using stablecoins for remittances,\u000d\u000asavings, and cross-border purchases by 2024, roughly twelve percent of the population.\u000d\u000aStablecoins, primarily USDT and USDC, account for approximately sixty percent of\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s ninety two billion dollar annual crypto trading volume. Nigeria receives over\u000d\u000atwenty billion dollars in remittances annually, and a significant and growing portion of\u000d\u000athat flows through stablecoin rails. These are not marginal statistics. They describe a\u000d\u000aproduct category that is already deeply embedded in how ordinary Nigerians manage\u000d\u000amoney.\u000d\u000aAnd yet the regulatory framework for stablecoins in Nigeria is, as of this writing, still\u000d\u000abeing constructed. In October 2025, the CBN and SEC Nigeria announced a joint\u000d\u000afifteen-member working group, led by CBN Governor Olayemi Cardoso, to develop a\u000d\u000acomprehensive stablecoin framework. Its report is expected in 2026. In February 2025,\u000d\u000acNGN, Africa\u2019s first regulated naira-pegged stablecoin, issued by WrappedCBDC Limited\u000d\u000aunder ISA 2025, listed on Quidax and Busha, demonstrating for the first time that a\u000d\u000a\u2014 91 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aprivately-issued naira-denominated stablecoin could operate within the Nigerian\u000d\u000aregulatory perimeter.\u000d\u000aWhat this means for founders is that you are building in a space where the rules are being\u000d\u000awritten around your product in real time. The window for founders who engage early,\u000d\u000adesign thoughtfully, and position themselves as compliant partners in the CBN\u2019s\u000d\u000astablecoin framework development is genuine and time-limited. But the mistakes made\u000d\u000aduring this window, particularly the three structural errors described in this chapter, are\u000d\u000aamong the most consequential a founder in this space can make.\u000d\u000aThe Trigger Map\u000d\u000aProduct Feature Regulator Regulatory Trigger Urgency\u000d\u000aNaira-pegged stablecoin issuance CBN + SEC Nigeria Electronic payment instrument +\u000d\u000adigital asset under ISA 2025\u000d\u000aCRITICAL\u000d\u000aDollar-pegged stablecoin (USDT\u000d\u000aequivalent)\u000d\u000aCBN + SEC Nigeria FX management concern + VASP\u000d\u000aregistration required\u000d\u000aCRITICAL\u000d\u000aStablecoin on-ramp / off-ramp\u000d\u000a(naira)\u000d\u000aCBN + SEC Nigeria Payment system licence + VASP\u000d\u000aregistration\u000d\u000aCRITICAL\u000d\u000aStablecoin remittance service CBN (IMTS\u000d\u000aGuidelines)\u000d\u000aIMTO authorisation or agent\u000d\u000aarrangement required\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aStablecoin savings / yield product SEC Nigeria Collective investment scheme risk \u2014\u000d\u000aDAI or DAOP registration\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aForeign stablecoin custody SEC Nigeria (DAC) DAC registration if holding\u000d\u000astablecoins for Nigerian clients\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aStablecoin payment API CBN (PSP licence) Payment solution provider\u000d\u000aauthorisation required\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aStructural Mistake One: The Naira-Pegged Stablecoin Without CBN\u000d\u000aEngagement\u000d\u000aBuilding a stablecoin pegged to the naira is, in Nigerian regulatory terms, one of the most\u000d\u000acomplicated products you can attempt to launch. It is complicated not because the\u000d\u000atechnology is difficult, it is not, but because it intersects with the CBN\u2019s core constitutional\u000d\u000amandate in a way that no other digital product does.\u000d\u000aThe Central Bank of Nigeria Act gives the CBN the sole right to issue naira and to\u000d\u000adetermine the naira\u2019s exchange rate against other currencies. A privately-issued\u000d\u000a\u2014 92 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000anaira-pegged stablecoin is, from the CBN\u2019s institutional perspective, a private entity\u000d\u000acreating a digital representation of the naira, which touches directly on the Bank\u2019s\u000d\u000amonetary sovereignty prerogatives. Whether the CBN views this as a complement to its\u000d\u000amonetary system or a challenge to it depends entirely on the product\u2019s design, its reserve\u000d\u000astructure, and the relationship its issuer has built with the Bank before launch.\u000d\u000aThe cNGN succeeded not because of clever regulatory arbitrage, but because its\u000d\u000aissuers engaged the CBN and SEC Nigeria from the beginning, built a reserve\u000d\u000astructure the CBN could examine and verify, and positioned the product explicitly\u000d\u000aas a complement to, not a substitute for the eNaira.\u000d\u000aThe structural trap for founders attempting a naira-pegged stablecoin without this\u000d\u000aengagement is threefold. First, a naira-denominated stablecoin that allows users to hold,\u000d\u000atransfer, or receive digital naira constitutes the provision of a payment service under the\u000d\u000aCBN\u2019s payment systems framework, specifically, it may constitute an e-money product\u000d\u000arequiring a Payment Service Bank or similar CBN licence, entirely separate from any SEC\u000d\u000aVASP registration. Second, the reserve management required to maintain the peg, holding\u000d\u000anaira reserves, managing liquidity, maintaining redemption capacity, requires\u000d\u000aengagement with the banking system in ways that only CBN-licensed entities can conduct\u000d\u000awithout restriction. Third, and most consequentially: the CBN\u2019s concern about the naira\u2019s\u000d\u000astability means that any naira-pegged stablecoin that achieves meaningful scale without\u000d\u000aCBN oversight will attract the Bank\u2019s attention, and that attention, when it arrives without\u000d\u000aa pre-existing relationship, will be adversarial rather than facilitative.\u000d\u000aThe Reserve Design Question\u000d\u000aEvery naira-pegged stablecoin issuer must answer one question before approaching either regulator:\u000d\u000awhat backs the token, where are the reserves held, who audits them, and what is the redemption\u000d\u000amechanism when a holder wants naira back? The CBN\u2019s concern about redemption risk is substantial.\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s history of naira devaluation means that a poorly designed reserve structure could produce a\u000d\u000arun on the stablecoin during a depreciation episode, with cascading effects on the banking system that\u000d\u000aholds the reserves. Design the reserve and redemption architecture first. It is the document that\u000d\u000aopens every regulator conversation.\u000d\u000a\u2014 93 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aStructural Mistake Two: The Dollar-Pegged Product and the FX Assumption\u000d\u000aThe second structural mistake is more subtle and more common: building a dollar-pegged\u000d\u000astablecoin product, essentially a USDT or USDC equivalent \u2014 and assuming that because\u000d\u000ait is denominated in dollars rather than naira, the CBN has no jurisdiction over it.\u000d\u000aThis assumption is wrong in two distinct ways.\u000d\u000aFirst: any platform that allows Nigerians to acquire, hold, or transact in\u000d\u000adollar-denominated instruments using naira, is operating in Nigeria\u2019s foreign exchange\u000d\u000amarket, which is the CBN\u2019s direct regulatory domain. The naira has lost more than\u000d\u000aseventy percent of its value against the dollar over the past decade. The CBN\u2019s FX\u000d\u000amanagement framework exists precisely to manage the structural pressure on the naira\u000d\u000athat dollar demand creates. A platform that efficiently enables Nigerians to hold dollars\u000d\u000adigitally, even if those dollars are stablecoins rather than physical currency, creates exactly\u000d\u000athe demand pressure the CBN\u2019s FX framework is designed to manage. The regulator will\u000d\u000anotice. The question is whether it notices because you approached it proactively, or\u000d\u000abecause a circular arrives in your inbox.\u000d\u000aSecond: the 2024 Binance episode is the most consequential illustration of this risk in\u000d\u000arecent Nigerian regulatory history. The CBN\u2019s allegations against Binance centred\u000d\u000asignificantly on the claim that Binance\u2019s P2P platform was being used to manipulate the\u000d\u000anaira\u2019s unofficial exchange rate, that the volume of naira-to-USDT transactions visible on\u000d\u000aBinance\u2019s platform was being used as a price discovery mechanism for the naira that\u000d\u000acompeted with the CBN\u2019s official rate. Whether or not the specific allegations were\u000d\u000aaccurate, the episode demonstrated with unmistakable clarity that the CBN does not treat\u000d\u000adollar-denominated stablecoin products as being outside its regulatory perimeter. Any\u000d\u000aplatform that creates a visible naira-to-dollar pricing mechanism, even one mediated\u000d\u000athrough stablecoins, is in the CBN\u2019s field of view.\u000d\u000aThe Binance Lesson\u000d\u000aIn early 2024, Binance executives were detained and Binance\u2019s operations in Nigeria were severely\u000d\u000arestricted following CBN allegations that the platform enabled naira exchange rate manipulation\u000d\u000athrough its P2P trading features. Binance subsequently removed the naira from its platform. The\u000d\u000afounders building dollar-pegged stablecoin products in Nigeria today should treat this episode not\u000d\u000a\u2014 94 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aas a story about Binance specifically, but as a clear signal about the CBN\u2019s willingness to act when\u000d\u000ait believes a platform is affecting the naira\u2019s stability, regardless of whether the platform considers\u000d\u000aitself to be operating in the digital asset sector or the FX sector.\u000d\u000aThe case of AbokiFX is still fresh in our memory.\u000d\u000aStructural Mistake Three: Assuming Existing Stablecoins Set a Permissive\u000d\u000aPrecedent\u000d\u000aThe third structural mistake is perhaps the most psychologically understandable:\u000d\u000aobserving that USDT and USDC are widely used in Nigeria, that millions of Nigerians\u000d\u000atransact in them daily, and concluding that the regulatory environment for new stablecoin\u000d\u000aproducts must therefore be relatively permissive.\u000d\u000aThis reasoning confuses tolerance with authorisation. The CBN\u2019s failure to suppress USDT\u000d\u000aand USDC usage is not an endorsement of those products. It is a recognition that\u000d\u000asuppressing them would be technically impractical and economically counterproductive,\u000d\u000aand would simply push the activity further underground, as the 2021 banking prohibition\u000d\u000ademonstrated. The absence of active enforcement against existing stablecoins reflects\u000d\u000aoperational pragmatism, not regulatory approval.\u000d\u000aThe distinction the CBN draws is sharp and consequential: between foreign-issued\u000d\u000astablecoins that Nigerians access through global platforms and use at their own risk, and\u000d\u000adomestically-issued stablecoin products that a Nigerian company is actively marketing to\u000d\u000aNigerian users as a regulated financial product. The first category the CBN tolerates while\u000d\u000adeveloping its framework. The second category it expects to engage directly with its\u000d\u000asupervision, because a domestic issuer has a physical presence, assets, and accountability\u000d\u000ain Nigeria that a foreign issuer does not.\u000d\u000aThe cNGN\u2019s successful launch is the proof of concept: a privately-issued naira-pegged\u000d\u000astablecoin can operate within the Nigerian regulatory perimeter, but only if its issuers\u000d\u000aengage both the CBN and SEC Nigeria from the outset, build an auditable reserve\u000d\u000astructure, and accept the ongoing supervisory relationship that domestic issuance\u000d\u000arequires.\u000d\u000a\u2014 95 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aHow to Cross the Minefield: The Four-Step Engagement Framework\u000d\u000aGiven the complexity of the stablecoin regulatory landscape, the question for founders is\u000d\u000anot whether to engage the CBN; it is how to do so in a way that produces a productive\u000d\u000aoutcome rather than an adversarial one.\u000d\u000aStep 1. Design the product before approaching the regulator \u2014 The CBN does not respond well to\u000d\u000aspeculative inquiries. It responds to product proposals that are specific about reserve structure,\u000d\u000aredemption mechanisms, AML architecture, user access tiers, and the economic logic of the product.\u000d\u000aBuild this document first. It is simultaneously your product specification, your regulatory engagement\u000d\u000adocument, and your investor pitch.\u000d\u000aStep 2. Approach SEC Nigeria first \u2014 The ISA 2025 classification of digital assets as securities means\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria has the primary licensing mandate. Obtaining ARIP approval, or at minimum, initiating the\u000d\u000aARIP process, before approaching the CBN gives you a credible regulatory footprint that signals\u000d\u000ainstitutional seriousness. The CBN is more receptive to conversations with entities already engaged\u000d\u000awith SEC Nigeria\u2019s framework.\u000d\u000aStep 3. Engage the CBN through the right channel \u2014 The CBN\u2019s Payment System Management\u000d\u000aDepartment is the primary touchpoint for stablecoin products that function as payment instruments.\u000d\u000aThe Financial Policy and Regulation Department is relevant for products that touch the FX market or\u000d\u000amonetary policy. Identify the right department before requesting an engagement. A meeting with the\u000d\u000awrong department is not just unhelpful, it can result in your proposal being misclassified before the\u000d\u000aright officials see it.\u000d\u000aStep 4. Position your product as a complement to the eNaira, not a competitor \u2014 This is the\u000d\u000aframing that has the highest probability of productive reception at the CBN. The eNaira project has\u000d\u000afaced adoption challenges. A privately-issued stablecoin that uses the eNaira\u2019s infrastructure,\u000d\u000areferences the eNaira as the monetary anchor, or creates use cases that expand eNaira adoption is a\u000d\u000afundamentally different conversation from one that implicitly competes with it. The cNGN model,\u000d\u000aexplicitly positioned as complementary to the eNaira, is the template.\u000d\u000aThe Joint Working Group Window\u000d\u000aThe CBN-SEC joint stablecoin working group announced in October 2025 is the single most\u000d\u000aimportant policy development for stablecoin founders in Nigeria right now. Its report, expected in\u000d\u000a2026, will define the framework within which all domestically-issued stablecoins will operate for\u000d\u000athe foreseeable future. Founders who engage with the working group process, through industry\u000d\u000abody submissions, direct requests to present, or written technical input, are not just complying\u000d\u000awith a future framework. They are shaping it. This window closes when the report is published.\u000d\u000aAct accordingly.\u000d\u000a\u2014 96 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 97 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Eleven\u000d\u000aVirtual Asset Services: VASP Licensing, Custody\u000d\u000a& Exchange Infrastructure\u000d\u000a\u201cA licence from SEC Nigeria is not a certificate of compliance. It is the beginning of a compliance\u000d\u000arelationship. The founders who treat it as the end of the process will learn the difference.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aIf Part One of this book convinced you that regulation is your moat, then this chapter is\u000d\u000awhere you build it. The ARIP framework, the SEC Nigeria Accelerated Regulatory\u000d\u000aIncubation Programme, is the most consequential regulatory pathway in the Nigerian\u000d\u000adigital asset market. It is the mechanism through which exchanges, custodians, offering\u000d\u000aplatforms, and intermediaries achieve the legal standing to operate, access banking\u000d\u000ainfrastructure, attract institutional capital, and compete on a level that unlicensed\u000d\u000aoperators cannot reach.\u000d\u000aIt is also a process that most founders approach without adequate preparation, and that\u000d\u000athe SEC\u2019s documentation, however well-intentioned, does not fully describe. This chapter\u000d\u000afills that gap.\u000d\u000aThe Trigger Map\u000d\u000aProduct Feature Regulator Regulatory Trigger Urgency\u000d\u000aRunning a trading platform for\u000d\u000adigital assets\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria DAX registration required \u2014 ISA 2025\u000d\u000as.357\u000d\u000aCRITICAL\u000d\u000aHolding client digital assets\u000d\u000a(custody)\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria DAC registration \u2014 separate from\u000d\u000aexchange licence\u000d\u000aCRITICAL\u000d\u000aFacilitating token sales / primary\u000d\u000aofferings\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria DAOP registration \u2014 investor\u000d\u000aprotection rules apply\u000d\u000aCRITICAL\u000d\u000aBrokerage / intermediary services SEC Nigeria DAI registration required HIGH\u000d\u000aP2P matching platform (naira pairs) SEC Nigeria + CBN DAX + CBN payment consideration CRITICAL\u000d\u000aStaking-as-a-service for clients SEC Nigeria Potential collective investment\u000d\u000ascheme \u2014 DAI or DAOP\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000a\u2014 98 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aWallet provision (custodial) SEC Nigeria (DAC) DAC registration if holding keys on\u000d\u000abehalf of clients\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aThe Four VASP Categories You Must Understand\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria\u2019s Digital Asset Rules establish four licensing categories, each targeting a\u000d\u000adistinct type of digital asset service. Understanding which category \u2014 or categories \u2014\u000d\u000aapplies to your business is the foundational decision of your regulatory engagement.\u000d\u000aDAX. Digital Asset Exchange \u2014 Platforms facilitating the secondary market trading of digital assets\u000d\u000abetween buyers and sellers. A DAX licence covers spot trading, order book matching, and\u000d\u000amarket-making activity. It is the most demanding category in terms of capital requirements,\u000d\u000agovernance obligations, and ongoing compliance. Quidax and Busha hold the first provisional DAX\u000d\u000aapprovals in Nigeria.\u000d\u000aDAOP. Digital Asset Offering Platform \u2014 Platforms facilitating the primary issuance of digital assets to\u000d\u000ainvestors, the functional equivalent of an investment platform or capital markets issuer. If your\u000d\u000aplatform runs token sales, IEOs, NFT drops with investment characteristics, or tokenised asset\u000d\u000aofferings, you are in DAOP territory. Emeka\u2019s tokenised real estate platform from Chapter One was a\u000d\u000aDAOP.\u000d\u000aDAC. Digital Asset Custodian \u2014 Entities that hold and safeguard digital assets on behalf of clients \u2014\u000d\u000aoperating the private keys. This is a separate registration from a DAX, reflecting the SEC\u2019s recognition\u000d\u000athat custody is a distinct and consequential activity. A DAX that also holds client assets must hold\u000d\u000aboth a DAX and a DAC registration. DACs must maintain specified proportions of client assets in cold\u000d\u000astorage and carry fidelity bonds.\u000d\u000aDAI. Digital Asset Intermediary \u2014 Brokers, advisors, and agents who facilitate digital asset\u000d\u000atransactions or provide advisory services without themselves operating an exchange or custody\u000d\u000afunction. The DAI category captures a wide range of intermediary business models including\u000d\u000ainvestment advisory, staking intermediaries, and portfolio management services.\u000d\u000aThe Dual Licence Trap\u000d\u000aOne of the most common ARIP structuring errors is applying only for the category that matches\u000d\u000athe founder\u2019s primary use case, without recognising that the business also conducts activities in a\u000d\u000asecond category. An exchange that holds client funds in a hot wallet is simultaneously a DAX and a\u000d\u000aDAC \u2014 and requires both registrations. A DAOP that also facilitates secondary trading of its issued\u000d\u000atokens may require a DAX registration as well. Map your entire product functionality against all\u000d\u000afour categories before submitting an ARIP application.\u000d\u000a\u2014 99 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aWhat the ARIP Documentation Does Not Tell You\u000d\u000aThe SEC Nigeria ARIP framework documentation specifies what is required. What it does\u000d\u000anot adequately describe is what that requirement means in practice, the standard to which\u000d\u000aeach element is assessed, the informal expectations that shape whether an application\u000d\u000amoves or stalls, and the specific failures that cause applications to be returned without\u000d\u000ameaningful feedback.\u000d\u000aThree dimensions of the ARIP process are consistently underestimated by first-time\u000d\u000aapplicants.\u000d\u000aThe Pre-Screening Conversation\u000d\u000aBefore submitting a formal ARIP application, experienced practitioners engage the SEC in\u000d\u000aan informal pre-screening conversation. This is not officially documented, but it is widely\u000d\u000apractised and substantially affects outcomes. The purpose is to test the SEC\u2019s preliminary\u000d\u000aassessment of your product\u2019s classification and your proposed structure, before investing\u000d\u000athe time and cost of a full formal submission.\u000d\u000aThe pre-screening conversation is typically initiated through a written request to the\u000d\u000aDigital Assets Unit, under the Licensing & Registration department, expressing interest in\u000d\u000athe ARIP process and requesting an initial consultation. Its primary value is twofold: it\u000d\u000aidentifies structural issues in your product design or corporate structure that would cause\u000d\u000aa formal application to be returned, allowing you to address them before submission; and\u000d\u000ait begins the relationship-building process with the officials who will review your\u000d\u000aapplication, which materially affects the quality and responsiveness of the feedback you\u000d\u000areceive during formal review.\u000d\u000aThe founders who get through the ARIP process most efficiently are the ones who\u000d\u000ahave already had three or four conversations with the Commission before their\u000d\u000aapplication hits the desk of the reviewing officer. The application arrives in a context\u000d\u000aof established relationship, not cold.\u000d\u000aGetting the pre-screening conversation right requires three things. First, a clear, concise\u000d\u000aproduct description that demonstrates you understand your product\u2019s regulatory\u000d\u000a\u2014 100 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aclassification, including the honest acknowledgement that it requires SEC oversight, rather\u000d\u000athan an attempt to argue it does not. Second, a summary of your corporate structure that\u000d\u000ademonstrates Nigerian incorporation, local management, and adequate capitalisation.\u000d\u000aThird, a specific agenda for the conversation that respects the official\u2019s time and\u000d\u000ademonstrates preparation.\u000d\u000aThe White Paper Standard\u000d\u000aThe ARIP framework requires a \u2018draft white paper\u2019 as part of the initial assessment\u000d\u000asubmission. The documentation describes this generically. The standard to which it is\u000d\u000aactually assessed is considerably more specific.\u000d\u000aThe white paper is not a marketing document. It is a technical and legal disclosure\u000d\u000adocument that must address, with specificity and rigour, the following: the technical\u000d\u000aarchitecture of the product and its underlying blockchain infrastructure; the token\u000d\u000aeconomics (if tokens are issued), including supply, distribution, vesting, and governance;\u000d\u000athe legal structure of the token and the rights it confers on holders; the risk factors relevant\u000d\u000ato the product and the investor; the team\u2019s qualifications and relevant experience; the\u000d\u000aAML/CFT framework the platform will implement; and the regulatory classification of the\u000d\u000aproduct and the basis for that classification.\u000d\u000aApplications returned or ignored at the initial assessment stage are almost always\u000d\u000areturned for one of three white paper deficiencies: insufficient detail on token economics\u000d\u000aand rights (the Commission cannot assess classification without understanding what the\u000d\u000atoken actually does); inadequate or absent AML/CFT framework description (reflecting\u000d\u000athe NFIU\u2019s AML compliance overlay on the ARIP process); or self-serving classification\u000d\u000aanalysis (a white paper that argues the product is not a security, rather than engaging\u000d\u000ahonestly with the classification question).\u000d\u000aThe Classification Honesty Test\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria\u2019s review team has become significantly more sophisticated in its ability to assess token\u000d\u000aclassification. A white paper that argues your token is a utility token based on the language of the\u000d\u000adocumentation, while the token\u2019s actual function carries economic return characteristics, will be\u000d\u000aidentified and returned. The Commission is not easily fooled by label engineering. The founders who\u000d\u000a\u2014 101 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000amove fastest through ARIP are the ones who say plainly in their white paper: \u2018our product is a\u000d\u000asecurity. Here is how we have structured it to meet your investor protection requirements.\u2019\u000d\u000aThe AIP Period: Not the Finish Line\u000d\u000aThe most consequential misunderstanding in the ARIP process is the treatment of the\u000d\u000aApproval-in-Principle as an endpoint rather than a beginning.\u000d\u000aThe AIP is a conditional authorisation to begin operating, valid for twelve months. During\u000d\u000athat period, the AIP holder must demonstrate ongoing compliance with the conditions of\u000d\u000aits approval, build out the full compliance infrastructure described in its application,\u000d\u000amaintain the minimum capital position, file periodic reports with the Commission, and,\u000d\u000amost critically, demonstrate that the product it is operating matches the product it\u000d\u000adescribed in its application.\u000d\u000aThe twelve months of the AIP period are the Commission\u2019s opportunity to observe the\u000d\u000aplatform in operation and assess whether it is ready for full registration. AIP holders who\u000d\u000atreat this period as a grace period, who defer building their AML systems, who delay\u000d\u000ahiring their compliance officer, who allow their capital position to fall below the required\u000d\u000aminimum, typically discover at the full registration stage that the Commission is not\u000d\u000aprepared to grant unconditional authorisation. Some AIP lapses, requiring the entire\u000d\u000aprocess to restart.\u000d\u000aThe AIP period is the most valuable phase of the ARIP process, because it is the period\u000d\u000aduring which the Commission and the operator are in the most active relationship.\u000d\u000aQuestions can be asked informally. Guidance on specific compliance situations can be\u000d\u000aobtained. The platform\u2019s operational reality can be tested against its theoretical\u000d\u000acompliance framework in a context where the consequence of a gap is remediation, not\u000d\u000arevocation.\u000d\u000aTreat the AIP period as twelve months of intensive compliance construction, with the\u000d\u000aCommission as an engaged observer whose questions are opportunities for improvement\u000d\u000arather than adversarial scrutiny.\u000d\u000a\u2014 102 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCapital Requirements: The Funding Implication\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria\u2019s minimum capital requirements for VASP registrations are substantial and\u000d\u000amust be paid-up, not pledged or committed, but actually deployed into the registered\u000d\u000acompany\u2019s account, verifiable by audited accounts at the time of application. The specific\u000d\u000aamounts are set in the Digital Asset Rules and reviewed periodically.\u000d\u000aThe capital verification process is a specific ARIP friction point that many first-time\u000d\u000aapplicants underestimate. The Commission does not merely check that the capital appears\u000d\u000aon the company\u2019s balance sheet. It expects to understand the source of that capital,\u000d\u000athrough audited accounts, bank statements, and shareholder declarations. Capital that\u000d\u000aarrives into the company\u2019s account immediately before the application, without a clear\u000d\u000apaper trail of its origin, raises source-of-funds questions that can stall or derail an\u000d\u000aapplication.\u000d\u000aThe Capitalisation Strategy\u000d\u000aPlan your ARIP capitalisation as a fundraising milestone, not an administrative requirement. The\u000d\u000aminimum capital for your chosen registration category should be in your company\u2019s accounts, clearly\u000d\u000adocumented by source, at least three months before your ARIP submission, so that the audit trail is\u000d\u000aclean, the source of funds is clear, and the capital is genuinely deployed in the business rather than a\u000d\u000atransient deposit made for application purposes. The Commission can distinguish between the two.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 103 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Twelve\u000d\u000aTokenisation: Real-World Assets, Securities, and\u000d\u000athe New Capital Markets\u000d\u000a\u201cA token does not change the nature of the asset it represents. It only changes the mechanism by which\u000d\u000athat asset is held, traded, and governed. The law governing the underlying asset still applies.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aWe have spent considerable time in this book with Emeka and his tokenised real estate\u000d\u000aplatform. His story is in the Introduction, in Chapter One, and woven through Part One as\u000d\u000aa case study in what happens when a genuinely good product runs into a regulatory\u000d\u000aframework its founder did not understand.\u000d\u000aThis chapter is written so that the next Emeka does not have to learn these lessons the\u000d\u000ahard way.\u000d\u000aReal-world asset tokenisation is one of the highest-growth product categories in global\u000d\u000adigital finance and one of the most consequential for African markets specifically. The\u000d\u000aability to fractionalise ownership of premium real estate, government bonds, agricultural\u000d\u000areceivables, or infrastructure assets creates investment access for individuals who have\u000d\u000ahistorically been excluded from these markets by minimum investment sizes, liquidity\u000d\u000aconstraints, and geographic barriers. In Nigeria, where real estate has historically been one\u000d\u000aof the most effective stores of value but has been accessible only to the wealthy,\u000d\u000atokenisation\u2019s financial inclusion potential is substantial.\u000d\u000aIt is also one of the most legally complex product categories to build correctly. Not\u000d\u000abecause the technology is difficult, but because tokenisation sits at the intersection of asset\u000d\u000alaw, securities regulation, and digital asset regulation in a way that requires all three to be\u000d\u000aaddressed simultaneously, and that Nigerian law, in several specific respects, creates\u000d\u000astructural challenges that have no clean technical solution.\u000d\u000a\u2014 104 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe Trigger Map\u000d\u000aProduct Feature Regulator Regulatory Trigger Urgency\u000d\u000aTokenised real estate (fractional\u000d\u000aownership)\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria + State\u000d\u000aLand Law\u000d\u000aDAOP + ISA 2025 securities rules +\u000d\u000aLand Use Act\u000d\u000aCRITICAL\u000d\u000aTokenised bonds / government\u000d\u000asecurities\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria + DMO DAOP + Debt Management Office\u000d\u000anotification\u000d\u000aCRITICAL\u000d\u000aTokenised agricultural receivables /\u000d\u000ainvoices\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria + CBN DAOP + potential payment system\u000d\u000aconsiderations\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aNFTs with investment\u000d\u000acharacteristics\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria DAOP if NFT carries economic return\u000d\u000arights\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aTokenised equity / company shares SEC Nigeria + CAC DAOP + Companies Act share transfer\u000d\u000aprovisions\u000d\u000aCRITICAL\u000d\u000aSecondary trading of RWA tokens SEC Nigeria DAX registration required for\u000d\u000asecondary market\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aCustody of RWA tokens for\u000d\u000ainvestors\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria (DAC) DAC registration required HIGH\u000d\u000aThe First Principle: The Token Does Not Change the Asset\u000d\u000aBefore examining the specific Nigerian legal challenges, it is worth establishing the\u000d\u000aprinciple from which everything in this chapter flows, because it is the principle most\u000d\u000acommonly misunderstood by founders entering the RWA tokenisation space.\u000d\u000aA token is not an asset. It is a representation of an interest in an asset. The legal rights that a\u000d\u000atoken confers on its holder are only as robust as the legal arrangements that connect the\u000d\u000atoken to the underlying asset. A token that claims to represent a fractional interest in a\u000d\u000aLagos apartment is worthless if there is no enforceable legal mechanism by which the\u000d\u000atoken holder can actually assert that interest in a Nigerian court.\u000d\u000aThis distinction has profound practical implications. Every RWA tokenisation project must\u000d\u000aanswer three questions before the token design is even relevant:\u000d\u000a1. Who legally holds the underlying asset? \u2014 The asset must be held by an identifiable legal entity,\u000d\u000atypically a Special Purpose Vehicle (SPV) incorporated at the CAC \u2014 that is separate from the issuer\u2019s\u000d\u000aoperating company. This separation protects investors from the issuer\u2019s insolvency and provides a\u000d\u000aclean legal structure for the asset\u2019s ownership and governance.\u000d\u000a\u2014 105 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a2. How is the SPV\u2019s title to the asset verified and maintained? \u2014 Title verification is the single most\u000d\u000aexpensive and time-consuming component of most Nigerian RWA tokenisation projects, because\u000d\u000aNigerian title infrastructure, particularly for real estate, is imperfect in ways that require thorough\u000d\u000alegal due diligence before any token can be issued.\u000d\u000a3. What is the token holder\u2019s enforceable right against the SPV? \u2014 The token must be connected to\u000d\u000aa legally binding agreement, a trust deed, a shareholder agreement, a beneficial ownership deed,\u000d\u000athat gives the token holder an enforceable claim to their proportional share of the asset\u2019s income and\u000d\u000acapital. The token itself is not the claim. It is the evidence of the claim. The claim exists in the legal\u000d\u000adocumentation.\u000d\u000aThe SPV Architecture\u000d\u000aThe standard architecture for Nigerian RWA tokenisation is: (1) an operating company that runs the\u000d\u000aplatform, holds the DAOP licence, and manages investor relations; (2) an SPV incorporated at the\u000d\u000aCAC that holds legal title to the underlying asset; (3) a trust deed or equivalent legal instrument\u000d\u000aexecuted by the SPV that defines the rights of beneficial owners; and (4) tokens issued by the DAOP\u000d\u000athat represent beneficial ownership interests in the SPV. These four-layer structure provide investor\u000d\u000aprotection, regulatory clarity, and operational separation that single-entity structures cannot\u000d\u000aachieve.\u000d\u000aThe Nigerian Real Estate Title Problem\u000d\u000aReal estate is the most common underlying asset for Nigerian tokenisation projects, for\u000d\u000aobvious reasons: it is the most reliable store of value in the Nigerian market, the demand\u000d\u000afor fractional access is large and real, and the existing market is dominated by\u000d\u000aintermediaries whose margins could be substantially reduced by tokenisation platforms.\u000d\u000aBut Nigerian real estate tokenisation faces a structural problem that has no equivalent in\u000d\u000athe US or European tokenisation markets, and that no amount of technological\u000d\u000asophistication can solve: the imperfection of Nigerian land title.\u000d\u000aThe Land Use Act 1978 vests all land in Nigeria in the state governor of each state.\u000d\u000aCitizens and companies do not own land outright, they hold long-term leases (Certificates\u000d\u000aof Occupancy) granted by the state governor. The implication for tokenisation is\u000d\u000aprofound: a Certificate of Occupancy is not freely transferable without the governor\u2019s\u000d\u000aconsent. Any transaction involving the transfer of an interest in land, including, arguably,\u000d\u000a\u2014 106 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000athe tokenisation of a beneficial interest in a land-holding SPV, may require gubernatorial\u000d\u000aconsent under the Land Use Act.\u000d\u000aThis is not a theoretical concern. Nigerian courts have in multiple cases held that\u000d\u000atransactions involving land interests conducted without the required governor\u2019s consent\u000d\u000aare void. A tokenised real estate project whose underlying SPV holds a Certificate of\u000d\u000aOccupancy, and whose tokens represent interests in that SPV, may be conducting what\u000d\u000aamounts to a transfer of land interests, one for each token transaction, without individual\u000d\u000agovernor\u2019s consent.\u000d\u000aThe practical approach that most experienced Nigerian real estate tokenisation\u000d\u000apractitioners adopt is to structure the SPV\u2019s interest as a beneficial interest rather than a\u000d\u000alegal interest in the land, and to obtain a general governor\u2019s consent for the SPV structure\u000d\u000aat the outset, covering the issuance and secondary trading of tokens. But this approach has\u000d\u000anot yet been definitively tested in Nigerian courts, and any founder building in this space\u000d\u000ashould obtain a specific legal opinion on the title and consent structure from a practitioner\u000d\u000awith verified experience in both Nigerian land law and digital asset securities regulation.\u000d\u000aThe Disputed Title Risk\u000d\u000aNigerian real estate title disputes are not rare. A significant proportion of premium properties in\u000d\u000aLagos, Abuja, and other major cities carry some form of title uncertainty, overlapping claims,\u000d\u000adisputed inheritance, fraudulent Certificate of Occupancy issuance. The cost of discovering a title\u000d\u000adispute after tokens have been issued to investors is catastrophic: the asset\u2019s value is frozen,\u000d\u000aredemptions cannot be processed, and token holders have a claim against an asset that cannot be\u000d\u000acleanly sold. Title due diligence for any Nigerian real estate tokenisation project must be exhaustive\u000d\u000aand independently verified by a qualified property lawyer. It is the most important, and most\u000d\u000afrequently underinvested, component of the project.\u000d\u000aThe Custody and Title Chain\u000d\u000aThe second inseparable component of RWA tokenisation is the custody and title chain, the\u000d\u000adocumented, verified, auditable sequence of legal arrangements that connects the\u000d\u000ainvestor\u2019s token to the underlying asset at every point in the product\u2019s life.\u000d\u000a\u2014 107 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe custody risk in RWA tokenisation is not primarily about digital asset custody in the\u000d\u000atechnical sense, the security of the private keys that control the tokens. It is about the\u000d\u000ainstitutional custody of the underlying asset itself. Who holds the Certificate of\u000d\u000aOccupancy? Where is the title deed? Who is the registered director of the SPV? What\u000d\u000ahappens to these arrangements if the SPV director is incapacitated or the operating\u000d\u000acompany becomes insolvent?\u000d\u000aThe most consequential RWA tokenisation collapses globally, and there have been several,\u000d\u000ahave not been caused by blockchain hacks or token contract bugs. They have been caused\u000d\u000aby the failure of the off-chain custody arrangements: the SPV that was not properly\u000d\u000aconstituted, the trust deed that was never properly executed, the underlying asset that\u000d\u000awas mortgaged to a bank without investor knowledge, the development that was never\u000d\u000abuilt.\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria\u2019s DAOP registration requirements address this directly: issuers must\u000d\u000ademonstrate that the underlying assets are properly held, that investor rights are\u000d\u000adocumented and enforceable, and that the custody chain between the token and the asset\u000d\u000ais complete. These are not bureaucratic requirements. They are the minimum\u000d\u000ainfrastructure of investor protection for a product category where the consequences of\u000d\u000afailure fall entirely on individual investors.\u000d\u000aISA 2025 and the Tokenisation Opportunity\u000d\u000aAgainst these structural challenges, ISA 2025 creates something that did not exist two\u000d\u000ayears ago: a clear legal foundation for RWA tokenisation in Nigeria. Digital assets are\u000d\u000asecurities. A tokenised interest in real estate, a bond, or a corporate receivable is a digital\u000d\u000asecurity. SEC Nigeria is the regulator. The DAOP is the licence.\u000d\u000aThe clarity this provides is commercially significant. Before ISA 2025, a Nigerian founder\u000d\u000abuilding a tokenised real estate platform could not point to a statutory provision that\u000d\u000aunambiguously recognised their product as a regulated, and therefore legitimate,\u000d\u000ainvestment instrument. Emeka received his SEC letter partly because the regulatory\u000d\u000aframework was still being assembled. The founders building today have ISA 2025 at their\u000d\u000aback.\u000d\u000a\u2014 108 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe tokenisation categories with the most immediate commercial opportunity in Nigeria\u000d\u000aare: real estate (the largest existing market), agricultural commodities and receivables (a\u000d\u000amajor financial inclusion opportunity for smallholder farmers who need working capital),\u000d\u000ainfrastructure assets (roads, bridges, utilities, where tokenisation could create retail\u000d\u000ainvestor access to assets historically reserved for institutional capital), and government\u000d\u000asecurities (where the Debt Management Office has expressed interest in the efficiency and\u000d\u000areach improvements that tokenisation could deliver).\u000d\u000aThe Market Timing\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s capital market is dramatically underdeveloped relative to the economy\u2019s size. The NSE\u2019s\u000d\u000amarket capitalisation is a fraction of GDP. A vast range of productive assets that could be investment\u000d\u000ainstruments, real estate, agricultural produce, infrastructure, exist outside the capital market\u000d\u000aentirely. RWA tokenisation is not competing with an existing capital market. It is building one that\u000d\u000adoes not yet exist. The founders who establish themselves in this space in the next three years,\u000d\u000aunder the ISA 2025 framework, will be the infrastructure of the Nigerian capital market that serves\u000d\u000athe next generation.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 109 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Thirteen\u000d\u000aDeFi, DAOs & Smart Contracts: Building\u000d\u000aDecentralised Products in a Centralised\u000d\u000aRegulatory World\u000d\u000a\u201cThe fact that no one controls the code does not mean no one is responsible for its consequences.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aEvery regulatory framework in the world has been built around a central assumption that\u000d\u000aDeFi systematically challenges: that there is a legal entity somewhere, a company, a\u000d\u000afoundation, an individual, that can be held responsible for the behaviour of a financial\u000d\u000aservice.\u000d\u000aDeFi protocols, at their most decentralised, have no such entity. The code runs on a public\u000d\u000ablockchain. Anyone can interact with it. The developers who wrote it may have\u000d\u000adeliberately relinquished control over it. There is no office to visit, no director to serve\u000d\u000awith papers, no account to freeze. When a DeFi protocol fails, is exploited, or produces\u000d\u000alosses for users, the question of who is responsible has no clean answer in any legal\u000d\u000asystem currently operating on earth.\u000d\u000aThis is, from a regulatory perspective, the most difficult product category in the digital\u000d\u000aasset space. It is also, from a founder\u2019s perspective, one of the most important to\u000d\u000aunderstand, because the regulatory uncertainty that surrounds it is not permanent, and\u000d\u000athe choices you make in product design today will determine whether your platform is on\u000d\u000athe right or wrong side of the framework that eventually arrives.\u000d\u000aThe Trigger Map\u000d\u000aProduct Feature Regulator Regulatory Trigger Urgency\u000d\u000aDeFi lending / borrowing protocol SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000a(emerging)\u000d\u000aPotential collective investment\u000d\u000ascheme or deposit-taking\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aDecentralised exchange (DEX) SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000a(emerging)\u000d\u000aNo formal DEX framework yet \u2014\u000d\u000awatch ARIP amendments\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000a\u2014 110 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aDAO governance token SEC Nigeria Likely security if token carries\u000d\u000aeconomic return rights\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aYield farming / liquidity provision SEC Nigeria Potential investment scheme \u2014 DAI\u000d\u000aor DAOP territory\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aSmart contract with Nigerian users No specific\u000d\u000aframework yet\u000d\u000aConsumer protection obligations may\u000d\u000aapply \u2014 FCCPC watch\u000d\u000aMEDIUM\u000d\u000aDAO with Nigerian employees /\u000d\u000acontractors\u000d\u000aCAC + FIRS + Labour\u000d\u000aLaw\u000d\u000aDAO has no legal personality \u2014\u000d\u000aliability falls on individuals\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aDeFi product with identifiable\u000d\u000aoperator\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria + NFIU VASP obligations apply if operator is\u000d\u000aidentifiable\u000d\u000aCRITICAL\u000d\u000aHow Nigerian Regulators Currently View DeFi \u2014 An Honest Assessment\u000d\u000aThe honest answer is that Nigerian regulators are in the earliest stages of forming a\u000d\u000acoherent position on DeFi. There is no DeFi-specific regulation. There is no DeFi-specific\u000d\u000aguidance from SEC Nigeria or the CBN. The NFIU\u2019s VASP guidelines do not address DeFi\u000d\u000aprotocols with specificity. The ISA 2025 classification of digital assets as securities creates a\u000d\u000abroad statutory net, but its application to protocols without identifiable issuers is a legal\u000d\u000aquestion that has not been tested in Nigerian courts.\u000d\u000aWhat exists is a set of institutional dispositions that are visible in how regulators have\u000d\u000aapproached adjacent questions, and that allow careful inference about how DeFi-specific\u000d\u000aquestions will eventually be resolved.\u000d\u000aThe SEC Nigeria\u2019s disposition is towards inclusivity of scope: if a product has the\u000d\u000afunctional characteristics of a financial service, investment, trading, lending, custody, it\u000d\u000awill seek to bring it within its supervisory perimeter, even if the mechanism for doing so is\u000d\u000anot yet designed. The ISA 2025\u2019s deliberately broad definition of digital assets and VASPs\u000d\u000ais consistent with this disposition. The Commission is not waiting for DeFi protocols to\u000d\u000aexceed a certain scale before forming a view. It is watching the space and developing its\u000d\u000aanalytical framework while the market develops.\u000d\u000aThe CBN\u2019s disposition is driven by its monetary and systemic stability mandate: DeFi\u000d\u000aprotocols that create naira liquidity, facilitate naira lending, or denominate positions in\u000d\u000anaira are within the CBN\u2019s field of vision regardless of their technical architecture. A DeFi\u000d\u000aprotocol that holds naira liquidity in smart contracts and enables naira-denominated\u000d\u000a\u2014 111 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000alending to Nigerian users is, from the CBN\u2019s perspective, conducting banking or payment\u000d\u000aservices without authorisation, whatever the technical means by which it does so.\u000d\u000aThe regulatory framework that will eventually govern DeFi in Nigeria will not\u000d\u000abe designed from first principles. It will be extrapolated from the VASP\u000d\u000aframework that exists for centralised operators. The founders who understand\u000d\u000ahow that extrapolation will work are the ones who can build ahead of it.\u000d\u000aThe FATF Extrapolation: When Is a DeFi Protocol a VASP?\u000d\u000aFATF\u2019s 2021 updated guidance on virtual assets provides the clearest available signal of\u000d\u000ahow DeFi will eventually be regulated, because it is the framework from which all African\u000d\u000aregulatory approaches will be derived.\u000d\u000aFATF\u2019s position is that a DeFi protocol, or its creators, owners, and operators, may\u000d\u000aconstitute a VASP if they retain control over the protocol, benefit financially from its\u000d\u000aoperation, or have the ability to modify its parameters. A truly decentralised protocol with\u000d\u000ano controlling entity, no revenue collection mechanism, and no administrative capability\u000d\u000ais harder to classify as a VASP. But FATF is explicit that \u2018decentralisation\u2019 does not\u000d\u000aautomatically remove a protocol from regulatory scope: the question is whether there is\u000d\u000aany natural or legal person who exercises sufficient control or benefit to constitute a VASP\u000d\u000arelationship.\u000d\u000aFor Nigerian founders, the practical implication is this: if your DeFi protocol has a team\u000d\u000athat deployed it, an admin key that can upgrade or pause the contracts, a fee collection\u000d\u000amechanism that flows to identifiable wallets, and a marketing presence targeting Nigerian\u000d\u000ausers, you are almost certainly within the scope of what SEC Nigeria and the NFIU will\u000d\u000aeventually classify as VASP activity, regardless of how decentralised the protocol\u2019s\u000d\u000aexecution layer is.\u000d\u000aThe founders who are building \u2018decentralised\u2019 products that are, in practice, centralised in\u000d\u000atheir governance and benefit structures are not avoiding regulation. They are deferring it,\u000d\u000a\u2014 112 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aand the deferral is creating accumulated compliance debt that will become due when the\u000d\u000aframework arrives.\u000d\u000aThe DAO Legal Personality Problem\u000d\u000aDAOs present a specific and serious legal problem in Nigeria that is distinct from the DeFi\u000d\u000aprotocol question: they have no legal personality.\u000d\u000aUnder the Companies and Allied Matters Act (CAMA) and the CAC\u2019s registration\u000d\u000arequirements, a business entity operating in Nigeria must be incorporated as a company,\u000d\u000abusiness name, or incorporated trustee. A DAO, governed by token holder votes and\u000d\u000asmart contract execution, fits none of these categories. It is not incorporated. It has no\u000d\u000adirectors. It has no registered address. It cannot open a bank account, enter into a lease,\u000d\u000aemploy staff, or appear as a party in a Nigerian court.\u000d\u000aThe practical consequence is that all of the legal obligations and liabilities of a DAO fall on\u000d\u000athe natural persons most closely associated with it. In Nigeria, that means the individuals\u000d\u000awho deployed the smart contracts, who hold administrative access, and who have\u000d\u000apublicly identified themselves as the DAO\u2019s founders or core contributors. If the DAO is\u000d\u000asued, those individuals are sued. If the DAO owes tax, those individuals owe it. If the\u000d\u000aDAO\u2019s protocol causes investor losses, those individuals face the consumer protection\u000d\u000aclaims.\u000d\u000aFounders who structure their projects as DAOs while avoiding personal legal liability\u000d\u000athrough the decentralisation narrative are operating under a significant misapprehension\u000d\u000aof Nigerian law. The DAO structure creates the worst of both worlds: no legal protection\u000d\u000afor the individual founders (because there is no incorporated entity to absorb liability),\u000d\u000aand no regulatory clarity for users (because there is no licensed entity to hold\u000d\u000aaccountable).\u000d\u000aThe DAO-as-Liability Structure\u000d\u000aIf you are building a DAO-governed product targeting Nigerian users, the minimum legally prudent\u000d\u000astructure is: an incorporated Nigerian company or foreign company with Nigerian registration that\u000d\u000aholds any licences, contracts, banking relationships, and employment arrangements; a DAO\u000d\u000agovernance layer on top of the incorporated entity that manages protocol parameters and\u000d\u000a\u2014 113 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000acommunity decision-making; and a clear legal separation between the incorporated entity\u2019s\u000d\u000aobligations and the DAO\u2019s governance activities. The DAO governance layer does not need to be\u000d\u000aeliminated, but it cannot be the only layer.\u000d\u000aSmart Contract Liability and Consumer Protection\u000d\u000aThe third dimension of DeFi\u2019s regulatory complexity is the one that will eventually force\u000d\u000aregulatory action in Nigeria, not because of AML concerns, and not because of VASP\u000d\u000aclassification disputes, but because of consumer losses.\u000d\u000aSmart contract exploits, protocol failures, and liquidity crises in DeFi have collectively cost\u000d\u000ausers billions of dollars globally. When Nigerian users lose money in these events, and\u000d\u000athey have, the question of who is responsible under Nigerian consumer protection law is\u000d\u000agenuinely unresolved. The FCCPC (Federal Competition and Consumer Protection\u000d\u000aCommission) has moved aggressively in the digital lending space, imposing fines and\u000d\u000aconduct requirements on platforms that engaged in predatory practices. Its jurisdiction\u000d\u000aover digital financial products is broad, and consumer harm from DeFi products falls\u000d\u000asquarely within the categories of harm it is mandated to address.\u000d\u000aThe smart contract liability question is not merely theoretical in this context. A DeFi\u000d\u000aprotocol that is marketed to Nigerian users as a \u2018safe\u2019 or \u2018secure\u2019 savings or investment\u000d\u000aproduct, and that suffers an exploit resulting in user losses, creates a consumer protection\u000d\u000aexposure for anyone who can be identified as having promoted or operated it. The\u000d\u000amarketing layer is often where the legal liability attaches, even when the protocol layer is\u000d\u000atechnically autonomous.\u000d\u000aBuilding in DeFi Without Building in Liability: Practical Guidance\u000d\u000aThree principles guide responsible DeFi product design for the Nigerian market:\u000d\u000a1. Be honest about decentralisation \u2014 If your protocol has admin keys, upgrade mechanisms, fee\u000d\u000aflows to identifiable wallets, or a team with ongoing involvement in its operation, present it as a\u000d\u000a\u2018protocol with governance controls\u2019 rather than a \u2018fully decentralised\u2019 system. Regulatory scrutiny of\u000d\u000adecentralisation claims is intensifying globally. The honest framing is also the most defensible one\u000d\u000awhen the regulator arrives.\u000d\u000a\u2014 114 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a2. Incorporate the controllable elements \u2014 Whatever aspects of your DeFi product can be legally\u000d\u000astructured \u2014 the interface, the fee collection, the customer onboarding, the customer support \u2014\u000d\u000ashould be operated through an incorporated Nigerian entity with appropriate licences. The protocol\u000d\u000alayer can be decentralised. The service layer should not be.\u000d\u000a3. Design for consumer protection from the outset \u2014 Risk disclosures, user education, clear\u000d\u000adocumentation of what the smart contract does and does not guarantee, and accessible dispute or\u000d\u000aloss reporting mechanisms are not just good practice. They are the evidence that demonstrates good\u000d\u000afaith when a consumer protection inquiry arrives. The FCCPC\u2019s 2025 digital lending rules \u2014 which\u000d\u000aintroduced fines of up to \u20a6100 million for prohibited conduct \u2014 are the most recent indication of\u000d\u000ahow seriously Nigerian regulators take consumer harm in digital financial products.\u000d\u000aThe DeFi White Space Window\u000d\u000aThere are currently no DAX, DAOP, DAC, or DAI-equivalent licences specifically designed for DeFi\u000d\u000aprotocols in Nigeria. SEC Nigeria has not issued DeFi-specific guidance. The ARIP framework does\u000d\u000anot have a DeFi-specific track. This whitespace is temporary \u2014 the SEC\u2019s ongoing Digital Asset\u000d\u000aRules development is expected to address DeFi explicitly in the next amendment cycle. Founders\u000d\u000aoperating in this space now have the opportunity to engage with that process proactively \u2014\u000d\u000athrough BNUG, FintechNGR, and direct submissions to the SEC\u2019s consultation processes \u2014 and to\u000d\u000ashape the framework that will eventually govern them.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 115 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Fourteen\u000d\u000aAI-Enabled Financial Products: The Emerging\u000d\u000aRegulatory Frontier\u000d\u000a\u201cAI does not create new regulatory categories. It adds a new layer of opacity and scale to every category\u000d\u000athat already exists. The regulator\u2019s question is always the same: when something goes wrong, who is\u000d\u000aresponsible?\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aArtificial intelligence is not a regulatory category in Nigeria. There is no dedicated AI Act\u000d\u000ain force, the AI Governance Bill introduced in late 2025 has not yet been signed, though its\u000d\u000apassage is widely anticipated in 2026. There is no AI-specific licensing regime. There is no\u000d\u000aAI-specific supervisory authority with a defined mandate over AI-powered financial\u000d\u000aproducts.\u000d\u000aWhat there is, increasingly, is a set of sector-specific expectations, from the CBN, from SEC\u000d\u000aNigeria, from NITDA, from the Nigeria Data Protection Commission, that apply to\u000d\u000aAI-powered products operating within their respective regulatory perimeters. And what\u000d\u000ais emerging, with accelerating speed, is a shared institutional disposition: AI is not exempt\u000d\u000afrom the consumer protection, AML, investor protection, and data privacy obligations that\u000d\u000aapply to non-AI financial products. It is, if anything, subject to heightened scrutiny\u000d\u000abecause of the opacity of its decision-making and the scale at which it can affect\u000d\u000aconsumers.\u000d\u000aThis chapter addresses three specific AI application categories that are already live in the\u000d\u000aNigerian financial services market and that are generating the most consequential\u000d\u000aregulatory attention: AI-driven credit scoring, AI-assisted AML and transaction\u000d\u000amonitoring, and AI agents operating autonomously in financial systems. The chapter\u000d\u000acloses with the governance framework that responsible AI financial product builders\u000d\u000ashould adopt now, before the regulation arrives, because the regulation will arrive, and\u000d\u000athe founders who are already compliant will have the advantage.\u000d\u000a\u2014 116 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe Trigger Map\u000d\u000aProduct Feature Regulator Regulatory Trigger Urgency\u000d\u000aAI credit scoring with alternative\u000d\u000adata\u000d\u000aCBN + NDPC + FCCPC Bias, explainability, consent, and data\u000d\u000aprotection\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aAI-automated AML / transaction\u000d\u000amonitoring\u000d\u000aNFIU + CBN Algorithmic accountability, false\u000d\u000apositive management\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aAI investment advisory\u000d\u000a(robo-advisor)\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria Investment advisory licence (DAI) \u2014\u000d\u000asuitability obligations\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aAI-driven trading algorithms SEC Nigeria + CBN Market manipulation risk, investor\u000d\u000aprotection\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aAI agents in DeFi protocols SEC (emerging) +\u000d\u000aNFIU\u000d\u000aVASP classification if agent is\u000d\u000aidentifiable operator\u000d\u000aHIGH\u000d\u000aAI content / chatbots for financial\u000d\u000aadvice\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria + FCCPC Consumer protection, false claims,\u000d\u000aunlicensed advice\u000d\u000aMEDIUM\u000d\u000aAI underwriting / insurance\u000d\u000aproducts\u000d\u000aNAICOM + NDPC Explainability requirement, data\u000d\u000aconsent\u000d\u000aMEDIUM\u000d\u000aAI-Driven Credit Scoring: The First Regulatory Confrontation\u000d\u000aAI credit scoring using alternative data is the application category that will produce\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s first significant AI-in-finance regulatory enforcement action. The product\u000d\u000acategory is already mature: dozens of Nigerian digital lenders, licensed under the\u000d\u000aFCCPC\u2019s digital lending framework, with CBN credit bureau relationships, are using\u000d\u000amachine learning models trained on alternative data (phone metadata, app usage, social\u000d\u000aconnections, transaction history) to make credit decisions for users who have no formal\u000d\u000acredit history.\u000d\u000aThe regulatory risk is not primarily about the technology. It is about three specific\u000d\u000aobligations that AI credit scoring products currently do not, in most cases, adequately\u000d\u000asatisfy.\u000d\u000aThe first is explainability. Nigeria\u2019s 2023 Data Protection Act, administered by the NDPC,\u000d\u000arequires that in cases where automated decisions significantly affect individuals, those\u000d\u000aindividuals must be informed that they are interacting with an automated system, and, by\u000d\u000aextension, must have the ability to understand and contest the decision. A credit decision\u000d\u000amade by a machine learning model that cannot be explained in plain terms to the\u000d\u000a\u2014 117 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aindividual it affects may violate the NDPA\u2019s requirements. The CBN\u2019s sandbox evaluation\u000d\u000aframework, expanded in 2024-2025, now explicitly assesses model explainability for\u000d\u000aAI-powered fintech tools.\u000d\u000aThe second is bias and fairness. Alternative data used to train credit models in Nigeria\u000d\u000acarries significant potential for demographic bias, not because of malicious intent, but\u000d\u000abecause the patterns in historical financial data reflect the inequalities that alternative data\u000d\u000ais supposed to overcome. A model trained on data that correlates certain demographic\u000d\u000acharacteristics with default risk will systematically disadvantage those groups, even if the\u000d\u000amodel makes no direct reference to protected characteristics. The NDPC\u2019s enforcement\u000d\u000afocus in 2024-2025 has included the processing of personal data for automated\u000d\u000adecision-making, and the FCCPC\u2019s 2025 digital lending rules explicitly address\u000d\u000adiscriminatory practices.\u000d\u000aThe third is data consent and provenance. AI credit models consume enormous quantities\u000d\u000aof personal data from sources that users may not realise are being used to assess their\u000d\u000acreditworthiness. Phone metadata, contact lists, social media activity, location data,\u000d\u000abrowser history, all of these have been used, by various Nigerian digital lenders, as\u000d\u000afeatures in credit models. The NDPA requires specific, informed consent for the\u000d\u000aprocessing of personal data for each purpose for which it is used. A blanket\u000d\u000aterms-of-service consent that buried a provision about alternative data use for credit\u000d\u000ascoring is not, under the NDPA\u2019s standards, adequate informed consent.\u000d\u000aThe FCCPC Enforcement Trajectory\u000d\u000aThe FCCPC\u2019s 2025 digital lending rules introduced fines of up to \u20a6100 million or one percent of\u000d\u000aannual turnover for prohibited conduct, including data scraping, harassment, and non-disclosure.\u000d\u000aThese rules apply to all digital lenders, including those using AI-powered credit scoring. The\u000d\u000atrajectory of enforcement is towards greater scrutiny of algorithmic decision-making, not less.\u000d\u000aFounders building AI credit products should implement explainability, fairness testing, and consent\u000d\u000adocumentation now, before the framework makes them mandatory.\u000d\u000a\u2014 118 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aAI-Assisted AML: The Product Regulators Want to Encourage\u000d\u000aAI-assisted AML and transaction monitoring is the application category where the\u000d\u000aregulatory opportunity is most clear and most immediate, because it directly addresses\u000d\u000athe problem that has most consistently frustrated Nigerian financial regulators.\u000d\u000aThe NFIU processes thousands of Suspicious Transaction Reports monthly. The CBN\u2019s\u000d\u000asupervisory teams monitor billions of transactions across the banking system. The\u000d\u000aanalytical challenge of identifying genuine financial crime signals within this volume is\u000d\u000abeyond the capacity of rule-based monitoring systems. The NFIU\u2019s embrace of SupTech,\u000d\u000asupervisory technology, as part of Nigeria\u2019s FATF grey list exit reforms, and the CBN\u2019s\u000d\u000aexpanding sandbox evaluation of AI-powered compliance tools, both reflect a regulatory\u000d\u000aestablishment that wants AI to solve its supervision problem.\u000d\u000aThis creates an unusual dynamic: AI-assisted AML is a product category where the\u000d\u000aregulator\u2019s disposition is actively supportive rather than cautious. The NFIU has\u000d\u000aexpressed interest in working with technology providers to improve its intelligence\u000d\u000aprocessing capabilities. SEC Nigeria\u2019s ARIP documentation explicitly welcomes\u000d\u000acompliance technology solutions. The CBN\u2019s 2025 SupTech roadmap includes AI-powered\u000d\u000atransaction monitoring as a priority development area.\u000d\u000aThe commercial opportunity is real and underexploited: building AI-assisted compliance\u000d\u000atools that help Nigerian VASPs meet their NFIU obligations, that help banks implement\u000d\u000athe CBN\u2019s AML requirements more effectively, and that help the regulators themselves\u000d\u000aprocess intelligence more efficiently is a category where the regulatory environment is\u000d\u000aactively supportive.\u000d\u000aBut the opportunity comes with its own accountability obligations. An AI system that\u000d\u000amisclassifies legitimate transactions as suspicious creates direct operational harm for\u000d\u000aNigerian users whose accounts are frozen or whose transactions are blocked. An AI\u000d\u000asystem that misses genuine suspicious activity creates AML liability for the VASP that\u000d\u000arelied on it. The liability chain for AI-assisted compliance failures is not yet clearly defined\u000d\u000ain Nigerian law, but the NFIU\u2019s emerging guidance suggests that the responsible\u000d\u000a\u2014 119 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000ainstitution, not the technology provider, bears the AML reporting obligation and therefore\u000d\u000athe consequences of algorithmic failure.\u000d\u000aThe Compliance Technology Opportunity\u000d\u000aFounders building AI-assisted compliance solutions, transaction monitoring, KYC automation,\u000d\u000asanctions screening, STR generation, are building in a category where Nigerian regulators are not\u000d\u000aadversaries but potential customers. The NFIU, the CBN, and SEC Nigeria all face analytical capacity\u000d\u000achallenges that technology can address. A well-designed AI compliance product that can\u000d\u000ademonstrate accuracy, explainability, and regulatory alignment has a direct sales path to regulated\u000d\u000afinancial institutions across Nigeria and West Africa. This is the category where \u2018RegTech\u2019 is not a\u000d\u000adescriptor but a business model.\u000d\u000aAI Agents in Financial Systems: The Frontier Nobody Has Mapped\u000d\u000aThe third AI application category, and the one with the most regulatory uncertainty, is the\u000d\u000aautonomous AI agent operating in financial systems on behalf of users.\u000d\u000aThese products already exist in embryonic form: DeFi yield optimisers that automatically\u000d\u000amove user funds between protocols to maximise returns; AI trading bots that execute\u000d\u000astrategies on behalf of users based on market signals; automated portfolio rebalancing\u000d\u000aservices that adjust digital asset allocations without human intervention. Their more\u000d\u000aadvanced versions \u2014 AI agents with wallet access, capable of executing complex\u000d\u000amulti-step financial strategies across multiple protocols autonomously \u2014 are in\u000d\u000adevelopment globally.\u000d\u000aFrom a regulatory perspective, an AI agent with wallet access and the authority to execute\u000d\u000afinancial transactions is simultaneously: a potential VASP (if it transfers digital assets on\u000d\u000abehalf of users); a potential investment adviser (if it makes investment decisions on behalf\u000d\u000aof users); a potential payment service provider (if it moves funds); and a potential AML\u000d\u000arisk (if its decision-making cannot be audited in real time for suspicious activity patterns).\u000d\u000aAn AI agent that executes a suspicious transaction on behalf of a user does not\u000d\u000aeliminate the user\u2019s AML liability. It potentially creates two liability\u000d\u000a\u2014 120 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aquestions: the user\u2019s obligation to know what their agent is doing with their\u000d\u000afunds, and the platform\u2019s obligation to monitor and report the agent\u2019s activity.\u000d\u000aThere is no Nigerian regulatory framework that specifically governs AI agents in financial\u000d\u000asystems. The ARIP framework does not have a category for autonomous agent services.\u000d\u000aThe NFIU\u2019s VASP guidance does not address algorithmic trading or yield optimisation\u000d\u000aagents. The CBN\u2019s payment system rules do not contemplate AI-initiated payment\u000d\u000ainstructions.\u000d\u000aWhat exists is a set of first principles from existing frameworks that can be applied to\u000d\u000athese products. FATF\u2019s guidance: the obligation to identify the beneficial owner of the\u000d\u000afunds being transacted applies regardless of whether the transaction was initiated by a\u000d\u000ahuman or an algorithm. SEC Nigeria\u2019s investor protection rules: the obligation to ensure\u000d\u000athat financial products are suitable for the investors who use them does not disappear\u000d\u000abecause the suitability assessment is made by an AI rather than a human. The NDPA: the\u000d\u000aobligation to obtain informed consent for automated decision-making that significantly\u000d\u000aaffects individuals applies to AI financial agents as much as to AI credit scorers.\u000d\u000aThe founders building AI agent financial products in Nigeria today are operating in\u000d\u000agenuine regulatory whitespace. The framework that will eventually govern them is not yet\u000d\u000awritten. But its contours are visible in the frameworks that govern adjacent products, and\u000d\u000athe founders who design their AI agents for accountability, explainability, and human\u000d\u000aoverride capability now will be significantly better positioned when the regulation arrives\u000d\u000athan those who defer these design questions until forced.\u000d\u000aThe AI Governance Framework for Financial Products\u000d\u000aPending the passage of Nigeria\u2019s AI Governance Bill and the formalisation of\u000d\u000asector-specific AI guidance, the following framework provides the minimum governance\u000d\u000ainfrastructure that responsible AI financial product builders should implement now:\u000d\u000a1. Explainability by design \u2014 Every AI decision that affects a user, a credit decision, a transaction flag,\u000d\u000aa portfolio recommendation, an account restriction, must be explainable in plain language to the\u000d\u000aaffected user. This is required by the NDPA and expected by the CBN\u2019s sandbox evaluation framework.\u000d\u000a\u2014 121 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aBuild the explanation capability into the model architecture from the beginning, not as a\u000d\u000aretrospective add-on.\u000d\u000a2. Bias testing and ongoing monitoring \u2014 Before deployment and on a regular ongoing basis, test\u000d\u000ayour models for demographic bias using representative Nigerian data. Document the testing\u000d\u000amethodology and results. Implement alert mechanisms for performance degradation or demographic\u000d\u000ashift that might indicate emerging bias.\u000d\u000a3. Human override and escalation \u2014 Every AI system making consequential financial decisions must\u000d\u000ahave an accessible, clearly communicated mechanism for human review. A user who believes an AI\u000d\u000acredit decision was wrong must have a real person to appeal to. A transaction flagged by an AI\u000d\u000amonitoring system must have a human reviewer in the escalation path before account restriction is\u000d\u000aimposed.\u000d\u000a4. Data consent architecture \u2014 Map every data source used in your AI models. For each source,\u000d\u000adocument the consent obtained from users for that data\u2019s use in automated decision-making. Where\u000d\u000aconsent is inadequate, either obtain specific consent or remove the data from the model\u2019s feature\u000d\u000aset.\u000d\u000a5. Liability chain documentation \u2014 Document clearly, for users, for regulators, and for your own\u000d\u000aoperational risk management, what the AI system decides, what the human oversight layer reviews,\u000d\u000aand where the liability falls when the system makes a wrong decision. The Nigerian regulatory\u000d\u000aenvironment will eventually assign this liability. The founders who have thought through the answer\u000d\u000abefore being asked are the ones who will shape how the question is resolved.\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s National AI Strategy, launched by NITDA in 2025, targets AI contributing fifteen\u000d\u000abillion dollars to Nigeria\u2019s GDP by 2030. AI is ranked seventy-second out of one hundred\u000d\u000aand ninety-five countries in the Oxford Government AI Readiness Index, reflecting\u000d\u000agenuine institutional momentum but also the distance yet to travel. The CBN sandbox,\u000d\u000aexpanded in 2024-2025, now evaluates model explainability, fairness, and consumer\u000d\u000atransparency before granting approvals for AI-powered fintech tools. The direction is\u000d\u000aclear: AI financial products will be regulated, and the regulatory framework will be built\u000d\u000aaround accountability, explainability, and consumer protection.\u000d\u000aThe founders who build those properties into their products today are not merely\u000d\u000acomplying with a future mandate. They are building the most durable version of their\u000d\u000aproduct, the version that survives regulatory scrutiny, attracts institutional capital, and\u000d\u000aearns the trust of Nigerian users who have very reasonable grounds for scepticism about\u000d\u000aautomated systems that make decisions about their money.\u000d\u000a\u2014 122 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 123 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aPart Four\u000d\u000aThe Practice\u000d\u000aBeing Compliant on Paper vs. Regulator-Ready in Practice\u000d\u000a\u2014 124 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThis is the part of the book where the theory stops and the work begins.\u000d\u000aParts One through Three gave you the mindset, the map, and the product-level regulatory\u000d\u000aframeworks. Part Four gives you the operational infrastructure to act on all of it. Five\u000d\u000achapters. Each one a toolkit. Each one written for the person who will close this book,\u000d\u000aopen their laptop, and start building.\u000d\u000aChapter Fifteen builds your AML/CFT programme from the ground up \u2014 not as a\u000d\u000atheoretical construct but as a working operational system. Chapter Sixteen teaches you\u000d\u000ahow to initiate and sustain productive relationships with Nigerian regulators before you\u000d\u000aneed them in a crisis. Chapter Seventeen reframes the innovation sandbox from a\u000d\u000acompliance mechanism into a strategic launch tool. Chapter Eighteen gives the technical\u000d\u000afounder the compliance architecture blueprint that determines whether a company can\u000d\u000ascale without regulatory crisis. Chapter Nineteen is the chapter you hope you never need,\u000d\u000aand will be deeply grateful to have read if you do.\u000d\u000aA note on tone. Part Four is the most direct section of this book. It is, in places,\u000d\u000aprescriptive, it tells you what to do, in what order, by when. This prescriptiveness is\u000d\u000aintentional. The founders who survive regulatory complexity in Nigeria are not the ones\u000d\u000awho understand the principles most deeply. They are the ones who execute most\u000d\u000aconsistently. Principles without execution produce beautiful compliance manuals that\u000d\u000anobody follows.\u000d\u000aThis part is about execution.\u000d\u000a\u2014 125 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Fifteen\u000d\u000aBuilding Your AML/CFT Framework From Scratch\u000d\u000a\u201cA compliance manual that nobody reads is not a compliance programme. It is a liability document,\u000d\u000aevidence that you knew what was required and chose not to implement it.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aThere is a version of AML/CFT compliance that Nigerian digital asset companies perform\u000d\u000arather than practise. The manual exists. The policies are documented. The compliance\u000d\u000aofficer has a title. And if a regulator asks, the company can produce a thick folder of\u000d\u000adocuments that, on their face, describe a robust risk management system.\u000d\u000aThere is another version where the compliance programme actually works: where\u000d\u000asuspicious transactions are identified and investigated, where customer risk profiles are\u000d\u000agenuinely monitored over time, where the compliance officer has real authority and real\u000d\u000aexpertise, and where the policies describe what the company actually does rather than\u000d\u000awhat it intended to do when someone wrote the manual.\u000d\u000aThe gap between these two versions is the gap between being compliant on paper and\u000d\u000abeing regulator-ready in practice. This chapter closes that gap.\u000d\u000aThree specific failures recur in Nigerian VASP AML programmes above all others. They\u000d\u000aare the failures that cause companies to fail regulatory reviews, attract NFIU scrutiny, and\u000d\u000aexpose founders to personal liability under the MLPPA 2022. Understanding them, and\u000d\u000abuilding specifically to avoid them, is the foundation of everything in this chapter.\u000d\u000aFailure One: The Beautiful Manual Nobody Reads\u000d\u000aThe most common AML/CFT failure in Nigerian VASPs is not the absence of\u000d\u000adocumentation. It is the presence of documentation that has no operational reality behind\u000d\u000ait.\u000d\u000aA well-written AML manual that describes transaction monitoring thresholds, alert\u000d\u000ainvestigation procedures, STR filing timelines, and staff training requirements is worse\u000d\u000a\u2014 126 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000athan no manual at all if the transaction monitoring system generates alerts that sit in a\u000d\u000aqueue for weeks, if STRs are filed months after the suspicious activity was identified, and\u000d\u000aif the last staff AML training session was conducted the day before the ARIP application\u000d\u000awas submitted and has not been repeated since.\u000d\u000aWhy does this happen? Because founding teams build the documentation under deadline\u000d\u000apressure, for a licence application, for an investor due diligence process, for an NFIU\u000d\u000aregistration, and then return to the work of building the product. The compliance\u000d\u000ainfrastructure is treated as a one-time deliverable rather than an ongoing operational\u000d\u000asystem. The manual is accurate on the day it is written. It becomes progressively less\u000d\u000aaccurate with every month that passes without the procedures being tested against real\u000d\u000atransactions, real alerts, and real suspicious activity.\u000d\u000aThe NFIU\u2019s supervisory reviews do not assess documentation quality. They assess\u000d\u000aoperational reality. An NFIU examination involves reviewing actual STR filing records,\u000d\u000aactual alert investigation logs, actual customer risk assessment histories, and actual staff\u000d\u000atraining attendance records. A company that has beautiful documentation but cannot\u000d\u000ademonstrate that any of it has been operationalised will fail that examination regardless of\u000d\u000athe quality of its manual.\u000d\u000aThe Operational Test\u000d\u000aBefore any regulatory examination, test your AML programme against one simple question: if an\u000d\u000aexaminer asked me to show them the last five suspicious transaction reports we filed, including\u000d\u000athe investigation notes that supported each filing, could I produce them within thirty minutes? If\u000d\u000athe answer is no \u2014 because the STRs have not been filed, because the investigation notes do not\u000d\u000aexist, or because the records are in a system that nobody knows how to access, your compliance\u000d\u000aprogramme has failed the operational test regardless of what your manual says.\u000d\u000aThe solution is not more documentation. It is operational cadence: a regular,\u000d\u000acalendar-based compliance cycle that makes AML activities routine rather than\u000d\u000aexceptional.\u000d\u000aThe minimum operational cadence for a Nigerian VASP compliance programme is:\u000d\u000a\u2014 127 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aDaily Transaction alert review\u000d\u000aA designated compliance team member reviews all system-generated transaction monitoring alerts.\u000d\u000aEach alert is either cleared with documented reasoning or escalated to investigation. No alert sits\u000d\u000aunreviewed for more than 24 hours.\u000d\u000aWeek\u000d\u000aly\u000d\u000aPEP and sanctions re-screening\u000d\u000aThe customer database is re-screened against updated PEP lists and sanctions lists. New matches are\u000d\u000aflagged for EDD review. Re-screening results are logged with timestamps.\u000d\u000aMont\u000d\u000ahly\u000d\u000aPEP register submission to NFIU\u000d\u000aThe PEP register is submitted to the NFIU via the goAML portal, as required under NFIU guidelines.\u000d\u000aThe submission record is retained for audit purposes.\u000d\u000aQuart\u000d\u000aerly\u000d\u000aCompliance training and AML/CFT testing\u000d\u000aAll staff with customer-facing or transaction-processing roles complete AML/CFT training. Results and\u000d\u000aattendance are documented. The NFIU requires quarterly compliance training evidence.\u000d\u000aAnnu\u000d\u000aally\u000d\u000aBusiness-wide risk assessment review\u000d\u000aThe Business-Wide Risk Assessment (BWRA) is reviewed and updated to reflect changes in the\u000d\u000aplatform\u2019s product mix, customer demographics, transaction patterns, and regulatory environment.\u000d\u000aThe updated BWRA is submitted to the NFIU as required.\u000d\u000aFailure Two: The Onboarding KYC That Never Grows Up\u000d\u000aThe second structural failure is subtler and more technically demanding: building a KYC\u000d\u000ainfrastructure that is excellent at onboarding and useless for everything that comes after.\u000d\u000aMost Nigerian VASP KYC programmes are designed to answer one question: is this\u000d\u000acustomer who they say they are at the moment they sign up? They collect the NIN, the\u000d\u000aBVN, the government-issued ID, the selfie, the address. They screen against sanctions and\u000d\u000aPEP lists at onboarding. They assign a risk tier. And then, in most cases, they do nothing\u000d\u000afurther with the customer\u2019s risk profile until something goes wrong.\u000d\u000aThis is the onboarding KYC trap. It creates a compliance infrastructure that is excellent at\u000d\u000athe front door and blind everywhere else.\u000d\u000a\u2014 128 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe practical problem is that financial crime patterns are dynamic. A customer who\u000d\u000aappears low-risk at onboarding may develop transaction behaviour six months later that\u000d\u000ais entirely inconsistent with their stated profile. A customer who was not a PEP at signup\u000d\u000amay become one when they are appointed to a public office. A customer whose address\u000d\u000awas in a low-risk jurisdiction may move to a FATF grey-listed country. A customer who\u000d\u000atransacted small amounts at onboarding may begin processing volumes that are entirely\u000d\u000adisproportionate to their stated income and business purpose.\u000d\u000aUnder the MLPPA 2022 and the NFIU\u2019s AML/CFT guidelines, the obligation for ongoing\u000d\u000amonitoring is explicit: financial institutions including VASPs must monitor customer\u000d\u000atransactions on a continuous basis, conduct periodic customer due diligence reviews, and\u000d\u000aupdate customer risk classifications when material changes occur. The re-screening\u000d\u000aobligation for PEPs and sanctions is ongoing, not a one-time onboarding check.\u000d\u000aCompliance begins at onboarding. It does not end there. The customer you\u000d\u000averified on day one is not necessarily the customer you are serving on day three\u000d\u000ahundred. Your compliance system must know the difference.\u000d\u000aBuilding ongoing monitoring capability requires three specific infrastructure investments\u000d\u000athat most early-stage VASPs defer:\u000d\u000a1. A customer risk profile that updates over time \u2014 The customer risk tier assigned at onboarding\u000d\u000ashould be a dynamic field, not a static one. Transaction volume, transaction frequency, counterparty\u000d\u000apatterns, geographic exposure, and product usage should all trigger automatic risk profile reviews\u000d\u000awhen they breach configured thresholds. A customer who was tier-one at onboarding and tier-three\u000d\u000aby month six should have a documented audit trail of why and when the re-classification occurred.\u000d\u000a2. A re-screening schedule with documented outcomes \u2014 PEP and sanctions screening must occur\u000d\u000aat onboarding and at regular intervals thereafter. The minimum practical schedule is weekly\u000d\u000are-screening for all active customers. The re-screening must produce documented results \u2014 not just a\u000d\u000alog that it occurred, but a record of what was checked against what list, at what time, and what the\u000d\u000aoutcome was. This is the evidence that the NFIU examines.\u000d\u000a3. A transaction-to-profile comparison mechanism \u2014 The most consequential ongoing monitoring\u000d\u000afunction is the comparison of actual transaction behaviour against the expected behaviour profile\u000d\u000aestablished at onboarding. A market trader who declared a monthly income of \u20a6200,000 and is\u000d\u000aprocessing \u20a620 million per month six months later has a transaction pattern that is inconsistent with\u000d\u000a\u2014 129 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000atheir stated profile. The system must identify this automatically, trigger a review, and document the\u000d\u000ainvestigation outcome.\u000d\u000aSTRs must be filed immediately upon identifying suspicious activity, not after the\u000d\u000asuspicious activity has been fully investigated, and not after it has been confirmed as\u000d\u000acriminal. The obligation under the MLPPA 2022 is to file when you have grounds for\u000d\u000asuspicion. The NFIU\u2019s goAML portal accepts electronic STR submissions and the filing\u000d\u000arecords are directly accessible to examiners. Failure to file an STR within the required\u000d\u000atimeframe after suspicious activity is identified is a separate and distinct compliance\u000d\u000abreach from the suspicious activity itself.\u000d\u000aFailure Three: The Compliance Officer Who Is Not a Compliance Officer\u000d\u000aThe third structural failure is the most consequential because it is the one that no amount\u000d\u000aof documentation or technology can compensate for: the appointment of a compliance\u000d\u000aofficer who does not have the knowledge, experience, or organisational authority to\u000d\u000aactually run an AML/CFT programme.\u000d\u000aThe pattern is consistent and recognisable. A co-founder with a legal background is given\u000d\u000athe compliance officer title because the licence application requires one. Or the company\u2019s\u000d\u000aaccountant assumes responsibility for compliance because \u2018it\u2019s all regulatory stuff\u000d\u000aanyway.\u2019 Or a junior team member is appointed because they expressed interest and\u000d\u000asomebody needed to do it. The title is real. The expertise is not.\u000d\u000aThe consequences are predictable. AML/CFT compliance for a digital asset platform\u000d\u000arequires specific knowledge: of the MLPPA 2022\u2019s obligations, of the NFIU\u2019s reporting\u000d\u000arequirements and goAML portal, of transaction monitoring methodologies, of blockchain\u000d\u000aanalytics tools, of the specific financial crime typologies relevant to Nigerian digital asset\u000d\u000amarkets, and of how to conduct and document investigation of suspicious activity. A\u000d\u000alawyer who has not been specifically trained in financial crime compliance does not have\u000d\u000athis knowledge. An accountant who has not worked in AML does not have it. A junior\u000d\u000ateam member who took an online course does not have it.\u000d\u000a\u2014 130 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe NFIU and SEC Nigeria both require that the compliance officer or Money Laundering\u000d\u000aReporting Officer (MLRO) be a person of sufficient seniority, independence, and expertise\u000d\u000ato discharge their obligations effectively. The compliance officer must be registered on the\u000d\u000agoAML portal as the reporting entity\u2019s designated MLRO. The SEC requires that\u000d\u000acompliance officer appointments be approved before the individual assumes the role. Both\u000d\u000arequirements are designed to prevent the \u2018nominal compliance officer\u2019 problem \u2014 and\u000d\u000aboth are enforced.\u000d\u000aThe Personal Liability Dimension\u000d\u000aThe MLPPA 2022 creates personal criminal liability for compliance officers who knowingly fail to\u000d\u000areport suspicious transactions. This is not a theoretical risk. An MLRO who is aware of suspicious\u000d\u000aactivity and fails to file an STR, or who advises management to delay filing, faces fines and\u000d\u000aimprisonment. This liability does not attach to a competent professional who applies good judgment\u000d\u000ain difficult circumstances. It attaches to someone who lacks the knowledge to identify suspicious\u000d\u000aactivity, the authority to act on it, or the integrity to report it despite management pressure. The\u000d\u000acompliance officer title is not ceremonial. It carries real legal consequences.\u000d\u000aThe minimum qualification standard for a Nigerian VASP\u2019s compliance officer is:\u000d\u000ademonstrated specific training in AML/CFT for financial services or digital assets (not\u000d\u000ageneral legal training), practical familiarity with the NFIU\u2019s goAML reporting system,\u000d\u000aunderstanding of the MLPPA 2022\u2019s obligations for VASPs, and sufficient organisational\u000d\u000aseniority to escalate concerns to the board without management interference. The\u000d\u000aCertified Cryptocurrency Compliance Specialist (3CS) certification, referenced in NFIU\u000d\u000aguidance, is one recognised pathway.\u000d\u000aThe Minimum Viable Compliance Stack\u000d\u000aHaving addressed the three structural failures, here is the minimum compliance\u000d\u000ainfrastructure every Nigerian VASP must have operational before it begins serving\u000d\u000acustomers:\u000d\u000a1 NFIU registration on goAML portal\u000d\u000aRegister as a reporting entity on the NFIU\u2019s goAML portal. Submit the letter of introduction, CAC\u000d\u000adocuments, industry regulator licence, compliance officer appointment evidence, and regulator\u000d\u000a\u2014 131 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aapproval. This is a separate registration from your SEC ARIP application and must be completed\u000d\u000aindependently.\u000d\u000a2 Business-Wide Risk Assessment (BWRA)\u000d\u000aDocument your platform\u2019s specific money laundering and terrorist financing risks \u2014 the products you\u000d\u000aoffer, the customers you serve, the geographies you operate in, and the transaction channels you\u000d\u000asupport. This is not a generic template. It must reflect your specific risk profile. The NFIU examines it.\u000d\u000a3 KYC tiering framework\u000d\u000aDocument your tiered KYC approach: what identity verification is required at each tier, what\u000d\u000atransaction limits apply to each tier, what triggers a tier upgrade, and what EDD requirements apply\u000d\u000ato high-risk customers and PEPs. Map this to NIN and BVN verification at minimum for Nigerian\u000d\u000aindividuals.\u000d\u000a4 Transaction monitoring system\u000d\u000aImplement a configured transaction monitoring system with documented thresholds, alert types, and\u000d\u000ainvestigation workflows. The system must generate alerts. The alerts must be reviewed. The reviews\u000d\u000amust be documented.\u000d\u000a5 Sanctions and PEP screening\u000d\u000aImplement ongoing screening against OFAC, UN Security Council, EU, and Nigerian domestic\u000d\u000adesignation lists. Screening must occur at onboarding and on a scheduled ongoing basis. Results must\u000d\u000abe logged.\u000d\u000a6 STR and CTR filing capability\u000d\u000aEstablish your STR and CTR filing workflow on the goAML portal. Conduct a test filing before you\u000d\u000abegin live customer operations. \u20a35 million cash equivalent for individuals, \u20a310 million for corporate\u000d\u000aentities triggers a CTR. Suspicious activity triggers an STR immediately upon identification.\u000d\u000a7 Record retention infrastructure\u000d\u000aAll customer identification records, transaction records, and compliance investigation records must\u000d\u000abe retained for a minimum of five years after the transaction or relationship ends. This must be in a\u000d\u000aformat that is accessible, searchable, and demonstrably tamper-proof.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 132 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Sixteen\u000d\u000aHow to Engage a Regulator Before They Engage\u000d\u000aYou\u000d\u000a\u201cThe regulator who knows your name is never the regulator you are afraid of.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aIn 1997, the Rwandan government convened a gathering of central bank officials from\u000d\u000aacross Africa to examine the emerging phenomenon of mobile money and its implications\u000d\u000afor monetary policy. One of the directors in attendance, a senior CBN official I met years\u000d\u000alater, at a training I facilitated in Kigali in 2023, made a remark that has stayed with me\u000d\u000asince the day he made it.\u000d\u000aWe had been discussing Nigeria\u2019s relationship with cryptocurrency, and I had raised the\u000d\u000aobservation that many in the industry felt the CBN had failed to regulate the space. He\u000d\u000areplied, with complete composure: \u201cNot regulating crypto is our regulation.\u201d\u000d\u000aI was, in his word, dumbfounded. And then, slowly, I understood.\u000d\u000aWhat he was describing was not negligence or avoidance. It was a deliberate institutional\u000d\u000aposture: the decision not to provide a framework is itself a framework. It signals risk. It\u000d\u000acreates deterrence. It preserves optionality for the institution while imposing compliance\u000d\u000acosts on the market. Regulators who do not yet understand a technology make a rational\u000d\u000achoice to withhold blessing rather than risk validating something they cannot yet\u000d\u000asupervise.\u000d\u000aThe implication for founders is direct and consequential: the regulator\u2019s silence is not an\u000d\u000ainvitation. It is a signal of institutional uncertainty, and the founders who respond to that\u000d\u000auncertainty by helping the regulator understand what they are doing, rather than by\u000d\u000atreating the silence as permission, are the ones who build productive relationships before\u000d\u000athe framework arrives.\u000d\u000aThis chapter is about how to do that.\u000d\u000a\u2014 133 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe Psychology of the First Engagement\u000d\u000aThree things are true about Nigerian regulators in a first engagement with a digital asset\u000d\u000afounder, and understanding all three simultaneously is what determines whether the\u000d\u000ameeting produces a relationship or a file.\u000d\u000aFirst: they are not in a hurry to regulate and they have accepted that innovation must\u000d\u000aoutpace the regulatory response. This is not resignation, it is pragmatism. Regulators who\u000d\u000ahave watched the Nigerian market long enough understand that the ecosystem will evolve\u000d\u000afaster than any framework can anticipate. The founders who acknowledge this reality,\u000d\u000awho do not present their product as something the regulator must immediately\u000d\u000aunderstand and approve, but as something the regulator can learn about over time\u000d\u000athrough engagement, are received with more openness than the founders who arrive with\u000d\u000aa deck designed to compress a licensing conversation into a single meeting.\u000d\u000aSecond: regulators carry institutional memory of every bad actor who occupied your\u000d\u000aproduct category before you. Every exchange that collapsed. Every P2P platform that was\u000d\u000aused for forex manipulation. Every token sale that turned out to be a Ponzi scheme. Every\u000d\u000afounder who promised compliance and delivered chaos. That memory is present in the\u000d\u000aroom before you open your mouth. Your job in the first engagement is not to prove your\u000d\u000aproduct works. It is to create sufficient distance from that history, through your\u000d\u000aseriousness of purpose, your preparation, and your willingness to acknowledge the\u000d\u000alegitimate concerns that produced it, before any substantive conversation can happen.\u000d\u000aThird: the first meeting is almost never about the subject on the agenda. It is about\u000d\u000awhether a productive relationship is possible at all. The regulator is assessing you\u000d\u000apersonally: Are you credible? Are you here for the long term? Do you understand what\u000d\u000athey are responsible for? Are you the kind of founder who will still be operating\u000d\u000acompliantly in two years, or the kind who will find a workaround the moment the\u000d\u000aregulatory inconvenience becomes commercially significant? The founder who treats the\u000d\u000afirst meeting as a relationship-building exercise, who asks more questions than they\u000d\u000aanswer, who listens more than they present, and who leaves without closing any asks,\u000d\u000aalmost always leaves with more than the one who arrives with a pitch.\u000d\u000a\u2014 134 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe most valuable thing that came from my call to the CBN the day the 2021 circular\u000d\u000adropped was not information. It was the continuation of a relationship that had been\u000d\u000abuilt over four years of showing up, being credible, and asking more questions than I\u000d\u000aanswered. That relationship was the reason the call was answered.\u000d\u000aBuilding the Relationship: The Four-Stage Framework\u000d\u000aProductive regulator relationships in Nigeria are not built in single meetings. They are\u000d\u000abuilt over time, through a sequence of engagements that each add a layer of trust,\u000d\u000afamiliarity, and credibility. The four stages below describe this sequence for the\u000d\u000arelationship with SEC Nigeria, the CBN, and the NFIU, the three most consequential\u000d\u000aregulatory relationships for most Nigerian digital asset founders.\u000d\u000aStage 1. Establish your institutional credibility before seeking any engagement \u2014 Before\u000d\u000aapproaching a regulator directly, ensure your institutional footprint is visible and credible. This means\u000d\u000abeing active in industry bodies, BNUG, FintechNGR, BiCON, that have established credibility with the\u000d\u000arelevant regulators. Regulators check. A founder who claims to represent a significant digital asset\u000d\u000abusiness but who has no visible presence in the industry\u2019s organised structures starts from a weaker\u000d\u000aposition than one whose name is already known through legitimate industry participation. Your\u000d\u000acredibility is partly borrowed from the organisations whose spaces you occupy.\u000d\u000aStage 2. Make your first contact informational, not transactional \u2014 The first formal engagement\u000d\u000awith a regulator should have no ask. It should be an introduction, a brief, well-prepared request to\u000d\u000apresent your business and your understanding of the regulatory landscape to the relevant\u000d\u000adepartment, with the explicit framing that you are seeking to understand the Commission\u2019s\u000d\u000aperspective on your product category, not to request any specific action. This framing is not\u000d\u000amanipulative. It is honest: you genuinely need to understand the regulator\u2019s view before you can\u000d\u000adesign a compliant product. And it positions you as a cooperative actor rather than a supplicant.\u000d\u000aStage 3. Demonstrate consistency before making substantive requests \u2014 Between your first\u000d\u000ainformational engagement and any substantive request, for a pre-screening conversation, for ARIP\u000d\u000aapplication guidance, for informal comment on a product structure, maintain a visible presence in the\u000d\u000aindustry dialogue. File your NFIU registration. Participate in consultation processes. Submit written\u000d\u000acomments on exposure drafts. Attend the workshops and training sessions that regulators host. The\u000d\u000apattern you are building is one of consistent engagement and institutional seriousness. This pattern is\u000d\u000awhat the regulator checks when your substantive request arrives.\u000d\u000aStage 4. Make the substantive ask precisely and in writing \u2014 When you are ready to make a\u000d\u000asubstantive request, a pre-screening meeting, an informal product classification opinion, a request for\u000d\u000a\u2014 135 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000asandbox consideration, make it in writing, with precision. Describe your product clearly. Identify the\u000d\u000aspecific regulatory question you are seeking to discuss. Reference the relevant provisions of ISA 2025\u000d\u000aor the SEC Digital Asset Rules. Propose a specific agenda and timeframe for the meeting. A precise,\u000d\u000awell-written request demonstrates competence and respect for the official\u2019s time. It also creates a\u000d\u000apaper trail of your good-faith engagement that becomes relevant if the regulatory relationship ever\u000d\u000abecomes adversarial.\u000d\u000aThe Regulator Meeting: What To Do and What Not To Do\u000d\u000aThe practical mechanics of a regulatory meeting with the CBN, SEC Nigeria, or NFIU\u000d\u000adeserve specific attention, because the behavioural mistakes founders make in these\u000d\u000ameetings are consistent and preventable.\u000d\u000aWhat to do:\u000d\u000a\u2022 Arrive with a one-page briefing document that the official can keep. It should contain your company\u000d\u000aname, product description, regulatory classification question, and the specific topics you would like to\u000d\u000acover. This document does two things: it demonstrates preparation, and it gives the official something\u000d\u000atangible after the meeting that will not be lost in the follow-up email chain.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Open the meeting by acknowledging the regulator\u2019s mandate and the legitimacy of their concern\u000d\u000aabout your product category. Explicitly. This is not flattery. It is an acknowledgement that creates the\u000d\u000acollaborative frame in which productive conversation is possible.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Ask about the regulator\u2019s current priorities and concerns in your product area before presenting your\u000d\u000aown views. The intelligence this produces is worth more than any answer you could give to a question\u000d\u000athat has not been asked.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Leave time for informal conversation at the end of the formal agenda. This is where relationships are\u000d\u000abuilt. The official who has been formal throughout the meeting may be significantly more\u000d\u000aforthcoming about the institution\u2019s actual thinking once the agenda is finished.\u000d\u000aWhat not to do:\u000d\u000a\u2022 Do not use language that implies the regulator has failed by not yet having a framework for your\u000d\u000aproduct. \u2018There\u2019s a regulatory gap here\u2019 translates in many officials\u2019 ears as \u2018you are behind and I am\u000d\u000ahere to help you catch up.\u2019 Frame the absence of a specific framework as an opportunity for\u000d\u000acollaborative development, not an oversight.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Do not over-present. A sixty-slide deck for a first regulatory meeting is not preparation. It is\u000d\u000aintimidation. Five slides or a single-page document is almost always more effective.\u000d\u000a\u2014 136 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a\u2022 Do not make commitments you cannot keep. If you say you will submit a product paper within two\u000d\u000aweeks, submit it within two weeks. The regulatory relationship is built on every interaction, and a\u000d\u000amissed commitment in a low-stakes context creates doubt about your reliability in high-stakes ones.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Do not bring your lawyer to the first meeting. A lawyer\u2019s presence signals adversarial framing, that\u000d\u000ayou are there to protect your position rather than build a relationship. Bring your lawyer when the\u000d\u000arelationship has matured to the point where specific legal questions are on the table.\u000d\u000aWhen the Regulator Engages You First\u000d\u000aEverything in this chapter to this point has been about proactive engagement, building the\u000d\u000arelationship before the regulator initiates contact. But what happens when the contact\u000d\u000acomes from the other direction?\u000d\u000aThe principles are the same, applied under different time pressure. The regulator who\u000d\u000asends you a letter, issues a query, or calls for a meeting has already formed a preliminary\u000d\u000aview of your business. Your job in the first response is to provide sufficient reassurance\u000d\u000athat the preliminary view is either wrong or incomplete, and to do so in a way that opens\u000d\u000aa dialogue rather than closing one.\u000d\u000aThe specific failure modes in this scenario are addressed in detail in Chapter Nineteen.\u000d\u000aThe principle to carry from this chapter is: the quality of the relationship you have built\u000d\u000abefore the regulator\u2019s contact determines almost entirely how that contact goes. A founder\u000d\u000awho has filed their NFIU registration, initiated the ARIP process, maintained visible\u000d\u000aindustry participation, and has a documented history of good-faith engagement is a\u000d\u000adifferent subject of regulatory inquiry from a founder who is entirely unknown to the\u000d\u000arelevant institutions when the letter arrives.\u000d\u000aThe Relationship Investment Calculation\u000d\u000aEvery hour you invest in building regulatory relationships before you need them is worth\u000d\u000aapproximately ten hours of crisis management after a regulatory notice arrives. This is not a\u000d\u000ametaphor. It is the observed ratio in every regulatory crisis I have seen managed well versus poorly.\u000d\u000aThe founders who have relationships walk into the regulator\u2019s office when the letter comes. The\u000d\u000afounders who do not send a lawyer and wait three weeks for a response.\u000d\u000a\u2014 137 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 138 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Seventeen\u000d\u000aUsing the Innovation Sandbox as a Launch\u000d\u000aStrategy\u000d\u000a\u201cThe sandbox does not exist to protect you from regulation. It exists to put you inside the regulatory\u000d\u000aconversation at the moment when the conversation is most open to influence.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aMost founders approach the SEC Nigeria ARIP framework and the CBN\u2019s Regulatory\u000d\u000aSandbox as compliance mechanisms, pathways to obtain permission to operate that must\u000d\u000abe navigated as efficiently as possible before getting on with the real business of building\u000d\u000aand growing.\u000d\u000aThis framing misses everything valuable about the sandbox.\u000d\u000aThe sandbox is not a waiting room. It is the most strategically productive environment a\u000d\u000aNigerian digital asset company can occupy in its first twelve months of regulated\u000d\u000aoperation. The founders who understand this, and who use the sandbox with strategic\u000d\u000aintentionality rather than treating it as a necessary bureaucratic obstacle, emerge from it\u000d\u000awith advantages that are not available to any other market participant.\u000d\u000aFour specific advantages. All of them real. All of them time-limited.\u000d\u000aThe Intelligence Advantage\u000d\u000aThe twelve months inside the ARIP sandbox give you something that no market research,\u000d\u000ano industry report, and no legal opinion can provide: direct access to the regulatory\u000d\u000athinking of the institution that will govern your market for the foreseeable future.\u000d\u000aDuring the AIP period, you receive feedback on your product design, your compliance\u000d\u000ainfrastructure, and your operational practices from the Commission\u2019s technical staff, the\u000d\u000apeople who are simultaneously developing the permanent regulatory framework. The\u000d\u000aquestions they ask, the concerns they flag, the additional documentation they request, all\u000d\u000a\u2014 139 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aof it is intelligence about the direction of regulatory travel that your unlicensed\u000d\u000acompetitors do not have.\u000d\u000aA founder who pays careful attention to the nature of the Commission\u2019s queries during\u000d\u000athe AIP period, and who understands them as signals of the framework\u2019s emerging\u000d\u000apriorities rather than mere administrative requests, will emerge from the sandbox with a\u000d\u000astructural product advantage. Their compliance infrastructure will be calibrated to the\u000d\u000aCommission\u2019s actual concerns, not to a general reading of the published rules. Their\u000d\u000aproduct design will have been tested against regulatory scrutiny and adjusted\u000d\u000aaccordingly. Their permanent licence application will be a formality, not a negotiation.\u000d\u000aThe Intelligence Practice\u000d\u000aKeep a detailed log of every formal and informal communication from the Commission during your\u000d\u000aAIP period. Every query. Every comment on your quarterly reports. Every informal observation\u000d\u000afrom the Commission\u2019s technical staff. Review this log quarterly and ask: what pattern of concern\u000d\u000ais this revealing? What does it tell me about what the permanent framework will emphasise? Then\u000d\u000aadjust your product and compliance architecture accordingly, before the permanent framework\u000d\u000amakes adjustment mandatory.\u000d\u000aThe Relationship Asymmetry Advantage\u000d\u000aThe sandbox creates the most asymmetric relationship in the Nigerian digital asset\u000d\u000amarket, and most founders squander it.\u000d\u000aDuring the AIP period, the Commission wants you to succeed. Not because of any\u000d\u000aparticular affection for your specific business, but because the ARIP programme\u2019s\u000d\u000acredibility depends on producing functioning, compliant, licensed operators. A successful\u000d\u000aARIP graduate who transitions to full SEC registration is evidence that the programme\u000d\u000aworks. A failed AIP holder who cannot demonstrate operational compliance is a problem\u000d\u000afor the Commission as much as for the company.\u000d\u000aThis creates an unusual dynamic: the regulator\u2019s interests and the founder\u2019s interests are\u000d\u000aaligned in a way that they are at no other point in the regulatory relationship. The\u000d\u000aCommission\u2019s technical staff are genuinely available during the AIP period to answer\u000d\u000aquestions, provide informal guidance, and help the company understand what the\u000d\u000a\u2014 140 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCommission\u2019s expectations actually mean in operational terms. This availability is not\u000d\u000aavailable to unlicensed operators or to companies that have not yet entered the ARIP\u000d\u000aprocess. It is exclusively available to AIP holders, and it expires when the AIP period\u000d\u000aends.\u000d\u000aThe founders who extract maximum value from this asymmetry are the ones who ask\u000d\u000asubstantive questions early, who request informal guidance on specific compliance\u000d\u000ascenarios, and who treat the Commission\u2019s technical staff as partners in building an\u000d\u000aoperationally sound compliance programme rather than as assessors to be managed at\u000d\u000aarm\u2019s length.\u000d\u000aThe Market Signal Advantage\u000d\u000aThe ARIP approval letter is not a licence. But it is the most credible market signal available\u000d\u000ato an early-stage Nigerian digital asset company, and it is worth significantly more to your\u000d\u000ainstitutional relationships than most founders realise.\u000d\u000aFor institutional investors considering a Nigerian digital asset investment, the ARIP\u000d\u000aapproval answers the most consequential due diligence question: is this company\u000d\u000aoperating legally? The answer \u2018yes, under SEC Nigeria\u2019s ARIP framework\u2019 transforms the\u000d\u000arisk profile of the investment. Without it, an institutional investor must either conduct\u000d\u000atheir own regulatory analysis of the company\u2019s compliance status (expensive, slow) or\u000d\u000aaccept a risk that most institutional mandates explicitly prohibit. With it, the question is\u000d\u000aanswered before it is asked.\u000d\u000aFor banking partners, the ARIP approval is the CBN\u2019s indirect signal that the company\u000d\u000acan be served. The CBN\u2019s 2023 VASP guidelines allow banks to open naira accounts for\u000d\u000aSEC-licensed digital asset companies. Without the ARIP approval, you cannot access this\u000d\u000aguidance. With it, your banking conversations transform from \u2018we cannot service your\u000d\u000atype of business\u2019 to \u2018what are your KYC documents?\u2019\u000d\u000aFor business development partnerships with regulated entities, banks, insurance\u000d\u000acompanies, payment processors, the ARIP approval answers the compliance team\u2019s\u000d\u000aquestion before the commercial team has finished their pitch. Regulated entities cannot\u000d\u000a\u2014 141 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000apartner with unregulated ones without a regulatory analysis of the risks. The ARIP\u000d\u000aapproval short-circuits this analysis.\u000d\u000aThe Compliance Proof Advantage\u000d\u000aThe fourth and most durable advantage of the sandbox is the one that founders least\u000d\u000aexpect: the ARIP process proves that your compliance infrastructure works, under real\u000d\u000aconditions, before the permanent licence assessment requires it to.\u000d\u000aThe twelve months of the AIP period are a live test of your KYC programme, your\u000d\u000atransaction monitoring system, your STR filing capability, your PEP screening, your\u000d\u000arecord retention, and your governance. Real customers. Real transactions. Real alerts. Real\u000d\u000afilings. The Commission observes all of it, through your quarterly reports, your audit\u000d\u000asubmissions, and its periodic examinations.\u000d\u000aThe founders who enter the full registration assessment with twelve months of\u000d\u000adocumented, operational, Commission-observed compliance history are in a categorically\u000d\u000adifferent position from those who construct a compliance system in the month before their\u000d\u000aapplication. The former has evidence. The latter has assertions.\u000d\u000aThe sandbox is not a shortcut to a licence. It is the most direct path to a licence\u000d\u000athat cannot be challenged. Every month of documented, observed compliance\u000d\u000aduring the AIP period is a month of unimpeachable evidence that your\u000d\u000aprogramme works.\u000d\u000aA practical note on the CBN\u2019s Regulatory Sandbox, which is distinct from the SEC\u2019s ARIP\u000d\u000abut serves complementary purposes for payment and banking-adjacent digital products.\u000d\u000aThe CBN sandbox is designed for payment innovation, open banking applications, and\u000d\u000afinancial inclusion products rather than specifically for digital asset securities. For\u000d\u000afounders whose product straddles both domains, as most stablecoin and\u000d\u000apayment-integrated digital asset products do, engagement with both sandboxes\u000d\u000asimultaneously is not merely permitted but strategically valuable. The two regulatory\u000d\u000arelationships reinforce each other, and the CBN\u2019s sandbox engagement creates exactly the\u000d\u000a\u2014 142 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000akind of visibility that supports the CBN\u2019s eventual relaxation of restrictions for your\u000d\u000aproduct category.\u000d\u000aThe Sandbox Application: What Gets You In\u000d\u000aThe ARIP initial assessment requires four core components, each of which is assessed for\u000d\u000aquality and completeness before a processing fee is accepted and the formal review\u000d\u000abegins.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Available from the SEC\u2019s website. Complete every field. The questions about corporate structure,\u000d\u000aproduct description, and intended regulatory category are the foundation of the Commission\u2019s\u000d\u000aclassification assessment. The Initial Assessment Form\u000d\u000a\u2022 As described in Chapter Eleven \u2014 a technical and legal disclosure document, not a marketing\u000d\u000adocument. It must address product architecture, token economics if applicable, AML/CFT\u000d\u000aframework, investor risk factors, and the legal basis for the regulatory classification you are\u000d\u000aclaiming. The Draft White Paper\u000d\u000a\u2022 CAC Certificate of Incorporation, proof of paid-up capital at the minimum required level for your\u000d\u000acategory, and documentation of the source of that capital. Evidence of Nigerian incorporation and\u000d\u000acapitalisation\u000d\u000a\u2022 Evidence that you have appointed a qualified compliance officer or MLRO and that they have been\u000d\u000aregistered on the NFIU\u2019s goAML portal as the entity\u2019s reporting officer. Compliance officer\u000d\u000aappointment documentation\u000d\u000aThe Timing Strategy\u000d\u000aThe optimal timing for an ARIP application is when you have completed your product design,\u000d\u000aestablished your corporate structure, deposited your minimum capital, appointed your compliance\u000d\u000aofficer, and initiated but not launched customer operations. Applying before you are operationally\u000d\u000aready creates the risk of failing the AIP period\u2019s compliance demonstrations. Waiting until you are\u000d\u000aalready serving customers without authorisation creates unnecessary regulatory exposure. The\u000d\u000asweet spot is: product built, compliance infrastructure deployed, capital in place, ready to launch\u000d\u000aunder regulatory oversight rather than before it.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 143 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Eighteen\u000d\u000aCompliance-First Product Architecture: Building\u000d\u000aIt Right From Day One\u000d\u000a\u201cThe compliance debt you accumulate in your first six months of development will compound for years.\u000d\u000aThe founders who build it right the first time do not pay that debt. They invest that capital in growth\u000d\u000ainstead.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aThis chapter is written specifically for the technical founder: the CEO who is also the lead\u000d\u000aengineer, the CTO who makes the architecture decisions, the product manager who\u000d\u000aspecifies the data model, and the developer who will live with the structural choices made\u000d\u000ain the next six months for the next six years.\u000d\u000aThe compliance failures described in Chapter Fifteen are mostly operational failures,\u000d\u000aprogrammes that existed but were not followed. The failures described in this chapter are\u000d\u000aarchitectural ones: products that were built in ways that make meaningful compliance\u000d\u000astructurally impossible, or possible only at the cost of a complete rebuild.\u000d\u000aThese failures are more expensive to fix than operational ones, because they are embedded\u000d\u000ain the codebase. And they are made earlier, in the product\u2019s first months, when the\u000d\u000afounding team is moving fast and the pressure to ship overrides the discipline to build\u000d\u000acorrectly.\u000d\u000aFour architecture decisions define whether compliance can be built in or must be rebuilt.\u000d\u000aAll four of them from your answers. All four of them foundational.\u000d\u000aArchitecture Decision One: The Identity and KYC Data Model\u000d\u000aThe most consequential single architecture decision a Nigerian digital asset platform\u000d\u000amakes in its first six months is how it structures user identity data.\u000d\u000aThe temptation is to build the simplest identity model that gets customers onboarded:\u000d\u000acollect the NIN and BVN, run a verification API call, store a pass/fail result, and move on.\u000d\u000a\u2014 144 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThis is the minimum viable KYC approach, and it is adequate for one thing only:\u000d\u000aonboarding a customer on day one. It is inadequate for everything the MLPPA 2022, the\u000d\u000aNFIU guidelines, and the SEC\u2019s ongoing monitoring requirements will eventually ask of\u000d\u000ayou.\u000d\u000aA compliance-first KYC data model has seven properties that the minimum viable\u000d\u000aapproach lacks:\u000d\u000a1. Versioned identity records \u2014 Every change to a customer\u2019s identity data, new ID document,\u000d\u000aupdated address, changed name, revised risk tier, is stored as a new version rather than an overwrite\u000d\u000aof the existing record. The audit trail of what was known about a customer at every point in time is\u000d\u000aessential for regulatory review and cannot be reconstructed from a model that only stores the current\u000d\u000astate.\u000d\u000a2. Linked risk classification history \u2014 The customer\u2019s risk tier is a field in the data model, but so is the\u000d\u000ahistory of every tier change, including when it changed, who authorised the change, and what\u000d\u000atriggered it. An NFIU examiner can ask: when did this customer\u2019s risk tier change and why? Your data\u000d\u000amodel must be able to answer that question from its own records.\u000d\u000a3. Embedded screening results with timestamps \u2014 Each sanctions and PEP screening run for each\u000d\u000acustomer is stored as a discrete record: which lists were checked, at what time, with what result. Not\u000d\u000aa single \u2018screened\u2019 flag. A complete screening history that demonstrates ongoing monitoring rather\u000d\u000athan a one-time onboarding check.\u000d\u000a4. Transaction-to-profile linkage \u2014 Every transaction is linked to the customer\u2019s identity record and\u000d\u000arisk profile at the time of the transaction, not just to a customer ID. When a transaction is reviewed\u000d\u000asix months later, it must be possible to reconstruct what the customer\u2019s declared income was, what\u000d\u000atheir risk tier was, and what their expected transaction profile was at the moment the transaction\u000d\u000aoccurred. This context is essential for meaningful transaction monitoring.\u000d\u000a5. EDD documentation storage \u2014 Enhanced due diligence documentation, source of funds\u000d\u000adeclarations, source of wealth evidence, PEP relationship documentation, is stored with direct linkage\u000d\u000ato the customer record, with document provenance and review date recorded.\u000d\u000a6. Relationship manager and compliance override records \u2014 Every manual override of a\u000d\u000asystem-generated risk decision, a compliance officer approving a customer that the system flagged, a\u000d\u000arelationship manager requesting an EDD waiver, is logged with the identity of the person who made\u000d\u000athe override, the reason stated, and the date. This creates the accountability trail that protects\u000d\u000acompliant overrides and exposes non-compliant ones.\u000d\u000a7. Regulatory reporting extracts \u2014 The data model is designed from the outset to generate the\u000d\u000aspecific extract formats required by the NFIU\u2019s goAML portal, the SEC\u2019s periodic reporting\u000d\u000a\u2014 145 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000arequirements, and the CBN\u2019s VASP guidelines. Not \u2018we can export to CSV and format it later.\u2019\u000d\u000aStructured, field-mapped extracts that match the regulator\u2019s ingestion format.\u000d\u000aArchitecture Decision Two: The Transaction Data Architecture\u000d\u000aThe second foundational architecture decision is how transactions are recorded \u2014\u000d\u000aspecifically, whether each transaction record contains the metadata necessary for AML\u000d\u000amonitoring or only the data necessary to process the payment.\u000d\u000aA transaction record built purely for settlement contains: sender ID, receiver ID, amount,\u000d\u000acurrency, timestamp, and status. This is sufficient for processing. It is insufficient for\u000d\u000acompliance.\u000d\u000aA transaction record built for compliance contains all of the above, plus: the wallet\u000d\u000aaddresses involved on both sides of the transaction (for any on-chain element), the\u000d\u000acounterparty VASP if the transaction involves a transfer to another platform, the source of\u000d\u000afunds declaration or inference for transactions above defined thresholds, the risk score\u000d\u000aapplied to the transaction at the time of processing, the monitoring alert (if any) generated\u000d\u000aby the transaction, and the outcome of any investigation of that alert.\u000d\u000aThe difference between these two architectures is invisible at transaction volume of ten\u000d\u000aper day. It becomes critically consequential at ten thousand per day \u2014 which is not an\u000d\u000aambitious scale for a Nigerian digital asset exchange in its second year of operation. A\u000d\u000atransaction monitoring system that must retroactively match transaction records to\u000d\u000acustomer risk profiles and wallet address data because the original transaction record did\u000d\u000anot contain them is not a monitoring system. It is a reporting system that happens three\u000d\u000amonths late, at enormous cost, for regulators who expected it three months ago.\u000d\u000aThe Retroactive Monitoring Trap\u000d\u000aThe NFIU\u2019s goAML platform and the CBN\u2019s supervisory framework both expect that STRs are filed\u000d\u000awhen suspicious activity is identified, not when a data extraction exercise eventually produces\u000d\u000athe metadata needed to identify it. A transaction monitoring architecture that requires manual\u000d\u000adata joining to generate monitoring outputs is not a monitoring architecture. It is a reporting\u000d\u000aarchitecture that will, under examination, demonstrate that genuine real-time monitoring was\u000d\u000anot occurring.\u000d\u000a\u2014 146 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aArchitecture Decision Three: The Audit Trail\u000d\u000aThe third architecture decision determines whether your compliance programme is\u000d\u000aauditable, and therefore whether it can withstand regulatory scrutiny at all.\u000d\u000aRegulators do not simply check whether compliance occurred. They check whether there\u000d\u000ais evidence that compliance occurred, created at the time it occurred, by the people\u000d\u000aresponsible for it, in a form that cannot be retrospectively altered.\u000d\u000aThis is a specific technical requirement, not a general documentation aspiration. It means:\u000d\u000a\u2022 Every material compliance action \u2014 KYC approval decision, transaction alert disposition, STR filing,\u000d\u000aPEP screening result, compliance override, is written to an append-only log. The log cannot be\u000d\u000aedited. Previous entries cannot be deleted. The logging infrastructure is separate from the\u000d\u000aapplication infrastructure, so that a change to the application does not alter historical log entries. \u000d\u000aImmutable logging\u000d\u000a\u2022 Every log entry carries a UTC timestamp. The NFIU\u2019s requirements reference specific filing\u000d\u000atimelines, STR filing within a defined period of suspicious activity identification, CTR filing for\u000d\u000atransactions above threshold amounts. These timelines are meaningless if the log timestamps\u000d\u000acannot be trusted. Timestamped with UTC precision\u000d\u000a\u2022 Every log entry identifies the human or system actor that created it. Not a generic \u2018system\u2019 or\u000d\u000a\u2018admin\u2019 identifier. A specific user ID, compliance officer ID, or automated process identifier that can\u000d\u000abe linked to a specific person at a specific point in time. Actor identification\u000d\u000a\u2022 The compliance log is not accessible for deletion or modification by any user, including technical\u000d\u000aadministrators. It is retained for a minimum of five years after the last relevant transaction. Access\u000d\u000afor read is controlled and itself logged. Access-controlled and retained\u000d\u000aThe practical implementation of this requirement does not require exotic technology. A\u000d\u000acloud-hosted, append-only logging database, AWS CloudTrail, Google Cloud Logging, or\u000d\u000aa dedicated compliance logging service, with access controls and a five-year retention\u000d\u000apolicy satisfies the requirement. The cost is negligible. The regulatory exposure of not\u000d\u000ahaving it is significant.\u000d\u000aArchitecture Decision Four: The Regulatory Reporting Pipeline\u000d\u000a\u2014 147 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe fourth architecture decision is the one most directly tied to operational compliance:\u000d\u000awhether your system can generate regulatory reports in the formats that regulators\u000d\u000arequire, without a manual data extraction exercise that takes days and introduces\u000d\u000atranscription errors.\u000d\u000aNigerian VASPs have four primary reporting obligations that require systematic data\u000d\u000aextraction: STR filing with the NFIU (event-triggered), CTR filing with the NFIU\u000d\u000a(transaction-threshold-triggered), the PEP Register submission (monthly), and the Annual\u000d\u000aTesting for adequacy of AML/CFT Compliance (annually). Each has a specific format \u2014\u000d\u000athe NFIU\u2019s goAML portal has defined data schemas for STR and CTR submissions. Each\u000d\u000ahas a defined timeline.\u000d\u000aA reporting pipeline is not a reporting button. It is the infrastructure that continuously\u000d\u000aextracts, validates, and formats compliance data against these schemas, so that when a\u000d\u000areportable event occurs, the report can be generated and filed within the required timeline\u000d\u000awithout a manual effort that risks missing the deadline.\u000d\u000aThe compliance programme that requires a data analyst to spend three days\u000d\u000aextracting data every time a report is due is not a compliance programme. It is a\u000d\u000acompliance aspiration with a recurring data problem.\u000d\u000aThe minimum viable reporting pipeline for a Nigerian VASP consists of: a configured\u000d\u000aconnection between the transaction monitoring system and the goAML portal\u2019s\u000d\u000asubmission interface; automated generation of PEP register extracts in the NFIU\u2019s\u000d\u000arequired format; a monthly reporting checklist that triggers automatically and is owned\u000d\u000aby the compliance officer; and a documented exception process for the rare cases where\u000d\u000aautomated extraction fails.\u000d\u000aThe Architecture Audit\u000d\u000aBefore your platform serves its first customer, conduct an architecture audit against the\u000d\u000afour dimensions described in this chapter. The audit is not a compliance exercise \u2014 it is an\u000d\u000aengineering exercise. Its output is a prioritised list of the gaps between your current\u000d\u000a\u2014 148 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aarchitecture and a compliance-first architecture, with implementation timelines and\u000d\u000aowners for each gap.\u000d\u000aThe gaps that can be closed before launch should be closed. The gaps that require more\u000d\u000adevelopment time should be documented, with a completion timeline, and disclosed to\u000d\u000athe Commission in your ARIP application as known gaps with a remediation plan.\u000d\u000aRegulators respond better to a founder who says \u2018this component is not yet built, here is\u000d\u000awhen it will be\u2019 than to a founder who says it is built when it is not.\u000d\u000aThe Engineering Investment Calculation\u000d\u000aBuilding the compliance-first architecture described in this chapter adds approximately two to four\u000d\u000aweeks of engineering time to a product build. Retrofitting these four components onto a product\u000d\u000athat was built without them takes, on average, four to eight months \u2014 and requires rebuilding\u000d\u000asignificant portions of the data model, the transaction processing layer, and the logging\u000d\u000ainfrastructure. The two-to-four week investment is not a compliance cost. It is the most efficient\u000d\u000aengineering decision the founding team will ever make.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 149 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Nineteen\u000d\u000aWhen Things Go Wrong: Responding to\u000d\u000aRegulatory Action\u000d\u000a\u201cThe difference between a regulatory matter that resolves in three months and one that consumes three\u000d\u000ayears is almost always determined in the first seventy-two hours.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aThis chapter is the one you hope you never need.\u000d\u000aIt is also the one that, if your business operates long enough in a regulated market, you\u000d\u000awill eventually need, because regulatory contact is not a function of wrongdoing. It is a\u000d\u000afunction of operating in a supervised market. The exchange that is doing everything right\u000d\u000astill receives periodic information requests. The custody platform with the cleanest\u000d\u000acompliance programme still faces occasional NFIU queries about specific transactions. The\u000d\u000amost well-governed VASP on the ARIP register still has its quarterly reports reviewed and\u000d\u000aits operational practices assessed.\u000d\u000aRegulatory contact becomes a regulatory crisis not because of the contact itself, but\u000d\u000abecause of how the first seventy-two hours are handled. This chapter gives you the\u000d\u000aframework for handling them correctly.\u000d\u000aThe Three Mistakes That Turn Administrative Matters Into Crises\u000d\u000aFrom your answers to the questions that shaped this chapter, three specific failure modes\u000d\u000arecur when Nigerian digital asset founders receive a regulatory notice. Each of them\u000d\u000atransforms a manageable administrative matter into something categorically more serious.\u000d\u000aAnd each of them is entirely preventable.\u000d\u000aMistake One: The Wrong Lawyer at the Wrong Moment\u000d\u000aThe instinct to call a lawyer when you receive a regulatory notice is correct. The question\u000d\u000ais which lawyer, and most founders get this wrong in a way that creates damage that the\u000d\u000aright lawyer must subsequently spend months undoing.\u000d\u000a\u2014 150 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe corporate lawyer who handled your CAC registration knows Nigerian company law.\u000d\u000aThe solicitor who reviewed your commercial contracts knows contract law. Neither of\u000d\u000athem knows how SEC Nigeria\u2019s enforcement process actually works, what the\u000d\u000aCommission\u2019s standard escalation sequence looks like, what language in an initial\u000d\u000aresponse signals cooperation versus confrontation to the reviewing officer, or what\u000d\u000ainformal engagement is possible before a formal response is filed.\u000d\u000aThe wrong lawyer\u2019s first instinct is to write a formal, legalistic response that establishes\u000d\u000athe company\u2019s legal position, asserts its rights, and requests an extension of the response\u000d\u000adeadline. This response, however well-intentioned, arrives at the Commission\u2019s offices as\u000d\u000aa signal of confrontation. It triggers a more formal review process than might otherwise\u000d\u000ahave occurred. It closes informal dialogue options that were available before the letter\u000d\u000aarrived. And it typically delays a resolution that a more collaborative initial response\u000d\u000awould have accelerated.\u000d\u000aThe regulatory notice that could have been resolved with a phone call and a\u000d\u000afour-page response memo becomes a six-month formal inquiry when it is\u000d\u000aanswered with a twelve-page letter from a lawyer the Commission has never\u000d\u000aheard of, asserting positions the Commission did not ask about.\u000d\u000aThe right response is to identify, immediately, a practitioner who has specific experience\u000d\u000ain SEC Nigeria digital asset enforcement matters, or, if the notice is from the CBN or\u000d\u000aNFIU, in CBN or NFIU regulatory matters respectively. This practitioner\u2019s first action\u000d\u000ashould be not to write a response but to make a phone call: to the relevant department, to\u000d\u000aestablish the nature of the inquiry, the seriousness with which it is being treated\u000d\u000ainternally, and the timeline for resolution that the Commission is working with. This\u000d\u000aconversation \u2014 which is available to someone with the right relationships and entirely\u000d\u000aunavailable to a cold-calling generalist lawyer, determines the appropriate tone and\u000d\u000acontent of the written response.\u000d\u000a\u2014 151 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aMistake Two: The Internal Communication Cascade\u000d\u000aThe second mistake is initiating an internal communication cascade, informing investors,\u000d\u000aco-founders, board members, senior staff, and in some cases advisors and partners, before\u000d\u000athe situation has been assessed and its significance understood.\u000d\u000aThe psychology is understandable. A regulatory notice feels like an existential event, and\u000d\u000athe instinct is to bring your key stakeholders into awareness immediately. But the\u000d\u000apractical effect of this communication, in most cases, is to create a set of secondary\u000d\u000aproblems that are more damaging than the original regulatory inquiry.\u000d\u000aInvestors who learn about a regulatory notice before the founder has assessed it will form\u000d\u000atheir own preliminary assessment, almost always more alarming than the reality \u2014 and\u000d\u000amay make decisions (withdrawing from a funding round, consulting their own lawyers,\u000d\u000adiscussing it with other portfolio company founders) that become independently\u000d\u000aconsequential. Board members who learn about it through informal channels rather than a\u000d\u000aconsidered briefing will have questions the founder cannot yet answer, creating a\u000d\u000agovernance crisis on top of a regulatory one. Staff who learn about it through rumour will\u000d\u000ahave conversations with each other, with partners, and potentially with the press that\u000d\u000acannot be recalled.\u000d\u000aThe discipline required in the first twenty-four hours is to contain the information to the\u000d\u000aabsolute minimum group necessary to begin the assessment: the founding CEO, the\u000d\u000acompany\u2019s most senior compliance resource, and, as soon as identified, the specialist\u000d\u000aregulatory practitioner. No broader communication until the assessment is complete and\u000d\u000athe response strategy is determined.\u000d\u000aThe Confidentiality Obligation\u000d\u000aThe MLPPA 2022\u2019s tipping-off prohibition \u2014 which criminalises informing a customer that an STR\u000d\u000ahas been filed about them \u2014 is one dimension of a broader principle: regulatory matters should not\u000d\u000abe communicated beyond those who need to know, particularly before the regulator has made its\u000d\u000aown communications. A founder who discusses a pending SEC enforcement matter publicly, or who\u000d\u000adiscloses it to third parties who are not parties to it, risks creating both legal liability and regulatory\u000d\u000acomplications that did not exist in the original matter.\u000d\u000a\u2014 152 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aMistake Three: Fixing the Problem Before Responding to the Regulator\u000d\u000aThe third and most consequential mistake is the decision to go dark, to stop\u000d\u000acommunicating with the regulator while you fix the underlying problem that the notice\u000d\u000aidentified, and to resurface weeks or months later with a solution that you hope will make\u000d\u000athe original inquiry irrelevant.\u000d\u000aThis approach is based on a logical fallacy: that a regulator who asked about a compliance\u000d\u000agap will be satisfied by evidence that the gap has been closed, if the evidence arrives after\u000d\u000athe response deadline has passed without any communication.\u000d\u000aWhat actually happens is: the regulator\u2019s administrative matter becomes an enforcement\u000d\u000amatter, because the failure to respond within the stipulated deadline is itself a regulatory\u000d\u000abreach, separate from and additional to whatever gave rise to the original inquiry. The\u000d\u000aCommission\u2019s internal file now contains not one compliance concern but two: the original\u000d\u000amatter and the non-response. The informal resolution options that were available in the\u000d\u000afirst two weeks are no longer available. The reviewing officer, who may have been\u000d\u000adisposed toward a collaborative resolution initially, is now managing a case that has\u000d\u000aescalated to enforcement status.\u000d\u000aThe correct approach is to respond within the deadline, acknowledging the inquiry and\u000d\u000aproviding whatever information is immediately available, while simultaneously\u000d\u000abeginning the work of addressing the underlying issue. The response does not need to be\u000d\u000aa complete solution. It needs to demonstrate engagement, acknowledge the Commission\u2019s\u000d\u000aconcern, provide a timeline for full remediation, and establish the basis for a continuing\u000d\u000adialogue.\u000d\u000a\u2014 153 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe 72-Hour Response Framework\u000d\u000aThe first seventy-two hours after a regulatory notice arrives determine the trajectory of\u000d\u000aeverything that follows. Here is the framework for using them correctly:\u000d\u000a0\u20136 Hours Read, assess, do not react\u000d\u000aRead the notice carefully. Identify: which regulator sent it, which department, what it is asking\u000d\u000afor, what the response deadline is, and what the maximum escalation risk is if you do nothing.\u000d\u000aDo not call your board. Do not call your investors. Do not draft a response. Assess.\u000d\u000a6\u201312 Hours Identify your specialist practitioner\u000d\u000aContact a practitioner with specific, demonstrable experience in matters from the relevant\u000d\u000aregulator. Not your general corporate lawyer. Ask specifically: have you handled SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000adigital asset enforcement inquiries before? CBN VASP matters? NFIU compliance reviews? If\u000d\u000athe answer is no, find someone whose answer is yes.\u000d\u000a12\u201324 Hours Informal assessment call\u000d\u000aYour specialist practitioner makes an informal contact with the relevant department to\u000d\u000aunderstand the nature and status of the inquiry. This is a relationship call, not a legal one. Its\u000d\u000apurpose is intelligence: how serious is this internally? What prompted it? Is there a specific\u000d\u000atransaction or practice that triggered it? What does the Commission expect in the response?\u000d\u000a24\u201348 Hours Internal assessment and response strategy\u000d\u000aWith the intelligence from the informal contact, assess the underlying issue honestly. Is the\u000d\u000aCommission\u2019s concern valid? What is the actual compliance gap, if any? What can be\u000d\u000aremediated quickly and what requires more time? Determine your response strategy:\u000d\u000aacknowledgment only, partial response with remediation timeline, or substantive full\u000d\u000aresponse.\u000d\u000a48\u201372 Hours Acknowledgment filing if deadline permits\u000d\u000aIf the response deadline is within seven days, file an acknowledgment response that: confirms\u000d\u000areceipt of the notice, identifies your company and its regulatory status, confirms the name\u000d\u000aand contact of your designated specialist practitioner, and provides a specific date for the\u000d\u000asubstantive response. This communication preserves goodwill and stops the clock on the\u000d\u000aescalation risk while you prepare the substantive response.\u000d\u000a\u2014 154 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aDay 4\u20137 Substantive response\u000d\u000aFile your substantive response. Address every specific question in the notice. Acknowledge\u000d\u000aany compliance gap honestly but constructively, not defensively. Provide a specific, credible\u000d\u000aremediation timeline for any gap identified. Close with a clear request for a meeting to discuss\u000d\u000athe matter further if appropriate. Do not assert legal positions. Do not deny facts that are\u000d\u000adocumented. Do not promise remediation that you cannot deliver in the stated timeframe.\u000d\u000aWhen the Matter Escalates: Account Freezes and Formal Enforcement\u000d\u000aThe framework above addresses the most common form of regulatory contact: an\u000d\u000aadministrative inquiry or information request. More serious regulatory actions, account\u000d\u000afreezes, formal enforcement notices, licence suspension, or EFCC involvement, require\u000d\u000aimmediate specialist legal counsel and a different operational posture.\u000d\u000aThree principles apply in all escalated regulatory matters:\u000d\u000a1. Segregate client funds immediately \u2014 If your platform holds client funds and you receive any\u000d\u000aindication of pending enforcement action, immediately verify the segregation of those funds from\u000d\u000aoperational funds and document that segregation. Client fund protection is your first and highest\u000d\u000aobligation in any enforcement scenario. It also demonstrates good faith to the regulator \u2014 a\u000d\u000acompany that protects its clients\u2019 assets under regulatory pressure is treated differently from one\u000d\u000athat does not.\u000d\u000a2. Appoint specialist external counsel immediately \u2014 Escalated enforcement matters require a\u000d\u000aspecialist in Nigerian capital markets or financial services enforcement law. This counsel should have\u000d\u000aan existing relationship with the relevant regulatory institution. They are not retained to fight the\u000d\u000aregulator. They are retained to negotiate the most orderly and client-protective resolution of the\u000d\u000amatter.\u000d\u000a3. Communicate with the regulator, not around them \u2014 Every material development in the\u000d\u000aenforcement matter should be communicated to the regulator first or simultaneously \u2014 not\u000d\u000adisclosed to investors, press, or partners before the regulator is aware. A company that maintains\u000d\u000atransparent communication with the regulator during an enforcement matter is consistently treated\u000d\u000awith more latitude than one that manages its public communications first and its regulatory\u000d\u000acommunications second.\u000d\u000a\u2014 155 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe Recovery Arc: Getting Back to Good Standing\u000d\u000aEvery regulatory crisis that resolves correctly produces, at its conclusion, a company that\u000d\u000ais in better regulatory standing than it was before the matter arose. This is not optimism, it\u000d\u000ais a structural observation about how Nigerian regulatory relationships work.\u000d\u000aA company that receives a regulatory inquiry, responds promptly and honestly,\u000d\u000aacknowledges any compliance gaps, remediates them within the stated timeline, and\u000d\u000amaintains transparent communication throughout the process has demonstrated, under\u000d\u000areal conditions, the compliance culture and institutional trustworthiness that regulators\u000d\u000amost value. The file that the Commission closes at the end of the matter contains not just a\u000d\u000arecord of the compliance gap but a record of how it was addressed. That record is the\u000d\u000afoundation of the next regulatory interaction.\u000d\u000aEmeka\u2019s story from Chapter One ends here, in a way. The nine months he spent\u000d\u000anavigating the SEC Nigeria engagement produced not just a compliant platform but a\u000d\u000acompliance culture, a set of practices, relationships, and institutional instincts that the\u000d\u000apre-letter version of his company did not have. The letter that felt like the end of his\u000d\u000aproject was, in retrospect, the beginning of the version of his company that could actually\u000d\u000asustain itself.\u000d\u000aRegulatory crises do not end businesses that are genuinely building something\u000d\u000avaluable. They reveal whether the compliance infrastructure is real or performed.\u000d\u000aThe businesses that are revealed to be genuinely compliant emerge from the\u000d\u000acrisis in better standing than they entered it.\u000d\u000aThat is the last lesson of Part Four, and the one I most want founders to carry into Part\u000d\u000aFive: the practice of compliance is not a cost of doing business in a regulated market. It is\u000d\u000athe foundation of the business itself. The founders who understand this do not dread\u000d\u000aregulatory contact. They are simply prepared for it, and readiness, in regulated markets, is\u000d\u000athe closest thing to invulnerability that exists.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 156 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aPart Five\u000d\u000aThe Future\u000d\u000aWhere This Is All Going and How to Stay Ahead of It\u000d\u000a\u2014 157 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aEvery chapter in this book to this point has been grounded in the present: in the\u000d\u000aregulations that exist today, the institutions that are active now, the compliance\u000d\u000aobligations that are currently in force. Part Five moves deliberately into the future, not to\u000d\u000aspeculate, but to give you the analytical tools to see it clearly before it arrives.\u000d\u000aThree chapters. Each one addresses a different time horizon.\u000d\u000aChapter Twenty looks at programmable money and the eNaira, a technology that is\u000d\u000aalready here, whose implications are still being worked out, and whose most important\u000d\u000aconsequences for founders are different from what the public narrative suggests. Chapter\u000d\u000aTwenty-One looks at pan-African digital trade and the long-arc question of continental\u000d\u000aregulatory convergence; what is real, what is overstated, and where the builder\u2019s\u000d\u000aopportunity actually lies. Chapter Twenty-Two is the chapter that earns its place in every\u000d\u000aedition of this book, regardless of how much the specific regulatory landscape changes: a\u000d\u000aframework for reasoning about rules that have not yet been written, that gives you the\u000d\u000aanalytical capability to navigate regulatory evolution without a guide.\u000d\u000aPart Five does not end the book with an answer. It ends it with a capability. The\u000d\u000aregulations described in this book will change. The institutions will evolve. The markets\u000d\u000awill shift. What will not change, what no regulatory reform can obsolete, is the ability to\u000d\u000aread the signals early, reason from first principles, and build in a way that is always one\u000d\u000astep ahead of the framework.\u000d\u000aThat is what Part Five is about.\u000d\u000a\u2014 158 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Twenty\u000d\u000aCBDCs, the eNaira, and What Programmable\u000d\u000aMoney Means for Your Business\u000d\u000a\u201cThe most important lesson the eNaira teaches is not about the eNaira. It is about what happens when a\u000d\u000atechnology outruns the institution trying to deploy it.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aIn November 2025, at the Cedi@60 International Currency Conference in Accra, Musa\u000d\u000aItopa Jimoh, the Director of Payment Systems at the Central Bank of Nigeria, the same\u000d\u000aofficial who signed the 2021 circular that the market called a crypto ban, the man I called\u000d\u000athe morning that circular arrived, stood at a podium and said, plainly and on the record,\u000d\u000athat the eNaira was not a \u201crosy story.\u201d\u000d\u000aHe described how Nigerians were not interested in the eNaira. He noted that the CBN had\u000d\u000anot been prepared to function as a retail bank. He acknowledged that the market had\u000d\u000aalready been providing solutions that the eNaira was designed to enable. And he\u000d\u000aannounced that the CBN was shifting its CBDC focus from retail to wholesale, from a\u000d\u000aproduct for ordinary Nigerians to an infrastructure for inter-institutional settlement.\u000d\u000aThis admission, by a senior CBN official at an international conference, is not a story of\u000d\u000afailure. It is one of the most instructive episodes in the history of African digital finance.\u000d\u000aAnd its implications for founders building in this market are precisely the opposite of\u000d\u000awhat the surface reading suggests.\u000d\u000aThe eNaira: What the Numbers Actually Say\u000d\u000aBy the end of 2024, the eNaira represented approximately 0.36 percent of total currency in\u000d\u000acirculation in Nigeria. Despite more than three years of operation, 98.5 percent of\u000d\u000aregistered wallets had never been used. Of the roughly 900,000 wallets opened, fewer than\u000d\u000aone in twenty showed any meaningful transaction activity. The CBN waived transaction\u000d\u000afees to stimulate adoption and then reinstated them. It expanded its agent network to\u000d\u000a\u2014 159 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a7,740 grassroots operators. It linked the eNaira to social cash transfer programmes as a\u000d\u000ause-case anchor. None of it moved the adoption needle in any sustained way.\u000d\u000aThe public narrative that follows from these numbers is straightforward: the eNaira failed.\u000d\u000aNigerians did not want it. The CBN should not have tried. The project was a political\u000d\u000ainitiative dressed in technological clothing, rushed to launch because Nigeria wanted to be\u000d\u000afirst in Africa, without adequate preparation for the product design challenge of\u000d\u000apersuading a cash-dependent population to trust a new digital instrument they did not\u000d\u000aunderstand and had no particular reason to use.\u000d\u000aAll of this is partly true. But it misses the three things about the eNaira that actually\u000d\u000amatter to founders.\u000d\u000aWhat the eNaira Actually Taught the CBN\u000d\u000aThe first and most consequential output of the eNaira project is not the product itself. It is\u000d\u000athe institutional knowledge that the product\u2019s failure was generated inside the Central\u000d\u000aBank of Nigeria.\u000d\u000aThe CBN spent four years trying to build a retail digital currency product that Nigerians\u000d\u000awould voluntarily adopt. In doing so, it confronted, for the first time, from the inside, the\u000d\u000aspecific product design challenges of digital financial services for the Nigerian market: the\u000d\u000atrust deficit in formal financial institutions, the resilience and familiarity of cash, the\u000d\u000ainadequacy of the existing distribution infrastructure for digital financial products, the\u000d\u000agap between a feature that sounds compelling in a policy document and a product that\u000d\u000apeople actually choose to use.\u000d\u000aThis is knowledge that the CBN did not have before the eNaira, and that no amount of\u000d\u000aresearch or consultation could have substituted for. It is the knowledge that Musa Itopa\u000d\u000awas acknowledging at the Accra conference: we tried to be a retail bank, and we were not\u000d\u000aready for it.\u000d\u000aThe CBN\u2019s eNaira experience is Nigeria\u2019s most expensive and most valuable\u000d\u000aproduct research study. It produced a generation of central bank officials who\u000d\u000a\u2014 160 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000anow understand, from direct experience, why digital financial products for\u000d\u000aordinary Nigerians are difficult to build. That understanding will shape every\u000d\u000aregulatory decision the Bank makes about private sector digital payment\u000d\u000aproducts for the next decade.\u000d\u000aFor founders, this means one specific thing: the CBN\u2019s approach to regulating private\u000d\u000astablecoins, digital wallets, and payment products is now informed by a four-year\u000d\u000aexperience of building one itself. The officials who will review your product\u2019s licence\u000d\u000aapplication, who will assess your distribution strategy, who will evaluate your user\u000d\u000aonboarding design, now have a practitioner\u2019s understanding of how hard the problem is\u000d\u000athat your product is trying to solve. That understanding creates both more sympathy for\u000d\u000athe challenge and more sophistication in the scrutiny.\u000d\u000aThe Wholesale Pivot: What It Means for the Market\u000d\u000aMusa Itopa\u2019s announcement of the CBN\u2019s shift to a wholesale CBDC focus is the most\u000d\u000astrategically significant CBDC development in Nigeria since the eNaira\u2019s launch. Its\u000d\u000aimplications are largely undiscussed in the market.\u000d\u000aA wholesale CBDC is not a consumer product. It is infrastructure for financial institutions,\u000d\u000aa digital form of reserves that banks and payment system operators use for\u000d\u000ainter-institutional settlement, rather than a wallet that ordinary Nigerians carry on their\u000d\u000aphones. It is the plumbing of the financial system rather than a tap in someone\u2019s kitchen.\u000d\u000aThe CBN\u2019s pivot to wholesale signals three things. First: the Bank has accepted that\u000d\u000adisplacing private payment solutions at the retail level is not a goal it can achieve through\u000d\u000aCBDC alone. Second: it is focusing instead on the infrastructure layer, where its sovereign\u000d\u000amandate is unambiguous and where the efficiency gains are real; inter-bank settlement,\u000d\u000across-border payment infrastructure, and government-to-institution payment flows.\u000d\u000aThird: it is opening, by this pivot, the retail digital payment market to private sector\u000d\u000ainnovation in a way that the eNaira\u2019s competitive framing had implicitly closed.\u000d\u000aThe Wholesale CBDC Opportunity\u000d\u000a\u2014 161 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aA wholesale CBDC infrastructure, once operational, creates new capabilities for private sector\u000d\u000afinancial products: programmable government disbursements that private platforms can help\u000d\u000adistribute, atomic settlement between banks and VASPs that reduces counterparty risk, and a digital\u000d\u000amonetary backbone on which stablecoin and tokenised asset products can be anchored with\u000d\u000asovereign backing. The founders who understand the wholesale CBDC roadmap are building\u000d\u000aproducts that integrate with it rather than compete with it.\u000d\u000aProgrammable Money: The Real Opportunity\u000d\u000aThe most transformative application of programmable money in Nigeria is not a\u000d\u000aconsumer savings product. It is not a retail payment wallet. It is not even a remittance\u000d\u000achannel, though that is where much of the current commercial attention is focused.\u000d\u000aThe most transformative near-term application of programmable money in Nigeria is\u000d\u000agovernment efficiency.\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s federal government distributes hundreds of billions of naira annually through\u000d\u000aconditional social transfer programmes, agricultural subsidy schemes, infrastructure\u000d\u000apayment systems, and salary disbursements to millions of civil servants across thirty-six\u000d\u000astates. The leakage, delay, and corruption embedded in these distribution systems is one\u000d\u000aof the most documented and least solved problems in Nigerian public finance. A\u000d\u000aprogrammable payment infrastructure that releases funds conditionally, only when a\u000d\u000abeneficiary receives verified goods, only when an MDA vendor completes a specified\u000d\u000adeliverable, only when a farmer produces evidence of planting, addresses this problem at\u000d\u000aits architectural root.\u000d\u000aThe CBN\u2019s own guidelines for 2024-2025 explicitly commit to enabling eNaira wallets for\u000d\u000agovernment-to-MDA payments and beneficiary disbursements. The NIBSS-Zone\u000d\u000ablockchain partnership, announced in August 2024, brings distributed ledger technology\u000d\u000ainto Nigeria\u2019s core payment infrastructure for real-time, decentralised POS transactions.\u000d\u000aThese are not theoretical developments. They are live infrastructure investments that will\u000d\u000acreate commercial opportunities for the private sector within the next three to five years.\u000d\u000aFour specific programmable money opportunities for Nigerian founders:\u000d\u000a\u2014 162 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a1. Conditional disbursement APIs \u2014 Building the interface layer between government MDA payment\u000d\u000asystems and programme beneficiaries, the smart contract or API infrastructure that releases funds\u000d\u000awhen specified conditions are verified. This is a B2G product with a massive addressable market and\u000d\u000ano adequate incumbent solution. \u201cChats\u201d by Convexity deserves honorable mentions here for already\u000d\u000asetting the stage for that type of innovation.\u000d\u000a2. Agricultural finance automation \u2014 Programmable payment products for smallholder farmers,\u000d\u000adisbursing input finance (fertiliser, seed) as conditional payments that release against verified\u000d\u000apurchase receipts, collecting repayment automatically against commodity sale proceeds. This\u000d\u000acategory alone represents a multi-billion naira market that traditional lending cannot serve at scale.\u000d\u000a3. Trade finance programmability \u2014 Smart contract escrow for intra-African trade; releasing payment\u000d\u000ato a Lagos exporter when a verified delivery confirmation arrives from an Accra importer, without the\u000d\u000a7-20 percent cost and 3-5 day delay of traditional correspondent banking. PAPSS provides the\u000d\u000asettlement rail; programmable money provides the conditional release logic.\u000d\u000a4. Tokenised remittance infrastructure \u2014 Building the programmable settlement layer on top of the\u000d\u000aeNaira\u2019s international interoperability capability, enabling diaspora remittances to arrive as\u000d\u000aprogrammable naira that beneficiaries can access, spend, or convert within a controlled, auditable\u000d\u000asystem that the CBN can observe and the NFIU can monitor.\u000d\u000aEach of these opportunities shares a common architecture: they use programmable money\u000d\u000aas a mechanism for introducing conditionality, verifiability, and auditability into payment\u000d\u000aflows that currently lack all three. They are not competing with the eNaira. They are\u000d\u000abuilding on the institutional infrastructure the eNaira created, and on the regulatory\u000d\u000asophistication the CBN developed in the process of building it.\u000d\u000aThe Design Principle That Survives Every CBDC Evolution\u000d\u000aRegardless of how the eNaira evolves, whether it is redesigned, expanded, contracted, or\u000d\u000aeventually superseded, one design principle for private sector digital money products\u000d\u000aemerges from the Nigerian CBDC experience with clarity.\u000d\u000aThe products that succeed in the Nigerian digital money market are the ones that make\u000d\u000athe naira more useful, not the ones that make the naira less necessary. Every private\u000d\u000adigital currency product that has thrived in Nigeria, the mobile money platforms, the\u000d\u000astablecoin savings products, the P2P payment tools, has done so by solving a specific\u000d\u000aproblem with the naira\u2019s existing distribution, storage, or accessibility, not by replacing\u000d\u000athe naira with something else.\u000d\u000a\u2014 163 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe CBN\u2019s most deeply held institutional concern, monetary sovereignty, the integrity of\u000d\u000athe naira as the unit of account for Nigerian economic life, is not a regulatory obstacle to\u000d\u000abe navigated around. It is a design parameter to be built within. The founders who design\u000d\u000adigital money products that make the CBN\u2019s monetary policy more effective, that extend\u000d\u000athe naira\u2019s reach, and that make the financial system more legible to supervisors will have\u000d\u000athe most durable products in the most important market in Africa.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 164 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Twenty-One\u000d\u000aAfCFTA, Cross-Border Digital Trade & the\u000d\u000aComing Pan-African Regulatory Convergence\u000d\u000a\u201cPan-African integration is not a destination. It is a direction. The founders who build in the direction\u000d\u000aof integration, before its structures are complete, are the ones who will own the infrastructures when\u000d\u000athey are.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aThe African Continental Free Trade Area is, on paper, the largest free trade area in the\u000d\u000aworld by number of participating countries, fifty-four member states representing 1.4\u000d\u000abillion people and a combined GDP of approximately three trillion dollars. Its Digital\u000d\u000aTrade Protocol, currently in the ratification process, will establish common frameworks\u000d\u000afor cross-border digital payments, data flows, e-commerce, and, potentially, digital\u000d\u000afinancial services that cut across the individual regulatory architectures of all member\u000d\u000astates.\u000d\u000aThe optimistic narrative about AfCFTA frames it as a near-term unlock for pan-African\u000d\u000adigital business: a single market, approaching fast, that will dissolve the multi-jurisdiction\u000d\u000acompliance complexity that currently makes scaling across Africa so expensive and so\u000d\u000aslow.\u000d\u000aThis chapter is an honest examination of how much of that narrative is true, how much is\u000d\u000apremature, and where the genuine opportunity sits for founders building today.\u000d\u000aWhat AfCFTA Is and What It Is Not\u000d\u000aAfCFTA is a trade agreement between governments. It creates obligations for member\u000d\u000astates to reduce tariffs, harmonise standards, and cooperate on trade facilitation. What it\u000d\u000adoes not do, and what no trade agreement can do by itself, is create a single regulatory\u000d\u000aframework for digital assets, establish mutual recognition of digital financial services\u000d\u000alicences, or resolve the jurisdictional complexity that currently faces any company\u000d\u000aoperating in multiple African markets.\u000d\u000a\u2014 165 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe Digital Trade Protocol is an important step in the direction of regulatory\u000d\u000aharmonisation, but its ratification and implementation will take years, and its actual effect\u000d\u000aon the operating environment for digital financial services businesses will depend on how\u000d\u000aeach member state translates its obligations into domestic law. The Protocol\u2019s most\u000d\u000aconsequential provisions, on mobile money interoperability, cross-border e-KYC\u000d\u000aauthentication, and PAPSS integration mandates, are mandates on governments, not\u000d\u000apermissions for businesses. They create the framework within which businesses can\u000d\u000aeventually operate more fluidly. They do not create that fluidity immediately.\u000d\u000aThe founders who are waiting for AfCFTA to resolve their multi-jurisdiction\u000d\u000acompliance complexity will wait indefinitely. The founders who are building\u000d\u000amulti-jurisdiction compliance infrastructure now, in advance of the framework,\u000d\u000awill be the ones who can take advantage of it fastest when it arrives.\u000d\u000aThe Infrastructure Gap: The Real Barrier\u000d\u000aThe second important correction to the optimistic AfCFTA narrative is about what the\u000d\u000aactual barrier to pan-African digital commerce is. It is not primarily regulation.\u000d\u000aCross-border payments through traditional channels currently cost between seven and\u000d\u000atwenty percent of the transaction value and take three to five days to clear. These costs are\u000d\u000anot primarily the product of regulatory complexity. They are the product of infrastructure\u000d\u000afragmentation: the absence of direct settlement mechanisms between African currencies,\u000d\u000athe reliance on correspondent banking routes through New York or London, and the\u000d\u000ainadequate interoperability between the continent\u2019s payment systems.\u000d\u000aA Nigerian company trying to pay a Ghanaian supplier in cedis, or to receive payment\u000d\u000afrom a Kenyan customer in shillings, faces a series of infrastructure bottlenecks that no\u000d\u000aregulatory harmonisation effort directly addresses. The naira must be converted to dollars,\u000d\u000arouted through an international correspondent bank, converted to cedis, and settled\u000d\u000athrough the Ghanaian banking system, incurring conversion fees, counterparty risk, and\u000d\u000asettlement delay at every step. The AfCFTA Digital Trade Protocol mandates PAPSS\u000d\u000a\u2014 166 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aintegration and mobile money interoperability as solutions to this problem. But\u000d\u000amandating the solution and building it are different things.\u000d\u000aPAPSS is real, and it is growing. As of November 2025, PAPSS connects sixteen African\u000d\u000acountries, fourteen payment switches, and more than 150 commercial banks, including\u000d\u000atwenty-two Nigerian banks. In April 2025, the CBN significantly relaxed PAPSS\u000d\u000atransaction documentation requirements, enabling transactions up to USD 2,000 for\u000d\u000aindividuals and USD 5,000 for corporations with only basic KYC. PAPSS is projected to\u000d\u000asave five billion dollars annually in transaction costs once fully operational across the\u000d\u000acontinent. These are meaningful milestones.\u000d\u000aBut PAPSS was designed for bank-to-bank settlement in African currencies. The majority\u000d\u000aof actual cross-border value flow in African digital assets currently moves through\u000d\u000astablecoins and P2P rails that PAPSS was not built for. A business that receives payment\u000d\u000afrom a Lagos customer in USDT and needs to pay a Nairobi supplier in shillings is not\u000d\u000awell served by PAPSS, because their payment flow never enters the African banking\u000d\u000asystem in the first place. The infrastructure gap is not just about PAPSS. It is about the gap\u000d\u000abetween where value actually flows in pan-African digital commerce and the institutional\u000d\u000ainfrastructure that was designed to facilitate it.\u000d\u000aThe Size Paradox: Why Nigeria\u2019s Advantage Can Become a Liability\u000d\u000aThe third important correction is the most challenging for Nigerian founders to hear:\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s size advantage in African digital commerce means nothing if its regulatory\u000d\u000acomplexity continues to make it harder to build in than smaller, more regulatory-coherent\u000d\u000amarkets.\u000d\u000aRwanda has consistently attracted more technology investment relative to its GDP than\u000d\u000aNigeria over the past decade. Mauritius has become the regulatory domicile of choice for\u000d\u000aAfrican digital asset businesses seeking international credibility. Kenya\u2019s Capital Markets\u000d\u000aAuthority sandbox has been operational and internationally benchmarked since before the\u000d\u000aARIP framework existed. These are not large economies. But they have made deliberate,\u000d\u000aconsistent choices to make themselves easy to build in: clear rules, responsive regulators,\u000d\u000a\u2014 167 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000apredictable timelines, and the institutional culture of treating builders as partners in\u000d\u000aeconomic development rather than subjects of administrative oversight.\u000d\u000aNigeria has made enormous progress in the last three years. ISA 2025 is a genuinely\u000d\u000alandmark piece of legislation. The ARIP framework, the CBN\u2019s VASP guidelines, and the\u000d\u000aFATF grey list exit are real achievements. But the founder who wants to build a\u000d\u000apan-African digital asset business and is choosing their primary jurisdiction of\u000d\u000aincorporation and operation is still asking: is Nigeria\u2019s regulatory environment worth its\u000d\u000acomplexity?\u000d\u000aThe answer is increasingly yes, because Nigeria\u2019s market size, consumer sophistication,\u000d\u000aand talent pool are irreplaceable advantages that no smaller market can substitute. But the\u000d\u000amargin is narrower than Nigeria\u2019s size suggests it should be, and the gap will close further\u000d\u000aif the framework\u2019s implementation becomes more predictable, the regulator\u2019s response\u000d\u000atimes improve, and the dual-regulator complexity between the CBN and SEC is\u000d\u000aprogressively resolved.\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s Competitive Imperative\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s size is a gravitational force in African digital commerce, but gravity is not enough on its\u000d\u000aown. Mauritius, Rwanda, and Kenya are not competing with Nigeria\u2019s market. They are competing\u000d\u000awith Nigeria\u2019s regulatory environment. The founders, investors, and ecosystem builders who most\u000d\u000aloudly advocate for regulatory improvement in Nigeria are not doing so from naivety about the\u000d\u000apolitical constraints the regulators operate under. They are doing so because they understand that\u000d\u000aevery Nigerian founder who incorporates in Mauritius, because the process is simpler, is a tax on\u000d\u000athe Nigerian economy that the regulatory reform dividend could eliminate.\u000d\u000aWhere the Genuine Opportunity Lies\u000d\u000aHaving corrected the optimistic narrative, it is important to be clear about what is\u000d\u000agenuinely real in the pan-African digital trade story, because the opportunity is\u000d\u000asubstantial.\u000d\u000aAfrica\u2019s digital economy is valued at approximately 180 billion dollars in 2025 and is\u000d\u000aprojected to reach 712 billion dollars by 2030. Africa\u2019s e-commerce users are projected to\u000d\u000areach 500 million in 2025, processing over 500 billion dollars in transactions, with 75\u000d\u000a\u2014 168 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000apercent of those transactions occurring on smartphones. The cross-border payment market\u000d\u000ais expected to triple from 329 billion dollars in 2025 to 1 trillion dollars by 2035. These are\u000d\u000anot speculative projections. They are the compounded effect of demographic trends, a\u000d\u000ayoung, digitally-native, increasingly connected population, which is already visible in\u000d\u000acurrent transaction data.\u000d\u000aThe founders who will capture the largest share of this opportunity are building in three\u000d\u000aspecific areas that AfCFTA\u2019s trajectory favours:\u000d\u000a1. Payment infrastructure for intra-African commerce \u2014 The gap between where value flows \u2014 in\u000d\u000astablecoins, P2P rails, and mobile money, and where institutional settlement infrastructure exists is\u000d\u000aan engineering problem that private sector founders can solve. Building the bridges between PAPSS,\u000d\u000amobile money systems, stablecoin rails, and the VASP-to-bank interfaces that allow cross-border\u000d\u000acommerce to settle reliably and cheaply is the most durable infrastructure investment in African\u000d\u000adigital finance.\u000d\u000a2. Multi-jurisdiction compliance infrastructure \u2014 The complexity of operating in multiple African\u000d\u000aregulatory environments simultaneously is a genuine barrier, but it is a soluble one, and the founders\u000d\u000awho solve it for themselves can sell the solution to others. A compliance platform that manages\u000d\u000aNigerian NFIU obligations, Ghanaian FIC requirements, Kenyan KRA reporting, and South African FSCA\u000d\u000amonitoring from a single interface is a product that every African VASP with cross-border ambitions\u000d\u000awill eventually need.\u000d\u000a3. Identity and trust infrastructure \u2014 Cross-border commerce requires cross-border trust, the ability\u000d\u000afor a Lagos merchant to verify that an Accra customer is who they say they are, and vice versa. The\u000d\u000aAfCFTA Digital Trade Protocol\u2019s cross-border e-KYC provisions are a mandate to create this\u000d\u000ainfrastructure. The private sector founders who build it, before the government mandate creates\u000d\u000ademand pressure, will have a first-mover advantage in the continental identity market that no\u000d\u000aincumbent financial institution currently occupies.\u000d\u000aThe pan-African regulatory convergence is coming. It will not arrive on the timeline that\u000d\u000aAfCFTA\u2019s optimists have projected. The Digital Trade Protocol will take longer to ratify,\u000d\u000alonger to implement, and longer to translate into operating reality than any\u000d\u000aannouncement suggests. But the direction is fixed, and the founders who build in the\u000d\u000adirection of convergence, designing products for multiple jurisdictions, building\u000d\u000acompliance infrastructure that scales across regulatory frameworks, and positioning\u000d\u000athemselves as the bridge between where the market is and where the framework will\u000d\u000a\u2014 169 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aeventually be, will be the ones who own the infrastructure when convergence eventually\u000d\u000aarrives.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 170 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCHAPTER Twenty-Two\u000d\u000aBuilding the Mental Model: How to Navigate\u000d\u000aRegulations That Don\u2019t Exist Yet\u000d\u000a\u201cThe most valuable regulatory skill is not compliance. It is foresight. The regulator who writes the rules\u000d\u000atomorrow is responding to the market signals that are visible today.\u201d\u000d\u000a\u2014 Chimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aThis is the last chapter of the book, and in some ways the most important.\u000d\u000aEvery specific regulation described in the preceding twenty-one chapters will change.\u000d\u000aSome of the changes will be incremental, amended rules, revised capital requirements,\u000d\u000aupdated NFIU guidelines. Some will be more fundamental, new legislation, new\u000d\u000aregulatory mandates, new institutions. The ISA 2025, which this book treats as the current\u000d\u000afoundation of Nigerian digital asset regulation, will itself eventually be amended or\u000d\u000asuperseded. The Digital Asset Rules, whose specifics have been detailed throughout, will\u000d\u000abe revised again. The market will generate new products that no existing framework\u000d\u000aanticipated, and the regulators will respond.\u000d\u000aA book that gives you only rules is a book that begins to expire on the day it is published.\u000d\u000aThe chapters you have read to this point have given you the current rules, the current\u000d\u000ainstitutions, and the current frameworks. This chapter gives you something different: a\u000d\u000away of thinking about regulatory development that does not expire, that remains useful\u000d\u000awhen the specific rules have changed, when new institutions have been created, and when\u000d\u000athe products you are building do not yet have a regulatory category.\u000d\u000aThe Three Signals That Precede Every Nigerian Regulation\u000d\u000aAfter nearly a decade of watching Nigerian regulatory frameworks develop, from inside\u000d\u000apolicy rooms, from industry bodies, from the market itself, I have observed three signals\u000d\u000athat reliably precede the formalisation of a new regulatory requirement. They are not\u000d\u000ainfallible. They are not perfectly timed. But they are consistent enough, across enough\u000d\u000a\u2014 171 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000acases, to constitute a genuine early warning system for founders who know how to read\u000d\u000athem.\u000d\u000aSignal One: The Conference Circuit\u000d\u000aWhen a concern is raised by senior regulatory officials at multiple different events;\u000d\u000aconferences, industry forums, central bank workshops, international policy meetings, over\u000d\u000aa period of six to twelve months, that concern is almost always in active internal policy\u000d\u000adevelopment. The framework that will address it will arrive within twelve to twenty-four\u000d\u000amonths of the concern becoming a consistent conference-circuit theme.\u000d\u000aThis signal is reliable for a specific institutional reason: Nigerian regulatory officials do not\u000d\u000atypically discuss matters publicly that are not already in some stage of internal\u000d\u000aconsideration. A CBN director who raises stablecoin dollarisation risk at three consecutive\u000d\u000afintech conferences is not theorising. They are preparing the market for a framework that\u000d\u000ais already being drafted.\u000d\u000aThe practical application: track what senior regulatory officials are saying in public\u000d\u000aappearances. Not the press releases, not the formal publications, those come after the\u000d\u000aframework is already fixed. The conference remarks, the panel discussions, the Q&A\u000d\u000asessions at industry events. These are where the concerns that will become regulations are\u000d\u000afirst articulated in forms that allow response.\u000d\u000aI have seen this signal produce regulatory frameworks across multiple cycles. The\u000d\u000aconcerns about untraceable P2P transactions that the CBN was articulating in 2019 and\u000d\u000a2020 produced the 2021 circular. The concerns about investor protection in token sales that\u000d\u000aSEC officials were raising at industry events in 2021 produced the 2022 Digital Asset\u000d\u000aRules. The concerns about stablecoin dollarisation risk that the CBN has been raising in\u000d\u000apublic forums since 2023 produced the joint CBN-SEC stablecoin working group in 2025.\u000d\u000aThe signal-to-framework timeline varies, but the signal itself is consistent.\u000d\u000aSignal Two: The International Standard-Setter Publication\u000d\u000aWhen FATF, the BIS, or the IMF publishes guidance on a specific risk category, a targeted\u000d\u000aupdate, a working paper, a policy recommendation, Nigerian regulators begin internal\u000d\u000a\u2014 172 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aframework development within six to eighteen months. This timeline is not coincidental.\u000d\u000aIt is the product of a compliance obligation: Nigeria\u2019s FATF membership and GIABA\u000d\u000aparticipation create peer review expectations that turn international guidance into\u000d\u000adomestic regulatory pressure.\u000d\u000aThe mechanism is direct: the FATF issues guidance on a virtual asset risk. GIABA\u2019s\u000d\u000amutual evaluation process will eventually assess Nigeria\u2019s implementation of that\u000d\u000aguidance. The CBN and NFIU, aware of this evaluation timeline, begin developing the\u000d\u000adomestic framework that addresses the guidance before the evaluation arrives. The\u000d\u000aframework emerges not because Nigerian regulators identified the risk independently, but\u000d\u000abecause the international evaluation cycle created a compliance deadline.\u000d\u000aSignal Type Source Lead Time Founder Action\u000d\u000aConference signal CBN, SEC, NFIU senior\u000d\u000aofficials at multiple\u000d\u000aforums\u000d\u000a12\u201324 months Track the concern, design for it,\u000d\u000aengage the working group when\u000d\u000aformed\u000d\u000aFATF guidance Annual Targeted\u000d\u000aUpdate, revised\u000d\u000aRecommendations\u000d\u000a6\u201318 months Implement aligned controls now;\u000d\u000aframe your product as part of the\u000d\u000asolution\u000d\u000aBIS publication Working papers,\u000d\u000aInnovation Hub outputs\u000d\u000a12\u201336 months Monitor for wholesale CBDC and\u000d\u000astablecoin design implications\u000d\u000aIMF Technical Assistance\u000d\u000areport on Nigeria\u000d\u000aCountry-specific TA\u000d\u000areports\u000d\u000a12\u201324 months These are the most direct signal of\u000d\u000aCBN/SEC framework priorities\u000d\u000aWorking group formation SEC, CBN, NITDA\u000d\u000aworking group\u000d\u000aannouncement\u000d\u000a18\u201330 months Engage immediately, the convening\u000d\u000asignals a committed intention to act\u000d\u000aEnforcement action without\u000d\u000aframework\u000d\u000aCBN circulars, SEC\u000d\u000aenforcement notices\u000d\u000a6\u201312 months The enforcement pattern is the draft\u000d\u000aframework; design to its logic now\u000d\u000aSignal Three: The Working Group Formation\u000d\u000aWhen a regulator convenes a working group or industry consultation on a topic that\u000d\u000apreviously had no formal engagement structure, the framework is coming within\u000d\u000atwenty-four to thirty months, regardless of what the consultation produces. The\u000d\u000aconvening itself signals institutional commitment to act.\u000d\u000aThis signal is the most reliable of the three because it requires the regulator to have\u000d\u000aalready made an internal decision: not just that the topic merits attention, but that it merits\u000d\u000a\u2014 173 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000athe resource investment of a formal consultation process. Regulators do not convene\u000d\u000aworking groups on topics they have decided not to regulate. The working group is the\u000d\u000aregulator\u2019s public declaration that it is going to do something; the question the working\u000d\u000agroup addresses is only what.\u000d\u000aThe practical implication is direct: when a working group is announced, engage with it\u000d\u000aimmediately and substantively. Not to lobby for outcomes that favour your specific\u000d\u000abusiness model, but to contribute technical knowledge that helps the framework be\u000d\u000awell-designed. The founders who sit in the working group rooms when the framework is\u000d\u000abeing shaped have the advantage of knowing exactly what the Commission was trying to\u000d\u000aachieve when it wrote each provision, and therefore understand how to satisfy its intent in\u000d\u000aways that go beyond technical compliance.\u000d\u000aThe CBN-SEC joint stablecoin working group announced in October 2025 is a live example\u000d\u000aof this signal. It was announced. The framework is coming. The founders who engaged\u000d\u000awith its process before its report was published, through industry body submissions,\u000d\u000adirect requests to present, and written technical input, will have shaped it. The founders\u000d\u000awho waited for the published report will implement it. The difference between these two\u000d\u000agroups, in terms of the product architecture implications of the framework, will be\u000d\u000amaterial.\u000d\u000aThe First Principles Framework\u000d\u000aBeyond the three signals, there is a deeper analytical capacity that this book has been\u000d\u000abuilding throughout: the ability to reason from first principles about what a regulator will\u000d\u000aeventually require, even before the specific framework exists.\u000d\u000aEvery Nigerian regulatory framework for digital financial products is ultimately an\u000d\u000aattempt to satisfy four foundational concerns. These concerns do not change. They are as\u000d\u000apresent in the 1958 CBN Act as they are in the ISA 2025. They will be as present in\u000d\u000awhatever legislation follows ISA 2025 as they are today. Understanding them is what\u000d\u000aallows you to anticipate regulatory requirements before they are written down.\u000d\u000a1. The legibility concern \u2014 Regulators must be able to see, understand, and assess the activities they\u000d\u000aare supervising. Any product that makes financial activity opaque, that obscures who is transacting, in\u000d\u000a\u2014 174 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000awhat amount, with what counterparty, for what purpose, will eventually trigger a regulatory\u000d\u000aresponse. The 2021 CBN circular was a legibility response. The Travel Rule is a legibility response. The\u000d\u000aNFIU\u2019s goAML registration requirement is a legibility response. Build legibility into your product from\u000d\u000athe outset: clear transaction records, clean identity trails, auditable flows. Not as a compliance\u000d\u000arequirement, but as a product design principle.\u000d\u000a2. The accountability concern \u2014 When something goes wrong, a platform failure, a fraud, a consumer\u000d\u000aloss, a money laundering incident, there must be an identifiable human or legal entity that can be\u000d\u000aheld responsible. The DeFi regulatory challenge is fundamentally an accountability challenge: no\u000d\u000acentral operator, no responsible party, no enforcement point. Any product architecture that\u000d\u000asystematically obscures or eliminates accountability will attract regulatory attention proportional to\u000d\u000aits scale. Build identifiable accountability at every layer of your product.\u000d\u000a3. The systemic stability concern \u2014 The CBN\u2019s mandate is monetary stability. The NDIC\u2019s mandate is\u000d\u000adepositor protection and system resilience. Any product that, at scale, could create systemic risk, that\u000d\u000acould amplify financial instability, reduce monetary policy effectiveness, or create contagion risk\u000d\u000aacross the financial system, will be regulated in proportion to its scale potential. Stablecoins concern\u000d\u000athe CBN not because they are new but because, at scale, they could substitute for naira in ways that\u000d\u000acompromise monetary sovereignty. Design your products with an honest assessment of their systemic\u000d\u000arisk at scale, and engage with regulators about that assessment proactively.\u000d\u000a4. The consumer protection concern \u2014 The SEC\u2019s mandate is investor protection. The FCCPC\u2019s\u000d\u000amandate is consumer protection. Any product that creates conditions for consumer harm,\u000d\u000ainformation asymmetry, opaque risk, inadequate disclosure, difficult redemption, or fraudulent\u000d\u000apromotion, will eventually attract the attention of one or both of these institutions. The FCCPC\u2019s 2025\u000d\u000adigital lending crackdown, the SEC\u2019s Finfluencer provisions, and the investor protection framework in\u000d\u000aISA 2025 are all expressions of this concern. Design products that treat consumer protection as a\u000d\u000afeature, not a compliance overhead.\u000d\u000aWhen you encounter a new product category, a new market, or a new technology that has\u000d\u000ano existing Nigerian regulatory framework, apply these four lenses. Ask: does this\u000d\u000aproduct create legibility problems for supervisors? Does it create accountability gaps?\u000d\u000aDoes it create systemic stability risks at scale? Does it create consumer protection\u000d\u000aconcerns? The answers will tell you where the regulatory attention will eventually focus,\u000d\u000ahow urgently, and from which institution. They will not tell you exactly what the\u000d\u000aframework will say. But they will tell you what it will be about.\u000d\u000a\u2014 175 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe Foresight Practice: Building Your Regulatory Intelligence System\u000d\u000aThe signals described in this chapter are only useful if you are in a position to receive\u000d\u000athem. That requires a deliberate, regular practice of regulatory intelligence gathering that\u000d\u000amost founders do not maintain.\u000d\u000aHere is the minimum practice:\u000d\u000a\u2022 Monthly scan of CBN, SEC Nigeria, NFIU, and NITDA websites for new publications, circulars, and\u000d\u000aconsultation papers.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Quarterly reading of the FATF Targeted Update on Virtual Assets, the single most predictive document\u000d\u000afor Nigerian digital asset regulatory development.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Active participation in at least one industry body (BNUG, FintechNGR, BICON) that has direct\u000d\u000aengagement with Nigerian regulatory working groups.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Attendance at two to four industry conferences per year where senior regulatory officials speak, with\u000d\u000adeliberate attention to the themes they raise in their remarks.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Maintenance of a simple log: new regulatory signals observed, their source, their apparent concern,\u000d\u000aand the product or compliance implication for your business.\u000d\u000aThis practice requires approximately four to six hours per month. It produces a rolling\u000d\u000apicture of the regulatory landscape that is worth considerably more than the cost of\u000d\u000amaintaining it.\u000d\u000aThe Closing Thought\u000d\u000aI want to end this book where it began: with Emeka, in his office in Yaba, looking at a\u000d\u000aletter he was not prepared for.\u000d\u000aEmeka\u2019s story is not a story about bad luck or regulatory aggression. It is a story about a\u000d\u000afounder who was building something genuinely valuable, in a regulatory environment he\u000d\u000ahad not invested in understanding, and who paid the price that founders pay when the\u000d\u000agap between those two things closes suddenly rather than gradually.\u000d\u000aThe book you have just read exists because that story is more common than it should be in\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s digital asset ecosystem, and because the information that would have prevented\u000d\u000a\u2014 176 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000ait was available, if it had been assembled in one place, in plain language, written for the\u000d\u000afounder rather than the lawyer.\u000d\u000aWhat I hope this book has done is give you what Emeka needed before the letter arrived: a\u000d\u000aworking map of the regulatory terrain, a practical understanding of the compliance\u000d\u000ainfrastructure that the terrain requires, a set of tools for engaging the institutions that\u000d\u000agovern it, and a mental model that will keep working for you when the specific details of\u000d\u000athe terrain have changed.\u000d\u000aThe regulated market does not belong to the founder who knows the most rules.\u000d\u000aIt belongs to the founder who understands the most deeply why the rules exist,\u000d\u000aand who has built something that the regulators are glad to see in their market.\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s digital financial future is genuinely extraordinary in its potential. The\u000d\u000ademographic foundation, a young, connected, financially underserved population, is\u000d\u000airreplaceable. The policy foundation, ISA 2025, the ARIP framework, the FATF grey list\u000d\u000aexit, and the CBN-SEC joint stablecoin work are more solid than ever before. The talent\u000d\u000afoundation, the engineers, the product builders, the policy advocates, the community\u000d\u000aorganisers who have built Nigeria\u2019s blockchain ecosystem from scratch over the past\u000d\u000adecade, are formidable.\u000d\u000aWhat the market has lacked, and what this book has tried to supply, is the knowledge\u000d\u000ainfrastructure: the clear, honest, insider-informed account of how the regulatory system\u000d\u000aworks, what it requires, and how to build within it without being broken by it.\u000d\u000aYou have that now.\u000d\u000aBuild something worthy of it.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000a\u2014 177 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aAppendix A\u000d\u000aThe 90-Day Regulatory Readiness Checklist\u000d\u000aThis checklist is sequenced for a Nigerian digital asset company at any stage from idea to\u000d\u000apost-ARIP. Work through it in order. Items in each phase depend on items in the phase\u000d\u000abefore. Assign a named owner to every item. Set a completion date. Review weekly.\u000d\u000aThe checklist assumes you are building for SEC Nigeria registration as your primary\u000d\u000aregulatory objective, with NFIU compliance and CBN engagement as parallel\u000d\u000aworkstreams. Adjust the sequencing if your product requires CBN payment system\u000d\u000aauthorisation as a first step.\u000d\u000aPHASE 1 \u00b7 WEEKS 1 \u20132: Foundation & Assessment\u000d\u000aA1 Determine your regulatory category\u000d\u000aMap every function your product performs against the four VASP categories: DAX (exchange), DAOP (offering\u000d\u000aplatform), DAC (custodian), DAI (intermediary). List every function, and assign each to a category. If you map\u000d\u000ato more than one category, you need more than one registration. Do not proceed until this mapping is\u000d\u000acomplete. Every other decision depends on it.\u000d\u000aA2 Identify all applicable regulators\u000d\u000aUsing the Product-to-Regulator Matrix (Appendix C), identify every regulator your product engages. For most\u000d\u000aVASPs: SEC Nigeria (mandatory), NFIU (mandatory), CBN (mandatory if naira on/off-ramp or payment\u000d\u000aproduct). Assign a relationship owner for each regulator.\u000d\u000aA3 Conduct a corporate structure gap analysis\u000d\u000aCompare your current structure against SEC Nigeria's requirements: Nigerian CAC incorporation \u2713; minimum\u000d\u000apaid-up capital at required level \u2713; Nigerian CEO/MD resident in Nigeria \u2713; 60% Nigerian board members\u000d\u000a\u2713; Nigerian office address \u2713. Document every gap with a remediation plan.\u000d\u000aA4 Identify your compliance officer\u000d\u000aAppoint a compliance officer or MLRO with specific AML/CFT experience in financial services or digital assets.\u000d\u000aThis person must: understand the MLPPA 2022, know how to use the NFIU goAML portal, have authority to\u000d\u000afile STRs independently. If no qualified person exists internally, begin search immediately. Do not apply for\u000d\u000aARIP without this role filled.\u000d\u000aA5 Conduct Business-Wide Risk Assessment (BWRA)\u000d\u000aDocument your platform\u2019s specific ML/TF risks across four dimensions: products and services offered,\u000d\u000acustomer types and geographies, delivery channels, and jurisdictions of operation. This is not a generic\u000d\u000a\u2014 178 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000atemplate. It must reflect your specific business. The NFIU examines it. Assign the compliance officer as author.\u000d\u000aComplete within two weeks.\u000d\u000aPHASE 2 \u00b7 WEEKS 3 \u20134: Compliance Infrastructure\u000d\u000aA6 Register on NFIU goAML portal\u000d\u000aRegister as a reporting entity on the NFIU\u2019s goAML portal. Required documents: CAC Certificate of\u000d\u000aIncorporation, industry regulator licence (or ARIP application confirmation), evidence of compliance officer\u000d\u000aappointment, letter of introduction. This registration is separate from your SEC application and must be\u000d\u000acompleted independently. URL: goaml.nfiu.gov.ng\u000d\u000aA7 Build your KYC tiering framework\u000d\u000aDocument your three-tier KYC framework: Tier 0 (basic mobile onboarding, NIN verification, daily limit\u000d\u000a#50,000), Tier 1 (NIN + BVN + address, daily limit #200,000), Tier 2 (enhanced, source of funds, higher limits).\u000d\u000aMap each tier to transaction limits, product access, and ongoing monitoring requirements. Ensure BVN and\u000d\u000aNIN verification APIs are integrated and tested.\u000d\u000aA8 Implement transaction monitoring system\u000d\u000aConfigure a transaction monitoring system with documented alert thresholds. Minimum alert types: large\u000d\u000acash transactions (individuals #5M+, corporates #10M+), unusual transaction patterns vs. declared customer\u000d\u000aprofile, transactions involving high-risk jurisdictions, rapid fund movement, structuring patterns. Assign daily\u000d\u000aalert review to a named compliance team member. Test with synthetic transactions before go-live.\u000d\u000aA9 Implement sanctions and PEP screening\u000d\u000aDeploy screening against: UN Security Council consolidated list, OFAC SDN list, EU consolidated sanctions list,\u000d\u000aNFIU domestic designated persons and entities list. Screen at onboarding and weekly on all active customers.\u000d\u000aLog all screening runs with timestamps and outcomes. Configure automated re-screening alerts for new list\u000d\u000aadditions.\u000d\u000aA10 Establish STR and CTR filing capability\u000d\u000aSet up your STR and CTR filing workflow on the NFIU goAML portal. File a test STR with synthetic data to\u000d\u000aconfirm the process works end-to-end before you have real customers. Document your internal STR escalation\u000d\u000apath: who identifies suspicious activity \u2192 who investigates \u2192 who authorises filing \u2192 who submits. STRs\u000d\u000amust be filed immediately upon identifying suspicion. CTRs required for cash transactions above #5M\u000d\u000a(individuals) or #10M (corporates).\u000d\u000aA11 Establish record retention infrastructure\u000d\u000aAll KYC documents, transaction records, and compliance investigation records must be retained for minimum\u000d\u000afive years post-relationship end. Implement append-only, access-controlled logging for all compliance actions.\u000d\u000aStore in a cloud system with geographic redundancy and defined retention policies. Document the retention\u000d\u000aarchitecture and appoint a records custodian.\u000d\u000a\u2014 179 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aPHASE 3 \u00b7 WEEKS 5 \u20138: ARIP Application Preparation\u000d\u000aA12 Draft your white paper\u000d\u000aWrite the ARIP white paper to the SEC\u2019s assessed standard (not the minimum formal requirement). Must\u000d\u000ainclude: technical architecture and blockchain infrastructure; token economics and rights if tokens are issued;\u000d\u000aAML/CFT framework summary; investor/user risk factors; team qualifications; legal classification of your\u000d\u000aproduct and the basis for that classification. Engage a specialist with digital asset securities experience to\u000d\u000areview. Do not submit until it honestly addresses the classification question.\u000d\u000aA13 Obtain legal opinion on token/product classification\u000d\u000aCommission a written legal opinion from a qualified practitioner with demonstrable ISA 2025 and SEC Digital\u000d\u000aAsset Rules experience. The opinion must address: whether your product constitutes a security under ISA\u000d\u000a2025; which VASP registration category applies; and any additional regulatory requirements (CBN, NFIU, NCC).\u000d\u000aThis document accompanies your initial assessment filing.\u000d\u000aA14 Verify and document minimum capital\u000d\u000aConfirm your paid-up capital meets the SEC requirement for your registration category. As of June 2025:\u000d\u000aexchanges and custodians #2 billion (to be met by 30 June 2027 for existing operators; new applicants should\u000d\u000aplan for this level). Capital must be in the company\u2019s account for minimum three months before application,\u000d\u000awith a clean audit trail of source of funds. Obtain audited confirmation from your external auditors.\u000d\u000aA15 Conduct informal SEC pre-screening\u000d\u000aBefore submitting formally, request an informal pre-screening conversation with the SEC\u2019s Digital Assets Unit.\u000d\u000aPrepare: one-page product description, proposed regulatory category, summary of your compliance\u000d\u000ainfrastructure. The purpose is to identify structural issues before the formal submission costs are incurred.\u000d\u000aThis step is not officially documented but materially improves application outcomes.\u000d\u000aA16 Submit ARIP Initial Assessment\u000d\u000aSubmit the Initial Assessment Form via the SEC ePortal at home.sec.gov.ng. Pay the non-refundable\u000d\u000aassessment fee (#200,000). (There\u2019s a rumor that this amount has been increased to #1.5M. DYOR). Include:\u000d\u000acompleted assessment form, draft white paper, legal classification opinion, CAC documents, evidence of\u000d\u000aminimum capital. Await SEC eligibility notification (within 30 days under the rules).\u000d\u000aPHASE 4 \u00b7 WEEKS 9 \u201312 / THE AIP PERIOD: Operational Readiness\u000d\u000aA17 Submit ARIP formal application\u000d\u000aUpon eligibility notification, submit the full ARIP application through an accredited solicitor or adviser. Pay the\u000d\u000anon-refundable processing fee (#2,000,000). Upon approval, receive your Approval-in-Principle (AIP) valid for\u000d\u000aup to 12 months. The AIP is the beginning of regulated operations, not the end of the compliance journey.\u000d\u000aA18 Engage the CBN if product requires it\u000d\u000a\u2014 180 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aIf your product involves naira on/off-ramps, stablecoin payment functions, or payment system infrastructure:\u000d\u000ainitiate engagement with the CBN\u2019s Payment System Management Department. Use the engagement\u000d\u000aframework in Chapter 16. Your SEC AIP is the credential that makes this conversation possible. Do not\u000d\u000aapproach the CBN before you have initiated the ARIP process.\u000d\u000aA19 Establish your AIP-period compliance cadence\u000d\u000aDuring the 12-month AIP period: file daily transaction monitoring reviews, weekly PEP and sanctions\u000d\u000are-screening, monthly PEP register submission to NFIU via goAML, quarterly compliance training for all staff,\u000d\u000aquarterly reports to SEC as required, annual BWRA review. Appoint a compliance calendar owner. Treat the\u000d\u000aAIP period as a live regulatory examination, because it is.\u000d\u000aA20 Prepare full registration application\u000d\u000aAt the 10-month mark of your AIP, begin preparing the full SEC registration application. This is filed via the SEC\u000d\u000aePortal and requires: evidence of 12 months of AIP-period compliance, audited accounts confirming\u000d\u000amaintained minimum capital, compliance officer appointment confirmation, updated BWRA, and any\u000d\u000aadditional documentation specified in your AIP conditions. Target submission at month 11.\u000d\u000aChecklist Review Cadence\u000d\u000aThis checklist is most effective when reviewed weekly in a 30-minute compliance team meeting. Assign RAG\u000d\u000a(Red/Amber/Green) status to each item. Red items are presented to the CEO at every board update. The\u000d\u000acompliance officer owns the checklist. The CEO owns the consequence of it being wrong.\u000d\u000a\u2014 181 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aAppendix B\u000d\u000aAfrica Regulatory Contact & Resource Directory\u000d\u000aThis directory provides official contact and resource information for the primary\u000d\u000aregulatory institutions relevant to Nigerian and African digital asset businesses. All URLs\u000d\u000aand contacts are current as of May 2026. Always verify on the institution\u2019s official website\u000d\u000abefore submitting applications or correspondence.\u000d\u000aPrimary Nigerian Regulators\u000d\u000aSecurities and Exchange\u000d\u000aCommission Nigeria (SEC)\u000d\u000asec.gov.ng \u00b7 home.sec.gov.ng (ePortal)\u000d\u000aPrimary regulator for digital assets and VASPs under ISA 2025. ARIP applications, Digital\u000d\u000aAsset Rules, investor protection. The SEC ePortal (home.sec.gov.ng) is the submission\u000d\u000aplatform for ARIP initial assessments, applications, and AIP-period reporting.\u000d\u000aT: (+234) 09-462-3600 \u00b7 E: info@sec.gov.ng\u000d\u000aCentral Bank of Nigeria\u000d\u000a(CBN)\u000d\u000acbn.gov.ng\u000d\u000aApex monetary authority. Payment Systems Management Department oversees\u000d\u000apayment product authorisations and VASP banking access guidelines. Financial Policy &\u000d\u000aRegulation Department handles monetary policy and stablecoin-adjacent product\u000d\u000aconsiderations.\u000d\u000aT: (+234) 0800-225-5226 \u00b7 E: info@cbn.gov.ng\u000d\u000aNigerian Financial\u000d\u000aIntelligence Unit (NFIU)\u000d\u000anfiu.gov.ng \u00b7 goaml.nfiu.gov.ng (goAML portal)\u000d\u000aFinancial intelligence unit. Mandatory registration on goAML portal for all VASPs as\u000d\u000areporting entities. STR, CTR, PEP register, and annual testing submissions via goAML.\u000d\u000aDecember 2024 guidelines are the current AML/CFT compliance standard for VASPs.\u000d\u000aT: (+234) 09-461-0000 \u00b7 E: info@nfiu.gov.ng\u000d\u000aNITDA \u2014 National\u000d\u000aInformation Technology\u000d\u000aDevelopment Agency\u000d\u000anitda.gov.ng\u000d\u000aAdministers National Blockchain Policy (2023), Nigeria Data Protection Regulation\u000d\u000a(NDPR), and National AI Strategy (2025). Primary engagement point for blockchain\u000d\u000aecosystem policy, data protection compliance, and AI governance questions.\u000d\u000aT: (+234) 09-291-5000 \u00b7 E: info@nitda.gov.ng\u000d\u000aCorporate Affairs\u000d\u000aCommission (CAC)\u000d\u000acac.gov.ng\u000d\u000aCompany registration, Beneficial Ownership Register (PSC register). All VASP applicants\u000d\u000amust be fully CAC-registered. The Beneficial Ownership Register (introduced as part of\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s FATF reform programme) requires annual updates.\u000d\u000aT: (+234) 09-461-8000 \u00b7 E: info@cac.gov.ng\u000d\u000a\u2014 182 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aEFCC \u2014 Economic and\u000d\u000aFinancial Crimes\u000d\u000aCommission\u000d\u000aefcc.gov.ng\u000d\u000aInvestigates and prosecutes financial crimes involving digital assets. Not a licensing\u000d\u000aauthority. Compliance with NFIU AML obligations and SEC registration is the primary\u000d\u000aprotection against EFCC scrutiny.\u000d\u000aT: (+234) 09-904-5096 \u00b7 E: info@efcc.gov.ng\u000d\u000aNAICOM \u2014 National\u000d\u000aInsurance Commission\u000d\u000anaicom.gov.ng\u000d\u000aRelevant for fidelity bond requirements in VASP registration and for founders building\u000d\u000ainsurance-adjacent blockchain products. SEC Nigeria\u2019s VASP rules require fidelity bonds\u000d\u000afrom NAICOM-approved insurers.\u000d\u000aT: (+234) 09-870-3006 \u00b7 E: info@naicom.gov.ng\u000d\u000aKey Legal & Regulatory Frameworks \u2014 Official Download Links\u000d\u000aDocument Source\u000d\u000aInvestments and Securities Act 2025 (ISA\u000d\u000a2025)\u000d\u000asec.gov.ng/investments-and-securities-act-2025\u000d\u000aSEC Digital Asset Rules (amended June\u000d\u000a2025)\u000d\u000asec.gov.ng/our-mandate/regulation/rules-and-regulations\u000d\u000aARIP Framework & Checklist home.sec.gov.ng (ARIP resources section)\u000d\u000aCBN Guidelines on VASP Banking (2023) cbn.gov.ng/Out/2023/PSM/CBN%20VASP%20Guidelines.pdf\u000d\u000aNFIU AML/CFT Compliance Framework for\u000d\u000aVASPs\u000d\u000anfiu.gov.ng/guidelines\u000d\u000aMLPPA 2022 (Money Laundering\u000d\u000aPrevention & Prohibition Act)\u000d\u000anfiu.gov.ng/laws\u000d\u000aNigeria Data Protection Act 2023 (NDPA) ndpc.gov.ng\u000d\u000aNational Blockchain Policy 2023 nitda.gov.ng/blockchain-policy\u000d\u000aNational AI Strategy 2025 ncair.nitda.gov.ng\u000d\u000aFATF Recommendation 15 (virtual assets) fatf-gafi.org/Recommendations\u000d\u000aFATF Annual Targeted Update on Virtual\u000d\u000aAssets\u000d\u000afatf-gafi.org (published each June)\u000d\u000aCBN Monetary Policy & VASP Guidelines\u000d\u000a(2024\u20132025)\u000d\u000acbn.gov.ng/AboutCBN/Reforms.html\u000d\u000a\u2014 183 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aRegional & International Bodies\u000d\u000aGIABA \u2014\u000d\u000aInter-Governmental\u000d\u000aAction Group Against\u000d\u000aMoney Laundering in\u000d\u000aWest Africa\u000d\u000agiaba.org\u000d\u000aFATF-style regional body for West Africa. Conducts mutual evaluations of member\u000d\u000astates including Nigeria. Publications and mutual evaluation reports available on\u000d\u000awebsite. Key reference for understanding Nigeria\u2019s AML/CFT obligations.\u000d\u000aE: info@giaba.org\u000d\u000aAfCFTA Secretariat afcfta.au.int\u000d\u000aOfficial source for AfCFTA Digital Trade Protocol progress, ratification status, and\u000d\u000amember state implementation guidance. Monitor for digital trade protocol\u000d\u000adevelopments.\u000d\u000aE: info@afcfta.au.int\u000d\u000aPAPSS \u2014 Pan-African\u000d\u000aPayment and Settlement\u000d\u000aSystem\u000d\u000apapss.com\u000d\u000aCross-border payment infrastructure for Africa. As of May 2026: 16 countries, 14\u000d\u000apayment switches, 150+ commercial banks including 22 in Nigeria. CBN relaxed PAPSS\u000d\u000adocumentation requirements in April 2025 to basic KYC for transactions under USD\u000d\u000a2,000 (individuals) and USD 5,000 (corporates).\u000d\u000aE: info@papss.com\u000d\u000aIndustry Bodies & Associations\u000d\u000aBlockchain Nigeria User\u000d\u000aGroup (BNUG), aka,\u000d\u000aBlockchain Experts\u000d\u000aAssociation of Nigeria\u000d\u000a(BEAN)\u000d\u000ahttps://blockchainexperts.ng/\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s largest Web3 innovation community (25,000+ members). Primary industry\u000d\u000avoice in national blockchain policy dialogue. Working group participation, regulatory\u000d\u000aconsultation submissions, ecosystem events and training.\u000d\u000aE: info@blockchainnigeria.org\u000d\u000aFintech Association of\u000d\u000aNigeria (FintechNGR)\u000d\u000afintechng.org\u000d\u000aPrimary fintech industry body with established relationships across CBN, SEC Nigeria,\u000d\u000aand NITDA. Domain expert for digital assets policy. Key channel for regulatory\u000d\u000aconsultation engagement.\u000d\u000aE: info@fintechng.org\u000d\u000aBlockchain Industry\u000d\u000aCoordinating Committee\u000d\u000aof Nigeria (BICCON)\u000d\u000ahttp://biccon.com.ng/\u000d\u000aProfessional association for blockchain practitioners. Board member training,\u000d\u000acertification, and policy advocacy.\u000d\u000aE: info@bean.org.ng\u000d\u000a\u2014 184 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aAppendix C\u000d\u000aProduct-to-Regulator Mapping Matrix\u000d\u000aThis matrix maps digital asset product categories to their primary Nigerian regulatory\u000d\u000atouchpoints. Use it at the beginning of every new product initiative, before you write a\u000d\u000aline of code or draft a single policy document. The matrix reflects the regulatory position\u000d\u000aas of May 2026 under ISA 2025 and the SEC\u2019s June 2025 Digital Asset Rules.\u000d\u000aProduct / Activity SEC CBN NFIU NITDA EFCC NCC Key Note\u000d\u000aDigital Asset Exchange\u000d\u000a(CEX / P2P)\u000d\u000aPRIMARY(\u000d\u000aDAX)\u000d\u000aSECONDA\u000d\u000aRY(naira\u000d\u000arails)\u000d\u000aPRIMAR\u000d\u000aY(AML)\u000d\u000aMONIT\u000d\u000aOR(data\u000d\u000a)\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 DAX + DAC if holding client\u000d\u000aassets. Naira pair delisting\u000d\u000arules apply.\u000d\u000aDecentralised Exchange\u000d\u000a(DEX)\u000d\u000aSECONDA\u000d\u000aRY(emerg\u000d\u000aing)\u000d\u000a\u2014 MONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000aMONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 No DEX-specific framework.\u000d\u000aVASP rules apply if\u000d\u000aidentifiable operator.\u000d\u000aDigital Asset Custodian PRIMARY(\u000d\u000aDAC)\u000d\u000a\u2014 PRIMAR\u000d\u000aY(AML)\u000d\u000aMONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 Cold storage ratio required.\u000d\u000aFidelity bond from NAICOM\u000d\u000ainsurer.\u000d\u000aToken/Digital Asset\u000d\u000aOffering (ICO/IEO)\u000d\u000aPRIMARY(\u000d\u000aDAOP)\u000d\u000a\u2014 PRIMAR\u000d\u000aY(AML)\u000d\u000aMONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 All offerings to Nigerians\u000d\u000arequire DAOP registration.\u000d\u000aForeign issuers included.\u000d\u000aNaira-Pegged Stablecoin\u000d\u000aIssuance\u000d\u000aPRIMARY(\u000d\u000aDAOP/DA\u000d\u000aC)\u000d\u000aPRIMARY(\u000d\u000apayment)\u000d\u000aPRIMAR\u000d\u000aY(AML)\u000d\u000aMONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 Joint CBN\u2013SEC stablecoin\u000d\u000aWG framework pending\u000d\u000a(expected 2026). Engage\u000d\u000aboth now.\u000d\u000aDollar-Pegged Stablecoin\u000d\u000a(USDT equiv.)\u000d\u000aPRIMARY(\u000d\u000aDAX/DAO\u000d\u000aP)\u000d\u000aSECONDA\u000d\u000aRY(FX\u000d\u000arules)\u000d\u000aPRIMAR\u000d\u000aY(AML)\u000d\u000aMONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 FX management concern\u000d\u000atriggered if naira\u000d\u000aconversion offered.\u000d\u000aStablecoin Payment /\u000d\u000aRemittance Service\u000d\u000aSECONDA\u000d\u000aRY\u000d\u000aPRIMARY(\u000d\u000aIMTS/PSP\u000d\u000a)\u000d\u000aPRIMAR\u000d\u000aY(AML)\u000d\u000aMONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000a\u2014 MONIT\u000d\u000aOR(mo\u000d\u000abile)\u000d\u000aIMTS Guidelines (Jan 2024)\u000d\u000aapply. PSP licence likely\u000d\u000arequired.\u000d\u000aTokenised Real Estate\u000d\u000a(fractional)\u000d\u000aPRIMARY(\u000d\u000aDAOP)\u000d\u000a\u2014 PRIMAR\u000d\u000aY(AML)\u000d\u000aMONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 Land Use Act title risk. SPV\u000d\u000astructure mandatory. ISA\u000d\u000a2025 s.357.\u000d\u000aTokenised Securities /\u000d\u000aBonds\u000d\u000aPRIMARY(\u000d\u000aDAOP/DA\u000d\u000aX)\u000d\u000a\u2014 PRIMAR\u000d\u000aY(AML)\u000d\u000aMONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 Debt Management Office\u000d\u000a(DMO) notification for\u000d\u000atokenised FGN securities.\u000d\u000aDeFi Lending / Yield\u000d\u000aProtocol\u000d\u000aSECONDA\u000d\u000aRY(emerg\u000d\u000aing)\u000d\u000a\u2014 PRIMAR\u000d\u000aY(AML)\u000d\u000aMONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 Collective investment\u000d\u000ascheme risk if client funds\u000d\u000apooled.\u000d\u000a\u2014 185 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aDAO-Governed Platform SECONDA\u000d\u000aRY\u000d\u000a\u2014 SECOND\u000d\u000aARY\u000d\u000a\u2014 MONIT\u000d\u000aOR\u000d\u000a\u2014 No DAO legal personality in\u000d\u000aNigeria. Liability falls on\u000d\u000aidentifiable founders.\u000d\u000aNFTs with Investment\u000d\u000aCharacteristics\u000d\u000aPRIMARY(\u000d\u000aDAOP)\u000d\u000a\u2014 PRIMAR\u000d\u000aY(AML)\u000d\u000aMONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 Economic return NFTs are\u000d\u000asecurities under ISA 2025.\u000d\u000aBlockchain Identity / KYC\u000d\u000aProduct\u000d\u000aMONITOR \u2014 MONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000aPRIMAR\u000d\u000aY(NDPA)\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 NDPA 2023 consent and\u000d\u000adata localisation\u000d\u000arequirements apply.\u000d\u000aAI Credit Scoring (alt.\u000d\u000adata)\u000d\u000aMONITOR PRIMARY(\u000d\u000aCBN\u000d\u000asandbox)\u000d\u000aMONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000aPRIMAR\u000d\u000aY(NDPA\u000d\u000a+AI)\u000d\u000aMONIT\u000d\u000aOR(FC\u000d\u000aCPC)\u000d\u000a\u2014 CBN sandbox evaluates\u000d\u000aexplainability. FCCPC 2025\u000d\u000alending rules apply.\u000d\u000aAI-Assisted AML /\u000d\u000aCompliance Tool\u000d\u000aMONITOR SECONDA\u000d\u000aRY\u000d\u000aPRIMAR\u000d\u000aY\u000d\u000aMONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 Regulator-friendly\u000d\u000acategory. NFIU SupTech\u000d\u000acooperation possible.\u000d\u000aCrypto Mining Operation\u000d\u000a(commercial)\u000d\u000aPRIMARY(\u000d\u000aISA 2025)\u000d\u000a\u2014 PRIMAR\u000d\u000aY\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 MONIT\u000d\u000aOR(po\u000d\u000awer)\u000d\u000aNTAA 2025 tax obligations.\u000d\u000aMining-as-a-service = VASP\u000d\u000aactivity.\u000d\u000aUSSD / Mobile Wallet\u000d\u000a(naira-linked)\u000d\u000aMONITOR PRIMARY(\u000d\u000aCBN)\u000d\u000aPRIMAR\u000d\u000aY\u000d\u000aMONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000a\u2014 PRIMA\u000d\u000aRY(USS\u000d\u000aD)\u000d\u000aNCC USSD licence and CBN\u000d\u000amobile money framework\u000d\u000aboth apply.\u000d\u000aCross-Border Payment\u000d\u000a(PAPSS-linked)\u000d\u000aMONITOR PRIMARY(\u000d\u000aCBN/PAPS\u000d\u000aS)\u000d\u000aPRIMAR\u000d\u000aY\u000d\u000aMONITO\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 CBN April 2025 relaxed\u000d\u000aKYC: basic docs for txns <\u000d\u000aUSD 2,000/month.\u000d\u000aRobo-Advisory / AI\u000d\u000aInvestment Advice\u000d\u000aPRIMARY(\u000d\u000aDAI)\u000d\u000a\u2014 SECOND\u000d\u000aARY\u000d\u000aSECOND\u000d\u000aARY\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 Investment advisory licence\u000d\u000a(DAI). Suitability\u000d\u000aobligations apply.\u000d\u000aFinfluencer / Token\u000d\u000aPromotion\u000d\u000aPRIMARY(\u000d\u000aSEC\u000d\u000aRules)\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 \u2014 MONIT\u000d\u000aOR\u000d\u000a\u2014 SEC 2024 amended Rules\u000d\u000adefine and regulate\u000d\u000aFinfluencer activities.\u000d\u000aKey to matrix:\u000d\u000aPRIMARY \u2014 Direct regulatory mandate. Engagement and (usually) registration required.\u000d\u000aSECONDARY \u2014 Indirect mandate or emerging jurisdiction. Monitor closely; likely requires engagement.\u000d\u000aMONITOR \u2014 Regulatory interest exists. Track for developments; no current registration requirement.\u000d\u000a\u2014 \u2014 Not currently applicable.\u000d\u000aMatrix Currency\u000d\u000aThis matrix reflects the regulatory position as of May 2026. The Nigerian digital asset regulatory landscape\u000d\u000ais actively evolving. Review this matrix whenever: (1) SEC Nigeria issues amended Digital Asset Rules; (2)\u000d\u000aCBN issues new VASP guidelines; (3) NFIU issues updated AML/CFT compliance standards; (4) a new\u000d\u000aproduct category is added to your platform. Check sec.gov.ng, cbn.gov.ng, and nfiu.gov.ng monthly for\u000d\u000aupdates.\u000d\u000a\u2014 186 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aGlossary of Key Terms & Acronyms\u000d\u000aA plain-language reference covering blockchain technology, digital asset regulation,\u000d\u000aAML/CFT compliance, and the regulatory frameworks of Nigeria, Ghana, Kenya, South Africa &\u000d\u000aMauritius\u000d\u000aHOW TO USE THIS GLOSSARY\u000d\u000aThis glossary contains over 160 entries covering four categories of vocabulary used throughout this\u000d\u000abook:\u000d\u000a\u2022 Foundational blockchain & technical terms \u2014 Blockchain, wallet, smart contract, consensus\u000d\u000amechanism \u2014 the building blocks every founder must understand.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Regulatory & compliance terms \u2014 AML, CFT, KYC, FATF, Travel Rule, VASP \u2014 the language of financial\u000d\u000aoversight that your business must speak fluently.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Nigerian institutional & legislative terms \u2014 CBN, SEC Nigeria, NFIU, ISA 2025, MLPPA, ARIP \u2014 the\u000d\u000aspecific laws, agencies, and frameworks that govern your business in Nigeria.\u000d\u000a\u2022 Regional comparative frameworks \u2014 Key terms specific to Ghana (VASP Act 2025), Kenya (VASP Act\u000d\u000a2025), South Africa (CASP/FSCA), and Mauritius (VAITOS) \u2014 for founders building across African\u000d\u000amarkets.\u000d\u000aEntries with a shaded blue note contain jurisdiction-specific guidance, primarily for Nigeria. Cross-references are\u000d\u000aprovided at the end of each entry. All definitions reflect the regulatory position as of May 2026.\u000d\u000a\u2014 187 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aA\u000d\u000aAddress (Blockchain)\u000d\u000aA unique alphanumeric identifier on a blockchain network \u2014 the equivalent of a bank account number \u2014\u000d\u000aused to send and receive digital assets. Every blockchain address is derived from a cryptographic key pair\u000d\u000aand is publicly visible on the ledger. Owning an address means owning the private key that controls it.\u000d\u000aSee also: Private Key, Public Key, Wallet\u000d\u000aAfCFTA (African Continental Free Trade Area)\u000d\u000aA continent-wide free trade agreement signed by 54 of the 55 African Union member states, aiming to\u000d\u000acreate a single continental market for goods and services. Its digital trade protocols, still under negotiation,\u000d\u000aare expected to include provisions for cross-border digital payments, e-commerce, and data flows that will\u000d\u000adirectly shape how digital asset businesses operate across African borders.\u000d\u000aNigeria ratified AfCFTA in 2019. The AfCFTA Secretariat's digital trade work is expected to intersect with\u000d\u000aNigeria's CBN payment frameworks, SEC digital asset rules, and the PAPSS cross-border settlement system.\u000d\u000aSee also: PAPSS, Cross-Border Payment\u000d\u000aAirdrop\u000d\u000aThe distribution of free tokens or digital assets to a specified group of wallet addresses, typically used for\u000d\u000amarketing, community building, or rewarding early adopters. While often perceived as free money, airdrops\u000d\u000acarry compliance implications: recipients may owe tax on their fair market value at the time of receipt, and\u000d\u000aairdrop promoters may trigger securities regulations depending on how the tokens are classified.\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria's amended Digital Assets Rules (2024) explicitly define and regulate 'airdrop' activities, signalling\u000d\u000aregulatory sophistication around token distribution mechanics. Tax treatment of airdrops in Nigeria falls under\u000d\u000athe Finance Act 2023.\u000d\u000aSee also: Token, Digital Asset, Securities\u000d\u000aAIP (Approval-in-Principle)\u000d\u000aA preliminary authorisation issued by a regulator \u2014 in Nigeria, by the Securities and Exchange Commission\u000d\u000a\u2014 confirming that an applicant has met the initial criteria for a licence, but must still satisfy remaining\u000d\u000aconditions before a full licence is granted. An AIP is time-limited (typically up to 12 months under SEC\u000d\u000aNigeria's ARIP framework) and allows conditional operation during the regularisation phase.\u000d\u000a\u2014 188 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aUnder SEC Nigeria's VASP licensing process, an AIP is granted after a successful ARIP application. The VASP may\u000d\u000abegin controlled operations under AIP before transitioning to full registration.\u000d\u000aSee also: ARIP, VASP, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aAML (Anti-Money Laundering)\u000d\u000aA set of laws, regulations, and procedures designed to detect, prevent, and report the conversion of illegally\u000d\u000aobtained funds into apparently legitimate assets. AML frameworks require financial institutions and VASPs\u000d\u000ato implement KYC procedures, monitor transactions, file suspicious activity reports, and maintain records.\u000d\u000aThe global AML standard-setter is FATF.\u000d\u000aNigeria's primary AML legislation is the Money Laundering (Prevention and Prohibition) Act 2022 (MLPPA). The\u000d\u000aNFIU coordinates Nigeria's AML reporting framework. VASPs are explicitly classified as financial institutions\u000d\u000aunder the MLPPA 2022 and must comply with all AML obligations.\u000d\u000aSee also: CFT, CPF, KYC, FATF, NFIU, MLPPA\u000d\u000aAMM (Automated Market Maker)\u000d\u000aA type of decentralised exchange protocol that uses mathematical formulas \u2014 rather than traditional order\u000d\u000abooks \u2014 to determine asset prices and facilitate trades. Liquidity providers deposit pairs of tokens into\u000d\u000aliquidity pools, and the AMM algorithm automatically prices trades based on the ratio of assets in the pool.\u000d\u000aUniswap, Curve, and PancakeSwap are prominent AMMs.\u000d\u000aSee also: DEX, Liquidity Pool, DeFi\u000d\u000aARIP (Accelerated Regulatory Incubation Programme)\u000d\u000aA pre-licensing regulatory programme introduced by the Securities and Exchange Commission of Nigeria to\u000d\u000aonboard virtual asset service providers and digital investment service providers into the Nigerian capital\u000d\u000amarket on a structured, provisional basis. ARIP allows applicants to operate under regulatory oversight\u000d\u000awhile completing the requirements for full SEC registration. It replaces and accelerates the earlier\u000d\u000aRegulatory Incubation (RI) programme.\u000d\u000aARIP is the mandatory first step for any VASP seeking to operate legally in Nigeria. Applicants must submit an\u000d\u000ainitial assessment form and draft white paper. Successful applicants receive an AIP, valid for up to 12 months,\u000d\u000abefore applying for full SEC registration. Registration fees currently stand at \u20a650 million.\u000d\u000aSee also: AIP, VASP, SEC Nigeria, DAX, DAOP, DAC\u000d\u000aAtomic Swap\u000d\u000aA smart-contract-based mechanism that allows the direct exchange of one cryptocurrency for another\u000d\u000aacross different blockchains without the need for a centralised intermediary. The 'atomic' quality means the\u000d\u000a\u2014 189 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000atransaction either completes in full for both parties or does not execute at all \u2014 eliminating counterparty\u000d\u000arisk. Relevant to cross-border digital asset settlement in Africa.\u000d\u000aSee also: Smart Contract, DEX, Cross-Border Payment\u000d\u000aB\u000d\u000aBOFIA (Banks and Other Financial Institutions Act)\u000d\u000aNigeria's primary legislation governing banks and other financial institutions, administered by the Central\u000d\u000aBank of Nigeria. BOFIA 2020 (which repealed the 1991 version) grants the CBN broad supervisory powers\u000d\u000aover deposit-taking institutions. While not specifically a digital asset law, BOFIA is relevant to fintechs that\u000d\u000ainterface with the banking system \u2014 particularly those holding client funds, operating payment\u000d\u000ainfrastructure, or seeking CBN licences.\u000d\u000aAny fintech or VASP that provides services involving the banking system \u2014 including naira settlement, escrow,\u000d\u000aor payment processing \u2014 will be subject to CBN oversight under BOFIA in addition to any SEC registration\u000d\u000arequirements.\u000d\u000aSee also: CBN, MLPPA, Payment Service\u000d\u000aBlockchain\u000d\u000aA distributed digital ledger that records transactions across a network of computers in a way that makes the\u000d\u000arecords tamper-evident and difficult to alter retrospectively. Each batch of transactions is grouped into a\u000d\u000a'block' and cryptographically linked to the previous block, forming a 'chain'. Blockchains can be public (open\u000d\u000ato anyone), private (permissioned), or consortium (controlled by a group of organisations). The underlying\u000d\u000atechnology behind Bitcoin, Ethereum, and most digital assets.\u000d\u000aNigeria's National Blockchain Policy (2023), developed under NITDA with the involvement of the Blockchain\u000d\u000aPolicy Steering Committee, establishes the government's strategic approach to blockchain adoption across\u000d\u000agovernment services, financial inclusion, and economic development. It does not create a licensing regime\u000d\u000a(that is handled by SEC), but establishes principles for responsible adoption.\u000d\u000aSee also: Distributed Ledger Technology, Smart Contract, Consensus Mechanism\u000d\u000aBridge (Blockchain)\u000d\u000aA protocol that enables the transfer of tokens or data between two different blockchain networks. Bridges\u000d\u000aare critical infrastructure for interoperability \u2014 they allow assets native to one chain (e.g. Ethereum) to be\u000d\u000aused on another (e.g. Binance Smart Chain). Bridges are also a significant security risk: they have been\u000d\u000aexploited for some of the largest thefts in crypto history.\u000d\u000a\u2014 190 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aSee also: Layer 1, Layer 2, Interoperability\u000d\u000aBSA (Bank Secrecy Act)\u000d\u000aThe United States' primary AML legislation, requiring financial institutions to assist government agencies in\u000d\u000adetecting and preventing money laundering. Mentioned in this book for comparative reference: the BSA is\u000d\u000athe model on which many AML frameworks worldwide \u2014 including Nigeria's MLPPA \u2014 have been partly\u000d\u000abased. VASPs serving US customers are subject to BSA obligations regardless of where they are\u000d\u000aincorporated.\u000d\u000aSee also: AML, MLPPA, FinCEN\u000d\u000aC\u000d\u000aCAC (Corporate Affairs Commission)\u000d\u000aNigeria's national agency responsible for the registration, regulation, and supervision of all companies and\u000d\u000abusiness names. Any VASP or fintech seeking SEC registration in Nigeria must first be incorporated at the\u000d\u000aCAC. The CAC is also relevant to DAO legal structure questions, as Nigerian law does not yet recognise DAOs\u000d\u000aas distinct legal entities.\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria requires all VASP applicants to be fully CAC-registered with a clear corporate structure, Nigerian\u000d\u000aoffice, and CEO/MD resident in Nigeria before submitting an ARIP application.\u000d\u000aSee also: SEC Nigeria, ARIP, VASP\u000d\u000aCapital Gains Tax (Digital Assets)\u000d\u000aTax levied on profits made from the disposal of digital assets. Nigeria's Finance Act 2023 amended the\u000d\u000aCapital Gains Tax Act to classify digital assets as chargeable assets, meaning any profit from selling,\u000d\u000aexchanging, or otherwise disposing of digital assets is subject to capital gains tax. This was a significant\u000d\u000aclarification of the tax treatment of crypto gains in Nigeria.\u000d\u000aNigerian founders should be aware that profits from token sales, NFT disposals, and crypto-to-fiat conversions\u000d\u000aare potentially subject to CGT under the Finance Act 2023. The Nigeria Tax Administration Act (NTAA) 2025\u000d\u000aintroduced enhanced reporting and penalty provisions for non-compliant VASPs.\u000d\u000aSee also: VASP, ISA 2025, NTAA\u000d\u000aCASP (Crypto Asset Service Provider)\u000d\u000a\u2014 191 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe term used in South Africa (and in the EU's MiCA regulation) to describe businesses providing services\u000d\u000arelated to crypto assets \u2014 equivalent to the VASP designation used in Nigeria, Kenya, Ghana, and by FATF.\u000d\u000aSouth Africa's Financial Sector Conduct Authority (FSCA) began licensing CASPs from June 2023, making\u000d\u000aSouth Africa one of the first African countries to operationalise a formal VASP/CASP licensing regime.\u000d\u000aSouth Africa (selective coverage): The FSCA is the primary regulator for CASPs in South Africa. Firms providing\u000d\u000acrypto asset services were required to apply for CASP authorisation by November 2023. The Financial\u000d\u000aIntelligence Centre (FIC) oversees AML/CFT obligations for CASPs under the Financial Intelligence Centre Act.\u000d\u000aSee also: VASP, FSCA, FIC (South Africa), MiCA\u000d\u000aCBN (Central Bank of Nigeria)\u000d\u000aNigeria's apex monetary authority, responsible for monetary policy, financial system stability, and the\u000d\u000aregulation of banks and payment systems under BOFIA 2020. The CBN's relationship with digital assets has\u000d\u000aevolved significantly: its 2021 circular restricted banks from servicing crypto transactions, but subsequent\u000d\u000apolicy shifts (including the 2023 relaxation for licensed entities) now allow banks to work with SEC-licensed\u000d\u000aVASPs. The CBN regulates the eNaira (Nigeria's CBDC) and oversees payment service providers.\u000d\u000aFounders should understand that the CBN and SEC Nigeria have overlapping but distinct jurisdiction over digital\u000d\u000aassets: SEC regulates digital assets as securities (investment, trading, custody), while the CBN regulates the\u000d\u000apayment rails, monetary aspects, and stablecoin implications. Any product that touches both dimensions \u2014\u000d\u000asuch as a stablecoin payment product \u2014 may require engagement with both regulators.\u000d\u000aSee also: SEC Nigeria, eNaira, BOFIA, Stablecoin, VASP\u000d\u000aCBDC (Central Bank Digital Currency)\u000d\u000aA digital form of a country's sovereign currency, issued and backed directly by the central bank. Unlike\u000d\u000acryptocurrencies, CBDCs are centralised, government-controlled, and carry the same legal tender status as\u000d\u000aphysical currency. CBDCs can be retail (accessible to the general public) or wholesale (restricted to financial\u000d\u000ainstitutions for interbank settlements).\u000d\u000aNigeria launched the eNaira \u2014 Africa's first CBDC \u2014 in October 2021, issued by the CBN. The eNaira operates\u000d\u000aon a permissioned blockchain and is designed to expand financial inclusion and facilitate remittances. Adoption\u000d\u000ahas been slower than anticipated, and the CBN has issued several revised guidelines to expand use cases.\u000d\u000aSee also: eNaira, Stablecoin, Digital Currency\u000d\u000aCDD (Customer Due Diligence)\u000d\u000aThe process by which regulated entities \u2014 including VASPs \u2014 verify the identity of their customers,\u000d\u000aunderstand the nature and purpose of the customer relationship, and assess the risk of financial crime. CDD\u000d\u000ais a foundational AML requirement. It encompasses identity verification, source of funds checks, and\u000d\u000aongoing monitoring. Enhanced Due Diligence (EDD) applies to higher-risk customers such as PEPs.\u000d\u000a\u2014 192 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aUnder Nigeria's MLPPA 2022, all financial institutions, including VASPs, must conduct CDD on their customers\u000d\u000abefore and during the business relationship. Failure to conduct adequate CDD is one of the most common AML\u000d\u000acompliance deficiencies identified in VASP supervisory reviews.\u000d\u000aSee also: KYC, EDD, AML, PEP, MLPPA\u000d\u000aCEX (Centralised Exchange)\u000d\u000aA digital asset trading platform operated by a central company that acts as an intermediary between buyers\u000d\u000aand sellers \u2014 holding custody of user funds, maintaining an order book, and facilitating trades. CEXs are\u000d\u000asubject to licensing and regulatory oversight in most jurisdictions. Examples include Binance, Coinbase, and\u000d\u000aNigerian platforms such as Quidax and Busha (the first two to receive SEC ARIP approval).\u000d\u000aNigerian CEXs operating as Digital Asset Exchanges (DAX) must be registered with SEC Nigeria. Local CEXs\u000d\u000a(Quidax, Busha) received their first ARIP-stage approvals in late 2024. Foreign CEXs targeting Nigerian users are\u000d\u000anow subject to SEC Nigeria's foreign VASP rules under the amended 2024 Digital Asset Rules.\u000d\u000aSee also: DAX, DEX, VASP, ARIP\u000d\u000aCFT (Countering the Financing of Terrorism)\u000d\u000aLegal and regulatory measures designed to prevent terrorists and terrorist organisations from raising,\u000d\u000amoving, and using funds to support violent activities. CFT obligations for financial institutions and VASPs\u000d\u000ainclude customer screening against terrorism designation lists, suspicious transaction monitoring, and\u000d\u000areporting to financial intelligence units. Paired with AML as 'AML/CFT' in most regulatory frameworks.\u000d\u000aNigeria's CFT regime is governed by the Terrorism (Prevention and Prohibition) Act 2022 and the Money\u000d\u000aLaundering (Prevention and Prohibition) Act 2022. VASPs must comply with both statutes. The NFIU\u000d\u000acoordinates intelligence relating to terrorism financing.\u000d\u000aSee also: AML, CPF, NFIU, MLPPA, PEP\u000d\u000aChain Analysis / Blockchain Analytics\u000d\u000aThe practice of analysing blockchain transaction data to trace the movement of digital assets, identify\u000d\u000apatterns, attribute addresses to known entities, and detect illicit activity. Blockchain analytics tools \u2014 such\u000d\u000aas those provided by Chainalysis, Elliptic, and TRM Labs \u2014 are used by regulators, law enforcement, and\u000d\u000acompliance teams to monitor on-chain activity.\u000d\u000aThe CBN and NFIU are developing supervisory capabilities in blockchain analytics as part of the AML/CFT\u000d\u000aSupervision Pilot for VASPs. Founders should assume that their platforms will eventually be subject to on-chain\u000d\u000asupervisory monitoring by Nigerian authorities.\u000d\u000aSee also: AML, On-Chain, NFIU, Suspicious Transaction Report\u000d\u000a\u2014 193 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aCold Wallet / Cold Storage\u000d\u000aA method of storing digital assets in which the private keys are kept entirely offline \u2014 on hardware devices,\u000d\u000apaper, or air-gapped computers \u2014 and therefore inaccessible to internet-based attacks. Cold storage is the\u000d\u000agold standard for securing large holdings of digital assets and is required by SEC Nigeria's Digital Asset\u000d\u000aCustodian (DAC) rules for a significant portion of client assets.\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria's rules on Digital Asset Custodians require VASPs providing custody services to maintain specified\u000d\u000aportions of client assets in cold storage as a security and solvency safeguard.\u000d\u000aSee also: Hot Wallet, DAC, Private Key\u000d\u000aCompliance Programme\u000d\u000aThe suite of policies, procedures, controls, and personnel that a regulated entity maintains to ensure it\u000d\u000ameets its legal and regulatory obligations. A robust compliance programme for a VASP includes AML/CFT\u000d\u000apolicies, KYC/KYB procedures, transaction monitoring, sanctions screening, staff training, independent\u000d\u000aaudit, and a designated compliance officer.\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria expects all registered VASPs to have a documented compliance programme in place at the time of\u000d\u000afull registration. The quality of the compliance programme is assessed during the ARIP and registration review\u000d\u000aprocess.\u000d\u000aSee also: AML, KYC, Sanctions Screening, VASP\u000d\u000aConsensus Mechanism\u000d\u000aThe process by which nodes in a blockchain network agree on the validity of transactions and the state of\u000d\u000athe ledger. The two dominant mechanisms are Proof of Work (PoW), which requires computational effort to\u000d\u000avalidate transactions (used by Bitcoin), and Proof of Stake (PoS), which requires validators to lock up ('stake')\u000d\u000atokens as collateral (used by Ethereum post-Merge). The choice of consensus mechanism affects energy\u000d\u000ause, speed, security, and decentralisation.\u000d\u000aSee also: Blockchain, Node, Staking\u000d\u000aCPF (Counter-Proliferation Financing)\u000d\u000aMeasures to prevent the financing of the development, acquisition, or transfer of weapons of mass\u000d\u000adestruction. CPF was added to the AML/CFT framework as a distinct obligation following FATF's 2012\u000d\u000aRecommendations revision. Financial institutions and VASPs are required to screen customers and\u000d\u000atransactions against UN Security Council proliferation-related sanctions lists.\u000d\u000aNigeria's AML/CFT/CPF Supervision Pilot for VASPs, launched by the CBN, explicitly includes CPF as a\u000d\u000asupervisory dimension \u2014 reflecting the full FATF framework. All registered VASPs must have proliferation\u000d\u000afinancing risk assessments and screening procedures in place.\u000d\u000a\u2014 194 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aSee also: AML, CFT, FATF, Sanctions Screening, NFIU\u000d\u000aCrypto-Dollarisation\u000d\u000aThe phenomenon whereby residents of a country with a volatile domestic currency substitute that currency\u000d\u000awith US dollar-denominated stablecoins (such as USDT or USDC) for savings, commerce, or cross-border\u000d\u000apayments \u2014 without formally adopting the US dollar as legal tender. Crypto-dollarisation poses a significant\u000d\u000amonetary sovereignty risk because it effectively reduces the demand for the domestic currency and\u000d\u000aconstrains the central bank's ability to conduct monetary policy.\u000d\u000aNigeria has experienced significant crypto-dollarisation driven by naira devaluation, FX scarcity, and high\u000d\u000ainflation. This is a central concern for the CBN's approach to stablecoin regulation \u2014 the Bank must balance the\u000d\u000alegitimate demand for stable-value instruments against the risk that widespread USDT adoption undermines\u000d\u000amonetary sovereignty.\u000d\u000aSee also: Stablecoin, Monetary Sovereignty, CBN, CBDC\u000d\u000aCustodial Wallet\u000d\u000aA digital asset wallet where a third party (the custodian) holds and manages the private keys on behalf of\u000d\u000athe user. When you hold digital assets on a centralised exchange, you have a custodial wallet \u2014 you trust\u000d\u000athe exchange to safeguard your assets. The risk is counterparty risk: if the custodian is hacked, insolvent, or\u000d\u000afraudulent, the user's assets may be lost.\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria's Digital Asset Custodian (DAC) registration category specifically governs entities that provide\u000d\u000acustodial wallet services. DACs must meet minimum capital requirements, maintain cold storage ratios, and\u000d\u000acarry fidelity bonds covering 25% of minimum capital.\u000d\u000aSee also: DAC, Non-Custodial Wallet, Private Key, Cold Wallet\u000d\u000aD\u000d\u000aDAC (Digital Asset Custodian)\u000d\u000aA regulatory classification under SEC Nigeria's Digital Asset Rules for entities that hold and safeguard digital\u000d\u000aassets on behalf of clients. DACs must be separately registered with SEC Nigeria, meet capital requirements,\u000d\u000amaintain prescribed cold storage ratios, and carry fidelity bonds. Providing custodial services in Nigeria\u000d\u000awithout DAC registration is a regulatory offence.\u000d\u000a\u2014 195 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe minimum capital requirement for a DAC under SEC Nigeria's 2024 amended rules is significant (specific\u000d\u000afigures are published in the Rules). DACs must ensure 60% of board members are of Nigerian origin and that\u000d\u000athe CEO is resident in Nigeria.\u000d\u000aSee also: Custodial Wallet, Cold Wallet, VASP, ARIP\u000d\u000aDAO (Decentralised Autonomous Organisation)\u000d\u000aAn organisation governed by smart contracts and encoded rules on a blockchain, rather than by traditional\u000d\u000alegal structures or human management hierarchies. DAO members typically vote on proposals using\u000d\u000agovernance tokens, with outcomes automatically executed by smart contracts. DAOs present significant\u000d\u000alegal challenges: most jurisdictions \u2014 including Nigeria \u2014 do not yet recognise DAOs as legal entities,\u000d\u000acreating liability and contract enforcement gaps.\u000d\u000aDAOs operating in Nigeria or targeting Nigerian participants have no specific legal recognition under current\u000d\u000alaw. The Companies and Allied Matters Act (CAMA) and CAC registration requirements technically apply to any\u000d\u000abusiness entity operating in Nigeria. Founders structuring DAOs for African markets should obtain legal advice\u000d\u000aon liability, contractual capacity, and regulatory status.\u000d\u000aSee also: Smart Contract, Governance Token, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aDAOP (Digital Asset Offering Platform)\u000d\u000aA regulatory classification under SEC Nigeria's Digital Asset Rules for platforms that facilitate the public\u000d\u000aoffering of digital assets \u2014 roughly equivalent to an investment platform or primary issuance venue. DAOPs\u000d\u000amust be registered with SEC Nigeria and comply with investor protection rules applicable to public offerings.\u000d\u000aAny platform facilitating the sale of tokens to Nigerian investors \u2014 whether structured as an ICO, IEO, or token\u000d\u000asale \u2014 may be classified as a DAOP and require registration with SEC Nigeria.\u000d\u000aSee also: DAX, DAC, VASP, ICO, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aDAX (Digital Asset Exchange)\u000d\u000aA regulatory classification under SEC Nigeria's Digital Asset Rules for platforms that facilitate the secondary\u000d\u000amarket trading of digital assets \u2014 the equivalent of a securities exchange but for digital assets. DAXs must\u000d\u000abe registered with SEC Nigeria and comply with market integrity, custody, and AML rules. Quidax and Busha\u000d\u000aare the first Nigerian exchanges to receive ARIP-stage DAX approval.\u000d\u000aDAX registration requires significant minimum capital, Nigerian incorporation, local management, fidelity\u000d\u000abonds, and compliance infrastructure. Foreign exchanges targeting Nigerian users without a local DAX licence\u000d\u000arisk regulatory action under the amended 2024 SEC rules.\u000d\u000aSee also: CEX, DAOP, DAC, ARIP\u000d\u000a\u2014 196 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000adApp (Decentralised Application)\u000d\u000aA software application that runs on a blockchain or peer-to-peer network rather than on a central server.\u000d\u000adApps use smart contracts for their backend logic and are typically open-source, auditable, and\u000d\u000acensorship-resistant. Examples include decentralised exchanges, lending protocols, and NFT marketplaces.\u000d\u000aThe regulatory treatment of dApps is complex: because they have no central operator, applying traditional\u000d\u000alicensing requirements is difficult.\u000d\u000aSee also: Smart Contract, DeFi, DAO\u000d\u000aDeFi (Decentralised Finance)\u000d\u000aA broad term for financial services \u2014 including lending, borrowing, trading, derivatives, and asset\u000d\u000amanagement \u2014 delivered through smart contracts on blockchains, without centralised intermediaries such\u000d\u000aas banks or brokers. DeFi protocols are typically non-custodial, permissionless, and globally accessible. They\u000d\u000apose significant regulatory challenges: there is often no identifiable legal entity to hold responsible, KYC is\u000d\u000agenerally absent, and users interact directly with code.\u000d\u000aFATF has issued guidance indicating that DeFi protocols that retain some degree of control or benefit from\u000d\u000aoperations may still constitute VASPs and be subject to AML/CFT obligations. Nigerian regulators have not yet\u000d\u000aissued specific DeFi guidance, but founders building DeFi products targeting Nigerian users should prepare for\u000d\u000aregulatory scrutiny as the SEC's sophistication in this area develops.\u000d\u000aSee also: Smart Contract, AMM, Liquidity Pool, VASP, FATF\u000d\u000aDe-Risking\u000d\u000aThe practice by which financial institutions \u2014 particularly correspondent banks \u2014 terminate or restrict\u000d\u000abusiness relationships with entire categories of customers or jurisdictions to avoid perceived regulatory or\u000d\u000areputational risk, rather than managing those risks on a case-by-case basis. De-risking has significantly\u000d\u000aimpacted African countries' access to international correspondent banking, contributing to the appeal of\u000d\u000ablockchain-based cross-border payment alternatives.\u000d\u000aNigeria and other West African jurisdictions have experienced de-risking by international banks, which has\u000d\u000areduced correspondent banking access and driven demand for P2P, stablecoin, and blockchain-based\u000d\u000aremittance solutions. The AfCFTA digital trade framework and PAPSS are partly intended to address the\u000d\u000astructural gaps created by de-risking.\u000d\u000aSee also: Correspondent Banking, PAPSS, Cross-Border Payment\u000d\u000aDEX (Decentralised Exchange)\u000d\u000aA digital asset trading platform that operates through smart contracts on a blockchain, without a central\u000d\u000acompany managing user funds or the order book. Users trade directly from their own wallets, maintaining\u000d\u000a\u2014 197 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000acustody of their assets throughout. DEXs are generally more resistant to censorship and hacking than CEXs,\u000d\u000abut offer less regulatory protection and can be harder to use.\u000d\u000aThe regulatory treatment of DEXs in Nigeria is still evolving. Because DEXs typically have no\u000d\u000aNigerian-incorporated entity, they fall into a grey area under SEC Nigeria's current framework. Founders\u000d\u000abuilding DEX products should anticipate that the amended Digital Asset Rules will eventually capture\u000d\u000aDEX-adjacent services.\u000d\u000aSee also: AMM, CEX, DeFi, VASP\u000d\u000aDigital Asset\u000d\u000aA broad term encompassing any asset that exists in digital form and has value, including cryptocurrencies,\u000d\u000atokens, NFTs, stablecoins, and CBDCs. Nigeria's ISA 2025 defines digital assets as a subset of 'virtual assets'\u000d\u000aand classifies them as securities under SEC Nigeria's jurisdiction. The terms 'digital asset', 'virtual asset', and\u000d\u000a'crypto asset' are often used interchangeably, though different jurisdictions may draw technical distinctions.\u000d\u000aUnder Nigeria's ISA 2025 (Section 357), digital assets are formally recognised as securities, ending years of\u000d\u000aregulatory ambiguity. This classification subjects all digital asset service providers to SEC Nigeria's oversight and\u000d\u000ainvestor protection framework.\u000d\u000aSee also: Virtual Asset, Crypto Asset, ISA 2025, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aDigital Asset Custodian\u000d\u000aSee DAC.\u000d\u000aSee also: DAC\u000d\u000aDigital Identity\u000d\u000aA set of attributes that uniquely identifies an individual or entity in a digital environment. Blockchain-based\u000d\u000adigital identity systems allow individuals to control their own identity data without relying on centralised\u000d\u000aauthorities \u2014 relevant to financial inclusion in Africa, where large portions of the population lack\u000d\u000agovernment-issued ID. Self-Sovereign Identity (SSI) is a specific blockchain-based approach to digital\u000d\u000aidentity.\u000d\u000aNigeria's National Identity Management Commission (NIMC) manages the national identity database and issues\u000d\u000athe National Identification Number (NIN). KYC requirements for Nigerian VASPs typically require NIN\u000d\u000averification as a foundational identity check. The CBN's regulatory framework for digital finance incorporates\u000d\u000aBVN (Bank Verification Number) and NIN as core identity anchors.\u000d\u000aSee also: KYC, CDD, Self-Sovereign Identity, NIN, BVN\u000d\u000aDistributed Ledger Technology (DLT)\u000d\u000a\u2014 198 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aA broader category of technology that encompasses blockchains and other systems in which data is\u000d\u000arecorded, shared, and synchronised across multiple locations or nodes without a central administrator. All\u000d\u000ablockchains are distributed ledgers, but not all distributed ledgers are blockchains. DLT is the umbrella term\u000d\u000aoften used in regulatory documents to avoid being prescriptive about the specific technology stack.\u000d\u000aNigeria's ISA 2025 uses 'distributed ledger technology' as a defined term in its description of digital asset\u000d\u000asystems, following FATF's approach of being technology-neutral in regulatory definitions.\u000d\u000aSee also: Blockchain, Node, Smart Contract\u000d\u000aDollarisation\u000d\u000aSee Crypto-Dollarisation.\u000d\u000aSee also: Crypto-Dollarisation, Stablecoin, Monetary Sovereignty\u000d\u000aE\u000d\u000aEDD (Enhanced Due Diligence)\u000d\u000aA higher level of customer due diligence applied to customers or transactions that present elevated money\u000d\u000alaundering or terrorist financing risks. EDD typically involves more detailed identity verification, source of\u000d\u000awealth and funds investigations, senior management approval, and enhanced ongoing monitoring. EDD is\u000d\u000amandatory for Politically Exposed Persons (PEPs), high-risk jurisdictions, and complex or unusual\u000d\u000atransactions.\u000d\u000aUnder Nigeria's MLPPA 2022 and the NFIU's AML/CFT compliance framework for VASPs, EDD must be applied\u000d\u000ato all PEPs and their associates, as well as to transactions from or to high-risk jurisdictions on the FATF grey or\u000d\u000ablack lists.\u000d\u000aSee also: CDD, KYC, PEP, AML, FATF\u000d\u000aEFCC (Economic and Financial Crimes Commission)\u000d\u000aNigeria's primary law enforcement agency responsible for investigating and prosecuting financial crimes\u000d\u000aincluding money laundering, advance fee fraud (419), and corruption. The EFCC operates under the\u000d\u000aEconomic and Financial Crimes Commission Act and works closely with the NFIU on financial intelligence\u000d\u000amatters. Digital asset transactions have increasingly been a focus of EFCC investigations.\u000d\u000aVASPs and fintech operators in Nigeria should be aware of the EFCC's broad investigative powers. The EFCC can\u000d\u000afreeze accounts, seize assets, and prosecute individuals at any stage of a business \u2014 not just at the company\u000d\u000alevel. Compliance with AML obligations is the strongest protection against EFCC scrutiny.\u000d\u000a\u2014 199 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aSee also: NFIU, AML, MLPPA, ICPC\u000d\u000aEgmont Group\u000d\u000aAn international network of financial intelligence units (FIUs) that facilitates the secure sharing of financial\u000d\u000aintelligence across jurisdictions. Membership in the Egmont Group enables Nigeria's NFIU to receive and\u000d\u000ashare financial intelligence with FIUs in other countries \u2014 critical for investigating cross-border financial\u000d\u000acrime involving digital assets.\u000d\u000aNigeria's NFIU is a member of the Egmont Group, enabling cross-border financial intelligence cooperation\u000d\u000arelevant to digital asset crime investigations.\u000d\u000aSee also: NFIU, AML, FIU\u000d\u000aeNaira\u000d\u000aNigeria's Central Bank Digital Currency (CBDC), launched by the CBN in October 2021 \u2014 making Nigeria the\u000d\u000afirst African country to issue a CBDC. The eNaira is a digital representation of the naira, backed 1:1 by the\u000d\u000aCBN, and operates on a permissioned blockchain infrastructure. It is intended to complement cash, expand\u000d\u000afinancial inclusion, and facilitate cheaper remittances. Adoption has been limited and the CBN has revised\u000d\u000aits eNaira guidelines multiple times.\u000d\u000aThe eNaira is distinct from privately issued stablecoins: it is sovereign money, issued by the state, with the same\u000d\u000alegal tender status as physical naira. Founders building payment products should understand how the eNaira\u000d\u000ainfrastructure can interact with (or compete with) their products.\u000d\u000aSee also: CBDC, Stablecoin, CBN, Digital Currency\u000d\u000aERC-20\u000d\u000aThe most widely used technical standard for fungible tokens on the Ethereum blockchain. ERC-20 defines a\u000d\u000acommon set of rules that all Ethereum-based tokens must follow \u2014 enabling interoperability between\u000d\u000awallets, exchanges, and DeFi protocols. Most stablecoins (USDT, USDC), governance tokens, and utility\u000d\u000atokens issued on Ethereum are ERC-20 tokens.\u000d\u000aSee also: ERC-721, Token, Ethereum, Smart Contract\u000d\u000aERC-721\u000d\u000aThe technical standard for non-fungible tokens (NFTs) on the Ethereum blockchain. Unlike ERC-20 tokens\u000d\u000a(which are interchangeable), each ERC-721 token is unique and cannot be exchanged on a like-for-like basis.\u000d\u000aERC-721 is the standard underlying most digital art, collectibles, and gaming assets in the NFT market.\u000d\u000aSee also: NFT, ERC-20, Token\u000d\u000a\u2014 200 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aEVM (Ethereum Virtual Machine)\u000d\u000aThe computation engine embedded in the Ethereum blockchain that executes smart contracts. The EVM is a\u000d\u000asandboxed environment in which smart contract code runs deterministically \u2014 meaning it produces the\u000d\u000asame output on every node in the network. Many other blockchains have built EVM-compatible\u000d\u000aenvironments, meaning Ethereum smart contracts can be deployed on chains such as Polygon, BNB Chain,\u000d\u000aand Avalanche.\u000d\u000aSee also: Smart Contract, Ethereum, Solidity\u000d\u000aF\u000d\u000aFATF (Financial Action Task Force)\u000d\u000aAn intergovernmental body established in 1989 that sets international standards for combating money\u000d\u000alaundering, terrorist financing, and proliferation financing. FATF's 40 Recommendations are the global\u000d\u000abenchmark for AML/CFT frameworks. Its Recommendation 15 (updated 2019) extends AML/CFT obligations\u000d\u000ato virtual assets and VASPs. Countries that fail to implement FATF standards may be placed on the 'grey list'\u000d\u000a(enhanced monitoring) or 'black list' (call for action), with serious consequences for banking access and\u000d\u000ainvestment flows.\u000d\u000aNigeria is a member of GIABA (the FATF-style regional body for West Africa). Nigeria was placed on the FATF\u000d\u000agrey list in 2023 and has been working to exit it through legislative reforms and supervisory actions, including\u000d\u000athe VASP supervision pilot and passage of the MLPPA 2022 and BOFIA 2020. Nigeria is identified by FATF as a\u000d\u000ajurisdiction with materially important VASP activity.\u000d\u000aSee also: AML, CFT, Recommendation 15, Travel Rule, GIABA, NFIU\u000d\u000aFCCPA (Financial Crimes Commission and Proceeds Act)\u000d\u000aNigerian legislation that consolidates provisions relating to the identification, tracing, freezing, and recovery\u000d\u000aof proceeds of crime. Relevant to digital asset businesses because virtual assets are expressly included as\u000d\u000aassets that can be seized and forfeited under proceeds of crime provisions.\u000d\u000aSee also: EFCC, AML, MLPPA\u000d\u000aFidelity Bond\u000d\u000aAn insurance instrument that protects a company against losses caused by employee dishonesty, fraud, or\u000d\u000atheft. SEC Nigeria requires all registered VASPs to maintain a fidelity bond covering at least 25% of their\u000d\u000aminimum capital requirement \u2014 a consumer and investor protection measure.\u000d\u000a\u2014 201 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe fidelity bond requirement applies to all VASP registration categories under the SEC Digital Asset Rules (DAX,\u000d\u000aDAOP, DAC, DAI). It must be current at all times and is reviewed as part of ongoing compliance.\u000d\u000aSee also: DAX, DAC, VASP, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aFIC (Financial Intelligence Centre)\u000d\u000aThe financial intelligence unit of South Africa (and separately, of Ghana). South Africa's FIC administers the\u000d\u000aFinancial Intelligence Centre Act (FICA) and oversees AML/CFT compliance for accountable institutions\u000d\u000aincluding, since 2023, registered CASPs. Ghana's Financial Intelligence Centre performs a similar function\u000d\u000aunder Ghanaian AML law.\u000d\u000aSouth Africa (selective coverage): The FIC is responsible for receiving and analysing suspicious transaction\u000d\u000areports from South African CASPs and coordinating financial intelligence with law enforcement. Ghana: The FIC\u000d\u000aadministers AML obligations for VASPs under the Anti-Money Laundering Act and works with the Bank of\u000d\u000aGhana on VASP oversight.\u000d\u000aSee also: CASP, AML, FSCA, STR\u000d\u000aFinfluencer\u000d\u000aA social media influencer who promotes financial products or services \u2014 including digital assets \u2014 to their\u000d\u000aonline audience, typically in exchange for payment. Finfluencers have been a significant channel for\u000d\u000apromoting token launches, exchanges, and investment schemes in Nigeria, sometimes without adequate\u000d\u000adisclosure of commercial relationships or risks.\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria's amended 2024 Digital Asset Rules explicitly define and regulate 'Finfluencers', requiring disclosure\u000d\u000aof commercial relationships and bringing promotional activities for digital asset products within SEC's oversight.\u000d\u000aFounders using influencer marketing for token or product launches should ensure their influencer\u000d\u000aarrangements comply with these rules.\u000d\u000aSee also: ICO, Token, SEC Nigeria, Digital Asset\u000d\u000aFIU (Financial Intelligence Unit)\u000d\u000aA national agency responsible for receiving, analysing, and disseminating financial intelligence \u2014 including\u000d\u000asuspicious transaction reports \u2014 to law enforcement and regulatory agencies. Every FATF member state\u000d\u000amust have an FIU. Nigeria's FIU is the NFIU.\u000d\u000aNigeria: The NFIU is the designated FIU under the Money Laundering Act. VASPs must file Suspicious\u000d\u000aTransaction Reports (STRs) and Currency Transaction Reports (CTRs) with the NFIU.\u000d\u000aSee also: NFIU, AML, STR, Egmont Group\u000d\u000aFSB (Financial Stability Board)\u000d\u000a\u2014 202 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aAn international body that monitors and makes recommendations about the global financial system. The\u000d\u000aFSB has published crypto-asset regulatory frameworks and high-level recommendations for stablecoin\u000d\u000aoversight that inform how central banks and financial regulators worldwide \u2014 including the CBN \u2014\u000d\u000aapproach digital asset policy.\u000d\u000aSee also: BIS, IMF, Stablecoin, CBDC\u000d\u000aFSCA (Financial Sector Conduct Authority)\u000d\u000aSouth Africa's market conduct regulator, responsible for licensing and supervising financial services\u000d\u000aproviders. The FSCA began licensing crypto asset service providers (CASPs) in 2023, making South Africa one\u000d\u000aof the first African countries to have an operational CASP licensing regime in practice.\u000d\u000aSouth Africa (selective coverage): CASPs must be authorised by the FSCA under the Financial Advisory and\u000d\u000aIntermediary Services (FAIS) Act. The FSCA and FIC jointly oversee CASPs \u2014 FSCA for market conduct, FIC for\u000d\u000aAML/CFT.\u000d\u000aSee also: CASP, FIC, South Africa\u000d\u000aFSC Mauritius (Financial Services Commission (Mauritius))\u000d\u000aThe primary financial regulator in Mauritius, responsible for licensing and supervising non-bank financial\u000d\u000ainstitutions including virtual asset service providers under the VAITOS Act 2021. Mauritius was one of the\u000d\u000afirst jurisdictions globally \u2014 and the first in Africa \u2014 to enact a comprehensive framework for digital assets\u000d\u000aand initial token offerings.\u000d\u000aMauritius (selective coverage): The FSC issues VASP licences across categories including broker-dealer,\u000d\u000acustodian, wallet provider, and marketplace. Mauritius issued additional guidance on stablecoins in 2025 and is\u000d\u000adeveloping a stablecoin regulatory framework. Its regime is considered one of the more mature and\u000d\u000ainternationally compliant on the continent.\u000d\u000aSee also: VAITOS, VASP, Mauritius\u000d\u000aFungible Token\u000d\u000aA token that is interchangeable with other tokens of the same type and denomination \u2014 like cash or gold.\u000d\u000aOne unit of a fungible token is identical to any other unit of the same token. Bitcoin and USDT are fungible\u000d\u000atokens: any one bitcoin is worth and interchangeable with any other bitcoin. Contrast with NFTs, which are\u000d\u000anon-fungible (each is unique).\u000d\u000aSee also: NFT, ERC-20, Token\u000d\u000a\u2014 203 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aG\u000d\u000aGas Fee\u000d\u000aThe fee paid to blockchain validators (or miners) to process and include a transaction in a block. On the\u000d\u000aEthereum network, gas fees are denominated in Gwei (a small denomination of ETH) and fluctuate based on\u000d\u000anetwork congestion. High gas fees during periods of peak demand can make small transactions\u000d\u000aeconomically unviable \u2014 a significant barrier to blockchain financial inclusion use cases in Africa.\u000d\u000aSee also: Ethereum, Layer 2, Transaction\u000d\u000aGIABA (Inter-Governmental Action Group Against Money Laundering in West Africa)\u000d\u000aThe FATF-style regional body (FSRB) for West Africa, with Nigeria as a founding member. GIABA conducts\u000d\u000amutual evaluations of member states' AML/CFT frameworks and provides technical assistance. Nigeria's\u000d\u000amutual evaluation results \u2014 and its grey list status \u2014 are directly influenced by GIABA assessments.\u000d\u000aGIABA's mutual evaluation of Nigeria identified deficiencies in Nigeria's AML/CFT framework that contributed\u000d\u000ato the 2023 grey listing. The reforms Nigeria has undertaken \u2014 including the MLPPA 2022, the VASP\u000d\u000asupervision pilot, and the ARIP framework \u2014 are partly aimed at satisfying GIABA and FATF assessment criteria.\u000d\u000aSee also: FATF, NFIU, AML, CFT\u000d\u000aGovernance Token\u000d\u000aA type of token that grants its holder voting rights on decisions affecting a blockchain protocol or DAO \u2014\u000d\u000asuch as fee structures, protocol upgrades, treasury allocations, or rule changes. Governance tokens may\u000d\u000ahave financial value (traded on exchanges) but are primarily instruments of decentralised decision-making.\u000d\u000aTheir classification as securities is an active regulatory question.\u000d\u000aGovernance tokens that carry economic benefits (revenue sharing, fee distributions) are likely to be classified\u000d\u000aas securities under Nigeria's ISA 2025 and may require SEC Nigeria registration. Founders issuing governance\u000d\u000atokens should obtain legal opinions on their classification before launch.\u000d\u000aSee also: DAO, Token, Security Token, ISA 2025\u000d\u000aGrey Listing (FATF)\u000d\u000aFormal placement of a jurisdiction on the FATF 'Jurisdictions Under Increased Monitoring' list (commonly\u000d\u000acalled the grey list), indicating that the jurisdiction has committed to resolve identified deficiencies in its\u000d\u000aAML/CFT framework within agreed timeframes. Grey listing can trigger heightened due diligence\u000d\u000arequirements from international banks and investors, increasing the cost of correspondent banking and\u000d\u000aforeign investment.\u000d\u000a\u2014 204 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aNigeria was placed on the FATF grey list in 2023. This contributed to increased scrutiny of Nigerian transactions\u000d\u000aby international banks and accelerated Nigeria's legislative reforms including the MLPPA 2022 and the VASP\u000d\u000asupervision framework.\u000d\u000aSee also: FATF, GIABA, De-Risking, AML\u000d\u000aH\u000d\u000aHard Fork\u000d\u000aA fundamental, backwards-incompatible change to a blockchain's protocol rules that causes a permanent\u000d\u000adivergence \u2014 effectively splitting the original blockchain into two separate chains. Hard forks can occur as\u000d\u000aplanned upgrades (e.g. Ethereum's transition to Proof of Stake) or as contentious community splits. Tokens\u000d\u000acreated by hard forks raise novel tax and legal questions.\u000d\u000aSee also: Soft Fork, Blockchain, Consensus Mechanism\u000d\u000aHash / Hash Function\u000d\u000aA mathematical function that converts any input of arbitrary size into a fixed-size output (the 'hash' or\u000d\u000a'digest'). Hash functions are fundamental to blockchain security: each block contains the hash of the\u000d\u000aprevious block (creating the 'chain'), and transactions are identified by their hash. The same input always\u000d\u000aproduces the same hash, but it is computationally infeasible to reverse the process.\u000d\u000aSee also: Blockchain, Mining, Digital Signature\u000d\u000aHot Wallet\u000d\u000aA digital asset wallet that is connected to the internet, allowing instant access to funds and fast transaction\u000d\u000aprocessing. Hot wallets are convenient but vulnerable to hacking and cyber-theft. SEC Nigeria's DAC rules\u000d\u000arequire custodians to limit the proportion of client assets held in hot wallets and maintain significant\u000d\u000aholdings in cold storage.\u000d\u000aSee also: Cold Wallet, DAC, Custodial Wallet\u000d\u000aI\u000d\u000aICO (Initial Coin Offering)\u000d\u000a\u2014 205 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aA fundraising mechanism in which a company or project sells newly created tokens to investors in exchange\u000d\u000afor established cryptocurrencies (typically Ethereum or Bitcoin) or fiat currency. ICOs were the dominant\u000d\u000acrypto fundraising mechanism in 2017-2018 and raised billions globally before regulatory crackdowns. Many\u000d\u000aICOs were later found to have issued tokens that qualified as securities without appropriate registration.\u000d\u000aNigeria's SEC issued a statement in 2017 warning the public about ICO risks. Under the ISA 2025, all digital asset\u000d\u000aofferings targeting Nigerians \u2014 including structures that may previously have been described as ICOs \u2014 require\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria registration as DAOPs and must comply with investor protection rules.\u000d\u000aSee also: DAOP, Security Token, ISA 2025, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aICPC (Independent Corrupt Practices and Other Related Offences Commission)\u000d\u000aNigeria's anti-corruption agency, responsible for investigating and prosecuting corruption, bribery, and\u000d\u000arelated offences. Relevant to digital asset businesses because corrupt practices involving digital assets \u2014\u000d\u000aincluding the use of crypto to pay or receive bribes \u2014 fall within ICPC's remit.\u000d\u000aSee also: EFCC, NFIU, AML\u000d\u000aInnovation Sandbox\u000d\u000aA controlled regulatory environment that allows companies to test innovative financial products and\u000d\u000aservices with real customers, under regulatory oversight and with relaxed application of certain rules, for a\u000d\u000adefined period. Sandboxes allow regulators to understand new technologies before writing permanent\u000d\u000arules, and allow businesses to test viability before committing to full compliance infrastructure.\u000d\u000aNigeria operates regulatory sandboxes through both the CBN (for payment and financial services innovation)\u000d\u000aand SEC Nigeria (the ARIP programme, which functions as a regulatory incubator for digital asset businesses).\u000d\u000aThe SEC sandbox has already produced Nigeria's first provisional VASP licences. Founders should view sandbox\u000d\u000aentry as a competitive advantage, not merely a compliance pathway.\u000d\u000aSee also: ARIP, Regulatory Sandbox, CBN, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aInteroperability\u000d\u000aThe ability of different blockchain networks, protocols, or systems to communicate, exchange data, and\u000d\u000atransfer value with each other seamlessly. Interoperability is a major technical challenge in blockchain: most\u000d\u000achains operate in isolation, requiring bridges or cross-chain protocols. In the African context, payment\u000d\u000ainteroperability \u2014 the ability to send money across different mobile money and banking systems \u2014 is a core\u000d\u000aobjective of initiatives such as PAPSS.\u000d\u000aSee also: Bridge, PAPSS, Layer 1, Layer 2\u000d\u000aIPFS (InterPlanetary File System)\u000d\u000a\u2014 206 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aA peer-to-peer protocol for storing and accessing files in a distributed manner, rather than relying on\u000d\u000acentralised servers. IPFS is commonly used to store the media files associated with NFTs (images, videos),\u000d\u000awith only the content-addressed hash stored on-chain. This avoids storing large files on the blockchain while\u000d\u000apreserving a verifiable link to the content.\u000d\u000aSee also: NFT, Decentralised Storage\u000d\u000aISA 2025 (Investments and Securities Act 2025)\u000d\u000aNigeria's comprehensive capital markets legislation, signed into law in 2025, which replaced the\u000d\u000aInvestments and Securities Act 2007. ISA 2025 is the most significant legislative development in Nigerian\u000d\u000adigital asset regulation to date: it formally classifies digital assets (including cryptocurrencies and NFTs) as\u000d\u000asecurities under Nigerian law, establishes SEC Nigeria as the apex regulator for all digital asset activities, and\u000d\u000aprovides the statutory basis for VASP licensing, the ARIP programme, and investor protection measures for\u000d\u000adigital asset holders.\u000d\u000aISA 2025 ends the regulatory uncertainty that surrounded digital assets in Nigeria for years. Under Section 357,\u000d\u000avirtual assets are securities. The Second Schedule specifically recognises DLT-based tokens and products as\u000d\u000ainvestments. All VASPs \u2014 including those that previously operated under the ARIP framework \u2014 must now\u000d\u000acomply with ISA 2025 and the revised SEC Digital Asset Rules.\u000d\u000aSee also: SEC Nigeria, VASP, DAX, DAOP, DAC, ARIP, Digital Asset\u000d\u000aK\u000d\u000aKenya VASP Act 2025 (Virtual Asset Service Providers Act, Kenya)\u000d\u000aKenya's dedicated digital asset legislation, which came into force in October 2025 following a nationwide\u000d\u000aconsultation process. The Act introduces a licensing regime for VASPs, establishes dual regulatory oversight\u000d\u000abetween the Central Bank of Kenya (for payment-related VASPs including wallet providers, stablecoin\u000d\u000aissuers, and payment processors) and the Capital Markets Authority (for exchanges, investment advisers,\u000d\u000aand tokenisation platforms), and introduces AML/CFT obligations for all licensed VASPs.\u000d\u000aKenya (selective coverage): The Act was partly driven by an IMF technical assistance report that identified\u000d\u000aKenya's regulatory gap as an AML risk, and by Kenya's FATF grey listing concerns. Kenya now requires VASPs to\u000d\u000abe physically present in the country.\u000d\u000aSee also: VASP, Capital Markets Authority (Kenya), AML/CFT\u000d\u000aKYB (Know Your Business)\u000d\u000a\u2014 207 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe business-entity equivalent of KYC: the process of verifying the identity, ownership structure, beneficial\u000d\u000aownership, and legitimacy of a business customer before establishing a financial relationship. KYB is\u000d\u000aparticularly important for VASPs that serve corporate or institutional clients. It includes verifying corporate\u000d\u000aregistration, understanding ultimate beneficial owners, and assessing the business's source of funds.\u000d\u000aNigerian VASPs must conduct KYB on business customers as part of their CDD obligations under the MLPPA\u000d\u000a2022. Beneficial ownership verification \u2014 identifying the natural persons who ultimately own or control a\u000d\u000abusiness \u2014 is a specific NFIU requirement.\u000d\u000aSee also: KYC, CDD, AML, Beneficial Ownership\u000d\u000aKYC (Know Your Customer)\u000d\u000aThe process by which regulated entities verify the identity of their customers before establishing a business\u000d\u000arelationship or executing transactions above specified thresholds. KYC typically includes collecting and\u000d\u000averifying government-issued identification, address, date of birth, and conducting screening against\u000d\u000asanctions and PEP lists.\u000d\u000aNigerian VASPs must implement tiered KYC as required by the NFIU AML/CFT compliance framework and the\u000d\u000aMLPPA 2022. Minimum KYC requirements include BVN (Bank Verification Number) and NIN (National\u000d\u000aIdentification Number) verification for Nigerian individuals. SEC Nigeria's rules also require KYC before\u000d\u000aonboarding customers to VASP platforms.\u000d\u000aSee also: CDD, EDD, AML, BVN, NIN, PEP, MLPPA\u000d\u000aL\u000d\u000aLayer 1 (L1)\u000d\u000aThe base blockchain protocol \u2014 the foundational layer on which everything else is built. Bitcoin, Ethereum,\u000d\u000aSolana, and BNB Chain are Layer 1 blockchains. Each L1 has its own consensus mechanism, native token,\u000d\u000aand rules. L1 limitations (speed, cost, capacity) have driven the development of Layer 2 solutions.\u000d\u000aSee also: Layer 2, Blockchain, Consensus Mechanism\u000d\u000aLayer 2 (L2)\u000d\u000aA secondary network or protocol built on top of a Layer 1 blockchain to improve its speed, reduce costs, or\u000d\u000aincrease throughput, while inheriting the security of the base chain. Examples include the Lightning\u000d\u000aNetwork (Bitcoin), Optimism, Arbitrum, and Polygon (Ethereum). L2 solutions are important for\u000d\u000aAfrica-focused use cases where transaction fees must be minimal.\u000d\u000aSee also: Layer 1, Rollup, Sidechain\u000d\u000a\u2014 208 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aLiquidity\u000d\u000aThe ease with which an asset can be bought or sold in a market without significantly affecting its price. In\u000d\u000athe context of digital assets, liquidity refers to the trading volume and depth of buy and sell orders on an\u000d\u000aexchange. Low liquidity means large trades can cause sharp price movements. Liquidity is a key concern for\u000d\u000amarket integrity regulation.\u000d\u000aSee also: Market Maker, DEX, AMM, CEX\u000d\u000aLiquidity Pool\u000d\u000aA smart contract that holds reserves of two or more tokens, used by automated market makers (AMMs) to\u000d\u000afacilitate trading. Liquidity providers deposit token pairs into the pool and receive LP tokens representing\u000d\u000atheir share. They earn a portion of trading fees as compensation. Liquidity pools are the foundational\u000d\u000ainfrastructure of DeFi exchanges.\u000d\u000aSee also: AMM, DeFi, DEX, Yield Farming\u000d\u000aM\u000d\u000aMarket Maker\u000d\u000aAn entity that provides liquidity to a market by continuously quoting buy and sell prices for an asset,\u000d\u000afacilitating trading even when there is no immediate counterparty. Market makers are compensated by the\u000d\u000abid-ask spread. In regulated markets, market making requires authorisation; in DeFi, AMM protocols replace\u000d\u000atraditional market makers.\u000d\u000aSee also: AMM, Liquidity, CEX, DEX\u000d\u000aMauritius VAITOS Act (Virtual Asset and Initial Token Offering Services Act, Mauritius)\u000d\u000aMauritius's comprehensive digital asset legislation, enacted in 2021 \u2014 one of the earliest dedicated VASP\u000d\u000aregulatory frameworks on the continent. The Act is administered by the FSC Mauritius and covers VASP\u000d\u000alicensing across multiple categories including broker-dealer, custodian, wallet provider, and marketplace.\u000d\u000aThe regime is notable for its strong AML/CTF requirements and international compliance orientation.\u000d\u000aMauritius (selective coverage): Mauritius issued additional stablecoin guidance in 2025 and is developing a\u000d\u000amore comprehensive stablecoin framework. Mauritius is increasingly used by African founders as a regulatory\u000d\u000abase for digital asset businesses seeking international credibility.\u000d\u000aSee also: FSC Mauritius, VASP, Stablecoin\u000d\u000aMiCA (Markets in Crypto-Assets Regulation)\u000d\u000a\u2014 209 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe European Union's comprehensive regulatory framework for crypto assets, which came into force in\u000d\u000a2024. MiCA establishes licensing requirements for crypto asset service providers (CASPs), issuers of\u000d\u000aasset-referenced tokens (ARTs), and issuers of e-money tokens (EMTs) across the 27 EU member states. It is\u000d\u000areferenced in this book as a comparative benchmark: African founders targeting European markets, or\u000d\u000aworking with European investors and partners, must understand MiCA's requirements.\u000d\u000aMiCA is not directly applicable in Nigeria or other African jurisdictions, but it sets the global standard that\u000d\u000aAfrican frameworks are increasingly benchmarked against. African VASPs serving EU customers may be subject\u000d\u000ato MiCA regardless of where they are incorporated.\u000d\u000aSee also: CASP, Stablecoin, VASP\u000d\u000aMining\u000d\u000aThe process of validating and recording new transactions on a Proof of Work blockchain (such as Bitcoin) by\u000d\u000asolving complex mathematical puzzles. Miners who successfully validate a block receive new cryptocurrency\u000d\u000aas a reward (the block reward) plus transaction fees. Mining requires significant computational hardware\u000d\u000aand electricity. It is distinct from 'staking', which validates transactions on Proof of Stake blockchains.\u000d\u000aOperating a commercial mining operation in Nigeria that offers mining services to others may constitute VASP\u000d\u000aactivity under the ISA 2025, requiring SEC Nigeria registration. The NTAA 2025 introduces tax and penalty\u000d\u000aprovisions relevant to mining businesses.\u000d\u000aSee also: Proof of Work, Staking, Consensus Mechanism, VASP\u000d\u000aMLPPA (Money Laundering (Prevention and Prohibition) Act)\u000d\u000aNigeria's primary anti-money laundering legislation, enacted in 2022. The MLPPA 2022 repealed and\u000d\u000areplaced the Money Laundering (Prohibition) Act 2011. It significantly expanded the scope of AML\u000d\u000aobligations, explicitly classified VASPs as financial institutions subject to AML requirements, and updated\u000d\u000aNigeria's framework to meet FATF standards. The NFIU operates under the MLPPA.\u000d\u000aEvery VASP operating in Nigeria is a 'financial institution' under the MLPPA 2022 and must comply with KYC,\u000d\u000aCDD, transaction monitoring, record-keeping, and suspicious transaction reporting obligations. Non-compliance\u000d\u000acan result in criminal prosecution, fines, and licence revocation.\u000d\u000aSee also: AML, NFIU, KYC, STR, FATF, VASP\u000d\u000aMonetary Sovereignty\u000d\u000aA country's ability to control its own monetary policy \u2014 including the supply of money, interest rates, and\u000d\u000aexchange rate \u2014 without undue external influence. Monetary sovereignty is threatened when a significant\u000d\u000aportion of the population adopts foreign-denominated assets (particularly stablecoins pegged to the US\u000d\u000a\u2014 210 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000adollar) for everyday transactions, effectively substituting the domestic currency with a foreign one beyond\u000d\u000athe central bank's control.\u000d\u000aThe CBN's cautious approach to stablecoins is substantially motivated by monetary sovereignty concerns.\u000d\u000aNigeria's history of naira devaluation and FX scarcity makes crypto-dollarisation a real and measurable\u000d\u000aphenomenon. Founders building stablecoin products must be prepared to explain how their product addresses\u000d\u000arather than exacerbates this concern.\u000d\u000aSee also: Stablecoin, Crypto-Dollarisation, CBN, CBDC, eNaira\u000d\u000aMultisig (Multi-Signature)\u000d\u000aA security mechanism that requires multiple private key holders to authorise a transaction before it can be\u000d\u000aexecuted. For example, a 2-of-3 multisig wallet requires any two of three designated key holders to sign a\u000d\u000atransaction. Multisig is widely used in DAO governance, institutional custody, and team treasury\u000d\u000amanagement to prevent single points of failure or theft.\u000d\u000aSee also: DAO, Wallet, Private Key\u000d\u000aN\u000d\u000aNFT (Non-Fungible Token)\u000d\u000aA unique digital token recorded on a blockchain that represents ownership of a specific asset \u2014 such as\u000d\u000adigital art, music, real estate, game items, or identity credentials. Unlike fungible tokens (where each unit is\u000d\u000aidentical), each NFT is distinct. NFTs derive their non-fungibility from unique identifiers encoded in their\u000d\u000asmart contracts.\u000d\u000aNFTs are explicitly classified as digital assets under Nigeria's ISA 2025. Their issuance, trading, and custody are\u000d\u000asubject to SEC Nigeria oversight. The SEC's ARIP framework applies to platforms facilitating NFT transactions\u000d\u000awhere those NFTs constitute securities (e.g., fractional NFTs representing investment interests).\u000d\u000aSee also: ERC-721, Token, Digital Asset, ISA 2025\u000d\u000aNFIU (Nigerian Financial Intelligence Unit)\u000d\u000aNigeria's financial intelligence unit, established under the NFIU Act 2018. The NFIU receives and analyses\u000d\u000asuspicious transaction reports (STRs) and currency transaction reports (CTRs) from financial institutions\u000d\u000aincluding VASPs, disseminates financial intelligence to law enforcement agencies, and coordinates with\u000d\u000ainternational FIUs through the Egmont Group. The NFIU also issues AML/CFT compliance guidelines for\u000d\u000aVASPs.\u000d\u000a\u2014 211 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aAll Nigerian VASPs must register with the NFIU and file STRs and CTRs in accordance with NFIU guidelines. The\u000d\u000aNFIU is distinct from the EFCC (which prosecutes) and the CBN/SEC (which licence and supervise): it is\u000d\u000aspecifically a financial intelligence function.\u000d\u000aSee also: AML, STR, CTR, EFCC, MLPPA, Egmont Group\u000d\u000aNIN (National Identification Number)\u000d\u000aThe unique identity number assigned to every Nigerian citizen and resident by the National Identity\u000d\u000aManagement Commission (NIMC). The NIN is increasingly used as a foundational identity verification tool\u000d\u000aby financial institutions and VASPs in Nigeria, and is required for SIM card registration and certain banking\u000d\u000aservices.\u000d\u000aNigerian VASP KYC procedures must incorporate NIN verification as a minimum identity requirement. SEC\u000d\u000aNigeria and the CBN have both issued circulars making NIN linkage a requirement for account opening and\u000d\u000afinancial services access.\u000d\u000aSee also: KYC, BVN, Digital Identity, CDD\u000d\u000aNITDA (National Information Technology Development Agency)\u000d\u000aNigeria's primary government agency for IT policy, standards, and development, operating under the\u000d\u000aFederal Ministry of Communications, Innovation and Digital Economy. NITDA developed Nigeria's National\u000d\u000aBlockchain Policy (2023), which established the strategic framework for blockchain adoption across\u000d\u000agovernment and the private sector. The National Blockchain Policy Implementation Steering Committee \u2014\u000d\u000achaired by Chimezie Chuta \u2014 operates under NITDA's oversight.\u000d\u000aNITDA's blockchain policy work is complementary to SEC Nigeria's regulatory framework: NITDA focuses on\u000d\u000aecosystem development, adoption, and standards, while SEC focuses on investor protection, licensing, and\u000d\u000amarket integrity.\u000d\u000aSee also: National Blockchain Policy, Blockchain, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aNode\u000d\u000aA computer that participates in a blockchain network by storing a copy of the ledger, validating transactions,\u000d\u000aand/or relaying data to other participants. Full nodes store the complete transaction history; light nodes\u000d\u000astore only block headers. In Proof of Stake networks, validators operate nodes and stake tokens to earn the\u000d\u000aright to validate blocks.\u000d\u000aSee also: Blockchain, Consensus Mechanism, Validator\u000d\u000aNon-Custodial Wallet\u000d\u000a\u2014 212 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aA digital asset wallet where the user holds their own private keys \u2014 and therefore has sole control over\u000d\u000atheir funds, without relying on a third party. Non-custodial wallets (such as MetaMask, Phantom, or\u000d\u000ahardware wallets) are the default in DeFi. They offer maximum security and sovereignty but place the full\u000d\u000aburden of key management on the user.\u000d\u000aFATF's 2021 guidance on virtual assets specifically addressed 'unhosted wallets' (non-custodial wallets) as a\u000d\u000apotential AML risk, because transactions to/from unhosted wallets are harder to attribute to identified\u000d\u000aindividuals. Nigerian VASPs must conduct enhanced monitoring of transactions involving non-custodial wallet\u000d\u000acounterparties.\u000d\u000aSee also: Custodial Wallet, Private Key, AML, FATF\u000d\u000aNostro/Vostro Account\u000d\u000aAccounting terms for cross-border interbank accounts: a 'nostro' account is an account that a domestic bank\u000d\u000aholds at a foreign bank in the foreign currency; a 'vostro' account is an account that a foreign bank holds at\u000d\u000aa domestic bank in the domestic currency. These accounts are the plumbing of international correspondent\u000d\u000abanking \u2014 and their costs, inefficiencies, and withdrawal by de-risking banks is a major driver of\u000d\u000ablockchain-based cross-border payment adoption in Africa.\u000d\u000aSee also: Correspondent Banking, Cross-Border Payment, De-Risking, PAPSS\u000d\u000aNTAA 2025 (Nigeria Tax Administration Act 2025)\u000d\u000aNigerian legislation signed into law in 2025 (effective 2026) that introduces strengthened tax administration,\u000d\u000areporting requirements, and penalty provisions for VASPs and other digital asset businesses. Under the\u000d\u000aNTAA 2025, VASPs that fail to comply with reporting standards face initial fines of \u20a610 million plus \u20a61\u000d\u000amillion per month of continued non-compliance.\u000d\u000aFounders operating VASPs in Nigeria should treat NTAA 2025 compliance \u2014 including transaction reporting and\u000d\u000atax filing \u2014 as a distinct obligation from their SEC and NFIU compliance obligations.\u000d\u000aSee also: VASP, SEC Nigeria, Finance Act\u000d\u000aO\u000d\u000aOff-Ramp\u000d\u000aThe process of converting digital assets into fiat currency \u2014 such as converting Bitcoin or USDT into Nigerian\u000d\u000anaira \u2014 and withdrawing those funds to a bank account or mobile money wallet. Off-ramps are a critical\u000d\u000apiece of financial infrastructure for digital asset adoption. SEC Nigeria's 2024 amended Rules explicitly\u000d\u000adefine 'off-ramp' services.\u000d\u000a\u2014 213 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aIn Nigeria, off-ramp services connecting digital assets to the naira banking system require both SEC VASP\u000d\u000aregistration (for the digital asset side) and compliance with CBN payment regulations (for the fiat side). This\u000d\u000adual-regulator landscape is a key operational challenge for Nigerian VASPs.\u000d\u000aSee also: On-Ramp, CEX, P2P, CBN, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aOn-Chain\u000d\u000aTransactions or data that are recorded directly on a blockchain ledger \u2014 permanently, transparently, and\u000d\u000averifiably. On-chain transactions are visible to anyone with access to a blockchain explorer. Contrast with\u000d\u000a'off-chain' transactions, which occur through separate systems and are later settled or referenced on-chain.\u000d\u000aSee also: Blockchain, Chain Analysis, Off-Chain\u000d\u000aOn-Ramp\u000d\u000aThe process of converting fiat currency into digital assets \u2014 such as converting naira into Bitcoin or USDT.\u000d\u000aOn-ramps are the entry point into the digital asset economy for most new users. They typically involve KYC\u000d\u000averification, bank transfer or card payment, and conversion at market rates. SEC Nigeria's 2024 amended\u000d\u000aRules define 'on-ramp' as a regulated activity.\u000d\u000aSee also: Off-Ramp, KYC, CEX, P2P\u000d\u000aOracle\u000d\u000aA service that provides external, real-world data to smart contracts on a blockchain. Because blockchains\u000d\u000aare isolated from external data sources, smart contracts cannot independently verify external information\u000d\u000a(such as asset prices, interest rates, or weather data). Oracles bridge this gap \u2014 but they also introduce a\u000d\u000acentralisation risk (the 'oracle problem'): if the oracle is compromised, the smart contracts that rely on it\u000d\u000acan be manipulated.\u000d\u000aSee also: Smart Contract, DeFi, Chainlink\u000d\u000aOTC (Over-the-Counter Trading)\u000d\u000aThe trading of digital assets directly between two parties, outside of a formal exchange. OTC desks facilitate\u000d\u000alarge trades (typically for institutional or high-net-worth clients) at negotiated prices, without moving the\u000d\u000amarket as a large exchange order would. OTC trading in digital assets is common in Nigeria, and OTC desks\u000d\u000arequire the same AML/CFT compliance as other VASPs.\u000d\u000aOTC desks in Nigeria are within the scope of SEC Nigeria's VASP framework. Their activities \u2014 particularly large\u000d\u000apeer-to-peer transactions \u2014 are a focus of the NFIU's AML monitoring, as OTC trading has been used to\u000d\u000afacilitate the movement of illicit funds.\u000d\u000aSee also: VASP, P2P, AML, CEX, DAX\u000d\u000a\u2014 214 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aP\u000d\u000aP2P Trading (Peer-to-Peer Trading)\u000d\u000aThe direct exchange of digital assets between two individuals, without using a centralised exchange\u000d\u000aplatform as an intermediary. P2P platforms (such as Paxful and Remitano, which were dominant in Nigeria)\u000d\u000amatch buyers and sellers, who then transact directly. P2P trading has been the dominant crypto trading\u000d\u000amethod in Nigeria due to CBN restrictions on bank support for crypto exchanges. P2P markets are a\u000d\u000asignificant AML risk because they may lack robust KYC.\u000d\u000aNigeria has one of the largest P2P crypto trading volumes in the world. The CBN's 2021 restrictions (since\u000d\u000apartially relaxed) accelerated P2P adoption. P2P platforms \u2014 even those that merely match parties without\u000d\u000aholding funds \u2014 are subject to VASP registration requirements under ISA 2025 and must implement AML/CFT\u000d\u000acontrols.\u000d\u000aSee also: CEX, DEX, OTC, AML, VASP\u000d\u000aPAPSS (Pan-African Payment and Settlement System)\u000d\u000aA payment infrastructure developed by the African Export-Import Bank (Afreximbank) and the African\u000d\u000aUnion, designed to enable instant cross-border payments in African currencies across the continent \u2014\u000d\u000aeliminating the need for payments to be routed through correspondent banks outside Africa (often via New\u000d\u000aYork or London). PAPSS is a key piece of AfCFTA digital trade infrastructure.\u000d\u000aNigeria's CBN is a member of PAPSS. As PAPSS matures, it has the potential to significantly reduce Nigeria's\u000d\u000areliance on the correspondent banking system for intra-African trade payments \u2014 and to compete with\u000d\u000astablecoin-based cross-border payment solutions.\u000d\u000aSee also: AfCFTA, Cross-Border Payment, Correspondent Banking, CBN\u000d\u000aPayment Token\u000d\u000aA type of digital token designed primarily for use as a medium of exchange \u2014 to pay for goods or services.\u000d\u000aPayment tokens are distinct from security tokens (investment instruments) and utility tokens (platform\u000d\u000aaccess). The regulatory treatment of payment tokens varies: some jurisdictions subject them to payment\u000d\u000aservices regulation, others to securities law.\u000d\u000aUnder Nigeria's ISA 2025, all virtual assets are broadly classified as securities. The CBN retains separate\u000d\u000ajurisdiction over payment instruments. A payment token product in Nigeria may require both SEC registration\u000d\u000aand CBN payment service authorisation depending on its structure.\u000d\u000a\u2014 215 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aSee also: Security Token, Utility Token, Stablecoin, CBN, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aPEP (Politically Exposed Person)\u000d\u000aAn individual who holds or has held a prominent public position \u2014 such as a head of state, government\u000d\u000aminister, senior judicial official, military officer, senior executive of a state-owned enterprise, or senior\u000d\u000aofficial of an international organisation \u2014 and their immediate family members and close associates. PEPs\u000d\u000aare subject to Enhanced Due Diligence because their positions make them more vulnerable to involvement\u000d\u000ain bribery and corruption.\u000d\u000aNigerian VASPs must screen all customers against PEP lists and apply EDD to any PEP customer or associate.\u000d\u000aGiven Nigeria's large public sector, PEP exposure is a significant compliance consideration for Nigerian digital\u000d\u000aasset platforms.\u000d\u000aSee also: EDD, KYC, CDD, AML, Sanctions Screening\u000d\u000aPrivate Key\u000d\u000aA secret cryptographic code \u2014 a long string of letters and numbers \u2014 that gives its holder sole authority to\u000d\u000aauthorise transactions from the corresponding blockchain address. The private key is the ultimate proof of\u000d\u000aownership in a blockchain system: whoever holds the private key controls the assets at the associated\u000d\u000aaddress. If lost, access to those assets is permanently forfeited; if stolen, assets can be irrecoverably\u000d\u000atransferred.\u000d\u000aSee also: Public Key, Wallet, Seed Phrase, Address\u000d\u000aProgrammable Money\u000d\u000aMoney that has conditions, rules, or logic encoded directly into it \u2014 so that it can only be spent,\u000d\u000atransferred, or accessed when specified conditions are met. Smart contracts enable programmable money:\u000d\u000afor example, a smart contract could release payment only upon verified delivery of goods, or distribute\u000d\u000aroyalties automatically whenever a digital asset is resold. CBDCs and tokenised currencies are increasingly\u000d\u000adesigned with programmable features.\u000d\u000aThe CBN and eNaira team have explored programmable payment features such as conditional disbursements\u000d\u000afor social transfers. Founders building payment automation, trade finance, or escrow products on blockchain\u000d\u000arails should understand how programmable money creates new product possibilities that the traditional\u000d\u000abanking system cannot easily replicate.\u000d\u000aSee also: Smart Contract, CBDC, eNaira, Stablecoin\u000d\u000aProof of Stake (PoS)\u000d\u000aA blockchain consensus mechanism in which validators are selected to create new blocks based on the\u000d\u000aamount of cryptocurrency they have 'staked' (locked up) as collateral. PoS is significantly more\u000d\u000a\u2014 216 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aenergy-efficient than Proof of Work. Ethereum adopted PoS in 2022 ('The Merge'). Validators who behave\u000d\u000adishonestly risk having their staked tokens 'slashed' (partially destroyed).\u000d\u000aSee also: Consensus Mechanism, Staking, Validator\u000d\u000aProof of Work (PoW)\u000d\u000aThe original blockchain consensus mechanism, used by Bitcoin, in which participants (miners) compete to\u000d\u000asolve computationally intensive mathematical puzzles to earn the right to add the next block to the chain.\u000d\u000aPoW is highly energy-intensive but battle-tested in security. The energy consumption of PoW mining has\u000d\u000abeen a point of regulatory scrutiny globally.\u000d\u000aSee also: Mining, Consensus Mechanism, Blockchain\u000d\u000aPublic Key\u000d\u000aA cryptographic code derived from the private key that can be shared publicly and used to verify digital\u000d\u000asignatures or derive a blockchain address. The public key is analogous to a bank account number \u2014 others\u000d\u000acan use it to send assets to you, but it does not grant access to your funds.\u000d\u000aSee also: Private Key, Address, Wallet\u000d\u000aR\u000d\u000aRecommendation 15 (FATF)\u000d\u000aThe FATF Recommendation, updated in 2019, that extended AML/CFT obligations to virtual assets and\u000d\u000avirtual asset service providers. Recommendation 15 requires countries to regulate and supervise VASPs for\u000d\u000aAML/CFT purposes, apply FATF standards to their activities, and implement the Travel Rule for virtual asset\u000d\u000atransfers. As of 2025, only 21% of assessed jurisdictions are fully compliant with R.15.\u000d\u000aNigeria is identified by FATF as a jurisdiction with materially important VASP activity, meaning its\u000d\u000aimplementation of R.15 is subject to ongoing monitoring. Nigeria's ARIP framework, VASP supervision pilot, and\u000d\u000aMLPPA 2022 are all partly aimed at achieving R.15 compliance.\u000d\u000aSee also: FATF, Travel Rule, AML, VASP, GIABA\u000d\u000aRegulatory Capital\u000d\u000aThe minimum amount of capital that a regulated entity must hold to absorb potential losses and protect\u000d\u000acustomers \u2014 determined by the regulator as a condition of licensing. All VASP categories in Nigeria have\u000d\u000aprescribed minimum capital requirements under SEC Nigeria's rules, with amounts varying by licence type\u000d\u000a(DAX, DAOP, DAC, DAI).\u000d\u000a\u2014 217 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria's minimum capital requirements for VASPs (as set in the 2024 amended Rules) are substantial:\u000d\u000afounders must factor capitalisation requirements into their funding strategy from an early stage, as they cannot\u000d\u000aapply for SEC registration without the requisite paid-up capital.\u000d\u000aSee also: SEC Nigeria, VASP, DAX, DAOP, DAC, Fidelity Bond\u000d\u000aRegulatory Sandbox\u000d\u000aSee Innovation Sandbox.\u000d\u000aSee also: Innovation Sandbox, ARIP, CBN, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aRemittance\u000d\u000aMoney transferred by a person in one country to recipients in another, typically by migrant workers sending\u000d\u000afunds home. Remittances are one of the largest sources of foreign exchange for many African countries.\u000d\u000aNigeria is consistently among the top remittance recipients in Africa, with inflows of over USD 20 billion\u000d\u000aannually. Digital assets and stablecoins are increasingly used for remittances due to lower costs compared\u000d\u000ato traditional wire transfers.\u000d\u000aThe CBN regulates international remittances under the Foreign Exchange (Monitoring and Miscellaneous\u000d\u000aProvisions) Act and associated regulations. VASPs facilitating crypto-based remittances into Nigeria must\u000d\u000acomply with both SEC digital asset rules and CBN FX regulations.\u000d\u000aSee also: Cross-Border Payment, Stablecoin, PAPSS, CBN\u000d\u000aRisk-Based Approach (RBA)\u000d\u000aThe principle \u2014 central to FATF's AML/CFT framework \u2014 that regulated entities should direct their\u000d\u000acompliance resources proportionally toward higher-risk customers, products, channels, and geographies,\u000d\u000arather than applying blanket measures uniformly. A risk-based approach requires conducting a\u000d\u000aBusiness-Wide Risk Assessment (BWRA) and customer-level risk assessments.\u000d\u000aThe NFIU and SEC Nigeria both expect VASPs to operate a risk-based AML/CFT programme. This means not all\u000d\u000acustomers are treated identically: lower-risk customers may be subject to simplified due diligence, while\u000d\u000ahigher-risk customers (PEPs, those from high-risk jurisdictions, unusual transaction patterns) must receive\u000d\u000aenhanced scrutiny.\u000d\u000aSee also: AML, CDD, EDD, KYC, NFIU\u000d\u000aRollup\u000d\u000aA Layer 2 scaling solution that processes transactions off the main chain (off-chain) but posts compressed\u000d\u000atransaction data back to the Layer 1 blockchain for security and finality. Optimistic rollups and ZK-rollups are\u000d\u000a\u2014 218 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000athe two main types. Rollups significantly reduce transaction costs and increase throughput while inheriting\u000d\u000aEthereum's security \u2014 making them important for low-cost financial applications in Africa.\u000d\u000aSee also: Layer 2, Zero-Knowledge Proof, Ethereum\u000d\u000aRWA (Real-World Asset Tokenisation)\u000d\u000aThe process of creating a digital token on a blockchain that represents ownership of or rights to a physical or\u000d\u000atraditional financial asset \u2014 such as real estate, gold, government bonds, invoices, or equity. RWA\u000d\u000atokenisation enables fractional ownership, 24/7 trading, automated compliance, and programmable\u000d\u000adistributions for assets that previously required expensive intermediaries.\u000d\u000aNigeria's ISA 2025 creates the legal foundation for RWA tokenisation under SEC Nigeria's oversight. Tokenised\u000d\u000asecurities \u2014 including tokenised bonds, equity, or real estate \u2014 are securities and require registration. The SEC\u000d\u000ahas flagged RWA tokenisation as a priority area for its regulatory development.\u000d\u000aSee also: Tokenisation, Security Token, ISA 2025, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aS\u000d\u000aSAR (Suspicious Activity Report)\u000d\u000aA report filed by a financial institution or VASP with the relevant financial intelligence unit when it identifies\u000d\u000aa transaction or pattern of activity that it suspects \u2014 based on reasonable grounds \u2014 may involve money\u000d\u000alaundering, terrorist financing, or other financial crime. In Nigeria, these are referred to as Suspicious\u000d\u000aTransaction Reports (STRs) and are filed with the NFIU.\u000d\u000aSee also: STR, NFIU, AML, MLPPA\u000d\u000aSanctions Screening\u000d\u000aThe process of checking customers, transactions, and counterparties against official lists of sanctioned\u000d\u000aindividuals, entities, and jurisdictions \u2014 including UN Security Council lists, OFAC (US Treasury) lists, EU\u000d\u000asanctions lists, and Nigeria's own designated persons and entities list. VASPs must screen at onboarding and\u000d\u000aon an ongoing basis.\u000d\u000aNigerian VASPs must screen against both international sanctions lists (UN, OFAC) and Nigeria's domestic\u000d\u000aterrorism financing designation lists maintained by the NFIU. Failure to screen and identify a sanctioned\u000d\u000aindividual or entity is a serious regulatory and criminal offence.\u000d\u000aSee also: AML, CFT, CPF, NFIU, PEP\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria (Securities and Exchange Commission Nigeria)\u000d\u000a\u2014 219 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aNigeria's apex capital markets regulator, established under the Investments and Securities Act. SEC Nigeria is\u000d\u000aresponsible for regulating the Nigerian capital market, protecting investors, and maintaining market\u000d\u000aintegrity. Following ISA 2025, SEC Nigeria is the primary regulator for all digital asset activities in Nigeria \u2014\u000d\u000aincluding VASP licensing, digital asset offerings, exchanges, and custodians.\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria's Digital Asset Rules (2022, amended 2024, further amendments effective June 2025) are the\u000d\u000aprimary operational framework for VASP licensing. The ARIP programme is SEC Nigeria's main tool for\u000d\u000aonboarding digital asset businesses. Founders must understand the distinction between SEC Nigeria's\u000d\u000ajurisdiction (securities and investment activities) and the CBN's jurisdiction (payment, banking, monetary\u000d\u000apolicy).\u000d\u000aSee also: ISA 2025, ARIP, VASP, DAX, DAOP, DAC, CBN\u000d\u000aSecurity Token\u000d\u000aA digital token that represents an investment contract \u2014 i.e., a financial security \u2014 such as equity in a\u000d\u000acompany, a debt instrument, a share of revenue, or a fractional interest in a real asset. Security tokens are\u000d\u000athe digital equivalent of traditional securities and are subject to full securities regulation wherever they are\u000d\u000aissued or traded.\u000d\u000aUnder Nigeria's ISA 2025, all virtual assets are classified as securities. Tokens that carry investment\u000d\u000acharacteristics (profit participation, dividend rights, capital appreciation) will be treated as security tokens\u000d\u000asubject to SEC Nigeria's full regulatory framework.\u000d\u000aSee also: ISA 2025, Utility Token, Governance Token, RWA, ICO\u000d\u000aSeed Phrase\u000d\u000aA human-readable sequence of 12 or 24 random words generated when a non-custodial wallet is created.\u000d\u000aThe seed phrase is the master backup of the wallet's private keys: anyone who holds the seed phrase can\u000d\u000arecover the wallet and all its assets on any compatible device. Seed phrases must be written down and\u000d\u000astored securely offline \u2014 they should never be shared, photographed, or stored digitally.\u000d\u000aSee also: Private Key, Non-Custodial Wallet, Cold Wallet\u000d\u000aSmart Contract\u000d\u000aSelf-executing code deployed on a blockchain that automatically enforces the terms of an agreement when\u000d\u000apredefined conditions are met \u2014 without the need for intermediaries. Smart contracts are immutable\u000d\u000a(cannot be altered once deployed) and transparent (their code is publicly visible). They are the foundational\u000d\u000abuilding blocks of DeFi, DAOs, NFTs, and tokenisation. Bugs in smart contract code can result in significant\u000d\u000afinancial losses and cannot be easily reversed.\u000d\u000a\u2014 220 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aSmart contracts do not currently have a specific legal recognition under Nigerian contract law \u2014 they are not\u000d\u000arecognised as legally binding agreements in themselves. Founders using smart contracts in products for\u000d\u000aNigerian markets should ensure that underlying legal agreements (in traditional contract form) complement the\u000d\u000asmart contract logic, to provide enforceability in Nigerian courts.\u000d\u000aSee also: Blockchain, DeFi, DAO, Ethereum, EVM\u000d\u000aSoft Fork\u000d\u000aA backwards-compatible upgrade to a blockchain's protocol rules, such that nodes that do not upgrade can\u000d\u000astill participate in the network (though they may not take advantage of new features). Soft forks are less\u000d\u000adisruptive than hard forks and do not create a split chain.\u000d\u000aSee also: Hard Fork, Blockchain, Consensus Mechanism\u000d\u000aSolidity\u000d\u000aThe primary programming language used to write smart contracts for the Ethereum blockchain and\u000d\u000aEVM-compatible networks. Solidity is a statically-typed, curly-bracket language designed specifically for\u000d\u000awriting contract logic that runs on the EVM. Most DeFi protocols, ERC-20 tokens, and NFT contracts are\u000d\u000awritten in Solidity.\u000d\u000aSee also: Smart Contract, EVM, Ethereum\u000d\u000aSouth Africa CASP Framework\u000d\u000aSouth Africa's regulatory framework for crypto asset service providers, administered by the FSCA. South\u000d\u000aAfrica was one of the first African jurisdictions to operationalise VASP licensing: the FSCA began accepting\u000d\u000aCASP authorisation applications in June 2023, with a deadline for existing businesses to apply by November\u000d\u000a2023. CASPs must also comply with FIC (AML/CFT) obligations.\u000d\u000aSouth Africa (selective coverage): South Africa's CASP framework is an important benchmark for other African\u000d\u000ajurisdictions. It demonstrates that a major African economy can implement operational VASP licensing \u2014 and\u000d\u000aprovides a comparative model for Nigerian founders who may also serve South African customers.\u000d\u000aSee also: CASP, FSCA, FIC, VASP\u000d\u000aStablecoin\u000d\u000aA type of digital asset designed to maintain a stable value by being pegged to a reference asset \u2014 typically a\u000d\u000afiat currency (such as the US dollar), a commodity (such as gold), or a basket of assets. Fiat-backed\u000d\u000astablecoins (USDT, USDC) are the most widely used and maintain their peg by holding reserves of the\u000d\u000aunderlying fiat currency. Algorithmic stablecoins attempt to maintain their peg through supply and demand\u000d\u000amechanisms rather than reserves \u2014 and have been involved in catastrophic collapses (notably TerraUSD in\u000d\u000a2022).\u000d\u000a\u2014 221 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aStablecoins are not regulated by standalone Nigerian legislation. Under ISA 2025, they are classified as virtual\u000d\u000aassets and fall under SEC Nigeria's framework. The CBN retains separate interest in stablecoins from a\u000d\u000amonetary sovereignty and payment system perspective. Nigeria's SEC 2024 amended Rules explicitly define\u000d\u000a'stablecoin' for the first time in Nigerian regulation. FATF's 2025 targeted update identified the increasing\u000d\u000acriminal use of stablecoins as a major AML risk.\u000d\u000aSee also: CBDC, eNaira, Crypto-Dollarisation, Monetary Sovereignty, CBN, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aStaking\u000d\u000aThe process of locking up cryptocurrency as collateral in a Proof of Stake blockchain to participate in\u000d\u000atransaction validation and earn rewards. Staking is analogous to earning interest on a deposit. Liquid staking\u000d\u000aprotocols allow stakers to maintain liquidity by issuing derivative tokens representing their staked position.\u000d\u000aThe regulatory treatment of staking rewards (as income, capital gains, or investment returns) varies by\u000d\u000ajurisdiction.\u000d\u000aStaking services offered to Nigerian investors are likely to constitute investment activity under ISA 2025 and\u000d\u000arequire SEC Nigeria oversight. Platforms offering staking yields to Nigerian users should assess whether they\u000d\u000aconstitute unlicensed collective investment schemes.\u000d\u000aSee also: Proof of Stake, DeFi, SEC Nigeria, Yield Farming\u000d\u000aSTR (Suspicious Transaction Report)\u000d\u000aThe formal report filed by a Nigerian financial institution or VASP with the NFIU when it identifies a\u000d\u000atransaction or pattern of customer behaviour that gives reasonable grounds for suspicion of money\u000d\u000alaundering, terrorist financing, or related financial crime. Filing an STR is mandatory under the MLPPA 2022;\u000d\u000atipping off the customer about the report is a criminal offence.\u000d\u000aNigerian VASPs must have clear internal procedures for identifying and escalating suspicious activity, and must\u000d\u000afile STRs with the NFIU within prescribed timeframes. The NFIU also requires the filing of Currency Transaction\u000d\u000aReports (CTRs) for cash transactions above specified thresholds.\u000d\u000aSee also: AML, NFIU, MLPPA, SAR\u000d\u000aSupTech (Supervisory Technology)\u000d\u000aThe use of technology \u2014 including AI, machine learning, blockchain analytics, and data automation \u2014 by\u000d\u000afinancial regulators and supervisors to enhance their monitoring, inspection, and enforcement capabilities.\u000d\u000aSupTech tools allow regulators to process large volumes of transaction data, identify anomalies, and\u000d\u000amonitor market integrity more efficiently than traditional manual processes.\u000d\u000a\u2014 222 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aThe CBN's VASP supervision pilot incorporates elements of SupTech, including the use of transaction data and\u000d\u000ablockchain analytics to monitor VASPs. As Nigerian regulatory capacity develops, founders should anticipate a\u000d\u000afuture in which on-chain and off-chain activity is subject to real-time regulatory monitoring.\u000d\u000aSee also: Blockchain Analytics, AML, CBN, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aT\u000d\u000aToken\u000d\u000aA unit of value recorded on a blockchain. Unlike 'coins' (which are native to their own blockchain, such as\u000d\u000aBitcoin or Ether), tokens are built on top of existing blockchains using smart contracts (such as ERC-20\u000d\u000atokens on Ethereum). Tokens can represent financial assets, access rights, governance rights, or proof of\u000d\u000aownership \u2014 and are classified by regulators as utility tokens, security tokens, payment tokens, or\u000d\u000agovernance tokens depending on their function.\u000d\u000aNigeria's ISA 2025 and SEC Digital Asset Rules classify virtually all tokens as virtual assets/digital assets and\u000d\u000asubject them to SEC Nigeria oversight. Founders must obtain a legal opinion on the classification of their token\u000d\u000abefore any public offering, as misclassification can result in unlicensed securities offering charges.\u000d\u000aSee also: ERC-20, Security Token, Utility Token, Governance Token, ISA 2025\u000d\u000aTokenisation\u000d\u000aThe process of representing ownership rights in an asset \u2014 whether financial (shares, bonds, invoices) or\u000d\u000aphysical (real estate, commodities, art) \u2014 as a digital token on a blockchain. Tokenisation enables fractional\u000d\u000aownership, programmable compliance, automated settlement, and 24/7 tradability for assets that\u000d\u000atraditionally required expensive intermediaries and slow processes.\u000d\u000aISA 2025 provides the legal foundation for securities tokenisation in Nigeria under SEC Nigeria's oversight. The\u000d\u000aSEC has signalled tokenised bonds, equity, and real estate as priority areas. Founders building RWA tokenisation\u000d\u000aproducts should expect SEC registration requirements for both the token issuance (as a DAOP) and the trading\u000d\u000aplatform (as a DAX).\u000d\u000aSee also: RWA, Security Token, ISA 2025, SEC Nigeria, DeFi\u000d\u000aTravel Rule (FATF)\u000d\u000aA requirement under FATF Recommendation 15 that virtual asset service providers must collect, verify, and\u000d\u000atransmit specified information about the originators and beneficiaries of virtual asset transfers above a\u000d\u000athreshold of USD/EUR 1,000. The Travel Rule is intended to prevent VASPs from being used to move illicit\u000d\u000a\u2014 223 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000afunds anonymously. Its implementation presents technical challenges because VASPs must securely share\u000d\u000apersonal data with counterparty VASPs \u2014 infrastructure that is still developing globally.\u000d\u000aAs of 2025, Nigeria has not yet fully operationalised Travel Rule compliance for VASPs. However, the NFIU and\u000d\u000aCBN's VASP supervision pilot are expected to include Travel Rule implementation requirements. Nigerian VASPs\u000d\u000a\u2014 particularly those with international transaction flows \u2014 should begin building Travel Rule compliance\u000d\u000ainfrastructure now.\u000d\u000aSee also: FATF, Recommendation 15, AML, VASP, NFIU\u000d\u000aTradFi (Traditional Finance)\u000d\u000aA colloquial term used in the crypto and Web3 community to refer to the conventional financial system \u2014\u000d\u000aincluding banks, insurance companies, stock exchanges, brokerages, and payment networks. TradFi is\u000d\u000acontrasted with DeFi (decentralised finance) and used to describe incumbent financial institutions\u000d\u000anavigating the transition to digital asset infrastructure.\u000d\u000aSee also: DeFi, CEX, Stablecoin, Web3\u000d\u000aU\u000d\u000aUtility Token\u000d\u000aA digital token that grants its holder access to a specific product or service within a defined platform or\u000d\u000aecosystem \u2014 rather than representing an investment interest. Utility tokens are the digital equivalent of\u000d\u000apre-paid vouchers or software licences. However, the line between utility tokens and security tokens is\u000d\u000aactively contested: regulators often find that tokens marketed as 'utility' in practice function as investments.\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria takes a functional approach to token classification: regardless of what a token is called, if it has the\u000d\u000aeconomic characteristics of a security (investment of money in a common enterprise with expectation of profit\u000d\u000afrom others' efforts), it will be treated as a security token. Founders should not rely on labelling a token 'utility'\u000d\u000ato avoid SEC Nigeria oversight.\u000d\u000aSee also: Security Token, Governance Token, ICO, ISA 2025\u000d\u000aV\u000d\u000aVAITOS (Virtual Asset and Initial Token Offering Services Act (Mauritius))\u000d\u000a\u2014 224 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aSee Mauritius VAITOS Act.\u000d\u000aSee also: Mauritius VAITOS Act, FSC Mauritius, VASP\u000d\u000aValidator\u000d\u000aA participant in a Proof of Stake blockchain network who locks up (stakes) tokens as collateral and is\u000d\u000aselected to validate and propose new blocks of transactions. Validators earn staking rewards for honest\u000d\u000aparticipation and risk having their staked tokens 'slashed' for malicious or negligent behaviour.\u000d\u000aSee also: Proof of Stake, Staking, Consensus Mechanism, Node\u000d\u000aVASP (Virtual Asset Service Provider)\u000d\u000aA business or individual that, as a commercial activity, conducts one or more of the following for or on\u000d\u000abehalf of another person: (1) exchange between virtual assets and fiat currencies; (2) exchange between\u000d\u000aone or more forms of virtual assets; (3) transfer of virtual assets; (4) safekeeping or administration of virtual\u000d\u000aassets or instruments enabling control over virtual assets; or (5) participation in or provision of financial\u000d\u000aservices related to an issuer's offer or sale of virtual assets. This is the FATF definition, which Nigeria has\u000d\u000aadopted.\u000d\u000aUnder Nigeria's ISA 2025 and SEC Digital Asset Rules, all VASPs operating in Nigeria or targeting Nigerian\u000d\u000ainvestors must be registered with SEC Nigeria through the ARIP process. VASPs are classified into four\u000d\u000acategories: Digital Asset Exchange (DAX), Digital Asset Offering Platform (DAOP), Digital Asset Custodian (DAC),\u000d\u000aand Digital Asset Intermediary (DAI).\u000d\u000aSee also: ISA 2025, SEC Nigeria, ARIP, DAX, DAOP, DAC, FATF, AML\u000d\u000aVirtual Asset\u000d\u000aFATF's terminology for a digital representation of value that can be digitally traded, transferred, or used for\u000d\u000apayment or investment purposes. Nigeria's ISA 2025 adopts this definition, classifying virtual assets as\u000d\u000asecurities. The terms 'virtual asset', 'digital asset', and 'crypto asset' are largely synonymous in the Nigerian\u000d\u000aregulatory context.\u000d\u000aSee also: Digital Asset, VASP, ISA 2025, FATF\u000d\u000aW\u000d\u000aWallet\u000d\u000aSoftware or hardware that stores the private keys needed to access and transact digital assets on a\u000d\u000ablockchain. A wallet does not 'store' digital assets in the way a physical wallet stores cash \u2014 the assets are\u000d\u000a\u2014 225 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aalways on the blockchain. The wallet stores the cryptographic keys that prove ownership and authorise\u000d\u000atransactions. Wallets can be custodial (managed by a third party) or non-custodial (managed by the user).\u000d\u000aNigerian VASP rules distinguish between custodial wallets (subject to DAC regulation) and non-custodial wallets\u000d\u000a(subject to FATF's unhosted wallet guidance and NFIU monitoring requirements for transactions involving\u000d\u000athem).\u000d\u000aSee also: Private Key, Custodial Wallet, Non-Custodial Wallet, DAC\u000d\u000aWeb3\u000d\u000aA conceptual evolution of the internet characterised by decentralisation, blockchain-based ownership, and\u000d\u000auser sovereignty over data and digital assets. Web3 envisions an internet where users own their identity\u000d\u000aand assets (via wallets and tokens), participate in governance (via DAOs), and interact with applications\u000d\u000adirectly through smart contracts \u2014 rather than through centralised platforms that own user data and\u000d\u000aextract rents.\u000d\u000aSee also: Blockchain, dApp, DAO, DeFi, NFT\u000d\u000aY\u000d\u000aYield Farming\u000d\u000aThe practice of deploying digital assets across various DeFi protocols to earn the highest possible return \u2014\u000d\u000athrough trading fees, liquidity incentives, governance token rewards, or interest. Yield farming strategies can\u000d\u000abe simple (depositing into a lending protocol) or highly complex (deploying capital through multiple\u000d\u000aprotocols simultaneously). The returns can be very high and the risks \u2014 including smart contract bugs,\u000d\u000aimpermanent loss, and protocol insolvency \u2014 are correspondingly significant.\u000d\u000aYield farming products offered to Nigerian investors are likely to constitute collective investment scheme\u000d\u000aactivity under ISA 2025 and require SEC Nigeria oversight, particularly if they involve pooling of client funds or\u000d\u000apromises of returns.\u000d\u000aSee also: DeFi, Liquidity Pool, Staking, AMM, SEC Nigeria\u000d\u000aZ\u000d\u000aZero-Knowledge Proof (ZKP)\u000d\u000a\u2014 226 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aA cryptographic method by which one party (the prover) can demonstrate to another party (the verifier)\u000d\u000athat a statement is true \u2014 without revealing any information beyond the truth of the statement itself. ZKPs\u000d\u000aare transformative for privacy-preserving compliance: they can allow a user to prove they are over 18, pass\u000d\u000aKYC checks, or satisfy AML requirements without revealing their underlying personal data.\u000d\u000aZero-knowledge proofs have significant potential for privacy-preserving compliance in Africa \u2014 allowing\u000d\u000aindividuals to prove identity or creditworthiness without surrendering full personal data to centralised\u000d\u000ainstitutions. This is relevant to both the financial inclusion agenda and the emerging data protection framework\u000d\u000aunder Nigeria's NDPR.\u000d\u000aSee also: ZK-SNARK, Blockchain, KYC, Digital Identity\u000d\u000aZK-SNARK (Zero-Knowledge Succinct Non-Interactive Argument of Knowledge)\u000d\u000aA specific and highly efficient type of zero-knowledge proof that allows verification of computations with\u000d\u000aminimal data exchange and no back-and-forth interaction between prover and verifier. ZK-SNARKs are the\u000d\u000acryptographic technology underlying ZK-rollups \u2014 Layer 2 scaling solutions that dramatically reduce\u000d\u000atransaction costs while preserving Ethereum's security.\u000d\u000aSee also: Zero-Knowledge Proof, Rollup, Layer 2\u000d\u000aTotal entries: 140 terms across 23 alphabetical sections. \u00b7 First Edition, 2026.\u000d\u000aAbout the Author\u000d\u000aChimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aChimezie Chuta is a nationally recognised blockchain strategist, digital asset policy\u000d\u000aarchitect, and full-stack systems architect with nearly ten years of experience building\u000d\u000atechnology infrastructure, shaping national policy, and developing Africa\u2019s blockchain\u000d\u000aand Web3 ecosystem from the ground up.\u000d\u000aHe currently serves as Chairman of the Federal Government of Nigeria\u2019s National\u000d\u000aBlockchain Policy Implementation Steering Committee under NITDA, and as a member of\u000d\u000athe Securities and Exchange Commission Nigeria\u2019s Blockchain and Virtual Asset Working\u000d\u000aGroup \u2014 making him one of the few practitioners in Nigeria who has simultaneously\u000d\u000a\u2014 227 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000ashaped the regulatory frameworks governing digital assets and built the products those\u000d\u000aframeworks govern.\u000d\u000aChimezie founded the Blockchain Nigeria User Group (BNUG) in 2016, building it from\u000d\u000azero to over 25,000 members and establishing it as the country\u2019s foremost Web3\u000d\u000ainnovation community and industry voice in national policy dialogue. He convened\u000d\u000aNigeria\u2019s first National Blockchain and Cryptocurrency Conference in 2017, secured the\u000d\u000acountry\u2019s first corporate sponsorship for blockchain education (Humaniq, 2017), and has\u000d\u000asince convened over twenty national conferences, hackathons, bootcamps, and\u000d\u000amasterclasses, training more than one thousand practitioners across blockchain, DeFi,\u000d\u000aWeb3, and digital innovation.\u000d\u000aHis market-facing career spans senior roles at the intersection of technology and African\u000d\u000afinancial infrastructure. As Africa Regional Director at Paxful, he built and managed the\u000d\u000acompany\u2019s pan-African market operations at a time when Nigeria was emerging as one of\u000d\u000athe world\u2019s largest peer-to-peer Bitcoin markets. As West Africa Advisor at Kinesis.money\u000d\u000a(2019\u20132024) and Advisor to the BANTU Blockchain Foundation, he provided strategic\u000d\u000aguidance on regulatory navigation, market entry, and digital asset infrastructure across\u000d\u000athe continent. As a Venture Partner at Adaverse VC, he continues to support Web3 startup\u000d\u000afounders across Nigeria, Kenya, Ghana, and Uganda.\u000d\u000aChimezie is the CEO of Blockspace Technologies Limited, through which he delivers\u000d\u000aenterprise blockchain advisory, systems architecture, and AI-enabled product design for\u000d\u000afinancial institutions, telecoms companies, and technology businesses across Nigeria and\u000d\u000aWest Africa. His enterprise advisory clients have included MTN, Stanbic IBTC, and\u000d\u000aleading Nigerian commercial banks.\u000d\u000aHe is the author of The DeFi Handbook, Seizing Opportunities in Blockchain and Digital\u000d\u000aCurrencies (2017), and The Building Blocks of Blockchain Founders. His commentary and\u000d\u000aanalysis have been featured by CNBC Africa, BBC World News, Al Jazeera, Channels TV,\u000d\u000aand Arise News. He has spoken at Binance Blockchain Week, Africa Tech Week,\u000d\u000aTechCabal, the UN Africa Digital Transformation Forum, and the Africa Fintech Festival.\u000d\u000aThis is his fourth book.\u000d\u000a\u2014 228 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aWorking with Chimezie\u000d\u000aAdvisory, Speaking & Board Engagements\u000d\u000aIf this book has done its job, you are reading this section with a specific problem in mind.\u000d\u000aBelow is a clear account of how to engage Chimezie\u2019s advisory work, and what each type\u000d\u000aof engagement looks like in practice.\u000d\u000aAdvisory Retainers\u000d\u000aChimezie works with a small number of digital asset companies, fintech firms, and\u000d\u000aenterprise institutions on a monthly retainer basis, providing ongoing strategic advisory\u000d\u000aon blockchain product development, regulatory navigation, and West African market\u000d\u000apositioning.\u000d\u000aSpeaking Engagements\u000d\u000aChimezie speaks at international conferences, corporate executive training programmes,\u000d\u000agovernment and regulatory capacity-building sessions, and university and research\u000d\u000ainstitutions on blockchain strategy, African digital finance policy, Web3 ecosystem\u000d\u000adevelopment, and the regulatory landscape for digital assets.\u000d\u000aHe has delivered keynotes and panel appearances at Binance Blockchain Week, Africa\u000d\u000aTech Week, TechCabal, the UN Africa Digital Transformation Forum, the Africa Fintech\u000d\u000aFestival, the Kanu Digital Summit, and numerous NITDA and SEC-hosted industry\u000d\u000aevents. In 2023 he facilitated a blockchain and digital asset strategy training for senior\u000d\u000aCBN management, including director-level officials, in Kigali.\u000d\u000aSpeaking engagements available:\u000d\u000a\u2022 Keynote addresses (45\u201360 minutes) on: The Future of African Digital Finance; Building in Regulated\u000d\u000aMarkets; Nigeria\u2019s Digital Asset Policy Landscape; The Blockchain Opportunity for African Enterprises\u000d\u000a\u2022 Executive and board-level training sessions (half-day to full-day) for financial institutions, telecoms,\u000d\u000aand regulators on blockchain, digital assets, DeFi, stablecoins, and AI-enabled financial products\u000d\u000a\u2014 229 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a\u2022 Panel moderation and expert commentary at industry conferences and regulatory forums\u000d\u000a\u2022 Academic and research institution lectures at graduate and postgraduate level\u000d\u000aTo enquire about speaking engagements: email the subject line \u2018Speaking Enquiry\u2019 with\u000d\u000athe event name, date, location, anticipated audience size, and the topic or question you\u000d\u000awould like addressed. Responses within five business days.\u000d\u000a(https://advisory.blockspace.digital/)\u000d\u000aBoard & Non-Executive Director Appointments\u000d\u000aChimezie accepts a small number of board and non-executive director appointments at\u000d\u000adigital asset companies, fintech firms, and blockchain-adjacent enterprises where his\u000d\u000aexpertise in Nigerian regulatory strategy, digital asset markets, and West African\u000d\u000aecosystem development creates genuine governance value.\u000d\u000aBoard appointments are evaluated on four criteria: the company is building something of\u000d\u000agenuine significance; the board appointment would materially strengthen its regulatory\u000d\u000aand market credibility; the time commitment is compatible with Chimezie\u2019s existing\u000d\u000aobligations; and the governance culture is one in which independent directors are\u000d\u000aexpected and empowered to provide honest challenge.\u000d\u000aTo initiate a board appointment conversation: send a brief (one page maximum) company\u000d\u000aoverview, the specific governance challenge or capability gap you are looking to address,\u000d\u000aand the proposed time commitment and meeting structure. Initial conversations are\u000d\u000aexploratory, no commitment is implied on either side until a formal offer has been made\u000d\u000aand accepted.\u000d\u000aContact Information\u000d\u000aEmail: chimeziechuta@gmail.com LinkedIn: linkedin.com/in/chimeziechuta\u000d\u000ahttps://advisory.blockspace.digital/ Phone: +234 816 543 0776. Please include your name, company, and\u000d\u000aa one-sentence description of your enquiry in all initial contact. Responses are prioritised in the order of\u000d\u000aspecificity: the more precisely you describe the problem, the faster and more useful the response.\u000d\u000a\u2014 230 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aAcknowledgements\u000d\u000aThis book was written from the inside of an ecosystem, and it could not have been written\u000d\u000afrom anywhere else. The people whose knowledge, generosity, and patience made it\u000d\u000apossible are too numerous to name fully, but some must be named.\u000d\u000aTo the founders who trusted me with the real stories, the letters that arrived on Tuesday\u000d\u000amornings, the investors who grew anxious, the lawyers who gave the wrong advice, the\u000d\u000aregulators who eventually became partners. You are in these pages, anonymised but\u000d\u000arecognisable to yourselves. I hope this book gives the next generation of founders a map\u000d\u000athey did not have.\u000d\u000aTo the regulatory officials across the CBN, SEC Nigeria, NITDA, NFIU, and NAICOM\u000d\u000awho have engaged with me over the years with genuine openness and patience, including\u000d\u000athose whose initial instinct was scepticism and who changed their view through dialogue.\u000d\u000aThe quality of Nigeria\u2019s regulatory framework today is partly the product of your\u000d\u000awillingness to learn alongside the industry you were learning to govern. That is not a\u000d\u000asmall thing.\u000d\u000aTo the team at the Blockchain Nigeria User Group, every coordinator, volunteer, event\u000d\u000aorganiser, and community member who showed up over nine years to build something\u000d\u000athat most people said could not be built. BNUG is the reason this book has any authority\u000d\u000aat all.\u000d\u000aTo my colleagues at Adaverse VC, the Fintech Association of Nigeria, the Blockchain\u000d\u000aExperts Association of Nigeria, and the National Blockchain Policy Steering Committee,\u000d\u000aBlockchain Industry Coordinating Committee of Nigeria (BICCON), the work we have\u000d\u000adone together in rooms that the public never saw is the foundation of everything\u000d\u000adescribed in Part Two of this book.\u000d\u000aTo the team at Blockspace Technologies, who have tolerated my simultaneous career as a\u000d\u000apolicy advocate, community builder, and now author without complaint, and who make\u000d\u000athe enterprise work that this work depends on.\u000d\u000a\u2014 231 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aTo the founders across Nigeria, Ghana, Kenya, Uganda, and beyond who attended the\u000d\u000aconferences, the bootcamps, and the masterclasses \u2014 who asked the hard questions and\u000d\u000adid not accept easy answers. You taught me more than you know.\u000d\u000aThis book is dedicated to every African founder who is building something serious in a\u000d\u000amarket that does not yet have the infrastructure to fully support it. The infrastructure is\u000d\u000acoming. Build anyway.\u000d\u000aChimezie Chuta\u000d\u000aLagos, Nigeria\u000d\u000aApril 2026\u000d\u000a\u2014 232 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aReferences\u000d\u000aThe frameworks, case studies, and regulatory analyses in this book draw on a\u000d\u000asubstantial body of primary legislative and regulatory source material. The references\u000d\u000abelow are organised by category and jurisdiction, reflecting the scope of the research\u000d\u000athat underpins the book's arguments and guidance.\u000d\u000aAll primary legislative and regulatory documents are cited at the point of reference in\u000d\u000athe main text. Where possible, direct links to official government and regulatory body\u000d\u000awebsites are provided. Given the pace of regulatory change in African digital finance,\u000d\u000areaders are advised to verify the currency of any specific provision directly with the\u000d\u000aissuing authority before relying on it for commercial or compliance purposes.\u000d\u000aReferences marked \u23f3 are identified as relevant but were awaiting official publication\u000d\u000aor public release at the time of going to press. Readers are encouraged to source them\u000d\u000adirectly from the relevant regulatory bodies as they become available.\u000d\u000aI. Nigerian Legislation and Regulatory Frameworks\u000d\u000aPrimary statutes and regulatory instruments of the Federal Republic of Nigeria.\u000d\u000aA. Statutes and Acts of the National Assembly\u000d\u000aDocument / Citation Jurisdiction /\u000d\u000aBody\u000d\u000aYear\u000d\u000aInvestments and Securities Act 2025 (ISA 2025) Nigeria \u2014\u000d\u000aNASS\u000d\u000a2025\u000d\u000aBanks and Other Financial Institutions Act 2020 (BOFIA\u000d\u000a2020)\u000d\u000aNigeria \u2014\u000d\u000aNASS\u000d\u000a2020\u000d\u000aCompanies and Allied Matters Act 2020 (CAMA 2020) Nigeria \u2014\u000d\u000aNASS\u000d\u000a2020\u000d\u000aMoney Laundering (Prevention and Prohibition) Act\u000d\u000a2022 (MLPPA 2022)\u000d\u000aNigeria \u2014\u000d\u000aNASS\u000d\u000a2022\u000d\u000aProceeds of Crime (Recovery and Management) Act\u000d\u000a2022 (POCA 2022)\u000d\u000aNigeria \u2014\u000d\u000aNASS\u000d\u000a2022\u000d\u000aTerrorism (Prevention and Prohibition) Act 2022 (TPPA\u000d\u000a2022)\u000d\u000aNigeria \u2014\u000d\u000aNASS\u000d\u000a2022\u000d\u000a\u2014 233 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aNigeria Startup Act 2022 Nigeria \u2014\u000d\u000aNASS\u000d\u000a2022\u000d\u000aNigeria Data Protection Act 2023 (NDPA 2023) Nigeria \u2014\u000d\u000aNASS\u000d\u000a2023\u000d\u000aNigeria Tax Administration Act 2025 (NTAA 2025) Nigeria \u2014\u000d\u000aNASS\u000d\u000a2025\u000d\u000aB. Securities and Exchange Commission Nigeria\u000d\u000aDocument / Citation Jurisdiction /\u000d\u000aBody\u000d\u000aYear\u000d\u000aSEC Digital Asset Rules: Rules on Issuance, Offering\u000d\u000aPlatforms and Custody of Digital Assets (2022)\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria 2022\u000d\u000aSEC Digital Asset Rules \u2014 Amended 2023 SEC Nigeria 2023\u000d\u000aSEC Digital Asset Rules \u2014 Amended 2024 (latest\u000d\u000aenacted)\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria 2024\u000d\u000aA Framework on Accelerated Regulatory Incubation\u000d\u000aProgram for the Onboarding of Virtual Assets Service\u000d\u000aProviders (VASPs) and other Digital Investments\u000d\u000aService Providers (DISPs) (ARIP Framework)\u000d\u000aSEC Nigeria 2024\u000d\u000aC. Central Bank of Nigeria\u000d\u000aDocument / Citation Jurisdiction /\u000d\u000aBody\u000d\u000aYear\u000d\u000aGuidelines on the Operation of Bank Accounts for\u000d\u000aVirtual Asset Service Providers 2023 (CBN VASP\u000d\u000aGuidelines)\u000d\u000aCBN 2023\u000d\u000aCBN Circular: Prohibition of Cryptocurrency Trading\u000d\u000ain Nigeria (February 2021) \u2014 subsequently superseded\u000d\u000aby the 2023 Guidelines\u000d\u000aCBN 2021\u000d\u000a\u2014 234 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aD. Nigerian Financial Intelligence Unit\u000d\u000aDocument / Citation Jurisdiction /\u000d\u000aBody\u000d\u000aYear\u000d\u000aAML/CFT Compliance Framework for Virtual Asset\u000d\u000aService Providers (December 2024)\u000d\u000aNFIU 2024\u000d\u000aAll Nigerian legislation is accessible via the National Assembly of Nigeria\u000d\u000a(nassnig.org), the Federal Ministry of Justice (justice.gov.ng), and the relevant\u000d\u000aregulatory body websites. SEC Nigeria's rules and frameworks are available at\u000d\u000asec.gov.ng. CBN circulars and guidelines are available at cbn.gov.ng. NFIU guidelines\u000d\u000aare available at nfiu.gov.ng.\u000d\u000aII. Pan-African Regulatory Frameworks\u000d\u000aPrimary legislation and regulatory frameworks from African jurisdictions addressed in this\u000d\u000abook.\u000d\u000aA. Ghana\u000d\u000aDocument / Citation Jurisdiction /\u000d\u000aBody\u000d\u000aYear\u000d\u000aGhana Investments and Securities Act 2025 Ghana \u2014\u000d\u000aParliament\u000d\u000a2025\u000d\u000aVirtual Asset Service Providers Act 2025, Act 1154\u000d\u000a(Ghana VASP Act)\u000d\u000aGhana \u2014\u000d\u000aParliament\u000d\u000a2025\u000d\u000aB. Kenya\u000d\u000aDocument / Citation Jurisdiction /\u000d\u000aBody\u000d\u000aYear\u000d\u000aVirtual Asset Service Providers Act 2025 (Kenya VASP\u000d\u000aAct)\u000d\u000aKenya \u2014\u000d\u000aParliament\u000d\u000a2025\u000d\u000a\u2014 235 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aC. Mauritius\u000d\u000aDocument / Citation Jurisdiction /\u000d\u000aBody\u000d\u000aYear\u000d\u000aVirtual Asset and Initial Token Offering Services Act\u000d\u000a2021 (VAITOS Act)\u000d\u000aMauritius \u2014\u000d\u000aFSC\u000d\u000a2021\u000d\u000aD. South Africa\u000d\u000aDocument / Citation Jurisdiction /\u000d\u000aBody\u000d\u000aYear\u000d\u000aCrypto Asset Service Provider (CASP) Regulatory\u000d\u000aFramework \u2014 Financial Sector Conduct Authority\u000d\u000aSouth Africa \u2014\u000d\u000aFSCA\u000d\u000a2023\u000d\u000aFinancial Intelligence Centre Act (FICA) South Africa \u2014\u000d\u000aParliament\u000d\u000a2001\u000d\u000aFinancial Advisory and Intermediary Services Act\u000d\u000a(FAIS Act)\u000d\u000aSouth Africa \u2014\u000d\u000aParliament\u000d\u000a2002\u000d\u000aGhanaian legislation is available at ghanalegal.com and through the Bank of Ghana\u000d\u000a(bog.gov.gh). Kenyan legislation is available at kenyalaw.org and the Capital Markets\u000d\u000aAuthority (cma.or.ke). Mauritius legislation and FSC guidance is available at\u000d\u000afscmauritius.org. South African regulatory frameworks are available at fsca.co.za and\u000d\u000athe Financial Intelligence Centre (fic.gov.za).\u000d\u000aIII. International Standards and Multilateral Frameworks\u000d\u000aStandards issued by international standard-setting bodies whose outputs directly shape African\u000d\u000aregulatory frameworks.\u000d\u000aA. Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\u000d\u000aDocument / Citation Jurisdiction /\u000d\u000aBody\u000d\u000aYear\u000d\u000a\u2014 236 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aRecommendation 15: New Technologies \u2014 Virtual\u000d\u000aAssets and Virtual Asset Service Providers (Updated\u000d\u000aOctober 2018, revised June 2019)\u000d\u000aFATF 2019\u000d\u000aTargeted Update on Implementation of FATF Standards\u000d\u000aon Virtual Assets and Virtual Asset Service Providers \u2014\u000d\u000a2021\u000d\u000aFATF 2021\u000d\u000aTargeted Update on Implementation of FATF Standards\u000d\u000aon Virtual Assets and Virtual Asset Service Providers \u2014\u000d\u000a2022\u000d\u000aFATF 2022\u000d\u000aTargeted Update on Implementation of FATF Standards\u000d\u000aon Virtual Assets and Virtual Asset Service Providers \u2014\u000d\u000a2023\u000d\u000aFATF 2023\u000d\u000aTargeted Update on Implementation of FATF Standards\u000d\u000aon Virtual Assets and Virtual Asset Service Providers \u2014\u000d\u000a2024\u000d\u000aFATF 2024\u000d\u000aTargeted Update on Implementation of FATF Standards\u000d\u000aon Virtual Assets and Virtual Asset Service Providers \u2014\u000d\u000a2025\u000d\u000aFATF 2025\u000d\u000aFATF Updates on Virtual Assets 2019\u20132025\u000d\u000a(consolidated reference)\u000d\u000aFATF 2019\u201320\u000d\u000a25\u000d\u000aAll FATF publications are available at fatf-gafi.org. The Targeted Update on Virtual\u000d\u000aAssets is published annually in June and is the single most important recurring\u000d\u000apublication for practitioners and founders in the digital asset space.\u000d\u000aB. GIABA \u2014 Inter-Governmental Action Group Against Money Laundering in\u000d\u000aWest Africa\u000d\u000aDocument / Citation Jurisdiction /\u000d\u000aBody\u000d\u000aYear\u000d\u000aMutual Evaluation Report: Nigeria \u2014 Assessment of\u000d\u000athe Implementation of the FATF Recommendations and\u000d\u000athe FATF Special Recommendations\u000d\u000aGIABA 2023\u000d\u000aGIABA is the FATF-style regional body for West Africa. Its mutual evaluation reports\u000d\u000aon member states, including Nigeria, are available at giaba.org.\u000d\u000a\u2014 237 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aC. European Union\u000d\u000aDocument / Citation Jurisdiction /\u000d\u000aBody\u000d\u000aYear\u000d\u000aRegulation (EU) 2023/1114 of the European Parliament\u000d\u000aand of the Council on Markets in Crypto-Assets (MiCA)\u000d\u000a\u2014 entered into full effect December 2024\u000d\u000aEuropean\u000d\u000aUnion\u000d\u000a2023\u000d\u000aMiCA is referenced in this book as a comparative benchmark and for its direct\u000d\u000aapplicability to Nigerian VASPs serving European Union customers. It is available in\u000d\u000afull at eur-lex.europa.eu.\u000d\u000aIV. Canonical Interpretive Reference\u000d\u000aThe following work serves as the primary interpretive layer throughout this book. It is\u000d\u000athe only secondary source to which the author assigns co-equal authority with\u000d\u000aprimary regulatory documents, on the grounds that it was produced from direct\u000d\u000aparticipation in the policy processes it describes.\u000d\u000aV. Key Institutional Sources\u000d\u000aThe following institutions are the primary official sources consulted in the preparation\u000d\u000aof this book. Their official websites and portals are the authoritative locations for\u000d\u000acurrent versions of all regulatory instruments referenced herein.\u000d\u000aNigeria\u000d\u000aSecurities and Exchange Commission Nigeria (SEC Nigeria) Primary regulator for\u000d\u000adigital assets, VASPs, and capital market operators under ISA 2025.\u000d\u000asec.gov.ng \u00b7 home.sec.gov.ng (ePortal) \u00b7 innovation@sec.gov.ng\u000d\u000aCentral Bank of Nigeria (CBN) Apex monetary authority. Payment systems, naira, banking\u000d\u000asupervision, VASP banking access.\u000d\u000acbn.gov.ng \u00b7 psmd@cbn.gov.ng\u000d\u000a\u2014 238 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aNigerian Financial Intelligence Unit (NFIU) Financial intelligence, AML/CFT compliance,\u000d\u000aSTR/CTR filing, goAML portal.\u000d\u000anfiu.gov.ng \u00b7 goaml.nfiu.gov.ng\u000d\u000aNational Information Technology Development Agency (NITDA) National Blockchain\u000d\u000aPolicy, Nigeria Data Protection Regulation, National AI Strategy.\u000d\u000anitda.gov.ng\u000d\u000aCorporate Affairs Commission (CAC) Company registration, Beneficial Ownership\u000d\u000aRegister, business name registration.\u000d\u000acac.gov.ng\u000d\u000aNational Insurance Commission (NAICOM) Insurance regulation; fidelity bonds required\u000d\u000afor VASP registration.\u000d\u000anaicom.gov.ng\u000d\u000aRegional and International\u000d\u000aFinancial Action Task Force (FATF) Global AML/CFT standard-setter. Publishes annual\u000d\u000aTargeted Update on Virtual Assets every June.\u000d\u000afatf-gafi.org\u000d\u000aGIABA \u2014 Inter-Governmental Action Group Against Money Laundering in West\u000d\u000aAfrica FATF-style regional body for West Africa. Mutual evaluation reports on member states\u000d\u000aincluding Nigeria.\u000d\u000agiaba.org\u000d\u000aBank of Ghana / Ghana Securities and Exchange Commission Dual regulators for\u000d\u000aGhana's VASP framework under Act 1154 (2025).\u000d\u000abog.gov.gh \u00b7 sec.gov.gh\u000d\u000aCapital Markets Authority Kenya (CMA Kenya) Primary VASP regulator under Kenya\u000d\u000aVASP Act 2025.\u000d\u000acma.or.ke\u000d\u000aFinancial Services Commission Mauritius (FSC Mauritius) VASP licensing authority\u000d\u000aunder VAITOS Act 2021. Issues stablecoin guidance.\u000d\u000afscmauritius.org\u000d\u000aFinancial Sector Conduct Authority \u2014 South Africa (FSCA) CASP licensing authority.\u000d\u000aRegulation began June 2023.\u000d\u000afsca.co.za\u000d\u000a\u2014 239 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000aA Note on Currency\u000d\u000aRegulatory frameworks governing digital assets in Africa are among the most rapidly\u000d\u000aevolving bodies of law anywhere in the world. Multiple instruments referenced in this\u000d\u000abook were amended or enacted during the period of the book's preparation. Readers\u000d\u000aare strongly advised to verify the current status of any specific provision directly with\u000d\u000athe issuing authority before relying on it for commercial, compliance, or legal\u000d\u000apurposes.\u000d\u000aWhere this book describes a regulatory position as current, that description reflects the\u000d\u000aposition as known at the time of going to press, May 2026. The author and publisher\u000d\u000aaccept no liability for decisions made on the basis of regulatory information that has\u000d\u000asubsequently changed.\u000d\u000a\u2756 \u2756 \u2756\u000d\u000aIntroducing Klarify\u000d\u000aThe Book Gives You the Framework. Klarify helps You Execute It.\u000d\u000aCompliance intelligence, readiness infrastructure, and regulatory guidance, built for founders\u000d\u000awho need to move from strategy to execution.\u000d\u000aThe book gives you the map. Klarify gives you the GPS.\u000d\u000aThe book explains the rules. Klarify runs the playbook.\u000d\u000ahttps://klarify.africa/\u000d\u000a\u2014 240 \u2014","THE FOUNDER'S GUIDE TO BUILDING IN REGULATED MARKETS\u000d\u000a\u2014 241 \u2014"]